<1ST_LINE>u i AM-RainbowWarrior     05-05 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rainbow Warrior,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Saboteur To Be Repatriated To France, Says Lange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister David Lange said
Friday that France has informed him it is allowing the return of a
second French secret agent who took part in the 1985 bombing of the
Rainbow Warrior off New Zealand.
   Lange accused the French government of flouting international
law with the move.
   The New Zealand prime minister said he was advised that Capt.
Dominique Prieur was returning to Paris ``forthwith'' from Hao
atoll.
   Ms. Prieur and Maj. Alain Mafart, the other French agent, were
supposed to remain in exile on the South Pacific island until July
1989 under an agreement worked out by the United Nations. The
accord stipulated that they could not leave the island without the
consent of New Zealand.
   Lange said he expected Ms. Prieur to arrive in Paris on Friday
or Saturday and that he intends to pursue the matter with French
authorities.
   ``There has been no confirmation of departure but it is not
consented to and should she leave it would be a clear breach of
France's obligation under international law,'' Lange said in a
statement.
   Ms. Prieur and Mafart were sent to New Zealand to stop the
Rainbow Warrior from leading a protest flotilla to Mururoa, a South
Pacific island where France conducts underground nuclear tests.
   One crewman on the Rainbow Warrior was killed in the bombing in
Auckland Harbor.
   The pair, who worked for the French secret service, the
Direction Generale de la Securite Exterieure, pleaded guilty in
1985 to manslaughter.
   Mafart was repatriated in December last year after complaining
of a stomach disorder.
   France's decision to end Ms. Prieur's exile on Hao atoll follows
the release of three French hostages from Lebanon and Thursday's
bloody rescue in New Caledonia of 23 hostages held by Melanesian
separatists.
   All three events could boost the chances of conservative
candidate Prime Minister Jacques Chirac in the runoff in France's
presidential election Sunday. He is running against President
Francois Mitterrand.
   Mafart and Ms. Prieur originally were sentenced to 10 years in
jail. Their conviction sparked an unprecedented diplomatic row
between Paris and Wellington which ended after seven months, when
the sentences were commuted under the agreement worked out by
Javier Perez de Cuellar, the U.N. secretary-general.
   Under the agreement the pair was released into French custody on
Hao, a tiny military outpost near Mururoa.
   In return Paris apologized for the bombing, paid $7 million
compensation and promised not to block New Zealand exports to
Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
