<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     05-05 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thinking a few moves ahead, producers of the
$6.2 million Broadway play ``Chess'' have cut more than 10 minutes
from the less-than-acclaimed show in an effort to improve its
position and check overtime costs.
   ``One comment we received from even the people who were
enthusiastic about the play was that it was too long,'' Gerald
Schoenfeld, chairman of the Shubert Organization, one of the play's
co-producers, said Wednesday. ``We wanted to enhance the show.
   ``We also save a bunch of money,'' said Bernard Jacobs,
Schubert's president. ``But that's incidental. If the show doesn't
make it, the amount spent in weekly operating costs is minimal over
a long-term period.''
   Before the cuts, the curtain came down at about 11:10 each
night. Because overtime begins at 11, the extra 10 minutes a night
amounted to about $25,000 a week, in part because its complicated
sets and lighting requires more than 40 stagehands.
   The cuts, which total between 11 and 12 minutes, bring the
curtain down before 11 and save all the overtime.
   They were agreed to last weekend by Trevor Nunn, the director;
Time Rice, the lyricist; and Benny Andersson and Bjorn Ulvaeus, the
composers, Schoenfeld said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McNicol Middle School is developing a reputation
around these parts for producing students with a sharp eye _ if not
for studies then at least for big cockroaches.
   Susan Qunn, a science teacher at the suburban Hollywood school,
challenged her students for the second straight year to spread out
and hunt for monster cockroaches. Her students turned in 21
entries, one of which won Wednesday.
   The state winner last year in the contest for biggest roach was
a sixth-grader at McNicol, and went on to win the national
Roach-Off.
   On Wednesday, the winning entrant, found by sixth-grader Marvell
Berry, was dead by the time of the judging, but that didn't detract
from the glory of the moment.
   ``You're going to be a star,'' Tom Daubert whispered to the tiny
corpse of Florida's champion cockroach as the 1.75-inch bug was
crowned in the state finals of the Great American Roach-Off II. The
winner will be flown to the Philadelphia Zoo to measure up against
seven other regional finalists for the national title on July 7.
   Daubert, an exterminator for Alert Pest Control in Miami and a
judge for the Roach-Off sequel, predicted that the winning roach
will successfully ``defend Florida's national cockroach crown.''
</TEXT>
