<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AdultPlayground     05-05 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Adult Playground,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veteran Gamers Buy Property That Was Playground to the Rich and
Famous</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landmark hotel-casino that was an adult
playground for the likes of Mae West, Judy Garland and Marilyn
Monroe in its heyday could get a new lease on life.
   Nevada gaming veterans George Karadanis and Robert Maloff, who
own the 600-room Sundowner hotel-casino and are building the
119-room Virginian in Reno, confirmed Wednesday they plan to buy
the 40-year-old Mapes hotel-casino, which has been closed since
1982.
   The two and First Interstate Bank of Nevada, which foreclosed on
the property in 1983, refused to release details of the pending
sale. But the bank previously rejected offers up to $8 million and
the property has been appraised at $10 million.
   ``There are no immediate plans for the Mapes,'' Karadanis said
through a spokeswoman on Tuesday.
   First Interstate President Ronald Zurek said the purchase deal
is expected to be closed in 30 days and Saturday's planned auction
of the 12-story hotel and casino and surrounding parking lot has
been cancelled.
   In the 1950s, big-name entertainers such as Judy Garland, Mae
West, Gypsy Rose Lee and Milton Berle performed in the 12th floor
Mapes Skyroom. Marilyn Monroe was a hotel guest when she was in the
Reno area filming the movie ``The Misfits,'' the last motion
picture she completed.
</TEXT>
