<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Norway-Nuclear     05-05 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Norway-Nuclear,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Official Confirms Diversion of Heavy Water</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Norwegian official confirmed Wednesday that a
shipment of ``heavy water,'' which can be used in nuclear reactors
and in making nuclear weapons, was diverted to an unknown
destination in 1983, The New York Times reported.
   ``We have confirmed today that 15 tons of Norwegian heavy water
is missing,'' Lasse Seim, a spokesman for the Norwegian Foreign
Ministry in Washington, told The Times in an interview.
   Seim said the diversion appeared to be the result of an
international conspiracy involving a West German company and that
Norway had asked West Germany to investigate, the newspaper
reported in its Thursday editions.
   The heavy water, or deuterium oxide, had been sold to a West
German company, Rohstoff Einfuhr, and was to be flown in December
1983 from Oslo to Frankfurt, Seim said. But the plane flew instead
to Basel, Switzerland, and the heavy water was then shipped to an
unknown destination, he said.
   The Oslo government and the company that sold the heavy water
were unaware of the diversion until press reports appeared in
Norway and Germany, Seim said.
   A man identified in Norwegian press reports as the operator of
Rohstoff Einfuhr, Alfred Hempel, has been linked in the past to
trade in heavy water, The Times reported, citing unidentified
American officials. One U.S. government specialist said he was
believed to have sold heavy water to India in the past, the
newspaper said.
   Heavy water can be used to enable nuclear reactors to run on
natural uranium rather than enriched uranium fuel, and to produce
plutonium which in turn can be used in nuclear weapons. India has
several nuclear reactors that use heavy water.
</TEXT>
