<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RaglandSlaying     05-05 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ragland Slaying,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Pleads Guilty To Murder, Gets Life Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager accused of taking part in the
1985 slaying of a convenience store clerk while playing a fantasy
game pleaded guilty to murder Wednesday and was sentenced to life
in prison.
   The plea bargain was reached during jury selection for Chris
White's capital murder trial in the slaying of 26-year-old Missy
Lee Macon.
   In pleading guilty to the lesser charge of murder, the
17-year-old could become eligible for parole after 10 years, said
Assistant St. Clair County District Attorney Gibson Holladay.
   If convicted of capital murder, White would have been sentenced
to the electric chair or life in prison without parole.
   White was the youngest of three Ragland teen-agers charged in
the 1985 shooting of the Ragland convenience store clerk. All were
certified to stand trial as adults. White was 14 when Mrs. Macon
was killed.
   Cayce Moore, 17 when Mrs. Macon was shot to death, was convicted
last year and sentenced to life in prison without parole. A third
defendant, Scott Davis, has yet to be tried. He also was 17 at the
time of the slaying.
   According to testimony, the three were playing Top Secret, in
which they pretended to be carrying out a secret mission, the night
Mrs. Macon was slain.
   White and Moore entered the store 40 miles northeast of
Birmingham while Davis waited in a car, and Moore fired the fatal
shot, according to testimony.
</TEXT>
