<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Cities-Income     05-05 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cities-Income,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rich Get Richer While the Poor Fade, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of the posh Connecticut suburbs of
New York City have the highest average incomes in the nation, more
than three times the income of Texans near the Mexican border, a
government report says.
   The Commerce Department, in its annual ranking of per capita
income in 317 metropolitan areas, said residents of the
Bridgeport-Stamford-Norwalk-Danbury area of Connecticut maintained
their No. 1 ranking with average incomes of $24,501 for every man,
woman and child in 1986.
   That was up 15.7 percent from $21,181 in 1984, when the
Bridgeport area average income also was the highest.
   The McAllen-Edinburg-Mission area of Texas, near the Mexican
border, posted the lowest per capita income. It traded places with
Laredo, Texas, another border town, which was last in 1984 and
next-to-last in 1986.
   McAllen area income was $6,800 and Laredo income was $6,850 in
1986.
   For the nation as a whole, average income grew by 11.6 percent
from $13,116 in 1984 to $14,639.
   However, the statistics show that the gap between the municipal
haves and have-nots is widening.
   Sixty-five percent of the richest 106 metropolitan areas had
faster-than-average income growth, while only 29 percent of the
poorest 105 areas had higher-than-average growth.
   Income in Bridgeport, for example, grew by 15.7 percent, while
income in McAllen grew 6.3 percent.
   The top and bottom average incomes were separated by $17,701 in
1986, compared with a $14,920 gap in 1984.
   The 15 metropolitan areas with the lowest per capita income were
generally located in the Southeast and Southwest. Of the 15
richest, all but two were in the Northeast, California or Florida.
   Four of the top 15 areas were in New Jersey while five of the
bottom 15 were in Texas.
   The top 15 areas and the average per capita personal income in
1986 were:
   Bridgeport-Stamford-Norwalk, Conn., $24,501; San Francisco,
$23,542; Bergen-Passaic, N.J., $21,518;
Middlesex-Somerset-Hunterdon, N.J., $21,142; San Jose, Calif.,
$20,935;
   Anchorage, Alaska, $20,550; Nassau-Suffolk, N.Y., $20,514; Lake
County, Ill., $20,265; Anaheim-Santa Ana, Calif., $20,154;
Washington, D.C., $20,148;
   West Palm Beach-Boca Raton-Delray Beach, Fla., $19,938; Newark,
N.J., $19,675; Trenton, N.J., $19,309; Sarasota, Fla., $19,248, and
Boston-Lawrence-Salem-Lowell-Brockton, Mass., $18,959.
   The bottom 15 and 1986 per capita income were:
   Pine Bluff, Ark., $10,529; Anniston, Ala., $10,476;
Houma-Thibodaux, La., $10,476; Biloxi-Gulfport, Miss., $10,449;
Huntington, W.Va.-Ashland, Ky., $10,426;
   Florence, Ala., $10,336; Pascagoula, Miss., $10,122;
Bryan-College Station, Texas, $10,081; Jacksonville, N.C., $10,013;
Las Cruces, N.M., $9,544;
   El Paso, Texas, $9,177; Provo-Orem, Utah, $8,528;
Brownsville-Harlingen, Texas, $7,205; Laredo, Texas, $6,850, and
McAllen-Edinburg-Mission, Texas, $6,800.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0412EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Miner'sFamily-Jackson Bjt   05-05 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miner's Family-Jackson, Bjt,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Years After Jackson's Visit, Coal Miner's Family Still
Supports Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four years have passed since Jesse
Jackson came to call on jobless coal miner Karnell Bryant. Since
then, the Bryant family has started to leave the hard times behind
_ but not their enthusiasm for Jackson.
   ``I voted for him in 1984 and I'm surely going to do so this
time,'' says Bryant's wife, Diane.
   West Virginia's primary is Tuesday, and Jackson, along with the
other candidates, is campaigning in the state next week. Again, he
will pay a visit to a coal miner's home, this time in Raleigh
County.
   During the 1984 presidential campaign, Jackson's visit with the
Bryants at their home at Mudfork in Logan County garnered national
attention, and gave a glimpse of the coalition of economically
struggling Americans _ both black and white _ that Jackson was
beginning to build.
   At the time, Bryant was eking out a living in the depressed
coalfields from occasional carpentry jobs. He had met Jackson
nearly 20 years earlier, when he was driven to Chicago by tough
economic times in his native state.
   ``I went there because you couldn't get crackers in West
Virginia,'' Bryant said this week. ``Times was really hard here,
with the coal economy so down.''
   In Chicago, Bryant was living in one of the numerous Appalachian
ghettos that sprang up when West Virginians and others fled to
urban areas to look for work.
   ``There was a lot of poor white people _ a real raggedy area,''
he said. ``And I wasn't doing too hot either. I was just a big ol'
knot-headed boy, working as a janitor, so I guess I was one of the
people who was underprivileged.''
   Though he may have considered himself underprivileged, Bryant
still had time and energy to devote to people who were even less
fortunate. He went to work as a volunteer in a food pantry, and
when the pantry needed additional support he contacted Jackson's
Operation PUSH.
   ``I worked around him and with him and I got to admire the
guy,'' Bryant said. ``He wasn't working for no personal gain, just
to help people.''
   These days, the Bryants are better off financially than they
were during Jackson's 1984 visit. About 3{ years ago, they
mortgaged their home and property to buy the store where Mrs.
Bryant worked as a butcher, and now they run the Wilcox Grocery.
   They work 12 hours a day, six days a week. Jackson likes to say
in his stump speech that many of America's poor people work hard
every day.
   ``The business is growing by leaps and bounds,'' Mrs. Bryant
said. ``We're doing real good, with the grace of God.''
   But Bryant doesn't want to forget the hard times.
   ``We're blessed so we can be a blessing to other people, that's
how I look at it,'' Bryant said. ``It seems like the people that
has the money don't care about God, country or human beings. They
just care about getting richer.''
   Bryant said his support for Jackson goes beyond a personal
fondness for the man.
   ``I'm getting a little bit disillusioned with our government and
the way it's been run,'' he said. ``If you ever ask a question,
seems like our government wants to say `You're just a communist, or
a rebel or a redneck.'''
   That's what attracted him to Jackson, Bryant said.
   ``Jesse Jackson don't believe in diplomacy _ he believes in
honesty,'' he said. ``There's a spirit about the man that makes you
want to be more like him.''
   ``What I like about the guy is he's specific and to the point,''
Bryant added. ``And he don't believe in babying people _ if you're
wrong, you're wrong.''
   Diane Bryant agreed.
   ``I think Jesse is the only one who can do the job _ he has the
ability and he's an honest person,'' she said.
   ``You know full well we already have too many crooks in
government.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
