<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SailorsInjured     05-05 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sailors Injured,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Sailors Hurt in Boating Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small boat fell Wednesday while
being lowered to the water from an amphibious ship, injuring seven
sailors, the Navy said.
   ``The injured were rescued from the water and taken ashore by
another Navy small boat which was operating in the vicinity,'' said
Lt. Cmdr. John Lloyd, a spokesman for the Atlantic Fleet Surface
Force, based in Norfolk.
   Lloyd said he did not know whether those hurt had been in the
small boat or if they were struck by it and tossed overboard from
the 522-foot amphibious vessel Manitowoc in the accident in the
Lynnhaven anchorage.
   Two of the injured were in stable condition at Sentara Norfolk
General Hospital, Lloyd said. He said that four others remained in
the hospital but that their conditions were not immediately
available.
   One sailor was treated at a Navy clinic and released, he said.
   The Manitowoc, which is used to land troops and equipment on
beaches via a ramp that extends more than 100 feet, was on a
routine exercise, Lloyd said.
   The vessel is based at Little Creek Amphibious Base, which
straddles Norfolk and Virginia Beach. The ship operates with a crew
of 290 and can carry up to 400 troops.
</TEXT>
