<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Amnesty-Scene     05-05 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-Scene,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mariachi Music, Blimp Helped Lure Applicants To Nation's Busiest
Center</HEAD>
<HEAD>PM-Amnesty Rush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unlikely combination of Mariachi music,
searchlights and the overhead drone of the Goodyear blimp lured the
last of thousands of aliens to the nation's busiest immigration
amnesty application center.
   But a line of aliens that in the past few weeks had numbered in
the thousands dwindled to only a few dozen Wednesday night.
   Still, hundreds of people merely wanting to watch the scene
gathered in the adjacent parking lot and a steady stream of cars
clogged traffic along the street just north of downtown.
   With ``Los Arrieros,'' a six-member Mariachi band, playing
Hispanic music in the background, Richard Rios, director of the
Immigration and Naturalization Service's amnesty center, earlier
surveyed the line of aliens.
   ``It may be a 6,000 day,'' he said simply.
   In the 12 months since the program began, the Houston office
became the nation's busiest single center, with applications
expected to top 110,000, officials said.
   One of the last minute applicants was Maria Flores, who used the
trunk of a car to fill out applications for two of her five
children. She already has submitted applications for her other
children and husband.
   ``We waited until now because we didn't have the money,'' she
said of the $50 fee for children and $185 for adults. A $420
ceiling was set for families.
   She decided to take advantage of the amnesty program for the
advantages of being an American citizen.
   ``Mexico's economy is so bad. It's so expensive and at least
here we can make enough money for food and a decent living,'' said
Mrs. Flores, who has been in this country since 1979.
   Overhead, the Houston-based Goodyear blimp circled, its lighted
sign proclaiming in Spanish and English: ``Time Is Growing Short.''
   A searchlight pierced the dark sky.
   Entrepreneurs sold refreshments and portable toilets were set up
to accommodate people who had camped out overnight.
   ``I kept saying tomorrow, tomorrow, tomorrow,'' said 24-year-old
Florentino Montiel, explaining why he waited until the last day.
   Some attorneys, conspicuous in their suits, and other volunteers
were seated at card tables outside the center, helping applicants
fill out the INS forms. A Spanish-language radio station broadcast
live while an artist sketched pictures of applicants.
   Even police officers directing the traffic helped aliens having
problems with the forms.
   ``I brought my father down here,'' Officer Joe Garcia Jr. said,
pointing to a man working with aliens at a table outside the center.
   Many INS workers wore T-shirts saying, ``I survived the IRACA
crush,'' referring to the Immigration Reform and Control Act.
   Others caught naps in a small lounge filled with sleeping bags.
   ``I'd say we are putting in 12- to 16-hour days,'' Yolanda
Arizola, an INS worker, said. ``I'm tired, but it's my job.''
</TEXT>
