<DOCNO> AP880505-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Thursday-ColdWar     05-05 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thursday-Cold War,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For 10 a.m. EDT Release, TIME set by source.</HEAD>
<HEAD>US-Soviet Groups Says The Two Powers Should Avoid Regional
Conflicts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and U.S. veterans of the Cold War are
proposing that the United States and the Soviet Union stop
intervening in the developing world as a step toward reducing their
military competition.
   The motto for the group might be ``No more Afghanistans, No more
Vietnams,'' said Arthur Macy Cox, a former CIA official who
organized the effort with Georgi Arbatov, head of Moscow's
USA-Canada Institute.
   In a position paper issued today, the Soviets and Americans call
for the ``progressive demilitarization of U.S.-Soviet
competition,'' including sharp cuts in strategic nuclear and
conventional arsenals, elimination of chemical weapons and
adherence to the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
   All those areas are under negotiation between the superpowers.
   The proposal breaks new ground by proposing a deal to end the
Cold War in the developing world, saying: ``We believe that
military intervention by the superpowers in regional conflicts has
reached a dangerous dead end and should be terminated by mutual
agreements.''
   Now is the right time for such a rapprochement, far better than
during detente, said one American in the group, Townsend Hoopes,
undersecretary of the Air Force under President Lyndon Johnson. The
Americans were all members of the American Committee on U.S.-Soviet
Relations and include former CIA director William Colby, former
undersecretary of state George Ball and former Sen. John Culver.
   Detente _ a period of thawing superpower relations under
Presidents Nixon, Ford and Carter _ produced a series of arms
control agreements and increased trade between the superpowers, but
floundered amid U.S. accusations that the Soviets were continuing
their military buildup and using force to install allied
governments in the developing world.
   ``We have a clear idea of why detente was ruined,'' Hoopes said
in an interview. The Soviets understood detente to exclude behavior
in the developing world, the opposite of the U.S. understanding.
   This time, says Hoopes, ``We are convinced of the sincerity on
the Russian side.''
   During detente, the United States withdrew from Vietnam.
   At the same time, the Soviet Union was supporting Marxist
insurgencies that took power in South Vietnam, Laos, Cambodia,
Angola, Nicaragua and Ethiopia. The Soviet invasion of Afghanistan
in 1979 and the military crackdown in Poland in 1981 nailed shut
the coffin of detente, in the view of many American analysts.
   President Reagan, on taking office in 1981, sought to reverse
Soviet advances in the developing world by supporting insurgent
movements, a policy that probably contributed to the Kremlin
decision to withdraw troops from Afghanistan, but has been less
successful elsewhere, notably Nicaragua.
   The Soviet-American group is proposing an understanding under
which the Soviets pull out of Afghanistan, their Cuban allies
withdraw troops from Ethiopia and Angola, and most Soviet bloc
military advisers in the developing world go home.
   In return, said Cox, ``the Reagan doctrine must end,'' and the
United States would stop supporting anti-Communist guerrilla
movements in Nicaragua, Angola and elsewhere.
   Additionally, the two sides would agree to a list of weapons
which they would not supply to developing nations.
   The main points of the proposal reflect suggestions that have
been made by Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorachev, Arbatov, and other
Soviets in the bilateral group: Valentin Falin, Fyodor Burlatsky,
Henry Trofimenko, Vitaly Zhurkin, and Andrei Kortunov.
   ``Every one of these people is a spokesman for Soviet policy.
Most of them are influential,'' said Cox.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TMIFuture     05-05 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TMI Future,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Staff Backs Plan To Mothball Contaminated Three Mile Island
Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government report says the contaminated
Three Mile Island nuclear reactor can be safely mothballed, but a
citizens' group fears that would effectively turn the site into a
high-level waste graveyard.
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission staff approved a plan by the
Pennsylvania plant's operator to place Three Mile Island Unit 2 in
storage for some 20 years while radiation decays inside.
   Significantly, the NRC staff's report, which was released upon
request Wednesday, said the plan was no better or worse than an
alternative under which further cleanup work would be performed
before the unit was mothballed.
   That is the approach favored by Three Mile Island Alert, a
citizens' group based near the plant in the middle of the
Susquehanna River, near Harrisburg.
   Eric Epstein of TMIA criticized the NRC on Wednesday for being
``willing to accept a high-level waste site on an island in the
middle of a river indefinitely.'' He said the plan enables GPU
Nuclear, the plant operator, ``to walk away from their commitment
to completely decontaminate and decommission the plant.''
   The idea, GPU said, was to place the plant in ``safe, stable and
secure'' condition while radiation was allowed to decay naturally
and new technologies were developed to permit easier access to the
insides of reactor.
   After studying the plan, the NRC staff concluded it could be
implemented ``without significant environmental harm'' and that
``no alternative was found to be clearly preferable from an
environmental impact perspective.''
   The NRC staff is soliciting comments from the public before
making its conclusions final.
   Unit 2 was disabled in the nation's worst commercial nuclear
accident on March 31, 1979. The reactor was allowed to lose vital
cooling water that normally covers it. Uncovered, material in the
radioactive core melted partially.
   The subsequent $1 billion cleanup, expected to completed in
mid-1989, has focused on water decontamination, waste shipment and
removal of fuel from the damaged core.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0429EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Summit     05-05 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Summit,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Displays Pre-Summit Conciliatory Tone Toward Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is softening his sharply
anti-Soviet rhetoric as the Moscow summit nears, a meeting he
contends shouldn't have ``a winner or a loser.''
   Reagan, in a speech Wednesday in Chicago, offered a startling
amount of praise for Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev and the human
rights reforms he's begun.
   The president's remarks came in sharp contrast to a speech he
gave April 21, in which he lambasted the Soviet role in Afghanistan
and suggested they wouldn't keep their pledge to withdraw from
their neighboring country.
   In his address to the National Strategy Forum, a group concerned
with foreign policy and national strategy issues, Reagan lauded
Gorbachev for loosening restrictions on religion, freedom of
speech, press and emigration.
   ``We applaud the changes that have taken place and encourage the
Soviets to go farther,'' Reagan said. ``We recognize that changes
occur slowly but that is better than no change at all.''
   Reagan's speech was the next-to-last in a series of addresses
designed to highlight the issues he intends to raise at the summit
in Moscow with Gorbachev, set for May 29-June 2.
   ``In recent months, the Soviet Union has shown a willingness to
respect at least some human rights. It is my belief that there is
hope for further change, hope that in the days ahead the Soviets
will grant further recognition to the fundamental civil and
political rights of all,'' Reagan said.
   He took note of a development he termed ``of tremendous
significance'' in recent months, that the Soviets themselves are
beginning to talk and print stories about economic shortages in
their country.
   The president also said some 300 political and religious
prisoners had been released from labor camps over the last three
years, and that the incarceration of dissidents in mental hospitals
and prisons has slowed, and in some cases, stopped.
   While Reagan said much religious activity remains repressed in
the Soviet Union, but controls have been relaxed.
   He added that he is ``heartened'' by the progress made in the
increased numbers allowed to emigrate, as well as the loosening of
controls on family visits.
   The president acknowledged that the United States has its own
problems with homelessness, racial discrimination and unemployment.
Moscow has used the problems in an attempt to counter U.S.
criticisms of Soviet human rights policies. In a bow to Soviet
concerns, Reagan said their critique ``deserves a full response.''
   In a brief question and answer session with the audience, Reagan
said he was willing to give Gorbachev ``the benefit of the doubt,
up to a point'' _ that the Soviet leader sincerely wants to achieve
the program of economic and social reforms known as ``glasnost.''
   The president said he believes Gorbachev is pursuing the reforms
because of economic problems in the Soviet Union.
   Reagan said he hoped he could offer Gorbachev some suggestions
at the summit on how he could move ahead with glasnost.
   ``That, I think, is preferable to staging a kind of contest with
him so that someone looks like a winner or loser,'' Reagan said.
   White House Communications Director Tom Griscom denied Reagan's
remarks were designed to mollify Gorbachev, who took issue with
Reagan's anti-Soviet attacks during a recent meeting with Secretary
of State George Shultz.
   Griscom argued that Reagan's approach to the Soviets was
consistent, but that his speeches varied because he addressed
different topics.
   The president also played down expectations for the Moscow
meeting, saying he didn't expect to sign a new treaty on long-range
strategic missiles. He added that both he and Gorbachev were
``hopeful'' their pact banning medium-range weapons could be ready
for signing, but noted the U.S. Senate hasn't moved rapidly to
approve the pact.
   Reagan said he continued to look for additional changes in the
Soviet Union, but was realistic, given Soviet history.
   He said the West has observed progress before, only to see it
wither away.
   That, Reagan said, was the reason U.S. dealings with the Soviets
must be based on ``candor and realism.''
   ``Just as previous hopeful moments in Soviet history ended all
too soon, so, too, glasnost, _ today's new candor _ will succeed if
the Soviets take steps to make it permanent, to institutionalize
it,'' Reagan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
