<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RabbitKidnapped     05-05 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rabbit Kidnapped,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-agers Kidnap 6-year-old's Rabbit, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENILWORTH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tricks may be for kids, but this
kidnapping case got the police hopping.
   It started when 6-year-old Michelle Rizzo discovered her pet
rabbit, Smokey, was missing Sunday morning and a ransom note was
left in the animal's place, police said.
   ``If you ever want to see your stupid rabbit alive again, leave
$50 in an envelope under the railroad crossing sign behind your
house,'' said the note, fashioned from newspaper clippings pasted
to a piece of paper.
   Michelle's parents, Joseph and Vera Rizzo, called Police Chief
Charles David, who is their neighbor, and detectives worked the
rabbit-napping case on their day off.
   Detective William Dowd photocopied $50 worth of currency and
placed it in an envelope. He told Michelle, her 8-year-old brother,
Joseph, and 10-year-old sister, Antoinette, to follow the
rabbit-napper's instructions and deliver the envelope to a
specified rock under the sign at 5 p.m. Sunday.
   About 40 minutes later, police arrested two boys, ages 14 and
15, after one of them grabbed the envelope. A third boy confessed
after questioning from his mother.
   Police found Smokey in a cardboard box in a shed behind one of
the culprits' homes.
   Written on the box were the words: ``Handle with care. Rabbit
inside. Thank you for the money.''
   The three boys were charged with theft of the rabbit and
released into the custody of their parents.
</TEXT>
