<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RevolvingDoor     05-05 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Revolving Door,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Subcommittee Examines Broadened Ethics Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House chairman says will move swiftly to
fashion a plan to stop former members of Congress and top executive
branch officials from becoming instant lobbyists right after they
leave government.
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., says he plans follow the Senate's
footsteps and begin moving ``revolving door'' legislation ``in a
very short time'' in his Judiciary government relations
subcommittee.
   ``There is broad agreement in the Congress that we should be
moving on this,'' Frank said Wednesday at a subcommittee hearing
prompted by Senate passage last month of an ethics bill to put
Congress for the first time under post-employment lobbying
restrictions.
   During Senate debate, supporters referred to the cases of Lyn
Nofziger and Michael Deaver, who ran into legal problems in
connection with high-priced lobbying after they left top White
House posts.
   Witnesses gave Frank's subcommittee mixed reviews about the
Senate bill, with John Keeney, acting head of the Justice
Department's criminal division, saying the Reagan administration
favored some parts of it and opposed others.
   Keeney said the Senate plan is too broad because it would simply
ban much for-pay lobbying by former lawmakers and senior political
appointees for a year after they leave their jobs.
   Instead, Keeney said, prohibitions against cashing in on inside
knowledge and connections should have a ``nexus'' between the
lobbying and the official's former position or responsibilities.
   A much-criticized 10-year-old ethics law does not cover Congress
_ which Keeney says the administration feels should be covered _
and puts a year's ban on top-drawer executive branch officials
lobbying their former agencies.
   Critics say the law has been eroded by Office of Government
Ethics rulings that compartmentalize agencies, banning a former
official's contacts with his or her previous section but leaving
them free to lobby elsewhere in the agency.
   The Senate bill would prohibit former high officials from
lobbying anywhere in the executive branch and trying to influence
members of Congress for a year. Former lawmakers could not lobby
Congress or top White House aides and Cabinet secretaries for a
year.
   ``If there ever was a bill whose time has come, this is it,''
said Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr. of Florida, the subcommittee's ranking
Republican. He said Congress has been ``extremely hypocritical'' to
exempt itself from the ethics law.
   ``We have a real problem,'' said Rep. Howard Wolpe, D-Mich.
``When Richard Nixon can go on `Meet the Press' and with a straight
face comment on the Washington sleaze factor, then we have a
problem.''
   Rep. Marcy Kaptur, D-Ohio, said that while the Deaver and
Nofziger cases have captured public attention, problems exist
elsewhere, such as the Office of U.S. Trade Representative, where
15 officials departed in 1986 to become lobbyists or foreign agents.
   ``Their institutional memory and knowledge of U.S. negotiating
strategies gives foreign interests a clear bargaining advantage,''
Kaptur testified.
   Ann McBride, senior vice president of Common Cause, the
self-described citizens' lobby, urged approval of a strong
``revolving door'' bill. But Morton Halperin of the American Civil
Liberties Union said there is no proven need to include former
members of Congress and that doing so would be ``bad policy'' and
possibly unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
