<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSPamphlet-Glance     05-05 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Pamphlet-Glance,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS Pamphlet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some details, at a glance, of the
Department of Health and Human Services project to mail a new
pamphlet, ``Understanding AIDS,'' to each household in America.
   FORMAT _ Eight pages in blue-and-white layout that includes
photographs and section headers and subheads for readability.
Targeted at seventh-grade reading level. Produced under government
contract by Ogilvy & Mather, a nationally known advertising and
public relations company.
   SCOPE _ 110 million copies in English and 4 million in Spanish;
107 million English-language versions mailed to every household
address on file with the U.S. Postal Service in the 50 states,
District of Columbia and Virgin Islands. Spanish versions to be
distributed to residents of Puerto Rico. U.S. distribution of
Spanish version planned through community organizations in
Spanish-speaking communities.
   TIMING _ First copies to appear in mailboxes May 26, with bulk
delivered within next two weeks and all by June 30.
   PUBLICITY _ Delivery preceded by three-week radio, television
and poster campaign to urge residents to be watching for pamphlet
in mail.
   PRECEDENT _ First national household mailing of health message
in U.S. history.
   COST _ $17 million, including $4 million for printing and rest
for third-class bulk postage. Average cost per household: 16 cents.
To come from current AIDS education and prevention appropriation to
federal Centers for Disease Control, headquartered in Atlanta.
   PRINTING _ Contract awarded to Gulf Printing Co. of Houston,
Texas, a subsidiary of Southwestern Bell Corp., on March 21 by
Government Printing Office. Has required 24-hour-a-day press runs,
six or seven days a week for more than a month. Being stored in
leased, football-field size warehouse pending initial post office
pickup May 9.
</TEXT>
