<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirlineScorecard     05-05 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airline Scorecard,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sun Belt Carriers Improve on-Time Records</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Good weather appeared to help three regional
airlines in the Sun Belt post the best on-time records for the
second straight month, according to the Transportation Department.
   The monthly statistics released Wednesday showed Pacific
Southwest Airlines, America West and Southwest Airlines with the
fewest number of delayed arrivals during March.
   Overall the 14 airlines reporting statistics to the
Transportation Department had 78.8 percent of their flights arrive
within 15 minutes of schedule, considered on time by the
government, during March.
   That was a slight improvement over the average 74.7 percent
on-time arrival rate in February.
   The department, in its monthly consumer scorecard on air travel,
said 92.3 percent of Pacific Southwest's flights arrived on time in
March. America West had an arrival rate of 89.9 percent and
Southwest 86.3 percent.
   At the other end of the scale were Northwest Airlines, Trans
World Airlines and Continental Airlines, all of which the
department said were on time 75 percent of the time or less. The
same three were also at the bottom in February.
   The number of reports of mishandled baggage filed with airlines
declined during March, from an average of 8.75 reports for every
1,000 passengers flown in February to 7.48 percent in March.
   Meanwhile, complaints to the Transportation Department's
consumer affairs office about air travel fell significantly from
2,584 in March to 2,033 in April.
   The department released the on-time arrival statistics for March
at the same time as the consumer complaint statistics, although
they cover a different month.
   The department received the most complaints about Continental
and Eastern airlines in March. Both have been at the top of the
complaint list since the beginning of the year.
   The department said it received 14.61 complaints about
Continental for every 100,000 passengers flown last month. For
Eastern, the department got 12.07 complaints per 100,000 passengers.
   Houston Intercontinental Airport had the worst arrival record of
the 27 airports monitored by the government, with 64.5 percent of
the flights arriving within 15 minutes of schedule. Denver's
Stapleton International Airport was second-worst with a 66.6
percent on-time record.
   The best arrival record was recorded at Phoenix, Ariz., which
had an on-time arrival rate of 85.2 percent. Next was Las Vegas,
Nev., with an on-time rate of 85 percent.
   In March, 12 flights _ six belonging to Continental, two
belonging to America West, two to Delta and one each to United and
Eastern _ were late at least 90 percent of the time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
