<DOCNO> AP880505-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Everest-Climb     05-05 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Everest-Climb,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Teams Reach Top Of Mount Everest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six men met at the peak of Mount Everest
on Thursday after scaling the world's highest mountain for the
first time simultaneously from two different directions, the Nepal
Mountaineering Association announced.
   It said China's Ringen Puncog, 45, Da Cering, 38, and Ang Phurba
Sherpa, 27, of Nepal, reached the top of the 29,028-foot mountain
at 9:25 a.m. (11:40 p.m. EDT Wednesday). They reached the summit
more than four hours after leaving Camp Five located at 27,880 feet
on the south side in Nepal.
   They met Japan's Noboru Yamada, 38, Nepal's Ang Lhakpa Sherpa,
27, and China's Cering Doji, 30, who scaled the mountain from the
northern side in Tibet, the association said.
   The group later plan a live television broadcast from the peak
of the mountain.
   The two teams are part of an expedition involving more than 200
people from Japan, Nepal and China, who started climbing last month
to celebrate the 35th anniversary of the first Everest conquest in
1953 by New Zealander Sir Edmund Hillary and Sherpa guide Tenzing
Norgay.
   The rest of the members are scattered in various camps, while
some are in China and Nepal.
</TEXT>
