<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Syria     05-05 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Syria,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Businessman Demands Loan Repayment From Jackson Campaign;
Threataens To Sue</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Language in 2nd graf may be offensive to some readers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DROSCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A North Carolina businessman who made a
$25,000 loan to Jesse Jackson to help pay for a trip to Syria in
1984 says he's considering taking the Democratic presidential
candidate's campaign to court if he's not repaid.
   Marion ``Rex'' Harris, a businessman from Fayetteville, N.C.,
said Wednesday he has not been reimbursed despite repeated
requests. He said he was ``mad as hell about it.''
   ``If I loan you five cents I expect to be paid back _ I'm a
businessman,'' said Harris, a 1984 North Carolina coordinator for
the Jackson campaign. ``I would take my sister to court (if she
owed me money),''
   In the course of the trip to Syria, Jackson scored a diplomatic
coup by securing the release of Navy flyer Robert Goodman, who was
captured by the Syrians after being shot down over Lebanon.
   Harris said he mentioned the loan to Jackson in 1985 at a
convention in Memphis, Tenn.
   ``He was highly upset that I was upset (and hadn't been paid),''
said Harris. ``I know he has instructed them (his campaign) many
times to pay me. I have a beef with his staff, not Jesse.''
   Harris said he was asked by Jackson associates to make the loan
to the Concerned Citizens Humanitarian Fund Inc., based in
Savannah, Ga. Records in Georgia show the fund was incorporated on
Jan. 3, 1984, the day Goodman was released.
   Jackson told the The Associated Press in a recent interview that
his campaign attorney, Edward Coaxum, created a special
humanitarian fund in 1984 to pay for the candidate's two foreign
trips to Latin America during the campaign.
   Little is known about the humanitarian fund, incorporated as a
nonprofit organization. The fund has never filed an annual report
listing its officers or any details about how much money it has
raised and spent, said Carolyn Harris of the Georgia secretary of
state's office.
   Harris said he was asked to lend the money to the fund by
Benjamin Polote, who owns a construction company in Savannah, and
helped raise money for Jackson's 1984 campaign.
   The Chicago Tribune reported Tuesday that bank records show the
humanitarian fund's account paid out $17,876 of Harris' $25,000
loan to a travel agency that handled the Syrian trip, but that it
was not clear what happened to the rest of the money.
   ``I gave them a deadline (to pay me back),'' said Harris, but
refused to say if the deadline had passed. ``They are going to pay
me. I demand payment.''
</TEXT>
