<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0510EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RussianArt     05-05 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Russian Art,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Variety Of Russian Art Being Exhibited By Washington Museums</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8,9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Glasnost is giving Americans a rare glimpse at
Russian and Soviet art ranging from religious icons to the
avant-garde of the early 20th century and works of ``official''
contemporaries.
   The Corcoran Gallery today opens a show of three contemporary
Soviet artists, the National Museum of American history next Friday
starts an exhibit of Russian religious icons, and in July the
Hirshhorn Museum is showing 90 important but seldom seen canvases
by Russian avant-garde painters.
   ``It's kind of the `glasnost' of the day around here,'' said
Sidney Lawrence, spokesman the Hirshhorn gallery, site of the most
important of the three shows.
   The exhibit is the ``first to come out of the Soviet Union made
up exclusively of paintings from this period that will show in the
West,'' Hirshhorn director James T. Demetrion said in statement.
   Many of the paintings, by such greats as Marc Chagall, Vasily
Kandinsky and Kasimir Malevich, were locked away for decades in the
basements of Leningrad and Moscow museums while Soviet authorities
enforced the official style known as ``Socialist realism.''
   For many Americans, this may the first and only glimpse of
paintings that art historians describe as among the most important
in the early 20th century.
   Malevich is particularly crucial because he is credited with
painting the first abstract canvases, in 1910-11, according to art
historians.
   The Hirshhorn exhibit runs from July 12 to September 25.
   The show at the Corcoran marks another first, part of a
pioneering official exchange that sent canvases by the Wyeth family
to the Soviet Union.
   In return, the Soviets sent works by Boris Ugarov, Tair Salakhov
and Dmitri Bisti, three ``official'' artists whose work illustrates
movement away from the sometimes stifling motifs of Socialist
Realism, such as tractors and smiling peasants and workers.
   The work of Ugarov, a native of Leningrad and winner of the
State Prize of the USSR in 1985, is reminiscent of such French
post-Impressionsts as Degas and Cezanne.
   Salakhov, born in Azerbaijan, has traveled abroad and his
canvases include such familiar images as the Empire State Building
in New York.
   Bisti, another State Prize winner, is a book illustrator who
appears to draw more heavily on purely Russian themes.
   Distancing himself from the abstract work that will be featured
at the Hirshhorn, Bisti told a news conference Wednesday that
``realism is the Russian tradition. Other styles are a departure
from the mainstream.''
   Of the three Washington exhibits, that at the American history
museum has the most traditional Russian art, 50 metallic icons from
the 17th to the late 19th century.
   The overall collection of 350 icons was sold to the Smithsonian
in 1892 by George Kunz, a Tiffany & Co. buyer who picked them up in
the Russian city of Nizhni-Novgorod, now known as Gorky.
   Although sizable collections of wooden icons exist in the West
and Soviet Union, the Smithsonian trove of metallic icons is
believed to be the largest of its kind in the West, and possibly
the most thoroughly studied in the world, said curator Richard
Ahlorn.
   Specialists began to restore and study the collection in the
early 1980s, and conceived the idea of holding an exhibition to
coincide with the 1,000-year anniversary of Christianity in Russia
which is being held in the Soviet Union this June.
   The icons, made of a copper alloy, where used in churches, in
homes and were carried by members of the Russian Orthodox faith
from about the 9th century, when Greek Orthodox missionaries
introduced Christianity into Russia, said Ahlorn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
