<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0522EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Trade     05-05 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Does Quick Rewrite of Trade Bill, Drops Alaska Oil Curbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans are grumbling that a quick rewrite
by House Democrats of the omnibus trade bill aims at winning enough
Senate votes to override a veto while retaining a plant-closing
provision opposed by President Reagan.
   The House voted 253-159 Wednesday to remove curbs on exports of
Alaskan oil from the 1,000-page bill, which won final passage last
week. The move was contained in a resolution authorizing technical
changes in the bill.
   The resolution would simply authorize an official known as the
enrolling clerk to erase the oil provisions while he is dotting the
i's and crossing the t's in the mammoth piece of legislation.
   Republicans complained that deleting curbs on Alaska oil exports
after the bill was passed violated House rules and was designed to
gain the votes of Alaska's two Senators. Democratic leaders,
however, said their plan was fashioned as a compromise gesture to
Reagan.
   ``What we need here is a good, old-fashioned compromise,'' Rep.
David Bonior, D-Mich., said Wednesday.
   But House Republicans were scornful.
   ``You've come the wrong half and you've done it the wrong way,''
Rep. William Frenzel, R-Minn., said. ``When it's over it's over.''
   ``We have here a technical procedure,'' said Minority Leader
Robert H. Michel, R-Ill., ``with which the majority will attempt to
surgically extract something from a piece of legislation that has
been officially, formally and finally adopted by both houses of the
Congress and should now by all rights be on the president's desk
for signature.''
   Reagan has been expressing concern for weeks over a provision of
the trade bill that would require companies with more than 100
employees to provide 60-day notice of plant closings and
large-scale layoffs.
   House Democrats, citing the hardship of surprise plant closings
on employees and their families, said they will not drop that
provision.
   ``Maybe they should consult their astrologer to find out when
they are going to be out of work,'' Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass.,
told the House.
   More recently, Reagan also has criticized the Alaska oil
provisions.
   One of those provisions would limit exports of petroleum
products from new refineries in Alaska to 70,000 barrels a day and
50 percent of output. The other would clear the way for sending
50,000 barrels of crude a day to Canada. But first the oil would
have to be transported in a U.S. vessel to a port in the lower 48
states before turning around and going north of the border.
   Both provisions are favorites of politically influential
maritime unions.
   Democratic leaders had been hoping to persuade Alaska's
Republican senators, Ted Stevens and Frank Murkowski, to vote in
favor of the trade bill. When the leaders were unable to strip out
the oil export curbs, the two Alaskans opposed the measure when the
Senate passed it 63-36 last week.
   Stevens later said he could not guarantee that he would support
the trade bill even if the Alaska provision had been dropped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0058 </DOCNO>
