<2ND_LINE>PM-Jet Landing,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jet With Jesse Jackson's Wife and Son Makes Unscheduled Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Midway Airline DC-9 made an emergency
landing here, but authorities reported no injuries among the 76
people aboard, including the wife and son of Democratic
presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson.
   The plane landed safely at Greater Pittsburgh International
Airport on Wednesday evening during as flight for Chicago.
   Flight 369, carrying 69 passengers and five crewmembers, left
Washington, D.C., about 6:30 p.m., said Sandy Allen, a Midway
spokeswoman.
   About 1{ hours into the flight, the pilot saw a light warning
that an engine oil filter was clogged, Ms. Allen said.
   The jet made the unscheduled landing after receiving permission
from the airport.
   Passengers were reboarded on another Midway flight for Chicago,
Ms. Allen said.
   Jackson said his wife, Jackie, son Jonathan and the Rev. Willie
Barrow, president of the civil rights group Operation PUSH, were on
the flight. He said they had been in Washington for the celebration
of Jackson's victory in Tuesday's presidential primary in the
District of Columbia.
   Jackson, who was in Kearney, Neb., said he reached his wife by
telephone in Chicago late Wednesday.
   ``Whenever a family has a brush with death its always
traumatizing,'' Jackson said. ``But it should make us more sincere
in our prayer life because we face danger so much.''
</TEXT>
