<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FAA-Inspections     05-05 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FAA-Inspections,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Chief Calls Older 737s Safe But Says Caution Needed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 older Boeing 737s belonging to
U.S. airlines are under special scrutiny for possible cracking and
corrosion as a result of last week's terror aboard an Aloha
Airlines jet in which the cabin tore open during flight.
   The Federal Aviation Administration announced Wednesday that all
Boeing 737s with more than 30,000 landings are to be visually
inspected for cracks and corrosion in the upper part of the
fuselage. Those with at least 50,000 landings must undergo special
tests with high-frequency electronic equipment, the agency said.
   The wider inspection was ordered in part because ``several
additional reports of corrosion, delamination and cracks'' were
discovered in a number of aircraft since the Aloha accident a week
ago, the FAA said.
   The agency did not say what airlines were involved in the
discovery of additional cracks and corrosion. The inspections apply
to the top section of the plane from just behind the cockpit to the
tail section.
   The FAA reiterated a warning issued in a directive last November
that such cracks if close together and allowed to corrode ``could
result in a structural failure of the fuselage'' if not corrected.
   Investigators believe such a sequence of events likely occurred
aboard the Aloha jet last Thursday when a 20-foot secton of the
cabin wall and ceiling ripped away 24,000 feet. A flight attendant
was swept to her death and 61 people were injured before the plane
landed in Hawaii.
   The 19-year-old plane was one of the oldest and most heavily
used Boeing 737s manufactured, with a history of nearly 89,000
landings.
   FAA Administrator Allan McArtor nevertheless said the older
Boeing 737s subject to the increased inspections are ``just as safe
as newer models.'' He said the aircraft warranted closer scrutiny
because in light of the Aloha accident ``it is time for an
abundance of caution''
   David Jimenez, a spokesman for the Boeing Co., said in Seattle
that there are 212 Boeing 737s operated by 19 U.S. airlines in
domestic service that would be subject to the FAA inspections
announced Wednesday.
   Another 161 Boeing 737s with more than 30,000 landings are owned
by foreign airlines and fly outside the United States, he said.
While these planes may be inspected they are not directly subject
to the FAA order.
   The FAA is concerned about the aircraft because the Boeing 737
is a short-haul plane that normally accumulates a high number of
takeoffs, cabin pressurizations, depressurizations and landings.
This cycle puts stress on the plane's fuselage and can after time
cause an increased number of cracks in the outer metal skin.
   In addition, the older Boeing 737s also used a so-called ``cold
bonding'' process to hold sections of the metal skin in place.
``The FAA has reason to believe that possible delamination of the
bond requires mandatory inspections,'' said McArtor.
   According to Jimenez, all of the Boeing 737s on which the cold
bonding process was used _ the first 291 planes built _ have more
than 30,000 landings and are already subject to the FAA's broader
inspection order.
   Last week the FAA ordered many of the older Boeing 737s to fly
no higher than 23,000 feet until they are inspected. But that
directive applied to only 66 planes that had 55,000 or more
landings. The altitude restrictions remain in effect for the planes
covered by the new requirements, officials said.
   The new order expands the visual inspections and requires those
with 50,000 landings to automatically undergo so-called ``eddy
current'' inspections using high-frequency electronic devices.
   McArtor said he does not think the inspection requirements will
disrupt air travel because airlines will have between 250 and 500
landings, depending on type of inspection, to comply. The airlines
must report to the FAA within 48 hours on the results of any
inspections.
   The Boeing 737 is widely used for short-haul flights, with more
than 1,500 of them in service around the world. The older 737-100
and -200 series aircraft, on which the concern about cracking and
corrosion has centered, total 1,139 worldwide, although many of
them have had fewer than 30,000 landings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
