<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AlienProfiles     05-05 0906</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alien Profiles,0938</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Amnesty Rush, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Amnesty Applicants: Different Stories, Same Goal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leocadia Hicks, a volunteer with the
Immigration and Naturalization Service's amnesty program,
understood the fears and suspicions of illegal aliens waiting to be
processed.
   Sixteen years ago, she illegally entered the United States at El
Paso, Texas, from her home of Ciudad Juarez, Mexico.
   For the past year, Mrs. Hicks worked as a volunteer at the INS
legalization office here. She has assisted hundreds of illegals who
were eligible to apply for amnesty and eventual permanent residency.
   Mrs. Hicks, 39, and the oldest in a family of 14 children, grew
up in Juarez. There, while working in a curio shop, she met T.L.
Hicks, a soldier stationed at the U.S. Army's Fort Bliss base at El
Paso.
   Because of her illegal status, she kept a low profile for almost
a year after their marriage. She finally obtained legal residency
status on April 9, 1973.
   ``I'll never forget that day,'' she said. ``No one ever does.''
   Mrs. Hicks and her husband helped many of the hundreds of aliens
Wednesday applying for amnesty here on the final day of the program
that expired at midnight.
   Mrs. Hicks said she initially was leery of the program and
``checked it out'' thoroughly before volunteering to help last May.
   ``You go through so many bad experiences, but I have never seen
so much caring as I have here,'' she said. ``It's like a dream and
it's beautiful to see people regain their respect and dignity.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HIALEAH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wendy Davis had no trouble sneaking into
the country, but she says she's been unable to sleep well in her
six years as an illegal immigrant.
   ``I went right through the border. They just asked if we had
fruits,'' said Mrs. Davis, one of the thousands of aliens who
jammed Immigration and Naturalization Service offices in South
Florida on Wednesday.
   But as an illegal alien, ``I didn't have a life of my own,
control of my destiny,'' said Mrs. Davis, 19, a Belize native who
married Judd Davis of Chicago on July 4. The newlyweds moved
recently to Miami Beach.
   ``I had insomnia. I worried at night that someone could come and
take me away. When my papers come, I'm going to sleep at night,''
she said.
   Lines were long at the INS office here, but most of the waiting
people were smiling.
   ``They say this place is bad, but it's the best there is,'' Mrs.
Davis said, referring to U.S. citizens who complain about their
government.
   A sister and two brothers in Belize ``keep writing, asking me
when I'm going to visit. I wanted to go but I couldn't. I'd say I
was going soon as I get my papers,'' she said, beaming at the
prospect of receiving a work permit next week and residency status
this summer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just hours before the midnight deadline
for illegal aliens to apply for amnesty under a one-year federal
program, the Immigration and Naturalization Service legalization
office here was quiet.
   ``The biggest problem tonight may be staying awake,'' said Ana
Pardo, who directs the office set up to handle applicants from
North Carolina and South Carolina.
   About 210 people _ half of them farm workers who have until Nov.
30 to apply for amnesty _ were processed Wednesday, Ms. Pardo said.
   ``The numbers are lower than they were yesterday, surprisingly
enough,'' she said Wednesday. ``I heard the Houston office had
13,000 people today.''
   As she spoke, only one person waited to submit his application
and $180 fee. Kong Hung moved to Hickory from Taiwan nearly 20
years ago.
   ``He likes to do things at the last minute,'' said his wife,
Karla, as she chased their twin 2-year-old sons, Christopher and
Albert. Their older brother Jim, 5, slept on a chair in the
near-empty waiting room.
   The Charlotte office has handled about 9,200 cases so far this
year, said Ms. Pardo. That's far below the 50,000 projected by INS
officials when the program began.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Luis Aguilar has been deported five times
since coming to the United States nine years ago, but he kept
coming back by swimming the Rio Grande.
   ``I've been so long here, I just make myself at home,'' Aguilar
said Wednesday while waiting to apply for amnesty at the
Immigration and Naturalization Service office. ``I've been here
since 1979. I don't even know who the president of Mexico is.''
   Aguilar, 26, said he wasn't worried whether he would receive
amnesty and had no fear of being deported again.
   ``If they send me back to Mexico, I figure I can't stay there,''
he said. ``I've spent almost half my life here. The last time I was
there, I stayed three days and came back. I figure I belong here.''
   Aguilar said he works on a ranch in Konawa, where he earns about
$200 a week. He met his wife, Rosie, seven years ago, and she
persuaded him to apply for amnesty.
   ``He would get deported, but he always knew where to find me,''
Mrs. Aguilar said. ``One time he came right back three days after
he was deported.''
   They were married in 1983, and A.J. Irwin, the chief
legalization officer at the Oklahoma City INS office, said he was
surprised Aguilar didn't apply for citizenship since his wife, a
Seminole Indian, is a U.S. citizen.
</TEXT>
