<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NebraskaSenate     05-05 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nebraska Senate,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Election Issues Are Scarce, But Electioneering Is Questioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED HOWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fierce challenge by Rep. Hal Daub has
Sen. David Karnes fighting for survival in next week's Republican
primary, and the victor has to face a popular Democratic
ex-governor in the main event.
   Democratic state chairman Tom Monaghan says he hopes the GOP
rivals wake up after the voting ``bloodied and broke.''
   Whoever wins Tuesday's GOP showdown will have to face former
Gov. Bob Kerrey, 44, who's expected to easily beat his Democratic
primary opponent, Ken Michaelis, a 45-year-old disbarred lawyer
from West Point, Neb.
   The GOP race is a dead heat, according to an Omaha World-Herald
poll taken last week. Karnes was backed by 41 percent, Daub by 40
percent and 19 percent said they were undecided. The margin of
error was 4 percentage points.
   The same poll found Kerrey leading either Daub or Karnes by more
than 20 percentage points.
   Karnes, 39, is in the unusual position of being an incumbent
facing a tough bid for nomination. He was appointed by Republican
Gov. Kay Orr in March 1987 to fill the unexpired term of the late
Sen. Ed Zorinsky, a Democrat.
   In announcing his appointment, Mrs. Orr said Karnes was the best
man for the job. Critics said Mrs. Orr chose Karnes because he
wouldn't threaten her status in the state party. She is a personal
friend of President Reagan and co-chair of the GOP National
Platform Committee.
   Karnes was a virtual unknown, but Daub was among the GOP
regulars who sought the seat. Karnes had headed Mrs. Orr's
successful 1986 gubernatorial effort in Omaha-dominated Douglas
County, a traditional Democratic stronghold.
   Daub, 47, a four-term congressman from the Omaha-dominated 2nd
District, took the offensive several weeks ago.
   At first, the opponents bickered about voting records. Each
accused the other of voting directly or indirectly for tax
increases. Each effectively said the other was lying without using
the word liar.
   Daub has more recently charged that Karnes wouldn't fight for
water projects in Nebraska.
   Karnes says the tape recording of his statement during a debate
made clear that he supported already planned projects, but that
water officials ``recognize that in the future we will not be able
to start any new projects.''
   Daub responded with a TV commercial using Karnes' statement,
contrasting it with a picture of cattle in a dry pasture and an
announcer saying: ``Frightening as it it may seem, a vote for Dave
Karnes is a vote to cut off your own water.''
   Those would be fighting words in the huge 3rd Congressional
District where cattle and crops are what counts and water is the
equivalent of liquid gold to many.
   Daub clearly annoyed seven-term Republican Rep. Virginia Smith,
who represents the 3rd District, when he claimed credit for shaking
loose federal money for a pending water project.
   While saying she wasn't endorsing Karnes, Mrs. Smith promptly
announced that it was she and Karnes _ not Daub _ who had done the
work on the project then made a campaign appearance with the
senator.
   Even implied support from Mrs. Smith is important because her
popularity in the mostly Republican district, which includes 62 of
the state's 93 counties. She usually wins it with pluralities of
tens of thousands of votes.
</TEXT>
