<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Steadfastly Holds Delegates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAHOMET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Paul Simon says he is virtually
certain Michael Dukakis will win the Democratic presidential
nomination but refuses to release his delegates ``in the unlikely
event that Michael Dukakis stubs his toe between now and the
convention.''
   The Illinois senator, who put his presidential campaign on hold
a month ago, said he would not surrender about 184 delegates
committed to his campaign despite pressure to do so by supporters
of Jesse Jackson.
   Chicago Mayor Eugene Sawyer and some black lawmakers have urged
Simon to officially drop out of the presidential race. Jackson, who
finished second to Simon in the Illinois primary, would then
inherit the bulk of the state's delegates.
   ``I'm going to hold out until the California and New Jersey
primaries on June 7 and see whether I can still have an influence
on the nomination,'' Simon said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ohio Dems Remain Neutral After Dukakis Primary Win</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis' landslide victory in
Ohio's Democratic presidential primary did not alter the neutral
stance of Gov. Richard Celeste or the state Democratic party,
officials said.
   ``Jesse Jackson wants it to continue, and that's OK with me. It
keeps the interest up, and that's good for the party,'' Ohio
Democratic Chairman James Ruvolo said Wednesday.
   Celeste said essentially the same through an aide, Heidi
Findley, who added told a reporter the governor ``wants to take a
united party to the convention.''
   On Tuesday night, after Dukakis had defeated the Rev. Jesse
Jackson with 63 percent of the vote to Jackson's 28 percent,
Celeste said he did not think the question of an endorsement is
important at this point.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kassebaum Says Job Doesn't Interest Her</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Nancy Kassebaum says she is not
interested in becoming vice president and doubts she would offer
the right balance to a Republican ticket headed by George Bush.
   ``I'm not interested,'' the Kansas Republican said in an
interview with KTKA-TV on Wednesday.
   ``I think anybody who is a politician and a woman would be
interested, but I have always enjoyed the legislative part of the
job,'' she said in the interview that will be aired Saturday. ``I
don't anticipate I will be offered the job and, in all honesty, I
don't think I'm the right balance for George Bush.''
   Mrs. Kassebaum toured California last weekend campaigning for
the re-election of Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., and was greeted with
Bush-Kassebaum stickers.
   But she told an interviewer, ``There are 50 or so people you see
listed, and there is a bumper sticker in Washington somewhere that
says, `Honk if George Bush has asked you to be vice president.''
</TEXT>
