<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Amnesty-Glance     05-05 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-Glance,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty Program At-a-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Amnesty Rush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of the status of the amnesty program for
undocumented aliens:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEADLINE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The amnesty application period, which began May 5, 1987, ended
at midnight Wednesday.
   The deadline does not apply to aliens applying for legal status
under the Seasonal Agricultural Worker provision of the immigration
reform act. They have until Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ELIGIBILITY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Illegal aliens who have lived in the United States since before
Jan. 1, 1982, were eligible.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PROCEDURES FOR APPLICATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Applicants had to submit a four-page application and provide
documentation such as utility bills, pay stubs, rent receipts or
school records to prove eligibility. Those who filed were allowed
to request up to 60 days for submitting required documents.
   Physical examinations, photographs and fingerprints also were
required.
   If a computer search turns up no history of illegal behavior,
the applicant receives his temporary residency card. He must later
apply for permanent legal residency. He can ultimately apply for
citizenship.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FEES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Application cost $185 a person and $50 per child with a limit of
$420 per family.
   In addition, applicants were urged to get help filling out their
applications. Cost varies with lawyers and volunteer organizations.
   Applicants also had to pay for identification photos, physicals
and fingerprinting.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NUMBER OF APPLICANTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   As of Monday, 1.4 million applications had been received, and
475,000 people sought legal status under the program for seasonal
agricultural workers, the INS said.
   The federal government estimated last year that from 1 million
to 3.9 million of the nation's estimated 6 million illegal aliens
would apply for amnesty.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ENFORCEMENT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The government will shift emphasis to employers now that the
amnesty program has ended. The immigration reform act mandates
sanctions against employers who knowingly hire undocumented workers.
   Starting June 1, the INS has the discretion to issue warning
citations or fine employers who violate the law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
