<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-Chronology     05-05 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Chronology,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Events Preceding Release of Three French Hostages in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten French hostages have been released since June
20, 1986, including three freed by the pro-Iranian Islamic Jihad on
Wednesday.
   Hostage negotiations, shrouded in official secrecy, have been
the subject on speculation in the press. Previous deals reportedly
have involved payment on the $1 billion loan owed to Iran and the
expulsion from France of Iranian exiles opposing Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini.
   Here is a chronology of major events involving French hostages
since 1986:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1986</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 7 _ Three months after conservative Premier Jacques Chirac
took office and announced efforts to improve relations with Iran,
the chief of the Iranian opposition Mujahedeen leaves France for
Iraq.
   June 20 _ Two journalists with the television network Antenne 2
_ Philippe Rochot, 40, and Georges Hansen, 46 _ are freed in Beirut
by the pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem Revolutionary Justice Organization
after 105 days of captivity.
   Nov. 11 _ Marcel Coudari, 54, and Camille Sontag, 84, are freed
by the Revolutionary Justice Organization. Coudari was abducted in
Beirut in February 1986. Sontag was kidapped May 7, 1986.
   Nov. 17 _ France and Iran sign an accord for a partial
reimbursement of $330 million on a $1 billion loan owed to Iran.
   Dec. 24 _ Aurel Cornea, 54, soundman for Antenne 2, is freed by
the Revolutionary Justice Organization in west Beirut, 10 months
after he was kidnapped.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1987</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 27 _ Jean-Louis Normandin, 36, an assistant cameraman at
Antenne 2, and journalist Roger Auque, 31, are freed by the
Revolutionary Justice Organization.
   Nov. 29 _ France allows Wahid Gordji, an employee at the Iranian
Embassy, to leave the country. Gordji, wanted for questioning in
connection with terrorist bombings in Paris in 1985, had been
hiding in the embassy since June 29.
   On July 17, France broke diplomatic relations with Iran over the
Gordji affair.
   France denied reports of ransom and of arms sales to Iran, but
said Iran's influence leading to the hostage release made other
actions possible. It did not specify what they were.
   Dec. 8 _ France expelled 17 Khomeini opponents from France, but
denied any connection with the hostage talks.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1988</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   May 4 _ Following weeks of reported negotiations between French
and Iranian officials, the Islamic Jihad releases diplomats Marcel
Fontaine, 45, Marcel Carton, 62, and Jean-Paul Kauffmann, 44.
Carton and Fontaine were kidnapped separately on March 22, 1985.
Kauffman was abducted May 22, 1985.
</TEXT>
