<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0632EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-Sunlight     05-05 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Sunlight,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunlight May Trigger AIDS Virus Reproduction, Study Suggests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunlight may make a dormant AIDS virus start to
reproduce itself by activating a genetic trigger, scientists
reported today.
   The results of new test-tube experiments do not necessarily mean
people infected with the AIDS virus should stay out of the sun,
scientists stressed.
   But ``I certainly wouldn't tell somebody who had the virus or is
seropositive (possibly infected) to go sit in one of these
ultraviolet (tanning) spas,'' said Martin Rosenberg of Smith Kline
& French Laboratories.
   Rosenberg and Smith Kline colleagues from King of Prussia, Pa.,
and Belgium report their work in the British journal Nature.
   They found that the virus grew faster in cells that had been
exposed to ultraviolet light, a component of sunlight, and that
exposing infected cells to ultraviolet light or sunlight activated
a genetic trigger that controls virus reproduction.
   Since ultraviolet light damages a cell's genetic material, the
work suggests that a dormant AIDS virus recognizes when an infected
cell is under stress, said Rosenberg.
   Cells under attack are ``no longer a nice place to be latent,''
so the virus reproduces and spreads elsewhere, he said.
   After the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome
has infected a cell, it can lie dormant for long periods before it
begins to reproduce itself and spread to other cells.
   Scientists are trying to understand just what triggers a latent
virus to start reproducing itself, in hopes of finding ways to keep
it dormant.
   While most cells infected by the AIDS virus are deep within the
body, shielded from sunlight and its ultraviolet light, the virus
has been found in cells called Langerhans cells that reside in the
skin.
   But so little is known about that kind of infection that the
possible effect of sunlight is not exactly clear, Rosenberg said in
an interview.
   Scientists do not know how often Langerhans cells are infected
or whether the virus spreads from there to elsewhere in the body,
he said.
   Donald Belsito, associate professor of dermatology at New York
University, said he knows of no experiments that show how much
ultraviolet light reaches Langerhans cells. The minimum dose that
produced an effect in the new experiments ``could reasonably be
expected from natural sunlight exposure to reach the Langerhans
cells,'' he said.
   But AIDS researcher William Haseltine of Harvard's Dana-Farber
Cancer Institute said more studies will be needed to determine any
effect of sunlight on infected people.
   ``It is far too early to draw any conclusions that would affect
behavior,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``I don't think at
this point people should be overly concerned that sunlight
represents a substantial risk.''
   In one of the new experiments, scientists exposed blood cells
called T-cells to ultraviolet light before infecting them with the
AIDS virus. They found evidence of viral reproduction four to five
days after infection in the exposed cells, significantly earlier
than the seven to eight days required for untreated cells.
   Other experiments focused on a segment of genetic material
called the long terminal repeat, which regulates reproduction of
the AIDS virus. Through genetic engineering, researchers inserted
the segment into an experimental cell line.
   After the cells were exposed to ultravolet light, the segment
showed up to 150 times as much activity as it did when light was
not used, researchers reported. Activity was first detected two to
four hours after irradiation, reaching a peak 20 to 24 hours later.
   The scientists also exposed the experimental cells to ordinary
sunlight, finding that a half-hour of exposure produced a 12-fold
increase in activity. Even 10 minutes was enough to cause a small
increase, they said.
</TEXT>
