<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrawleyCase     05-05 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brawley Case,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports: Brawley Seen At Party; Had Run Away Before</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Contents of 4th graf may be offensive to readers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black teen-ager had run away from home at
least twice before she disappeared last November, and was seen at a
party during the period she claims she was abducted and raped by a
group of whites, according to news reports.
   When Tawana Brawley was 13 and 14 years old she caused frantic
family searches _ and beatings when she was found _ by staying away
from home at least 24 hours, the Daily News reported today, quoting
her friends and their parents.
   Wednesday night, WCBS-TV reported that Miss Brawley, 16, was
seen at a birthday party in Newburgh on Nov. 27, three days after
she disappeared and one day before she was found behind an
apartment complex where she used to live.
   Miss Brawley was found huddled in a trash bag with racial slurs
scrawled on her torso and feces smeared on her body. She has said
she was a victim of a sexual and racial assault involving up to six
white men, one of whom flashed a police-like badge. She has since
refused to tell her story to a state grand jury investigating the
case.
   Attorney General Robert Abrams, the special prosecutor for the
case, issued a statement saying: ``All aspects of this case,
including reports that Tawana Brawley may have been seen in
Newburgh, are under continuing investigation.''
   According to the News, the first runaway incident allegedly
occured when Tawana was 13. She spent the night with a teen-age boy
watching television, the newspaper said. When Brawley's mother and
aunt tracked her down the next day she first hid from them and then
tried to flee, the News said.
   In the second incident, in April 1986, Miss Brawley left school
on a Friday afternoon and spent two days in Beacon, smoking
marijuana, drinking beer and partying with a girlfriend and two
men, the report said.
   Miss Brawley's mother, Glenda, tracked her down at the house of
the teen-ager and smacked her repeatedly with her fists, the report
said.
   Neither disappearance was reported to police.
   The News said Mrs. Brawley could not be reached to comment on
the report, but the Rev. Al Sharpton, who has advised Miss Brawley
not to cooperate with the officials investigating her case, said he
could not confirm the reports.
   ``If anything, it says Tawana came from a family who cared. And
if she got out of line, they attempted to take care of it,'' he
said.
   Sharpton, who said he watched the WCBS-TV report with the
Brawley family in Wappingers Falls, said he and family attorneys
Alton Maddox Jr. and C. Vernon Mason planned to hold a news
conference today to comment on the reports.
   In the WCBS-TV report, a witness who was not identified, and
spoke on camera with his face concealed, said he knew Miss Brawley,
saw her at the party and talked to her there.
   He also said that during part of the four-day period when Miss
Brawley claimed she was held captive she spent time with ``a former
boyfriend'' and ``drug dealer,'' identified by WCBS-TV as Jason
``Chico'' Colon.
   Several newspapers have quoted other friends of Miss Brawley as
saying they thought her claims of sexual abuse and racial assault
were exaggerated or untrue.
</TEXT>
