<1ST_LINE>u a PM-RefineryBlast 1stLd-Writethru a0542 05-05 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Refinery Blast, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0542,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Explosion, Fire At Oil Refinery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout; No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NORCO, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge explosion ripped through the Shell Oil
Co. refinery early today, breaking windows 20 miles away in New
Orleans and igniting a fire that could be seen for miles, civil
defense officials said.
   At least three people were injured, one of them critically, a
hospital official said.
   ``It is a serious thing, but we don't know anything much about
it yet,'' said Raymond Barvaro at the St. Charles Sheriff's
department.
   Shell officials reported the fire was under control, indicating
there was no danger of further explosion although the fire
continued to rage at the refinery on the Misssissippi River, the
sheriff's operations center said.
   The blast about 4 a.m. rocked the New Orleans metropolitan area,
shaking buildings, setting off burglar alarms and awakening people.
The shock broke windows in New Orleans and the fire's glow was
visible in downtown New Orleans.
   Two people were taken by helicopter to West Jefferson Medical
Center in New Orleans, one in critical condition with burns over 80
percent of his body, the other in guarded condition with cuts and
other injuries, officials said.
   Nursing supervisor Beverly Trahan said the helicopter returned
to the refinery where there were reports of another person with
burns.
   An evacuation center was set up at Destrehan High School, but
Jules Hymel, assistant director of civil defense for St. Charles
Parish, said it was voluntary and that no one was forced to leave
home.
   Hymel said the explosion was in a catalytic cracker, which
separates crude oil in various grades for the refining process.
   Two state police hazardous materials specialists were called to
the scene, but there were no reports of toxic fumes.
   Tim Vial, spokesman for the operations center, said said the
fire was under control.
</TEXT>
