<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0710EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-05 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar traded lower against major foreign
currencies in Europe this morning. Gold prices rose.
   Currency dealers said there was little trading in dollars, as
most activity focused on trading among European currencies.
   ``Dollar trading is very slow and dull,'' said one dealer in
Rome.
   ``We have seen phases like this before, where the dollar is in a
state of equilibrium and neither side sees an imbalance that has to
be corrected,'' said a dealer at a large West German bank.
   Interest could pick up Friday, they said, when U.S. employment
figures for April are scheduled to be released.
   In London, the dollar was quoted at 124.51 yen, compared with
124.95 late Wednesday. Banks and other financial institutions were
closed in Japan because of the Children's Day national holiday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.6765 West German marks, down from 1.6796
   _1.3955 Swiss francs, down from 1.4000
   _5.7030 French francs, down from 5.7075
   _1.8796 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8840
   _1,248.80 Italian lire, down from 1,250.50
   _1.2340 Canadian dollar, down from 1.2353
   One British pound cost 1.8650 in London this morning, unchanged
from late Wednesday.
   Gold prices rose in sluggish trading. One trader said the
bullion market lacks direction because the dollar is virtually
motionless and because the Tokyo market is closed.
   The metal opened in London at a bid price of $444.50 a troy
ounce, little changed from late Wednesday's $444. At midmorning
today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended
price of $445.35.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $445.20, up from $443.50 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.36 to close at a bid $447.07.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.35 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Wednesday.
</TEXT>
