<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Glance,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Developments At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a glance at today's developments in Poland:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In KRAKOW, police surprise sleeping workers and break up a
10-day strike by half the force at the huge 32,000-worker Nowa Huta
steel mill. The government says no one is injured, but at least 38
people are arrested. Opposition activists' telephones appear to be
cut.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In GDANSK, authorities order a lockout at the Lenin shipyard,
site of the nation's other major stoppage. Police in full riot gear
ring the yard and Solidarity founder Lech Walesa, inside with
hundreds of strikers, predicts authorities will next move on the
shipyard and vowed to be ``the last to leave.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In WARSAW, Solidarity national spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz is
reported arrested. The government accuses strike leaders of trying
to provoke crisis and reports new stoppages among transit workers
in the northwestern port of Szczecin and the nearby municipality of
Police.
   Students also are striking at Warsaw University.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The wave of strikes, which began April 25, are Poland's most
serious since the 1981 military crackdown on Solidarity. Two
earlier strikes were settled when the government agreed to increase
wages to offset price increase of 42 percent so far this year.
   At Nowa Huta and Gdansk, strikers demanded independent local
unions, reinstatement of fired union activists and the release of
political prisoners.
</TEXT>
