<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-Pool     05-05 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Pool,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convoy Arrives At Kuwait As US Warships Watch For Iranian Mines Or
Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDITOR'S NOTE _ This story was filed by the Pentagon news pool.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE USS JACK WILLIAMS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warship-escorted convoys
moved through the Persian Gulf without incident, but U.S. warships
that prowled the waterway were still on alert for mines and
possible Iranian attack.
   ``It's very quiet out there,'' Lt. Cmdr. Mark Van Dyke said
Wednesday on the 3,700-ton guided-missile frigate that played a
pivotal role in fierce fighting with Iranian warships two weeks ago.
   A U.S.-escorted tanker convoy arrived off the coast of Kuwait on
Wednesday morning without incident after clearing through the
narrow Strait of Hormuz, gateway to the gulf, the day before, Navy
officials reported.
   The two Kuwaiti tankers reflagged as American vessels, the
Townsend and the Sea Isle City, were escorted by the destroyer USS
Merrill and the guided missile frigate USS Sides. The tankers were
left in international waters off Kuwait.
   Iran has threatened revenge for the April 18 battle in which
Washington claimed three Iranian vesssels were sunk. Three others
were hit by missiles and bombs.
   Adm. William J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of
Staff, told a Pentagon media pool aboard the command ship USS
Coronado on Tuesday that Tehran's threats of revenge are taken very
seriously.
   ``They have considerable capability and they have ... missile
capability which we are always concerned about,'' Crowe said during
a surprise visit to the gulf. He came to tour some of the 28 ships
plying the vital oil trade route.
   Shipping executives said a civilian helicopter pilot reported
Tuesday seeing two ships thought to be Iranian between Das island,
an oil terminal off the United Arab Emirates, and the Iran-owned
Sassan platform that U.S. forces destroyed April 18.
   His report raised fears the ships were sowing mines.
   Crowe met with senior Bahrain government officials on Wednesday,
the second day of a visit to the Persian Gulf, where Iran and Iraq
have been at war since September 1980.
   Although no new mines have been found since the April 18 sea
battle, mine-sweepers and lookouts in the bow of the Williams and
other passing ships kept lookouts on constant duty to survey the
placid turquoise sea for fear Iran may use mines to even the
balance after its naval losses.
   ``I don't care if one of my boys forces us to reverse speed for
a dead sheep or cow,'' says Cmdr. Edward Mann, captain of this
warship. ``I still praise him for spotting it because it shows he
his doing his job.''
   Dead sheep and cattle, with their four hoofs poking through the
calm waters, have provided a scary imitation of the mines the
United States blames Iran for floating in international waters.
   One mine put on display yesterday aboard the Coronado, recovered
in September from the mine-laying Iran Ajr by the U.S. Navy, has
deadly hoof-like prongs that can detonate 250 pounds of explosives.
   Crowe visited the badly damaged 3,700-ton guided missile frigate
USS Samuel B. Roberts, which is in a gulf drydock undergoing
repairs, to pay tribute to its crew for its heroic effort in saving
the ship from sinking last month after it nudged a mine as it tried
to back away. Ten crew members were injured.
   The incident prompted the U.S. attack on Iranian oil platforms
April 18 which in turn led to the naval skirmish with Iran.
   As this warship sailed back into the central gulf to resume
patrol duties after a brief port stop, its officers and men seemed
more concerned about mines than Iranian attacks.
   ``You can even plant one of those from a dhow,'' said executive
officer Lt. Cmdr. Wally Bloss of the bow-shaped Arab fishing boats
that dot the steamy horizon.
   While the Pentagon has still not decided if Iran actually fired
Silkworms at U.S. ships in the April 18 engagement, the Williams'
crew shows little doubt.
   They have ordered 1,000 T-shirts with the slogan on the front:
``Persian Gulf Escort Service.'' The back displays an empty tequila
bottle with the words: ``We drank the bottle, but we didn't eat the
worm.''
   President Reagan has warned Tehran of strikes against coastal
Silkworm missile batteries if they were ever fired at American
ships, but the Pentagon says it lacks definite proof Iran used them
in the daylong battle.
</TEXT>
