<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GulfRdp     05-05 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims Warplanes Hit Ship, New Convoy Heads Down Gulf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its warplanes attacked an oil
tanker off the Iranian coast today, and a new convoy of
U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers escorted by American warships headed
south down the Persian Gulf.
   The reported Iraqi raid was the first in a week. There was no
immediate confirmation from independent shipping sources.
   The convoy, the fourth in the past week, left Kuwait as the U.S.
Navy accelerated its escort operations in an effort to make up for
delays caused by last month's mine threat and a one-day naval
battle with Iran.
   Iraq's official news agency said a ``large naval target,'' the
Iraqi term for a tanker, was attacked this morning. The report was
monitored in Cyprus.
   It quoted a military spokesman as saying the planes scored a
``direct and effective hit'' on the unidentified vessel and
returned safely to base.
   The raid was aimed at ``depriving the Iranian regime of its oil
revenues which are used for aggressive purposes,'' the spokesman
was quoted as saying.
   It was the first raid claimed by Iraq since April 29, when it
said two Iranian tankers were attacked by its jets the day before.
But those raids also have not been verified by independent sources.
   The last confirmed Iraqi air strike on Iranian shipping was
March 30, when the 259,000-ton Cypriot tanker Anax was set on fire
by missiles.
   Iraq and Iran have been at war since September 1980. More than
400 ships have been hit or damaged since the so-called ``tanker
war'' broke out in early 1984.
   The convoy, the 29th this year and the 51st since the United
States began escorting 11 reflagged Kuwaiti tankers last July,
included the 79,999-ton oil products tankers Chesapeake City and
Ocean City.
   The ships had reached Kuwait in a northbound convoy April 29.
They left a few hours after another convoy arrived in Kuwait
Wednesday.
   The movements have been stepped up in the past week after
falling behind schedule because of Iran's mining of international
waters and the subsequent naval clashes between U.S. and Iranian
forces April 18.
   Shipping executives, who reported the latest convoy, did not
name the escort warships and U.S. officials were not available.
   The warships were believed to be the destroyer Merrill and the
guided missile frigate John H. Sides, which had accompanied
Wednesday's convoy to Kuwait. U.S. warships do not normally enter
Kuwaiti waters.
</TEXT>
