<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People--Sanders     05-05 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People--Sanders,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspense Writer Gets $2.85 Million for New Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest book by suspense novelist Lawrence
Sanders has been sold at auction for $2.85 million in a tug-of-war
that involved eight publishing houses.
   On Wednesday, the Putnam Publishing Group bought the hardback
and paperback rights for the book, titled ``The Devil in the White
House.''
   The author of such successful novels as ``The Anderson Tapes''
and ``The First Deadly Sin,'' Sanders demanded and got a 15 percent
royalty on all hardcover and paperback sales. Under most publishing
contracts, hardcover royalties begin at 10 percent, while paperback
royalties rarely reach 15 percent until hundreds of thousands of
copies are sold.
   Sanders' last contract also was with Putnam, for $1.2 million.
He decided to hold an auction this time to test the market.
   It was the second blockbuster literary sale this week. On
Monday, Simon & Schuster and Pocket Books agreed to pay
mystery-suspense writer Mary Higgins Clark a minimum $10.1 million
for four books and a collection of short stories. Strong sales
could push the value of the package to $11.6 million.
</TEXT>
