<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0909EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Beaches     05-05 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Beaches,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Appeals Court Decision Opening Beaches To All Races</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today appealed
a court order that opened segregated beaches in the southern city
of Port Elizabeth to all races.
   The Port Elizabeth Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that the city
council acted without proper authority in 1966 when it passed a
resolution proclaiming the beaches segregated.
   The court declared the beaches in the country's fifth largest
city open to all races. Some blacks immediately went to previously
``whites only'' beaches and ran triumphantly along the sand.
   But today, Constitutional Development Minister Chris Heunis and
the administrator of Cape Province, Gene Louw, filed court papers
seeking to appeal the decision. The documents said the beaches
should remain segregated until the court rules on their appeal.
   City Councilor Graham Richards, who filed the application
calling for desegregated beaches, said Louw was ``using procedures
of the court as a purely political maneuver.''
   Heunis and President P.W. Botha have taken a middle ground on
the volatile issue of ``beach apartheid,'' contending that some
beaches should be integrated while others remain reserved for
whites.
   Most beaches in the two largest coastal cities, Durban and Cape
Town, are open to all races. Blacks are barred from many beaches in
smaller communities.
   In January 1987, Port Elizabeth's beaches figured in a political
confrontation between Botha and the Rev. Alan Hendrickse, leader of
the mixed-race chamber of Parliament.
   Hendrickse waded into the surf in a well-publicized defiance of
apartheid laws. He later apologized to Botha for causing any
offense to the president, lowering his credibility among his
constituents.
   ``Somebody owes me an apology,'' Hendrickse said Wednesday in
Parliament after learning of the court ruling.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
