<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MethodistConference     05-05 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Methodist Conference,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Methodists Reject Abortion For Birth Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Methodists, who have condoned abortion
in ``some tragic conflicts of life,'' voted to oppose it as a means
of birth control or because the expected baby isn't of the desired
sex.
   ``We cannot affirm abortion as an acceptable means of birth
control, and we unconditionally reject it as a means of gender
selection,'' says the amendment approved Wednesday night by the
denomination's governing conference.
   The 9.6-million-member denomination is the country's second
largest Protestant group, next to the Southern Baptist Convention,
which sweepingly condemns abortion except to save the life of the
mother.
   Several other Protestant bodies in recent years have taken a
sterner position about abortion, modifying pro-choice stands, while
others have turned completely against it.
   The conference here acted after it defeated a broader
condemnation of abortion that said ``unborn human life is a human
being and therefore has a right to be born, loved and cared for.''
   Supporting that position, Eve G. Kirk of Hinckley, Ill., told
the nearly 1,000 delegates that ``if God is for the poor, weak and
helpess, to take a human life in the womb is wrong.''
   She cited biblical passages saying God knows people before they
come from the womb, adding that those words are ``for the millions
of unborn human babies that will never see the planet earth.''
   However, the Rev. Tex A. Sample, a Kansas City theologian,
opposed the proposal, declaring, ``If this view is carried, it will
take away from parents and children the right to safe, medical
abortion.''
   The proposal, offered by a minority of a legislative committee,
lost by 649 to 308, while the majority proposal tightening
limitations on abortion in some cases passed overwhelmingly, 805 to
130.
   The Rev. Edmond W. Robb of Marshall, Texas, said the approved
statement was ``the strongest position the church has ever taken
about abortion, a more responsible position.''
   Robb said the Methodist rejection of abortions for birth control
or convenience puts the church against about 90 percent of
abortions carried out for those reasons in America.
   The new reservations were added to the church's past postion,
which said:
   ``Our belief in the sanctity of unborn human life makes us
reluctant to approve abortion. But we are equally bound to respect
the sacredness of the life and well-being of the mother, for whom
devastating damage may result from unacceptable pregnancy.
   ``In continuity with past Christian teaching, we recognize
tragic conflicts of life with life that may justify abortion, and
in such cases support the legal option of abortion under proper
medical procedures.''
   In another action, the conference voiced opposition to the
movement for a constitutional amendment making English the
country's official language.
   Opposing it, Methodist delegates declared, ``These efforts and
their implications are another manifestation of the systemic racism
which has infected this country for generations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0098 </DOCNO>
