<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Cambodia     05-05 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Cambodia,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United States Revises Estimate Of Vietnamese Occupation Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam has withdrawn about 15,000
soldiers from Cambodia, leaving a force of about 125,000, a U.S.
official said today.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 to topple the Khmer Rouge
regime, which massacred hundreds of thousands of people. With
Soviet military aid, the Vietnamese have been fighting 50,000 or
more Cambodian resistance guerrillas armed by China and politically
backed by the United States.
   ``We believe that Hanoi did withdraw about 15,000 troops from
Cambodia last November and that there would be about 125,000 there
right now,'' said Ross Petzing, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in
Bangkok.
   ``We don't have any evidence that fresh troops have replaced the
personnel that departed, but Vietnam is able to very quickly return
troops to Cambodia if it so desires,'' he said. He quoted
information the State Department sent to U.S. embassies in Asia on
April 28.
   Vietnam withdrew what it said were 20,000 troops last November
in the largest of six annual withdrawals made since 1982. Most if
not all of the previous pullouts were dismissed by the United
States and other countries as mere troop rotations.
   The U.S. government estimate of Vietnamese troop strength in
Cambodia is widely used by news organizations, Western diplomats
and others. The non-communist nations of Southeast Asia generally
give higher estimates.
   The figure of 140,000 had been the official estimate since 1986.
   In an interview with The Associated Press early last month,
Vietnam's Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach said Hanoi had over the
past six years withdrawn half of the forces it had stationed in
Cambodia. Hanoi will withdraw the remaining half over the next
three years to keep its pledge of a total pullout by 1990, Thach
said without giving any figures.
   Petzing also quoted the State Department as saying it had seen
reports indicating Vietnam has withdrawn some of its troops
stationed in Laos. He said the department had no firm figures,
however.
   Western diplomats in Hanoi also have cited such reports. Some
said they believed it was part of Vietnam's effort to streamline
its military in order to devote resources to economic development.
   Vietnam's communists helped the Laotian communists come to power
in 1975 and since has maintained a ``special relationship'' with
that country, including the stationing of what some estimates have
put at 40,000 or more soldiers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0950EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrashHoax     05-05 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash Hoax,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laconia Man Convicted Of Faking Plane Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA ENGLERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radio enthusiast who faked a plane crash
was convicted in federal court of making a false report to the
government after a neighbor testified he heard the man say, ``I am
in trouble. I am losing blood.''
   The fake Jan. 8 report during the height of a snowstorm
triggered a search for a downed plane, three dead passengers and a
weakening pilot. The hunt involved 20 aircraft, six police agencies
and up to 100 people at a cost of $50,000.
   Jurors deliberated for about two hours Wednesday before
convicting Mark Blair, 29. Blair faces a fine and up to five years
in prison when he is sentenced July 1 by U.S. District Judge Shane
Devine.
   In closing arguments, Assistant U.S. Attorney Peter Papps
portrayed Blair as a radio enthusiast who enjoyed instigating the
crash hoax during one of the worst storms of the year.
   ``Imagine the power he felt making this Navy plane run east to
west and north to south,'' Papps said, referring to a plane that
for nearly four hours flew low over risky terrain searching for the
downed jet.
   Defense lawyer Paul Twomey said he will appeal the verdict on
grounds of insufficient evidence, saying, ``This case is garbage,
absolute garbage.''
   But Papps said the testimony of the neighbor and the Navy pilot
``clearly identified Mark Blair as guilty.''
   Blair had testified he couldn't have committed the hoax because
he was asleep and wasn't aware that a plane was reported down until
he woke and turned on a police scanner after 10:47 p.m.
   Blair said he then overheard the downed pilot tell the Navy
plane that he believed passengers were dead, that he had lost a lot
of blood, was having trouble staying conscious, and could see and
hear the Navy plane overhead.
   But his account conflicted with times given Monday by David
Webster, the Navy reservist and Delta Airlines pilot flying the
Navy plane. He said conversations with the lost plane ended shortly
after 10:35 p.m.
   Timothy Dinan, 24, who lived in Blair's apartment building, said
he heard the scratchy sound of a two-way radio through an open
window in Blair's apartment and a voice clearly saying, ``I am in
trouble. I am losing blood.''
   When police searched Blair's apartment and a nearby storage
shed, they seized radio equipment and printed material that
included the name Dale, the name given to searchers by the man who
said he was the injured pilot.
   The materials also contained highlighted references to a radio
frequency used that night and information about police emergency
codes.
</TEXT>
