<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NotDead     05-05 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Not Dead,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Social Security Claims Living Man is Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arvel Crawford admits to a bad back and
legs, but says he's very much alive despite Social Security's
listing him as dead for more than a month.
   And officials told Crawford's wife it will be three more months
before they reclassify him among the living.
   ``I don't think that's right having me down dead for three more
months,'' Crawford said. ``I'm not dead at all.''
   Crawford, 43, suffers from a bad back and legs, unstable nerves
and a paranoid schizophrenic personality disorder.
   He gets about $370 in Social Security a month, and his three
children get about $180. In addition, he receives $280 from
Supplementary Security Income and Medicaid each month for
medication.
   The family discovered that Crawford was listed as dead when they
called his Social Security office Friday to correct a problem.
   Crawford's wife, Marylou, spent Monday morning trying to
resurrect him at the office.
   ``I had to bring him in and show all kinds of ID,'' she said.
``They made him sign a paper that said `I, Arvel Crawford, live at
2041 Monroe Street and I am alive.'''
   Maureen Theodore, Social Security supervisor in Hollywood, said
the family still will get its monthly payments even though a
bureaucratic glitch lists Crawford as dead since March 31.
   But it'll take three months to get corrected paperwork to
regional Social Security offices in Baltimore and Birmingham, Ala.,
Mrs. Crawford said she was told.
</TEXT>
