<DOCNO> AP880505-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0954EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Angola     05-05 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Outlines Terms For Leaving Angola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba will withdraw its troops from Angola under a
four-year timetable if South Africa ends its occupation of
South-West Africa, a Cuban official said today.
   Jorge Risquet Valdes, Cuba's delegate in Angolan peace talks,
outlined his country's terms for withdrawing from Angola at a news
conference.
   Angola, Cuba, South Africa and the United States concluded a
two-day conference Wednesday aimed at ending the Angolan civil war.
   Cuban troops were sent into Angola in 1975 to defend the Marxist
government against pro-Western rebels of the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola. The United States aids the rebel
group.
   South Africa troops also are in southern Angola to back the
rebel movement and to attack Angolan bases of the South-West
African People's Organization, which is fighting for independence
of the South African-held territory of South-West Africa, or
Namibia.
   Risquet said Havana would withdraw its troops from Angola under
a four-year timetable hinging on South African readiness to give
independence to Namibia.
   He also said South Africa and the rebels must cease attacks on
Angolan soil.
   A joint statement Wednesday at the end of the talks said
progress was made and the parties agreed to meet again in a few
weeks at a still undecided African location.
   ``Our optimism could be defined as moderate,'' Risquet said.
   He said the Cubans came to the London talks seeking
``non-interference in the internal affairs of Angola and assurances
that Angola is not going to be attacked again.''
   Cuban forces in Angola, which he said numbered aver 35,000,
would remain ``as long as Angola needs us.''
   But ``if the abovementioned conditions are met then Cuba's role
will have been fulfilled,'' Risquet said.
   He declined to disclose Cuba's casualties in the 12 years it has
had forces there, but said the economic cost to Havana had been
heavy.
   He also called for an end to U.S. aid to Angolan rebels. Chester
Crocker, U.S. assistant secretary of state for African affairs who
chaired the London talks, said U.S. aid to the Angolan rebels was
not negotiable.
</TEXT>
