<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Poland     05-05 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Poland,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets `Regret' Polish Unrest But See No Link With Their Own
Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet government regrets the labor unrest in
Poland but denies it has any relevance to Soviet economic reforms,
a Foreign Ministry spokesman said today.
   Soviet media were silent about the crackdown by Polish
authorities on strikers at a steel mill outside Krakow and a
lockout of workers at a Gdansk shipyard.
   Official Radio Moscow reported only that 61 percent of the
people polled in the Soviet Union's western neighbor thought the
strikes would damage the economy.
   Asked at a regular news briefing about the labor unrest, Foreign
Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said: ``We regret that such
events take place in Poland.''
   He declined to say whether Soviet officials had offered advice
or suggestions to the Polish government.
   Asked whether the labor unrest, sparked by price increases
imposed by the government, was a warning for Soviet officials who
say prices must go up to reform the Soviet economy, he said:
   ``We closely follow the events in Poland. They go their way and
we go ours. I don't see any definite links. We have our own
problems here.''
   But Gerasimov noted that among the economic reforms being
discussed in the official Soviet press are price increases and
consumer demand that cannot be met because of a lack of goods.
   Soviet officials say prices will go up in the early 1990s to cut
the billions of rubles the government spends every year on
subsidies for food and other basic items.
   That has caused an outcry among consumers, and the Communist
Party newspaper Pravda has said it receives more letters about the
pending price increases than almost any other topic.
   Polish workers are seeking pay increases of up to 60 percent to
offset prices that have gone up 42 percent so far this year. The
Polish government has said the price increases are necessary to
straighten out Poland's economic problems and that the strikes
damage the reform effort.
   Pravda on Wednesday accused ``anti-Polish centers'' in the West
and domestic dissidents of trying to exploit the unrest in Poland.
</TEXT>
