<DOCNO> AP880505-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ImpaledMan     05-05 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Impaled Man,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Logger Survives Being Impaled By Tree Limb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man impaled by 22 inches of a tree limb
that penetrated his abdomen in a logging accident is out of
intensive care today and says he considers himself very lucky to be
alive.
   Gary Crawford, 31, of Hazlehurst, was listed in fair condition
at a Savannah hospital.
   ``I remember everything,'' Crawford said. ``I remember asking
the Lord to help me, to get the stick out of me.''
   Crawford was operating a skidder, a heavy tractor used to haul
logs, near Stilson on April 29 when a tree limb penetrated the
heavy cage that protects the driver's seat from falling limbs.
   Candler County Sheriff Homer Bell said Crawford was driving over
cut-down trees and a branch on one of those trees struck him.
   Crawford's mother, Colleen Crawford, said the branch entered her
son's body in the groin area and bypassed his liver, kidneys and
bowels to press against the skin of his back.
   ``It (the limb) didn't break the skin in his back,'' she said.
``But 22 inches of the stick were inside my son's body.''
   He underwent several hours of surgery at Memorial Medical Center
in Savannah to remove the limb and was in an intensive care unit
for almost five days.
   Crawford said he suffered only nerve damage. ``I consider myself
pretty lucky,'' he said. ``I don`t know if I will be able to walk,
but I am not paralyzed. I just can`t s myth'' that Presser's and Williams'
elections ``had
been engineered and manipulated by organized crime elements.''
   ``The FBI and the Department of Justice know that at this time
no such influence exists,'' said John R. Climaco, the union's
general counsel. ``It's a fiction, pure fiction.''
   Climaco said Presser and other top union officials ``feel
vindicated ... and are comforted by the fact that after over one
year of testimony, this jury was able to accurately ferret out the
truth.''
   Despite the setback in the Salerno case, some Teamster
officials, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said they still
fear that Rudolph Giuliani, the U.S. attorney for Manhattan, will
pursue a civil takeover attempt.
   ``They have been extremely adamant and cocky the past 30 days
about their intention to file this thing,'' one union official
said. ``Even this might not deter them.''
   The Justice Department used a similar suit under the RICO law in
1986 to place the 8,000-member Teamsters Local 560 in Union City,
N.J., under the control of a court-appointed trustee.
   The local, one of the largest in the union, had been under the
control of convicted and now imprisoned mob figure Anthony ``Tony
Pro'' Provenzano, who has been liked to the still-unsolved 1975
disappearance of former Teamsters President Jimmy Hoffa.
   However, the government's takeover of Local 560 lacked the
political ramifications of its contemplated attempt to place an
entire international union under the control of a court-appointed
trustee.
   When word of the anticipated suit was leaked by anonymous
government sources last August, the Teamsters went on the
offensive, saying government ``takeovers of unions are nothing new
_ communists have been doing it for years.''
   The AFL-CIO, which had ousted the Teamsters on corruption
charges in 1957, immediately came to their defense, likening the
suit to the Soviet Union's crushing of the Solidarity labor
movement in Poland in 1981.
   Three months labor, the Teamsters were welcomed back into the
AFL-CIO in a move that the federation's president, Lane Kirkland,
said would not have happened had it not been for the contemplated
takeover suit. Some AFL-CIO leaders admitted the Teamsters'
reaffiliation was a defensive move.
   Government prosecutors had acknowledged that if the suit against
the Teamsters succeeded, their next targets were the Laborers
Union, the Hotel and Restaurant Workers Union and the International
Longshoremen's Association.
   All three of those longtime AFL-CIO affiliates, along with the
Teamsters, were identified in a 1985 report by a White House
Commission on Organized Crime as being under the control or
influence of mob figures.
   Despite the Salerno verdict, the Teamsters' problems with the
Justice Department are far from over.
   Presser is scheduled to go on trial July 12 in Cleveland on
charges of participating in a payroll padding scheme to embezzle
$700,000 from a local there that he also heads.
   His attorneys have acknowledged that two men with alleged
organized crime connections were on the local's payroll while
performing no work for the union. But they said the FBI had
acquiesced in and even encouraged the scheme, and had used Presser
as a government informant for two decades.
</TEXT>
