<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0484 05-05 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0484,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Cites Concern Over ``Kiss And Tell'' Books</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3 grafs for top 2 grafs pvs, to raise reference to
making Reagan choose and to CORRECT Thursday to Wednesday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush says he sometimes
holds back from speaking in White House meetings out of fear of
leaks and reluctance to have the president ``choosing between his
vice president'' and members of the Cabinet.
   He said the prospect of ``kiss and tell'' books about the Reagan
administration hinders the free exchange of views in the
government's highest circles.
   ``It inhibits freedom of expression, the vehemence with which
people express their views,'' Bush told a group of reporters
Wednesday during a campaign stop in Sacramento.
   He was referring to a recent book by former White House press
secretary Larry Speakes and a forthcoming one by former chief of
staff Donald T. Regan.
   ``If you think somebody is there writing a book putting his or
her own spin on it, you hold back,'' he said.
   ``I hold back speaking in meetings because I don't want the
president to have to be choosing between his vice president and the
other members of the Cabinet,'' said Bush.
   ``And I hold back sometimes because I worry about leaks.''
   The vice president planned to visit a high school in East Los
Angeles today before flying to Idaho as he continued a three-day
campaign swing through the West.
   Calling California a ``major battleground'' in the fall
election, Bush said: ``I'll be back. I'll be back. Have to. Got to
win this state.''
   He said he would ``absolutely not'' rule out California Gov.
George Deukmejian as a potential running mate.
   But he said he has not talked to the Republican governor about
the subject, nor to anyone else at this point, insisting he wants
to wait until after the Democratic convention in July before
deciding.
   Bush made light of reports, based on Regan's new book, that
Nancy Reagan has sought the help of astrologers in making
recommendations to her husband on scheduling.
   Bush said: ``I know it is a fascinating, titillating subject for
all, with particular emphasis on the journalistic community.''
   ``I may get more interested,'' he joked.
   A spokesman, Stephen Hart, said the vice president ``does not
consult astrologers or horoscopes or anything of the kind. He
doesn't even know where the horoscope is in the newspaper.''
   But speaking to reporters on Air Force II on Thursday, Bush
said: ``I'll tell you one thing: there are two edges to this
sword.''
   ``There are a helluva lot of people across this country that
read these columns. Otherwise, they wouldn't be in the papers.''
   Asked about Joyce Jillson, a Los Angeles astrologer who contends
she helped unidentified Reagan campaign aides select Bush as a
running mate in 1980, Bush said he had never heard of her.
   But he joked: ``I'll likely work closely with her. She's
brilliant.''
   In Sacramento, Bush said: ``Generally speaking, I don't like
kiss-and-tell books.''
   Bush also said Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega
should go, denying he had signed on to any possible White House
compromise to enable Noriega to step down from power instead.
   ``I want him to leave the country,'' Bush said.
   Bush also reiterated his charge that both Democratic
front-runner Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson lack foreign policy
experience.
   When a reporter noted that Reagan did not have such experience
either upon taking office in 1981, Bush said: ``Maybe this guy
(Dukakis) could muddle through and make it; maybe Jackson could
too.''
   ``We'll never know whether President Reagan could have done an
even better job if he had foreign policy experience,'' he said. He
quickly added that Reagan's performance in foreign policy had been
splendid.
</TEXT>
