<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Lebanon 3rdLd-Writethru   05-05 0788</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Lebanon, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0589,0811</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Says Cross-Border Raids Will Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY7,8</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with more fighting in Maydoun
and to move up reference to troops blowing up houses; picks up 9th
graf pvs: Critics questioned...; Edits thereafter to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>METULLA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops seized 20 guerrillas and
brought them back to Israel after a two-day raid into southern
Lebanon that left at least 40 Arabs dead, sources said today.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said Israel would not hestitate
to make raids similiar to the strike that began Monday into the
area of southern Lebanon that Israel has designated its ``security
zone.''
   Three Israeli soldiers were killed during the operation.
   ``The point was to purge the security zone,'' Rabin told Israel
radio. ``There is nothing worse than allowing terror elements who
are active against us to establish themselves freely and feel free
to act against Israeli and targets in the security zone.''
   He said the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, Shiite
Moslem movement was singled out by the Israeli forces this time
because it ``has become one of the elements that most cooperates
with (Palestine Liberation Organization Chief Yasser) Arafat.''
   The Israelis confronted Hezbollah guerrillas Wednesday in the
village of Maydoun north of the security zone in the fiercest
fighting of the operation.
   Reports from Lebanon said Israeli troops abandoned Maydoun after
blowing up houses and using bulldozers to cover up the rubble and
the bodies of the guerrillas. Army officials denied the village was
destroyed.
   ``Maydoun was not destroyed. What was destroyed were the
trenches, the bunkers,'' Col. Raanan Gissin, deputy army spokesman,
told reporters in Tel Aviv.
   Israeli sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that
Israeli-backed troops of the South Lebanon Army militia entered
Maydoun after the Israeli withdrawal to conduct a ``cleaning up''
mission.
   Israel Radio reported that the militiamen left Maydoun after
conducting searches and blowing up houses in the village. Army
officials confirmed that the militiamen returned to the security
zone.
   Military officials said a South Lebanon Army tank opened fire on
a guerrilla vehicle approaching Maydoun today and killed the
guerrillas inside. They did not elaborate.
   The Israeli sources also said today that Israeli troops arrested
20 guerrillas during the operation and brought them back to Israel.
   Critics questioned the wisdom of attacking Hezbollah, noting
that its guerrillas had not participated in any of the dozen
infiltration attempts by Palestinian guerrillas into Israel since
November.
   ``Why Hezbollah?,'' asked military analyst Uzi Mahanaimi in a
front page commentary in the Yediot Ahronot daily.
   ``Hezbollah is not the Israeli army's main enemy in south
Lebanon'' and has not tried to penetrate into northern Israel since
1982, Mahanaimi wrote.
   On Wednesday, helmeted soldiers riding armored personnel
carriers waved and made the ``V''-for-victory sign as they crossed
back into Israel.
   ``The mission ... was intended to clear the area from terrorist
strongholds, serve a warning signal to the local population, and
enhance our deterrence ... against terrorist activity,'' Gissin
said.
   But some experts said the mission could backfire and lead to
more guerrilla strikes against Israel.
   It was Israel's largest military operation in south Lebanon in
two years. Security sources said up to 2,500 Israeli troops took
part.
   Soldiers searched five villages in southeastern Lebanon on
Tuesday and Wednesday and distributed leaflets telling residents
not to assist guerrillas.
   Gissin said Shiite Moslem militiamen of Hezbollah drove
villagers out of Maydoun last year and took over the community. He
described Maydoun as a Hezbollah ``stronghold, fortified with
trenches, dugouts, and gun emplacements.''
   Army officials said Maydoun threatened outposts of the
Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia and civilians living in
the Christian-dominated security zone, a six- to 10-mile-wide strip
north of Israel's border.
   Reporters covering the attack said there were 60-70 guerrillas
in Maydoun.
   Israeli paratroopers surrounded the village on Tuesday night
and, led by a dozen tanks, moved into Maydoun at dawn. Troops met
fierce opposition as they advanced slowly while fighting in
trenches and in house-to-house battles.
   One soldier died in the fighting and two others were killed when
Hezbollah and Lebanese army gunners shelled the assault force from
nearby Mashghara, site of a 50-man Syrian garrison.
   Israeli troops fired on Mashghara, and Israel radio quoted
Lebanese reports as saying five Lebanese army gunners were wounded.
The Israeli army said its ``attack helicopters and artillery struck
at and destroyed ... Lebanese army guns.'' Gissin denied Lebanese
reports that the Syrian garrison was hit.
   ``We took precautions that our artillery fire or even flat
trajectory fire would not be directed against the Syrians,'' Gissin
said. ``The results prove we succeeded. The Syrians did not make an
offensive move.''
</TEXT>
