<2ND_LINE>PM-Saudi-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0590,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudis Deny Iran Spy Claim, Warns Iran Of `Venomous Campaign'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 9th graf, `The Wahabis...' to CORRECT that Wahabis are
movement, sted sect. Pick up 10th pvs, `IRNA earlier...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia today rejected Iran's
claim that it arrested a Saudi spy and told Tehran not to pursue
``misleading and venomous campaigns'' against the kingdom.
   Iran also claimed Wednesday that the Saudis beat up Iranian
diplomats before they left Saudi Arabia after Riyadh's decision to
severe relations with Tehran April 26.
   Riyadh rejected the claims as ``totally baseless.''
   ``It is not difficult for the government of Iran, with its
stigma of lying, to hire a mercenary from among its followers to do
and say what he is ordered,'' a Saudi government official said in a
statement distributed by the Saudi Press Agency.
   ``We warn the rulers of Tehran against exceeding the limits in
this manner, which is spurned by all sons of the Islamic nation,''
he said. ``We have decided to confront this misleading and venomous
campaign with all firmness and determination.''
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said Wednesday
security authorities ``arrested an agent of the Riyadh regime who
had entered the country illegally with 300 million rials ($4.5
million).''
   ``He will be dealt with as a spy,'' the statement said.
Convicted spies may be sentenced to death under Iran's Islamic law.
   IRNA also quoted an unidentified Information Ministry official
as saying the man was planning to ``spread Wahabi faith and the
American brand of Islam.''
   The Wahabis are an ultra-conservative Sunni Moslem movement.
Most Saudis, including Saudi Arabia's ruling family, are Wahabis.
The majority of Iranians are Shiite Moslems.
   IRNA earlier quoted Iranian officials as saying the Saudi
authorities had dealt ``barbarically'' with Iranian diplomats in
their embassy in Riyadh and consulate in the Red Sea port city of
Jidda Tuesday.
   That was the deadline for them to leave following the April 26
rupture of ties.
   Saudi television today screened a 15-minute film report showed
75 Iranian diplomats and their dependents at Riyadh and Jidda
airports as they left calmly with Saudi officials offering them
coffee and refreshments in the VIP lounges.
   An Iranian Boeing 707 was allowed to pick them up.
   Saudi-Iranian relations have deteriorated sharply over the past
year amid Iranian charges that the Saudis are aiding Iraq in its
war against Iran.
   The Iranians have attacked Saudi ships and vessels trading with
the kingdom in retaliation for Iraqi air strikes on their tankers
in the gulf.
   Relations between the two countries plummeted after
Iranian-inspired riots in the holy city of Mecca during the annual
Moslem pilgrimage last July 31.
   More than 400 Moslem pilgrims, including 275 Iranians, were
killed in the violence.
   The Iranians accused Saudi security forces of massacring the
Iranians. An Iranian mob later stormed the Saudi embassy in Tehran
and fatally injured a Saudi diplomat.
   Iran also has called for the overthrow of the Saudi royal family
and stripping it of custody of Islam's holy shrines in Mecca and
Medina.
</TEXT>
