<DOCNO> AP880505-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MITSuicides     05-05 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MIT Suicides,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fourth Suicide In Six Months Spurs Debate At MIT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fourth student suicide in six months
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology has spurred debate
about the rigors of attending one of the world's top technological
schools.
   Since the death of Mark Kordos, 18, who jumped from his 13th
floor dormitory room April 8, students and faculty have questioned
whether MIT drives its already top-flight students too hard.
   Kordos, a junior from Morristown, N.J., was an excellent student
majoring in computer science who apparently had no academic or
personal problems. Family and friends said he was applying to the
best graduate schools in the country.
   But he left a note saying he considered himself a failure, and
friends said he was having trouble with some of his course work.
   Andrew Fish, editor-in-chief of the campus newspaper The Tech,
blamed unwarranted pressures on students, insensitive and
overachieving faculty members and a climate that creates loneliness
and depression.
   ``The compulsion to constantly work, often at the exclusion of
all other activities, can warp the minds and bodies of students,
sometimes with tragic results,'' Fish wrote in a column.
   Kordos was the sixth MIT student to kill himself since 1986. All
were young men, and there is no evidence that any had known one
another.
   Administrators at MIT, which has about 9,600 students, said the
overall rate of suicide at the school is no higher than the
national average of approximately 1.4 suicides per 10,000
college-age students a year.
   Before the recent deaths, suicides were rare at MIT, officials
said. There were none in 1985, one in 1984, two in 1983 and none
from 1979-82.
   The suicide rate of Americans under 25 has tripled in the last
30 years, and suicide is now the second-leading cause of death of
college students.
   ``There is no evidence I've been able to come across that
matters at MIT are out of line with what is happening with youth
throughout the country,'' MIT Provost John Deutch told The Boston
Globe.
   Six members of MIT's faculty are Nobel Laureates, and 14 have
received the National Medal of Science. Because MIT draws students
who are in the top 5 percent of their high school classes, it is a
place where the best and brightest quickly can become average or
below average.
   Ron Kordos, Mark's father, said MIT ``was absolutely a factor''
in his son's death.
   ``He was a superachiever _ he never earned a `B' in his life,''
Kordos said. ``But the issue was pressure. The sleep deprivation
and competition were so excessive. He was just being driven by the
system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
