<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis-Taxes     05-05 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Taxes,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis and Wife Show $108,957 in '87 Income, $25,892 in Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael S. Dukakis and his
wife, Kitty, had joint income of $108,957 last year and paid nearly
a quarter of that amount in federal taxes, according to personal
income tax reports made public today.
   The Massachusetts governor's income was about half the total
reported by Democratic rival Jesse Jackson and a little more than
one-third the 1987 income reported by Vice President George Bush,
the likely Republican presidential nominee.
   The Dukakises paid $25,892 in taxes, or just under 24 percent of
their income.
   The governor also is the actual or potential beneficiary of
family trusts totaling more than $1 million. No income from the
trusts was listed on his tax returns.
   Dukakis earned nearly $85,000 in salary as governor laat year.
   The couple also reported $1,445 in taxable interest income, from
two Massachusetts bank accounts, along with $452 in income they had
from tax refunds they received a year ago.
   In addition, Dukakis reported $176 in income from the state of
Massachusetts beyond his government salary. Aides said the amount
reflected the benefit the governor receives from his occasional use
of state automobiles on personal business.
   Mrs. Dukakis reported $20,000 in salary for her role as director
of the Public Space Partnership Project at the Kennedy School of
Government at Harvard University, a collaborative program that
mobilizes public and private resources to improve the appearance of
prominent public spaces.
   In addition, Mrs. Dukakis reported $2,000 in income for her role
as a director of Mastery Education Corp., a publisher of college
textbooks.
   As in past years, Dukakis reported no deductible interest
payments. The mortgage on his home in suburban Brookline has been
paid off, and the governor does not use credit cards.
   His tax form said he spent $300 to have his taxes prepared by an
accountant.
   Two weeks ago, Bush and his wife Barbara reported 1987 earnings
of $308,396. They paid $86,684 in taxes.
   Earlier this week, Jackson and his wife, Jacqueline, reported
1987 earnings of nearly $210,000 and payments of $53,631 in federal
taxes.
</TEXT>
