<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Cocaine-Lumber 1stLd-Writethru a0533 05-05 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cocaine-Lumber, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0533,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Report Apparent U.S. Record Cocaine Seizure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `By late ...,' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
latest DEA figures on haul.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents expect they'll have a record,
4-ton cocaine seizure once they finish inspecting all 9,000 boards
in a shipmment of hollowed-out, cocaine-packed Brazilian lumber.
   Two Colombians and an American, meanwhile, were in custody on
drug conspiracy charges, awaiting bond hearings Friday before a
federal magistrate.
   The haul from the British-registered Amazon Sky reached 3,500
kilograms, or 7,700 pounds, by late morning, said authorities, who
expect the yield to hit 8,800 pounds by the time the inspection is
finished later today or Friday.
   ``If true, it would represent the largest cocaine seizure in
U.S. history,'' U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle said at a news
conference Wednesday.
   The largest previous cocaine seizure was 8,700 pounds found
stuffed inside picnic furniture delivered to Port Everglades in
November 1987.
   An anonymous letter from Cali, Colombia, in February tipped drug
agents that the freighter Amazon Sky would be docking in Florida
with 4,000 kilos of cocaine hidden in lumber, authorities said.
   U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agents believe the cocaine,
with an estimated street value of $1.7 billion, was imported by the
Cali cartel.
   The cocaine was headed for New York, Chicago, Los Angeles and
Miami, centers of the Cali cartel's distribution network, agents
said.
   The Cali group ``is a world-class competitor of the Medellin
cartel,'' the violent Colombian gang believed responsible for up to
80 percent of U.S. cocaine imports, said Tom Cash, head of the
Miami DEA office.
   Michael Tsalickis, owner of the Amazon Sky and a Tarpon Springs
warehouse where the cocaine-filled lumber was stashed, was charged
with conspiracy to import and distribute cocaine, as were Fredy
Perez and Pedro Narvaez, authorities said.
   Tsalickis, 60, is an associate of two top Cali cartel leaders,
Gilberto Rodriguez and Jose Santacruz Londono, according to DEA
files.
   Tsalickis, a native of Tarpon Springs who has been written about
in National Geographic magazine, has operated numerous businesses,
including a monkey farm and lumber mills in Leticia, Colombia.
   The Amazon Sky loaded 459 bundles of cedar in Brazil, then
stopped in Leticia, Colombia, where perhaps half of the boards were
hollowed out, stuffed with cocaine in one-kilo packets and
resealed, Cash said.
   The vessel then went down the Amazon River and arrived at
Bayboro Harbour in St. Petersburg on April 19.
   DEA and U.S. Customs Service inspectors staked out the ship. A
Customs inspector later slipped aboard, drilled into a lumber
bundle and found cocaine on his first try, Cash said.
   Federal agents set up round-the-clock surveillance, obtained
search warrants and brought in audio-video and X-ray equipment.
   The whole shipment was unloaded to a warehouse in St.
Petersburg. A few days later, 224 bundles of 24 boards each were
transported to Tsalickis' Tarpon Springs warehouse, authorities
said.
   Merkle said the cocaine-filled lumber was found at the Tarpon
Springs site, not in the wood left behind in St. Petersburg.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0462 05-05 0922</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Insists `It's Not Over;' Bush Says Fear Of Leaks Inhibits
Him</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 14 grafs new with Dukakis, Jackson comments, Dukakis tax
returns; pick up 13th graf pvs bgng ``Since the vice...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Jesse Jackson complained today that front-runner
Michael Dukakis has an ``inflated padded lead'' in convention
delegates that does not reflect the popular primary vote. Vice
President George Bush said he sometimes keeps quiet at Cabinet
meetings to avoid making the president choose sides.
   For a second day, Jackson criticized his party's nominating
rules. He told reporters he will contact every ``super delegate'' _
the 643 party leaders and elected officials who have a voice in
choosing the nominee _ with ``appeals for fairness'' and try to
persuade them that the super delegate split should correspond to
the primary and caucus vote.
   Of those 643 super delegates, Jackson has 46, Dukakis 166 and
the others remain uncommitted. Overall in the delegate chase,
Dukakis has 1,500 of the 2,081 needed to clinch the nomination and
Jackson has 927.
   Despite the numbers, Jackson continued to insist ``we're within
striking distance'' as he campaigned in Nebraska, which holds its
primary next week.
   But the Dukakis people were beginning to talk about being within
striking distance too _ of the nomination. Campaign communications
director Leslie Dach said Dukakis could clinch it in the remaining
five weeks worth of primaries _ a goal that seemed impossible in
the muddled contest of a few months ago.
   ``The arithmetic is clearly there,'' said Dach.
   Dukakis himself kept to a careful course, avoiding any direct
objections to the criticism Jackson has been leveling at him lately.
   ``I don't mind the competition at all as long as we can keep the
campaign up where it belongs and keep it positive,'' the
Massachusetts governor told reporters in Boston.
   Dukakis headed today for the poverty-scarred coal country of
West Virginia, which also holds a primary next Tuesday, and
criticized Bush for his standard campaign line of wanting to be
``the education president.''
   ``The next president must be this nation's No. 1 advocate for
educational opportunity and good schools, not just during election
years but every day and every week and every month,'' Dukakis said.
   At home in Boston, the Dukakis campaign released tax returns
that showed the governor and his wife earned $108,957 last year and
paid $25,892 in taxes.
   On the Republican side, Bush was campaigning in California
today, as aides talked of the importance of the West in the general
election.
   On Wednesday, Bush said that fear of ``kiss and tell'' books has
sometimes kept him from speaking up in Cabinet meetings.
   Bush said Wednesday that other times he keeps quiet at the
meetings ``because I don't want the president to have to be
choosing between his vice president and the other members of the
Cabinet.''
   Since the vice president already has secured enough delegates to
win the nomination, the main suspense concerns his running mate.
Bush said Wednesday he would ``absolutely not'' rule out
California's governor, George Deukmejian. Kansas Sen. Nancy
Kassebaum, meanwhile, said she's not interested in the job.
   Bush has sometimes been criticized for not saying more about his
opinions of Reagan administration policies and his role in
developing them. Dukakis, for one, has called him a ``blank slate.''
   On Wednesday, Bush offered an explanation for his reticence,
saying it stems from concern about ``kiss and tell'' books written
by former White House insiders.
   The vice president cited books like the ones written by ex-White
House spokesman Larry Speakes and former chief of staff Donald
Regan.
   ``It inhibits freedom of expression, the vehemence with which
people express their views,'' Bush told reporters in Sacramento.
``If you think somebody is there writing a book putting his or her
own spin on it, you hold back. ... I hold back sometimes because I
worry about leaks.''
   The vice president made lighthearted reference to one of the
revelations in the forthcoming Regan book _ that Nancy Reagan has
consulted astrologers about the president's schedule. He joked that
an astrologer claiming to have helped pick him as Reagan's running
mate in 1980 might make a good member of his own Cabinet.
   ``She's brilliant,'' Bush said, adding that if anyone was
interested, he and his wife Barbara are both Geminis.
   Spokesman Stephen Hart said Bush himself doesn't consult
astrologers or horoscopes himself, but the vice president said:
``I'll tell you one thing. ... There are a helluva a lot of people
across this country that read these columns.''
   Dukakis also had a little fun with the reports of astrological
influence at the White House. He joked to a crowd at a New York
Democratic dinner that his horoscope said he was headed for better
things. According to the stars, Dukakis said, it was ``pointless to
remain'' in his present position.
   While Dukakis studiously avoids saying he expects to be the
Democratic nominee, in the past few days he has been recruiting
some experienced political operatives to work in his likely
campaign against Bush.
   He picked Marcia Hale as his manager for the Democratic National
Convention, and joining the campaign as advisers are Democratic
veterans Richard Moe, Kirk O'Donnell and Anne Wexler.
   Meanwhile, Democrat Paul Simon, whose presidential campaign is
on hold, said he is ``95 percent certain'' that Dukakis will win
the nomination. But Simon said he'll hang onto his own delegates
``in the unlikely event that Michael Dukakis stubs his toe between
now and the convention.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
