<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TextbookBan     05-05 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Textbook Ban,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Joins Challenge of Ban on School Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state has joined parents and civil
liberties groups in opposing a federal judge's decision that
permits a school district to ban two classics criticized as
promoting sex and women's liberation.
   When U.S. District Judge Susan Black ruled for the Columbia
County School Board on Jan. 29, she cited a controversial Jan. 13
Supreme Court ruling that allowed school officials in Hazelwood,
Mo., to censor a school newspaper.
   The Florida Department of Education joined the education
departments of Maryland, California and Wyoming and 14 other groups
in an appeal of the ruling, which upheld a ban on ``Lysistrata''
and ``The Miller's Tale.''
   The groups, marshaled by People For the American Way, prepared a
friend-of-the-court brief that was submitted to the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals earlier this week.
   Syd McKenzie, general counsel for the state Department of
Education, said the department was concerned ``because it involved
a state-approved textbook and for that reason we think Judge Black
was overbroad in the authority she granted to the School Board.''
   Four parents filed suit against the Columbia County School Board
after it banned the two works from high school classrooms.
   Black, in her ruling, said she did not like the action taken by
the Columbia County School Board in 1986 after receiving complaints
from a pastor that the works promoted ``pornography and women's
lib.''
   But the judge ruled that the Hazelwood decision affirmed the
broad power of school boards to make curriculum decisions.
   Jan. G. Levine, an attorney for People for the American Way, a
270,000-member organization founded in 1980 by television producter
Norman Lear, said the case is important because it is one of the
first to follow the Hazelwood ruling.
   ``We hope the ruling is not interpreted so broadly that it
allows banning of the classics,'' she said.
   In the ancient Greek comedy ``Lysistrata,'' by Aristophanes,
women of warring Sparta and Athens conspire to deny sex to their
husbands until the men end their fighting.
   In ``The Miller's Tale,'' written in the 14th century by
Geoffrey Chaucer, a carpenter's wife deceives her husband and a
would-be suitor to cavort with a tenant in her house.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
