<DOCNO> AP880505-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseSpending 1stLd-Writethru a0452 05-05 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Spending, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,840</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with drug vote; picks up 2nd graf pvs, His
admonition, but deletes last 5 grafs pvs, During the, to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted 385-23 today to order
President Reagan to use U.S. military might to stop the flow of
illegal drugs into the United States.
   The vote approved a proposal backed by conservative Republicans
to tell Reagan to ``deploy equipment and personnel of the Armed
Forces sufficient to halt the unlawful penetration of United States
borders by aircraft and vessels carrying narcotics.''
   But the measure is a long way from becoming law. Even Rep. Jack
Davis, R-Ill., one of its strongest supporters, admitted, ``Yes, it
is flawed.''
   The proposal was added as an amendment to a Pentagon budget
bill. The final provisions of the huge bill will be worked out
later this year by a House-Senate conference committee after the
Senate approves its version of the bill.
   In two previous years, 1985 and 1986, the House also voted to
use the military to help stop drug trafficking, but those
provisions were knocked out by the conference committee. They were
strongly opposed by the Pentagon.
   ``The problem is that our southern borders are just a sieve of
cocaine and heroin coming over unchallenged every night,'' Davis
told his colleagues. ``We want to bring the front lines into this
battle against this poison coming across our borders.''
   Rep. Tommy Robinson, D-Ark., said, ``It's time to use the armed
forces to stop the drug cartel.''
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, opposed the amendment because he said it should be
considered as part of a separate package of anti-drug legislation
now being prepared.
   ``We do not want to deal with this problem on a piecemeal
basis,'' Aspin said. ``We have a drug bill coming up in which we
have to deal with not just the military involvement, but all the
questions about drugs.''
   But Davis and other supporters didn't want to discuss
technicalities. ``Americans aren't going to understand what we're
doing here. America only wants this amendment to be adopted. They
want the military involved in stopping drug traffic,'' said Davis.
   Today's vote came a day after Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci warned that he might recommend a veto of the bill unless
Congress votes enough money for Reagan's Star Wars missile defense
system.
   His admonition came as the Democratic-controlled House voted
223-195 to provide $3.5 billion for the Strategic Defense
Initiative, as Star Wars is formally known.
   That is $1.3 billion less than Reagan sought for the fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1 and is even below the current $3.9 billion budget
for the 5-year-old program.
   But the decision Wednesday is part of the maneuvering in the
complicated congressional budget process, according to Rep. Les
Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee.
   The Senate next week will begin considering its version of the
defense budget bill and even though that chamber is also controlled
by Democrats, it is more conservative and Reagan's defense program,
including Star Wars, has generally fared better in the Senate.
   The Senate bill proposes $4.6 billion for Star Wars. If that
figure remains, the House-Senate conference committee called to
reconcile differences will likely reach a compromise at about $4.1
billion, Aspin said.
   ``We'll probably split the difference in conference between our
$3.5 billion we voted today and the Senate number and come in
around $4.1 billion,'' Aspin said after the long series of votes.
   The House Armed Services Committee had originally recommended
$4.1 billion, but that was rejected on a 227-190 vote. Earlier, a
312-105 decision turned down an amendment to grant Reagan his
entire $4.9 billion request, and a 299-118 tally rejected another
proposal to block all SDI spending.
   Carlucci, in a letter read during the debate, said he was
unhappy with the $4.1 billion level voted by the committee because
it ``would cause major restructuring and delays in the program.
Further reductions in funding or other restrictions on the program
would have the gravest consequences.''
   Carlucci said that ``if the Congress sends the president a
defense bill that contains a funding level for SDI that is in my
view inadequate, I would have no choice but to recommend a veto of
that bill.''
   But his letter didn't define that inadequate level. Aspin said:
``I don't know exactly what it is, but I would think that if we do
come in at $4.1 billion, that would be enough. I would hope so.''
   Aspin noted that Reagan has threatened in past years to veto
Pentagon budget bills which contain Democratic-backed restrictions
the administration opposes, but has yet to carry out that threat.
   The House also voted 244-174 Wednesday to limit spending on
SDI's ``phase one'' to 40 percent of the total budget. ``Phase
one'' is aimed at building an early version of the missile defense
and current plans called for raising ``phase one'' spending from 40
percent to 50 percent of the SDI program.
</TEXT>
