<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InvestigatorShooting     05-05 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Investigator Shooting,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Shot In State Office, Employee Charged And Jailed Without Bond</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMBARD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state child protection worker with a
history of disciplinary problems shot her supervisor and a
co-worker in their office, killing one and critically injuring the
other, authorities say.
   Paulette M. Fiedler, 37, of Aurora, an investigator with the
state Department of Children and Family Services since 1980, was
ordered held without bond Thursday, said Assistant State's Attorney
Robert Kilander.
   Ms. Fiedler was charged Wednesday with murder and attempted
murder in the death of Dale Rowell, 39, of Wheaton, and the
wounding of Bob Heft, 38, of Villa Park.
   Police believe she walked into the office of Rowell, her
supervisor, Wednesday afternoon and shot him while he sat at his
desk.
   ``Mr. Rowell was on the telephone and told the person to whom he
had just been speaking that he had just been shot,'' said DCFS
spokeswoman Jo Warfield.
   Police said Heft apparently heard the shots and approached.
   ``Seeing what had happened, he turned to walk away and was shot
in the back,'' said Du Page County Sheriff's Lt. Bruce Wachtel.
   After the shooting, office workers said, Ms. Fiedler walked to
her desk and sat there until police arrested her.
   Heft was in critical condition today at Loyola University
Medical Center, said Linda Blaha, a spokeswoman.
   Ms. Warfield said DCFS officials were checking files to
determine what problems might have existed between Ms. Fiedler and
Rowell.
   ``I think it could be best characterized as a troubled
relationship with her supervisor,'' the spokeswoman said. She added
that she did not know if Ms. Fiedler had been threatened with
dismissal.
   But Ms. Warfield said Ms. Fiedler had ``experienced difficulties
in dealing with co-workers, and the department had been working
with her trying to resolve that.''
   The DCFS child-protection system recently came under fire from
employee representatives. Two women who had worked as agency
caseworkers were indicted in April on charges of criminal
misconduct for falsifying records of home visits. At issue in both
cases was the death of an abused child.
   Union leaders contend the two women are being used as scapegoats
for an overburdened system.
</TEXT>
