<HEAD>Administration Hopes No Deals Were Made for French Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration said today it still
does not believe in deals with hostage-takers and hopes none was
made for the freedom of the three French hostages released in
Lebanon.
   ``We hope that deals were not made of a kind that we object to
in our own policies on terrorism,'' White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said. ``We always hold the kidnappers responsible for the
safety of the hostages and we certainly hold them responsible for
the remaining hostages there.''
   ``We do not have details on the negotiations or what happened in
this case, but nevertheless our policy is unchanged,'' Fitzwater
said. ``We do not believe we should make deals with
hostage-takers.''
   Nine Americans, three Britons and six others are still believed
to be captive in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
