<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-DHLawrence     05-05 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-DH Lawrence,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banned D.H. Lawrence Novel To Be Published In China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   D.H. Lawrence, the controversial author whose
sexually explicit novel, ``Lady Chatterley's Lover,'' was
effectively banned in China last year, is now hailed here as one of
England's finest writers.
   For the past year, conservatives in China's leadership launched
a so-called ``anti-bourgeois liberalization campaign'' against
Western culture, and Lawrence's classic was one of the targets.
   Although the book was not illegal, the government had
discouraged its publication, according to the Press and Publication
Administration.
   In January, a publishing house in southern China's Hunan
province announced plans to again publish the novel, in addition to
a six-volume collection of Lawrence's works.
   ``Lawrence seems to be regaining his place in China's literary
community,'' said the official English-language China Daily on
Thursday. It said the change was the result of more open attitudes
toward art and literature.
   The author of the comments was Suo Tianzhang, an English
professor who wrote the introduction to the six-volume collection
of Lawrence works.
   Suo said the announcement by the North China Literature and Arts
Publishing House of plans to publish the novel ``heralded his
(Lawrence's) rehabilitation.''
   ``Lawrence is not a frivolous writer, and his `Lady Chatterley's
Lover' is not pornography,'' he said.
   ``Lady Chatterley's Lover,'' written in 1928, is the story of an
English noblewoman who has a love affair with her husband's
gamekeeper. It caused an uproar because of the explicit sex scenes
and was banned in the United States and England for many years.
   According to Suo, participants at a recent Chinese literary
seminar called Lawrence ``the most important English novelist since
Thomas Hardy, some placing him one niche higher than Irishman James
Joyce.''
   He said Lawrence was introduced to China in the late 1920s and
early 1930s but lost favor in the 1950s and was regarded as a
decadent writer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
