<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Hong Kong-Nuclear,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says New A-Plant Does Not Require Evacuation Planning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's construction of a nuclear power plant
43 miles away does not require Hong Kong to draw up an emergency
evacuation plan, a report released Thursday said.
   The report, drawn up for the British colony by the United
Kingdom Atomic Energy Authority, said Hong Kong is far enough away
from the Daya Bay plant that only monitoring and possibly control
of foodstuffs was needed in case of an accident, a government
statement said.
   The report called for establishment of a hot line between the
Daya Bay Control Center and Hong Kong's Royal Observatory.
   The Daya Bay plant is scheduled for completion in 1991.
   After the Chernobyl nuclear plant accident in the Soviet Union
in 1986, nearly 1 million Hong Kong's 5.7 million residents signed
petitions calling for the scrapping of Daya Bay.
</TEXT>
