<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RefineryBlast-Evacuees     05-05 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Refinery Blast-Evacuees,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``It Knocked Me To The Floor and ... Knocked Me Down Again''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refinery Blast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO S. FRANCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DESTREHAN, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neighbors of a Shell Oil Co. refinery said
thoughts of bombings, plane crashes or worse crossed their minds as
they were jolted out of bed today by an explosion.
   The powerful blast blew doors from their hinges and damaged
roofs, walls and furnishings. One plant worker died, several people
were missing and at least 30 people were injured, authorities said.
   About 2,800 people were briefly evacuated from the area around
the plant.
   ``When I first heard it, I thought it was either a small plane
crash or the Shell plant,'' said Alan Migliore, who lives about
three blocks from the refinery complex.
   ``I was sleeping in the kitchen and it knocked me to the floor.
From there, I looked up and could see that the whole area to the
Shell was on fire. ... It blew both of the front doors in, and the
deadbolts took the frames out,'' he said.
   His mother, Mary, said: ``I have a four-post bed and one of the
posts stopped the door from hitting me. That post saved my life.''
   Another neighbor, Adam Mashia, said: ``When it blew, it knocked
me out of bed. I had no idea what it was. It was just a great
thunder. It went boom and then boom again. It knocked me to the
floor and as I was getting up, it knocked me down again.''
   Mashia, 65, was among 55 people who sought shelter at Destrehan
High School.
   Mashia said he pulled on some clothes, got into his car and
drove to the shelter immediately. He noticed the ground was still
shaking as he made his way out of the house.
   ``It all went through my mind,'' he said. ``I thought, `Well,
maybe the Russians dropped a bomb.'''
   Eula Vickner, 53, was spending the night with her mother, Lelia
Landry, 80, across the street from Migliore. ``I was laid down on
the bed and then we heard the explosions. All the windows were
blown in and the doors,'' she said.
   Mrs. Landry said she had just spent more than $1,000 to buy a
new roof and repairs walls.
   ``It sounded like a big bomb. What am I going to do now?'' she
said.
</TEXT>
