<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--ThompsonMurder     05-05 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Thompson Murder,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reward for Killers of Racing Promoter Boosted to $255,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADBURY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slain racing promoter Mickey Thompson's
friends, relatives and associates boosted their reward for
information on the contract-style shootings of Thompson and his
wife to $255,000.
   The people who raised the reward also announced a 60-day
deadline on the offer in hopes of jarring a response from anyone
who may know about the March 16 killings.
   Police say they believe Thompson, 59, and his wife, Trudy, 41,
were the victims of hired killers, but have few leads.
   The reward had stood at $175,000 as of March 21.
   ``In addition to losing loved ones, it is the terrible feeling
of knowing that the person or persons who did this are still out
there somewhere, living scot free,'' Collene Thompson Campbell,
Thompson's sister, said Wednesday at a news conference.
   Investigators are circulating composite drawings of two men
believed to have been the gunmen and a third seen nearby.
   Thompson, the first driver to break the 400-mph land speed mark,
promoted motor sports events in arenas and stadiums.
</TEXT>
