<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Statue Thefts,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crooks Snatch Lawn Art Worth $15,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thieves have plucked lawn art worth
nearly $15,000 from three homes, police said.
   In the latest theft, John Childs said the life-sized bronze
statue of an Oriental woman playing a flute vanished from his lawn
Monday or Tuesday.
   ``They had to be very clever,'' Childs said. ``The statue was
secured on a coral stone and pedestal, and they didn't take the
pedestal.''
   The lawn ornaments were taken since last weekend, police
spokesman Craig Gunkel said Wednesday.
   The largest theft occurred Friday night, when two ``extremely
heavy'' bronze sphinxes were unbolted from their marble pedestals
in a yard, Gunkel said. The 2-foot statues are worth about $4,500
each.
   In another incident, a 19th-century stone urn valued at $500 was
stolen, police said.
