<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WVa-Senate     05-05 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WVa-Senate,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Byrd Concentrating On General Election, Not Tuesday's Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE M. ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With heated races for governor and
state Supreme Court competing for the voters' attention, Sen.
Robert C. Byrd's bid for a sixth term has attracted little notice
in West Virginia _ and that's just fine with him.
   Byrd, who recently announced he is giving up his post as Senate
majority leader, faces only a nominal challenge in Tuesday's
Democratic primary.
   The 71-year-old politician, who has become a fiddle-playing
institution in the Mountain State, held several fund-raisers last
fall but plans no campaign stops and no media blitz before the
primary, said Tina Evans, a spokeswoman for the senator.
   ``In the early stages of the campaign, I am focusing on talking
with individual West Virginians, getting around the state and
working for West Virginia in the Senate,'' Byrd said.
   His only opponent in the primary is 59-year-old former state
Board of Education member Bob E. Myers who says ``no one should be
allowed to run unopposed, especially in a six-year office.''
   Byrd has amassed a 1988 election war chest of more than $1
million, while Myers said in his latest spending report that he has
raised nothing and spent $212.
   In the Republican primary, freshman state Sen. Jay Wolfe faces
Bernie Lumbert of Buckhannon, a welfare recipient whose campaign
consists maily of telephoning reporters to relate tales of
conspiracies by public officials.
   Byrd's announcement that he would give up his majority leader
job amid growing dissatisfaction over his style of leadership among
fellow Democrats in Washington. He said that if Democrats retain
control of the Senate next year, he would assume the chairmanship
of the Senate Appropriations Committee in an effort to funnel more
federal dollars to West Virginia.
   Byrd acknowledged that ``the economic recovery that other
regions have enjoyed for the most part bypassed our state.''
   He said he ``cannot work miracles'' but will have ``a new
opportunity to have a more direct influence on the allocation of
our nation's scarce fiscal resources.''
   Byrd's move has been labeled a demotion by some political
observers, and Republican Gov. Arch Moore said he would be
``hard-pressed to suggest West Virginians will notice any
difference as a result of the change.''
   Wolfe, 33, decided to try for Byrd's Senate seat after backing
out of the gubernatorial primary, in which he would have faced
Moore and Morgantown millionaire John Raese.
   Wolfe flew to Washington earlier this year to discuss his plans
with the Republican National Senatorial Committee and hopes to
raise at least $250,000 for the general election.
   In the state Senate, Wolfe primarily has been a proponent of
right-to-work legislation and also has called for a constitutional
amendment to prohibit abortion on demand.
   Lumbert, 57, said he is on welfare and cannot afford to spend
money on the election. He said he campaigns as often as he can
``for free'' by addressing groups and organizations, but his
requests to speak to groups nearly always are turned down.
   ``I'm a very hated person,'' Lumbert said. ``I'm probably the
most despised person in the state.''
   The primary ballot will be crowded with contests, including
Moore vs. Raese and seven Democrats competing for their party's
nomination for governor. In addition, five Democrats are battling
for two nominations to the state Supreme Court, including
incumbents Darrell McGraw and Thomas Miller. Two issues in the
bitter campaign have been allegations that the court is
anti-business, and complaints about McGraw's repeated run-ins with
court employees, sheriff's deputies, lawyers amd reporters.
</TEXT>
