<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Carlucci-NATO     05-05 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci-NATO,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Asking Allies To Pay More for Defense Is Risky Game, Carlucci Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional demands that America's allies
pay more for defense are misguided and amount to a ``high-stakes
game of `chicken''' that the United States can't afford to play,
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said Thursday.
   Carlucci, addressing the Foreign Policy Association in New York
City, said recent attacks in Congress on the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and other allies like Japan and South Korea suggest
``a growing inclination towards isolationism _ a kind of withdrawal
syndrome from our international obligations and interests.''
   ``It is now quite commonly assumed that the United States
carries more than its `fair share' of the burdens of alliance
defense, and that in return America gets little in the way of
support or even appreciation from its allies,'' the defense
secretary said.
   ``Calls for cutting back our contributions to our alliances _ or
punishing allies who fail to contribute more _ are getting a
hearing. These proposals are sometimes recommended as a sort of
shock treatment that will result in our allies deciding to shoulder
more responsibility for alliance security.
   ``Well, I do not think we should risk our security interests in
what is in effect little more than a high-stakes game of `chicken.'
We cannot trust to chance America's national security.''
   The Pentagon released a copy of the speech in Washington.
Carlucci aides described the address as a statement of policy aimed
at the growing number of members of Congress who have begun
attacking the NATO alliance.
   Last week the House voted on two different proposals to reduce
the number of American troops in Europe. While both proposals were
defeated, the debate featured harsh attacks on NATO by the two
sponsors, Reps. John Bryant, D-Texas, and Tommy Robinson, D-Ark.
   ``Let's get smart and begin to tell our allies that we expect
them to pay their fair share,'' Bryant said at the time. ``We are
subsidizing their defense.''
   Robinson was even more blunt. ``The real purpose of this
amendment is to demonstrate to our allies that we've had it. These
people are stealing our jobs because we have been suckered into
paying for their defense.''
   But in his speech, Carlucci said the United States does not
maintain alliances ``as a favor to our allies. We do so because it
is in our interest. Collective security and the strategy of forward
defense have been central to our national security for more than
four decades.''
   Over and beyond military factors, America's economy depends upon
international trade, the secretary continued.
   ``And we cannot expect to protect those interests and prosper if
we isolate ourselves from the rest of the world,'' Carlucci said.
``The implications for our national security should be clear: We
cannot hope to expand our economic horizons at the very moment we
scale back our international security commitments.''
   On the other hand, there is no question but that ``there remains
room for improvement'' on defense spending among the allies, he
said.
   ``Determining an equitable allocation of roles, risks and
responsibilities among 16 sovereign NATO partners is not an easy
task,'' Carlucci said.
   ``But, clearly, the United States will be hard pressed to
persuade its allies to do more to bolster their defenses if we
ourselves succumb to the temptation to do less,'' he concluded.
</TEXT>
