<DOCNO> AP880505-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-EasternAirlines     05-05 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern Airlines,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Urges DOT To Widen Probe of Eastern Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee approved legislation today
urging the Transportation Department to widen its investigation of
Eastern Airlines and its parent company, Texas Air Corp.
   By a voice vote, the Public Works and Transportation Committee
sent the measure to the full House. The resolution already has 210
co-sponsors, nearly half the House's membership.
   The resolution is non-binding, and simply states that the
Department of Transportation should look more closely at the
management, labor practices and safety procedures of Texas Air and
Eastern.
   But the issue has aroused strong feelings among lawmakers, whom
the company's management and labor unions have been lobbying hard
for support. The airline has been seeking wage concessions from
workers, and the two sides have been fighting each other for months
in Congress, the courts and in newspaper advertisements.
   ``Morale is very much related to ability to do the job,'' said
the measure's original sponsor, Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif.,
chairman of the House aviation subcommittee. ``And to me, that very
much becomes a safety concern.''
   The Transportation Department said last month that it would
examine the management and business practices of Texas Air,
Eastern, and Continental Airlines, another Texas affiliate. The
congressional resolution calls on the department to look more
closely at how Texas Air's and Eastern's practices affect the
public.
   In another development, Eastern asked a federal appeals panel
today to overturn a contempt citation and injunction barring the
sale of its shuttle, but the court questioned whether it had
jurisdiction in the case.
   Philip A. Lacovara, an attorney representing the financially
troubled airline, told the U.S. Court of Appeals panel that selling
the Northeast shuttle operations was ``essential to Eastern's
ability to survive.''
   Eastern last year arranged to sell its profitable Boston-New
York-Washington shuttle to a newly created Texas Air subsidiary for
$225 million.
   The International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers, AFL-CIO, challenged the proposed sale and transfer to the
new subsidiary of about 6,000 jobs, claiming a violation of the
collective bargaining agreement.
   ``This is part and parcel of a scheme to dismantle Eastern
Airlines to rid Texas Air of its only unionized subsidiary,''
contended union attorney Joseph Guerrieri Jr.
   In March, U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt held Eastern in
contempt for trying to sell the shuttle in violation of his July 2,
1987, injunction directing Eastern to maintain the status quo under
its contract with the union. He barred Eastern from taking further
steps to sell the shuttle.
   Appeals Court Judge Harry Edwards told Lacovara that since the
case was still pending before Pratt and contempt citations could
rarely be appealed, there was doubt as to whether the appeals court
had jurisdiction at this stage.
   ``There is a significant question as to whether you are properly
here because contempt citations are not generally appealable,''
Edwards said.
   Eastern contends that the proposed sale is a ``managerial
prerogative'' that does not affect the collective bargaining
agreement. The union says the sale is in violation of the Railway
Labor Act because it changes working conditions without an attempt
at bargaining.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
