<2ND_LINE>PM-Fire Arrest, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0640,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrest Made in Rooming House Fire Deaths</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th-5th grafs, `Brady set ...,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with prosecutor's, defense lawyer's comments on motive, other
details, bail set</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-year-old man pleaded innocent today to
15 counts of second-degree murder and one count of arson in
connection with a rooming house fire that killed 15 people four
years ago on the Fourth of July.
   James Carver broke down, shaking and in tears, during the
reading of the indictment in Salem Superior Court before Judge
Peter Brady. He left the courtroom for 15 minutes to regain his
composure.
   Carver, of Ipswich, was accompanied by his wife, MaryJane, 21,
his parents and his attorney, Dennis Jackson.
   Carver was arrested Wednesday night on a warrant after an Essex
County grand jury handed up a sealed indictment. Brady set bail at
$1 million surety or $100,00 cash. A pre-trial conference was set
for May 23.
   Jealousy and a love-triangle were the apparent motives, Essex
County District Attorney Kevin Burke said today. He said Carver
formerly was engaged to a woman who was dating a resident of the
boarding house. The alleged target of Carver's jealousy died in the
fire.
   Burke said Carver was among many early suspects because he had
been seen around the rooming house right after the fire. But he
said the case was cracked when an unidentified individual told
police that Carver had confessed.
   But Jackson said Carver was asleep at home in Danvers when the
fire broke out. Jackson said Carver ``feels pretty strongly that
they don't have a case against him'' but that he was not surprised
by the indictment.
   The July 4, 1984, predawn fire at the Elliott Chambers rooming
house was the worst in Beverly's history.
   It shocked local and state officials into improving safety for
boarding houses, which accommodate people who often have nowhere
else to go.
   The 36 people staying at the seedy, 35-year-old rooming house
the night of the fire were a mix of the elderly, welfare
recipients, people released from psychiatric hospitals and drifters.
   The fire began in the front stairway of the three-story, wooden
building, trapping people inside. The building had no sprinklers,
although it had a new fire alarm.
   Flames raced up the stairs and through the top floor, trapping
six people in their beds. Others died while trying to beat down a
locked entryway. One man died after jumping from a third-story
window. All told, 14 people died in the fire and another died later.
   Six of the dead were so badly charred they could only be
identified through dental records and jewelry found on their bodies.
   Investigators said the fire was deliberately set and that it was
started in newspapers inside a locked front door.
   In the aftermath of the fire in this town 25 miles north of
Boston, fire officials stepped up enforcement of safety codes, the
state Department of Mental Health expanded fire safety training for
mentally ill patients and the state enacted a law giving the
communities the option to require sprinklers in rooming houses.
   After the fire, the building was converted to office space.
</TEXT>
