<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Activist     05-05 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Activist,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freed Activist Says He Can't Return To Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An prominent labor activist freed from a
Polish jail so he could receive medical treatment abroad said
Thursday he was forced off a plane and deported after he flew back
to Poland.
   Morawiecki, leader of a militant splinter group of the outlawed
trade union federation Solidarity, said Polish officials initially
told him he would be allowed to return home, then blocked his
attempt to return Wednesday.
   Morawiecki, a 47-year-old physicist, is the head of the
underground group known as Fighting Solidarity.
   He was flown from Poland last week just as a series of tense
labor strikes and political demonstrations were beginning. He was
allowed out under a deal worked out by the Roman Catholic Church.
   ``I think the church was cheated as much as I was. The
authorities broke their guarantee to me and to the church that I
would be able to go back,'' he said.
   In Warsaw, a Polish government official confirmed that
Morawiecki tried to return home Wednesday. The official said
Morawiecki was given the choice of jail or leaving the country and
chose to leave.
   Morawiecki said he was jailed in November while authorities
investigated what he called bogus charges of smuggling.
   Speaking through an interpreter, Morawiecki said he and fellow
prisoner Andrzej Kolodzej were released from jail in Warsaw on
Saturday on the condition they travel to Rome for medical treatment.
   But after learning of the labor strikes in Poland, the men
refused to board the plane and were returned to prison, Morawiecki
said.
   Two intermediaries from the Roman Catholic church persuaded the
men to depart, arguing that refusal to leave would jeopardize
church efforts to solve similar cases for other prisoners,
Morawiecki said.
   The men flew to Rome, he said. Kolodzej started to receive
treatment for suspected duodenal cancer, but Morawiecki said
doctors found nothing seriously wrong with him, and he decided to
return to Poland.
   Polish authorities had given the men passports containing stamps
permitting them to return to Poland until 1991, he said.
   However, Morawiecki said he was denied permission Tuesday to
board a flight from Rome to Warsaw on Polish LOT airlines. The next
day, he took a flight from Frankfurt to Warsaw but was taken from
the plane by police, held for four or five hours and then put on a
plane for Vienna.
   Morawiecki said authorities canceled the stamp on his passport
allowing him to return to Poland.
</TEXT>
