<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC--Malaria     05-05 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--Malaria,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Malaria Continues To Pose Risk To Many U.S. Travelers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Malaria continues to pose a risk for U.S.
travelers to many countries, striking about 1,000 a year, federal
experts said Thursday.
   The national Centers for Disease Control, in its weekly report,
reviewed for physicians and other health and travel professionals
the details of pre-travel precautions and post-infection treatment
for malaria.
   The disease, which causes fever and flu-like symptoms and can be
fatal, is transmitted by mosquitoes.
   Although malaria is almost never reported in the United States,
transmission continues in parts of Central and South America,
sub-Saharan Africa, the Indian subcontinent, Southeast Asia, the
Middle East and the Pacific Islands, the CDC said.
   ``All travelers to malaria-endemic areas are advised to use an
appropriate drug regimen and personal protection measures to
prevent malaria,'' the CDC said. ``However, travelers must be
informed that, regardless of methods employed, malaria can still be
contracted.''
   The CDC recommends that most travelers to malaria areas begin
taking anti-malaria drugs a week or two before travel, continuing
during the trip and for four weeks afterward.
   In some areas, the drug chloroquine should be sufficient, but
resistance to that drug has become widespread in malaria areas, the
CDC said.
   ``That's the reason that nowadays the risk of malaria is much
higher than it used to be,'' said Dr. Hans Lobel, a CDC malaria
specialist.
   An alternate drug, Fansidar, can cause severe and even fatal
skin reactions, the CDC cautioned. Travelers to areas with
chloroquine-resistant malaria should carry a dose of Fansidar and
take it only if they develop a feverish illness when professional
care is not available, the Atlanta-based agency said.
   ``We really discourage the drug ... it's caused so many serious
adverse reactions,'' Lobel said. ``We are really waiting for some
more effective and safer drugs to come down.''
   Each year, malaria strikes about 1,000 Americans traveling
abroad, Lobel said, noting that if a traveler takes no precautions,
the risk in an area such as west Africa is about one in 50.
   The risk in Kenya, where many Americans traveling to Africa
visit, is about one in 200.
   In addition to drug precautions, the CDC urges travelers in
malaria areas to take other precautions at night, when mosquitoes
feed. These include wearing clothes that cover most of the body and
using mosquito nets and insect repellent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
