<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MoneyRecovered     05-05 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Recovered,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nothing Routine On This Trash Collection Route</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENID, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raymond Keller was routinely following his
trash collection route when he found that someone had put out a
better quality trash than usual _ a pile of bills that added up to
$2,178.
   ``I thought, `What did somebody do, rob a bank or something?'''
Keller said Wednesday.
   He stuffed the money in his pocket, finished his route and went
to his boss for advice. Then Keller went to Garfield County Sheriff
Bob Burnett.
   ``He came in and said he needed to talk to me and then reached
into his pocket and pulled out a wad of bills,'' Burnett said. ``We
counted it over and over and it came to $2,178.''
   Burnett traced the money to a businessman, at whose home the
money was found with the trash.
   The businessman, who asked to remain anonymous, said the money
accidentally got in the trash when his wife cleaned out his safe.
   Keller, who was given a $200 reward, said he never thought about
keeping the money.
   ``My dad told me you've got to be honest and stay honest. If you
get into trouble you aren't going to get out,'' he said.
</TEXT>
