<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Prisons-Cubans 1stLd-Writethru a0630 05-05 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prisons-Cubans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630,270</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Edits thruout to quote directly from report</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at two federal prisons where Cuban
inmates rioted last November failed to secure the facilities partly
because early signs of trouble were not relayed to them by prison
personnel, according to a Justice Department report.
   Officials at the Oakdale, La., and Atlanta, Ga., federal prisons
also had no plans for dealing with institution-wide disturbances,
said the report, dated Feb. 1 but not made available until
Wednesday.
   The rioting, which lasted for eight days at Oakdale and 11 days
at Atlanta, included the taking of prison guards as hostages and
resulted in one death of a detainee and millions of dollars in
damage to the institutions. It was triggered by a State Department
announcement of a pact with Cuba that would have led to deportation
of some of the inmates.
   The report said ``takeovers as complete as those at Oakdale and
Atlanta literally were unimagined.''
   It said Oakdale officials ignored ``warning signs,'' including
an inmate food fight in the cafeteria, and said important
information was not conveyed to the warden or other officials.
   On Atlanta, the report said Warden Joseph Petrovsky ``would have
attempted a lock-down had he received enough reliable information
that a disturbance was likely.'' It said he was told by his staff
that Atlanta inmates were calm after the Oakdale rioting began.
   ``In actuality,'' the report said, ``line staff had overheard
detainees' conversations about hostage-taking, received warnings
from informants and noticed other indications of potential unrest.''
   Thomas Boyd, assistant attorney general, acknowledged in a
letter accompanying the report that Justice Department training
programs dealing with emergency responses and hostage situations
``may be further improved.''
</TEXT>
