<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dyson     05-05 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dyson,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dyson Denies Rumors of Homosexuality</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STUCKEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUGHESVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emerging from seclusion following the
apparent suicide of his top aide, Rep. Roy Dyson firmly denied that
either he or the aide were homosexuals.
   The Maryland Democrat said at a Wednesday news conference that
he thinks Tom Pappas committed suicide Sunday because he believed
his reputation would be destroyed by a story in The Washington Post.
   The Post had reported that Pappas imposed unorthodox demands on
young male staffers, requiring them to attend social functions,
asking one to perform a strip tease at a staff retreat and firing
another for leaving a party.
   Pappas, Dyson's administrative aide and campaign manager, died
in a fall from the 24th floor of a New York hotel on Sunday.
   Asked the nature of his relationship with the 46-year-old
Pappas, who had been with him throughout his political career,
Dyson said the two ``were very, very good friends.''
   ``He was like a brother. We had a personal and professional
relationship,'' Dyson said.
   Dyson was asked if Pappas was a homosexual.
   ``No, he was not,'' he said.
   ``Are you?'' he was asked.
   ``No, I am not,'' he replied firmly.
   Dyson complained that the Post story was based on interviews
with a few disgruntled former staffers and gave only one side of
the story.
   ``What I would certainly have preferred was that the other side
be given a chance,'' he said. However, he admitted that the Post
had asked him for comment on the original story and he had declined
on the advice of his attorneys.
   Dyson said he, Pappas and Todd Skipper, another staff member,
had gone to New York for a long-scheduled trip to visit a defense
contractor's plant. He said part of the expenses, including
Saturday night tickets to the hit musical ``Phantom of the Opera,''
were paid for by the contractor.
   Reviewing the hours before Pappas died, Dyson said he talked to
his aide twice after the Post story was read to Pappas by a staffer
in Maryland on Sunday morning.
   ``The impression I had was that he was very upbeat, that we
could cope with it,'' Dyson said. But he said Pappas also knew
``that his reputation would be ruined.''
   Dyson said he doesn't recall the contents of a note left in the
room by Pappas, but that it was not addressed to anyone, did not
mention any names and ``did not seem like a suicide note to me.''
   The congressman said he didn't think his chances of winning
another term will be hurt by publicity surrounding Pappas' death.He
said he has a new chief of staff, Katie Tucker, and a new campaign
chairman, Christopher Robinson, and is ready to get back to work.
   Dyson said Pappas made some mistakes, but called him ``a man of
integrity, of compassion.''
</TEXT>
