<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlantBlast-Fuel 1stLd-Writethru a0546 05-05 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Blast-Fuel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0546,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blast Could Cause Shuttle Booster Production Delays, Thiokol Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 6th, ``If the Pacific xxx, to include
definition of oxidizer; adds five grafs at end, Pentagon comment</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Plant Blast, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The destruction of a Nevada plant that
makes fuel for the space shuttle could delay production for the
shuttle's booster rocket, but NASA says it probably won't delay the
shuttle's next flight.
   The explosions Wednesday leveled the Pacific Engineering &
Production Co. plant at Henderson, Nev., but Billie Deason, a NASA
spokeswoman in Houston, said the Kerr-McGee plant in Henderson
could provide Morton Thiokol Inc. with the oxidizer, ammonium
perchlorate, used in the boosters.
   ``The production of both suppliers was planned to support a
shuttle flight rate of about 24 per year. We don't expect supply
problems,'' she said.
   Don Amitor, a spokesman for NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center
in Huntsville, Ala., said Thiokol had enough ammonium perchlorate
for the next five shuttle launches. Under the present schedule, the
fifth launch would be in mid-1989.
   However, Thiokol spokesman Rocky Raab said there could be
performance differences in the oxidizers produced by the two plants.
   ``If the Pacific Engineering plant is down for an indefinite
period of time, there could be delays in our production,'' Raab
said. ``We're looking into our stockpiles to determine how much of
the material we have.''
   An oxidizer is needed in the booster rockets to provide an
oxygen supply so that the rockets' fuel can ignite and burn.
   Raab said the matter is complicated further because government
specifications for solid-fuel rockets are based on which plant
produces the oxidizer.
   ``Whatever supplier made the materials for the motor you qualify
for, that's the supplier you're supposed to use in the kind of
motor you're making,'' he said.
   ``We're determining what motors were designed for the ammonium
perchlorate we got from Pacific Engineering. We just don't have an
answer yet on exactly how we'll be affected.''
   Every solid-fuel rocket motor made in the United States has some
ammonium perchlorate in it, and only Kerr-McGee and Pacific
Engineering produce it. Thiokol buys material from both plants, as
do other aerospace companies and the Department of Defense.
   ``The Department of Defense could step in and claim all the
production at Kerr-McGee,'' Raab said.
   Ted Olsen, spokesman for rocket-maker Hercules Inc. in Magna,
Utah, said Kerr-McGee and Pacific Engineering also supply Hercules
with oxidizer. He said company officials are working to determine
what impact the plant's destruction will have on Hercules.
   A Pentagon official, who asked not to be named, said it was
``certainly premature'' to suggest the Defense Department might
monopolize production at Kerr-McGee.
   ``We do not expect to see any immediate impact,'' the official
added.
   According to the Pentagon, ammonium perchlorate is used on the
MX, Titan and Minuteman missiles and would be needed if a decision
is made to build the Midgetman mobile nuclear missile.
   The Pentagon and armed forces do not contract with Pacific
Engineering directly, however, instead leaving that to three prime
contractors: Morton Thiokol; Hercules, and Aerojet.
   The first 50 MX missiles are now being deployed and the accident
won't affect that work, the Pentagon added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
