<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Captain Kangaroo is OK for kids, but some
students at Western Connecticut State University say it could be a
tad embarrassing to have Bob Keeshan as commencement speaker.
   ``This is the first time in 35 years I have encountered this
reaction,'' Keeshan said Wednesday from his Babylon, N.Y., home.
``I don't know what they expect, Mr. Moose and dropping pingpong
balls? I will give them stuff to think about and if they can't be
open to my message, then WestConn did not do a good job on them.''
   Supporters note that Keeshan, 61, has received the Peabody Award
for Outstanding Television three times and six Emmy Awards, among
other honors.
   But Joshua P. Marks, a senior, wrote in a letter to the school
newspaper: ``I'm sure Captain Kangaroo is a delightful fellow, but
it is of the opinion of many students he offers no insight or
inspirational impetus for our seniors to attain career pursuits.''
   Rick Haught, the school's assistant director of student
activities, worked with the senior class in picking Keeshan for the
May 15 ceremonies.
   ``OK, I'll admit it, I love the Captain!'' Haught wrote in the
school paper. ``But Captain Kangaroo is not the person who will be
addressing our new graduates, Bob Keeshan the man, will.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa, awarded the Nobel Peace
Prize for her work with the poor and sick in India, will establish
a mission in Memphis, the Roman Catholic bishop of Memphis said.
   The mission could be a hospice for AIDS patients, a home for
abused mothers and children or a home for unwed mothers, Bishop
Daniel M. Buechlein said Wednesday.
   ``It's not a question of if, it's a question of when,'' said
Buechlein.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henny Youngman remembers the Brooklyn
neighborhood where he grew up as tough ...
   ``My neighborhood was so tough,'' he said, ``I played a
nightclub there _ my boss used to stab me good night.''
   Youngman has been selected as the homecoming king for the sixth
annual Welcome Back to Brooklyn festival, and the legendary
comedian is already dusting off some lines for the June 12 affair.
   Youngman follows singer Connie Stevens, comedian Danny Kaye,
singer Ben Vereen and comedian Dom DeLuise as the reigning monarch
of the festival, expected to draw 20,000.
   Born in London in 1906, Youngman came to Brooklyn as an infant.
   ``I've got a lot of Brooklyn jokes,'' he told New York Newsday.
``Thousands of them, committed to memory. Consider yourself
warned.''
   He paused. He couldn't resist. ``Take Brooklyn. Please,'' he
said. ``And I'm taking it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Scottsdale-based company that markets a
product called Rain-X is suing Andy Rooney.
   The company is displeased with remarks the commentator made
April 17 on CBS's ``60 Minutes.'' In short, Rooney said Rain-X
doesn't work.
   The lawsuit, filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Phoenix,
names Rooney and CBS Inc. as defendants.
   Unelko, the company that markets Rain-X, is seeking $15 million
in punitive damages, saying Rooney's comments tarnished the
reputation of its product.
   Rain-X is a liquid that, when applied to a vehicle's windshield,
is supposed to make rain and snow roll off more quickly to improve
visibility.
   An attorney for CBS, Douglas Jacobs in New York, said that when
Unelko demanded a retraction, CBS officials asked them to make an
official request by letter, but Unelko declined.
   CBS had ``60 Minutes'' anchor Mike Wallace read a letter on the
air Sunday from race-car driver Mario Andretti praising Rain-X. But
Wallace also noted that Andretti is a spokesman for Unelko.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Devil in the White House'' provoked the
Battle of the Publishing Houses, and suspense novelist Lawrence
Sanders is richer for it.
   His latest book sold at auction Wednesday for $2.85 million in a
tug-of-war among eight publishing houses. The Putnam Publishing
Group bought the hardback and paperback rights.
   The author of such successful novels as ``The Anderson Tapes''
and ``The First Deadly Sin,'' Sanders demanded and got a 15 percent
royalty on all hardcover and paperback sales. Under most contracts,
hardcover royalties begin at 10 percent, while paperback royalties
rarely reach 15 percent until hundreds of thousands of copies are
sold.
   It was the second blockbuster literary sale this week. On
Monday, Simon & Schuster and Pocket Books agreed to pay
mystery-suspense writer Mary Higgins Clark a minimum $10.1 million
for four books and a collection of short stories.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Librarians and manuscript curators are uneasy
about Nobel laureate Saul Bellow's plans to sell all rough draft
material from his 1970 novel ``Mr. Sammler's Planet.''
   The unprecedented sale has them echoing the concerns of Lola
Szladits, curator of the Berg Collection of the New York Public
Library. She worries that a purchase by an investor will cut
scholars' access to the archive.
   ``For him (Bellow) it's over, but it's not over for the reader
and the literary critic, and it is not over in the flow of literary
history,'' Ms. Szladits said. ``The written traces of great
creative minds will just disappear if their manuscripts do.''
   The material is on loan to the Regenstein Library of the
University of Chicago, where Bellow is a professor of English and
social thought.
   The four handwritten notebooks, typescript, galleys and all
papers relating to the book go on the block June 7 at Sotheby's. It
will be the first archive of a major living author's published work
to be auctioned, and the first manuscript material sold by Bellow.
   The pre-sale estimate of the collection's value is $60,000 to
$100,000, according to David Redden, head of Sotheby's books and
manuscripts department.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trade, presidential politics, women in politics
and ice breakers were among the topics of conversation between the
prime minister of Finland and Lt. Gov. Evelyn Murphy.
   Prime Minister Harri Holkeri, who said he was in the United
States to celebrate the 350th anniversary of the landing of the
first Finns in America, flew to Boston from Washington.
   ``Most of the ice breakers in the world are made in Finland and
used all over ... except in the United States,'' Holkeri said.
   He added, with some pride, that the Finns also make cruise ships
_ including the Pacific Princess, featured in television's ``The
Love Boat.''
   Holkeri also called it ``quite obvious'' that Gov. Michael S.
Dukakis will be the Democratic presidential nominee and told Murphy
``I'm informed that your personal future is involved.''
   ``Yes, I'm cheering him on,'' Murphy said.
</TEXT>
