<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   05-05 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settlers March Near Beita, Army Shuts Down West Bank Commerce</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for Beita-dated item on digest</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAPPUAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops barking orders
through megaphones demanded a three-day halt to all West Bank
commerce Thursday and threatened to weld shut the shops of defiant
Arab merchants.
   Near the village of Beita, where an Israeli teen-ager was slain
last month, hundreds of Jewish settlers trudged along a mountain
path waving Israeli flags. They chanted ``expel the Arabs!'' and
vowed not to leave the occupied West Bank.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, troops fired tear gas at about 150
children who set tires ablaze and raised the Palestinian flag to
protest the army's closing of Arab schools.
   Israeli troops ordered the ban on West Bank commerce to punish
Arab residents for a one-day strike Wednesday that was called by
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Soldiers ordered shops to stay closed until Sunday, and they
threatened to weld shut the shops of merchants who disobeyed the
mandate.
   In Jericho, the army shut down the West Bank's largest vegetable
market, and stores were ordered shut in Nablus, Jenin, Tulkarem,
Hebron and Bethlehem.
   In Nablus, troops erected roadblocks and prevented Arab taxis
and buses from leaving the city to punish residents for adhering to
Wednesday's work stoppage, which paralyzed the occupied territories.
   Businessman Saed Kenaan of Nablus said the army action was aimed
at creating dissension between Palestinians and the underground
leaders who order the strikes.
   ``It's clear the Israelis are trying to drive a wedge between
the people and the leaders,'' Kenaan said. ``But people are aware
of the Israeli games.''
   In Gaza City, scores of school children chanting ``PLO yes,
Israel no!'' hoisted the Palestinian flag onto a pole at a school
run by the United Nations Relief and Works Agency, an Arab reporter
said. The Palestinian flag is outlawed in Israel.
   Troops fired tear gas to disperse the children, who erected
barricades of boulders and set tires ablaze in front of the school,
the reporter said.
   During a four-hour march Thursday, about 1,000 Jewish settlers,
many with rifles slung over their shoulders, retraced the route
taken by teen-age hikers when a bloody clash erupted April 6 at the
Arab village of Beita. A 15-year-old Israeli girl and two
Palestinians were killed.
   ``We want to finish what we started 30 days ago,'' said Menachem
Ilan, one of two armed escorts with the hikers last month. ``We
intend to show people everywhere that the nation of Israel can walk
freely in every part of the land of Israel.''
   ``I'm proud to do it again, but it feels like a nightmare,''
said 15-year-old Ariel Avivi, one of 16 teen-agers who took part in
the April hike.
   In a report that caused an uproar in Israel, the army determined
the slain girl, Tirza Porat, was accidentally shot to death by an
Israeli guard accompanying the hikers. But Jewish settlers have
accused Arabs have causing her death by stoning the hikers.
   The girl and a soldier are the only Israelis to die since
Palestinians began their five-month uprising against Israeli rule
in the occupied lands. According to U.N. figures, 183 Palestinians
have died in the violence.
   On Thursday, the hikers clapped and sang nationalist songs as
they trekked along a rocky path that began in the Jewish settlement
of Tappuah, about five miles south of Beita. It ended at an army
base about eight miles away, where the settlers held a ceremony in
the girl's honor.
   The march did not go through the village of Beita or to the dry
riverbed nearby where the Israeli hikers clashed with Arab
villagers. Organizers of the march said it followed the route the
hikers intended to take before they were led by the Arabs into
Beita.
   A military helicopter circled overhead and dozens oftroops
watched the march from a mountaintop.
   ``We want to show those Arabs they can't destroy us and we're
not afraid of them,'' said 15-year-old Rina Efrach, from the nearby
settlement of Kadumim. ``Of course I'm afraid personally, but we
can't show that because then they will break us.''
</TEXT>
