<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1421EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Extradition 1stLd-Writethru a0698 05-05 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Extradition, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0698,460</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 2 grafs after 4th graf pvs, A federal, with
prosecutor's comments, defense plans.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Supreme Court justice today refused to block
the extradition of a former Argentine general charged with 39
murders in his country's so-called ``dirty war'' against suspected
subversives in the 1970s.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, by denying an emergency request,
cleared the way for the return of Carlos G. Suarez-Mason to
Argentina from San Francisco, where he is in the custody of federal
marshals.
   He had sought to stay in this country while a federal appeals
court studies his case.
   A federal judge and the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
previously had refused to grant Suarez-Mason any emergency help.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Zanides, who represented the
Argentine government in the case, said O'Connor's action removes
the last practical barrier to Suarez-Mason's extradition. Zanides
said all records in the case are now in the hands of the State
Department, which makes the final decision on extraditions.
   Lawyers for Suarez-Mason have said that if the courts refuse
emergency intervention, they will ask Secretary of State George
Shultz to postpone action on an extradition until their appeal of
last week's ruling can be heard in full.
   Suarez-Mason, 64, was a high-ranking general in Argentina's Army
during the reign of a military junta that took power after
President Juan Peron's death in 1974.
   Suarez-Mason commanded one of five military zones, the one in
which the capital city of Buenas Aires was located.
   According to U.S. District Judge D. Lowell Jensen, the military
junta's method of dealing with suspected opponents ``was direct:
abduct anyone they suspected of subversion off the street or out of
their homes; transport them to secret detention centers; torture
them physically, psychologically and often sexually; and, in vast
numbers, kill them.''
   Jensen said more than 12,000 people disappeared, and were
presumably killed, during the junta's reign, which ended in 1983.
The judge said some 5,000 people disappeared in the military zone
commanded by Suarez-Mason.
   He faces charges on 39 counts of homicide in Argentina.
   Suarez-Mason asked O'Connor to postpone his extradition, which
he said could be imminent, until the 9th Circuit court considers a
formal appeal he has filed with it.
   If Suarez-Mason is turned over to Argentine officials before
then, his lawyers said, ``his appeal becomes meaningless.''
   The emergency request said a treaty between the United States
and Argentina forbids extradition for either political or military
offenses.
   Suarez-Mason also has been sued in U.S. courts by survivors of
the military junta's ``dirty war.''
   A federal judge in San Francisco recently ordered him to pay
$21.7 million in damages to Horacio Martinez-Baca, an Argentine
lawyer who was imprisoned and tortured for four years in the Buenas
Aires area but now lives in Oakland, Calif.
   Suarez-Mason's ability to pay any of the judgment against him
remains a matter of contention.
   The case is Suarez-Mason vs. Robinson, A-847.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
