<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ContraAid 2ndLd-Writethru a0679 05-05 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0679,740</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs from Contras' news conference after 3rd graf
pvs, Fitzwater said</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration today charged
Nicaragua's government with systematically undermining peace talks
by moves that a Republican congressman said are designed to hold up
U.S. humanitarian aid to the Contra rebels.
   ``We are very concerned by the systematic moves of the
Sandinista government to undermine the peace process and intimidate
its political opposition,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
said.
   Fitzwater said actions in the last 72 hours by Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega ``have once again held his true colors
high, showing that he has little intention of supporting a free
press, of allowing democratic dissent or making the reforms called
for by the Guatemala City peace plan.''
   Meanwhile, at a news conference, Contra political leader Adolfo
Calero accused the Sandinistas of trying to force the rebels into a
choice between ``hunger and surrender.''
   He said the insurgents refuse to accept that choice and plan to
continue negotiations with the Sandinistas on the basis of the
temporary cease fire agreement signed six weeks ago.
   But, he said, the rebel forces will not enter the seven cease
fire zones which have been mutually agreed to ``if there is no
assurance of delivery of the aid which has been approved.
   The aid of the U.S. government ``has been held as hostage by the
Sandinista government all this time.''
   In Managua, Nicaragua, spokesmen for opposition parties said
that police detained more than 25 opposition leaders who had
gathered to support workers on a hunger strike and held the leaders
for about two hours.
   On Tuesday, the Nicaraguan Interior Ministry barred the
privately owned Radio Mundial and the Roman Catholic station Radio
Catolica from broadcasting news for eight days. It also closed
Radio Corporacion for 24 hours for airing ``false news'' about the
strike.
   Fitzwater said, ``This intimidation of the media and political
opposition can only be a further hindrance to the peace process.''
   Rep. William Broomfield, R-Mich., who met with Secretary of
State George Shultz along with other members of the House Foreign
Affairs Committee, said, ``There is a deep concern about the
situation that is developing in Nicaragua.''
   ``The Sandinistas are stalling on the negotiations and holding
U.S. aid as hostage,'' Broomfield said after an hour-long
closed-door meeting with Shultz, who declined to answer reporters'
questions. ``You could just feel his letdown on this development.''
   Broomfield said a $49 million aid package approved a month ago
to encourage peace talks between the two warring sides seemed to be
having the opposite effect. ``The action taken by Congress has
really helped the Sandinistas jeopardize the Contras,'' he said.
   ``It seems to me the Democrat leadership has a responsibility to
put pressure on the Sandinistas to carry out the intent of Congress
and supply humanitarian aid,'' he said.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, acknowledged that aid was not
flowing as Congress intended but said the problem seemed to be more
with State Department officials administering the aid than with the
Sandinistas.
   Wright was scheduled to meet separately later in the day with
officials of the State Department's Agency for International
Development and with a group of Contra leaders.
   ``We're going to sit down with them and find out what's the
holdup,'' he said. But he noted that none of the $10 million
earmarked to pay expenses of a Nicaraguan verification commission
has been spent. ``That's where the thing may have broken down.''
   The commission is made up of Nicaraguan Cardinal Miguel Obando y
Bravo and Joao Baena Soares, secretary general of the Organization
of American States, and is to monitor the March 23 cease-fire
agreement between the two sides.
   Among the commission's tasks is to inspect cargo destined for
the Contras in the field to ensure there are no weapons included,
and to mediate disagreements over what agency or contractor is to
deliver the aid.
   AID officials have awarded contracts to begin a $17.7 million
program of medical care for children on both sides of the conflicts
who are victims of the nearly seven-year war, and a small amount of
that money has begun to flow. A limited amount of food, clothing
and medicine also has been delivered to Contra troops inside the
Honduran border.
   Negotiations to implement a 60-day cease fire agreed to March 23
in Sapoa, Nicaragua, have stalled, and the situation has been
further complicated by a split in Contra ranks over negotiating
strategy and who is to provide military leadership.
</TEXT>
