<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ClassReunion     05-05 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Class Reunion,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1918 Graduates of Danvers High Class Reunite: Both of Them</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was a great turnout for the 70th
reunion of Danvers High School's class of 1918. All the graduates
showed up _ all two of 'em.
   It was a no-fuss affair. Elsie Stahly, 87, cooked cube steaks
and Louise Gaddis, 88, supplied the Rocky Road cookies and set the
table. There was plenty of reminiscing and laughter about their
school days.
   ``I don't remember ever having an argument,'' said Mrs. Stahly,
who was valedictorian. ``We always saw eye-to-eye on things.''
   Their class originally had 16 members but by the time they were
seniors, all but Elsie and Louise had left school and the entire
student body had dwindled to nine. The school in Danvers,
population 920, closed in 1967.
   At last week's reunion in Mrs. Stahly's apartment, the two
talked fondly of their other friends at school and how the boys and
girls each had ``secret societies.'' And there was the war effort
for which they remembered knitting white string washcloths.
   ``Those were the days,'' Mrs. Stahly said. The two knew many in
the war, but said they could not recall any of their classmates
leaving school for the war effort.
   Their graduation ceremony included a formal baccalaureate
service, despite its size.
   ``We had the works,'' Mrs. Stahly said. ``We had a real
program.''
   Although there were no caps and gowns, a speaker came from
Springfield, the girls chose a motto _ ``Only a Commencement'' _
and their colors were khaki _ because of the war _ and rose.
   Announcements went out and the girls, decked out in their white
graduation dresses, were handed diplomas rolled in their class
colors.
   ``All at once it came to me,'' Mrs. Stahly said. ``This is the
end of high school. This is the end. I thought I was going to cry
up there on stage.''
   Mrs. Gaddis also was caught up in the emotion of the ceremony.
   ``It was sentimental,'' she said.
   However, their friendship was far from over. Both taught school
after graduation and married farmers the same year. Their first
babies were the same age and graduated together from Danvers High.
   Now, both are widows and live in apartments in Bloomington,
about 10 miles east of Danvers. They've celebrated about six
reunions, although last year, they simply spoke on the telephone.
   ``I'm so thankful we're together yet,'' Mrs. Stahly said.
``We're figuring on hanging in there for our 80th reunion.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
