<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryMoves 1stLd-Writethru a0726 05-05 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Moves, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Studeman Nominated to Head NSA</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds one graf with Army engineers announcement</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has nominated the admiral in
charge of Navy intelligence operations to become the next director
of the super-secret National Security Agency, the Pentagon said
Thursday.
   Assuming Senate confirmation, Rear Adm. William O. Studeman will
be promoted to vice admiral and replace Army Lt. Gen. William E.
Odom, who is retiring on Aug. 1.
   Studeman, 48, a native of Brownsville, Texas, has been director
of Naval Intelligence since September 1985. A highly decorated
veteran of Vietnam, Studeman has spent nearly his entire Navy
career in the intelligence arena.
   He is a graduate of the Naval War College and the National War
College and holds a master's degree in international affairs from
George Washington University.
   The NSA is the most secret of all American spy agencies, with
responsibility for electronic intelligence-gathering around the
world as well as for the security of U.S. government electronic
systems. It is based at Fort Meade, Md.
   In other military moves, the Pentagon said the president had
nominated Adm. Powell F. Carter Jr. for assignment as the
commander-in-chief of the U.S. Atlantic Fleet. Carter, 56, of Los
Angeles, now is the U.S. representative to the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization's Military Committee.
   Reagan nominated Rear Adm. Roger F. Bacon for promotion to vice
admiral and assignment as commander of Atlantic Fleet Submarine
Forces, and Rear Adm. Peter M. Hekman Jr. for a promotion and new
assignment as the head of the Naval Sea Systems Command.
   Bacon, 50, from San Diego, Calif., now commands Submarine Group
Eight.
   Hekman, 54, a native of Ripon, Calif., is a deputy commander at
Sea Systems Command, the organization responsibility for new ship
contracting. Hekman will replace Vice Adm. William H. Rowden, who
will retire on Oct. 1.
   The Pentagon also said Reagan has chosen Maj. Gen. Henry J.
Hatch to become chief of Army engineers with the rank of lieutenant
general. Hatch, 52, of Pensacola, Fla., now is director of civil
works for the Army engineers.
</TEXT>
