<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LinderWeek     05-05 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Linder Week,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commissioner Withdraws Bid for Linder Memorial Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city commissioner has withdrawn a
resolution calling for a week of official mourning for Benjamin
Linder, the former Portland resident shot to death by Nicaraguan
rebels.
   Commissioner Mike Lindberg withdrew the resolution at
Wednesday's City Council meeting, which about three dozen people,
many wearing badges reading ``No Honor for Treason,'' attended.
   Lindberg later said he withdrew the resolution because he didn't
want the hearing to become a forum for a debate over U.S. policy in
Central America.
   ``I was afraid that what was supposed to be a simple memorial
would end up being hurtful and damaging to the family,'' he said.
   Opponents of the resolution said they were prepared to speak
about Linder at the hearing, said Mike Wiley of the Oregon
Citizens' Alliance. ``In my opinion, Benjamin Linder was a traitor.
He's not a hero or martyr, he's a traitor,'' Wiley said.
   Linder, 27, was killed in an attack by the U.S.-backed rebels,
known as Contras, on April 28, 1987, while he was working on a
hydroelectric project in rural Nicaragua. Relatives have traveled
around the nation during the past year to speak out against U.S.
military involvement in Nicaragua.
   Last year, the City Council unanimously approved a resolution
honoring Linder and opposing further U.S. aid to the Contras. That
resolution, introduced by Lindberg, drew little opposition. Because
of the lack of opposition last year, Lindberg said, he hadn't
expected a fight this time.
</TEXT>
