<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1536EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HerbicideRequest     05-05 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Herbicide Request,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmental Groups Want Lasso Herbicide Withdrawn; Monsanto Says
No</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocacy groups asked Monsanto Corp. to take
Lasso, the nation's most popular herbicide, off the market Thursday
because of its cancer-causing potential. The company refused.
   In a letter to Monsanto's chairman delivered to the company's
Washington office, the groups asked that the company honor previous
pledges not to sell unsafe products ``by recognizing the
unacceptable risks posed by Lasso.''
   Though the names of 58 organizations were attached to the
letter, many were state or local affiliates of four groups whose
staffs passed out leaflets or addressed a sidewalk rally six floors
below: Clean Water Action Project, National Coalition Against the
Misuse of Pesticides, Public Interest Research Group and Public
Citizen.
   Upstairs, Robert Harness, vice president for environmental
affairs, told reporters: ``Monsanto has absolutely no intention of
pulling Lasso from the market. We are very proud of the product.''
   Lasso is the trade name for alachlor, a herbicide used widely
for weed control on corn, soybeans and peanuts. More than 80
million pounds are used each year.
   After three years of special study, the Environmental Protection
Agency in December decided to allow continued sale of alachlor, but
restricted use to state-certified applicators.
   Alachlor causes tumors in laboratory animals, and EPA classifies
it as a probable cause of cancer in humans.
   EPA has required Monsanto to undertake new studies of
groundwater, into which it says alachlor can leach. The herbicide
has been found in groundwater in 11 states.
   An earlier Monsanto study found alachlor in 4 percent of 246
wells in the cornbelt, in concentrations ranging from 0.2 to 22
parts per billion. EPA said it believed a lifetime of drinking
water contaminated at 1 ppb would increase the chance of cancer in
humans by four in a million at most.
   Harness said Monsanto does not believe alachlor can leach into
groundwater and when it has been found there ``generally speaking,
that's been tied back to an improper well or a spill, and that's
sopmething that can be corrected.''
   Outside, Rick Hind of Public Interest Research Group noted that
Du Pont Co. is supporting the withdrawal of ozone-destroying
chemicals and said, ``Our last hope is the good will of companies
like Monsanto,'' since federal pesticide law requires EPA to permit
sale of chemicals whose benefits outweigh the risks of use.
   Kevin Thorpe, an entomologist on the staff of the National
Coalition Against the Misuse of Pesticides, said EPA's risk-benefit
calculation was flawed because it did not consider non-chemical
weed control.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShuttleBoosterTest     05-05 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Booster Test,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Joints Passed Test; Results Expected on Another, Thiokol Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of three redesigned joints on the
space shuttle booster rocket passed their first qualifying tests
with flying colors, Morton Thiokol Inc. engineers said Thursday.
   Engineers have inspected both the aft and center joints between
segments of the solid fuel booster and found both worked as
designed during an April 22 full-scale test-firing, Dave Mobley,
NASA deputy project manager for the redesign effort, said.
   Results of tests on the forward joint are expected Friday.
   The center joint held up even though an intentional flaw was
built into it for the test-firing at the Morton Thiokol plant 25
miles west of here.
   Two more full-scale qualifying tests of the booster are planned
for June and July, and the shuttle is tentatively set for launch in
late August or early September, the first since Challenger exploded
on Jan. 28, 1986.
   Mobley said the center joint flaw allowed superhot gases from
the burning fuel to reach insulation and the joint's O-ring gasket,
but the ring held.
   ``There was no damage to the O-ring at all,'' he said. ``There
was no evidence the gas got past'' the ring.
   Failure of an O-ring seal is blamed for allowing exhaust gas to
escape from one of Challenger's boosters. A presidential commission
found the gas ignited the shuttle's exterior liquid fuel tank,
triggering the explosion that destroyed Challenger and killed its
seven crew members.
   Mobley also said engineers found no damage to the rocket's
nozzle section. In a December test-firing, a NASA-designed boot
ring on the section came apart. The April test used a Morton
Thiokol-designed boot ring that was reliable in the past.
   A final report, based on more extensive study, isn't expected
for several weeks, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
