<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Mideast     05-05 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mideast,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Says Israel's Raid Brought Tragic Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Thursday marked the
conclusion of a two-day Israeli raid into Lebanon by equally
condemning all parties to cross-border violence and declining to
accept Jerusalem's explanation that the drive was aimed at
terrorists.
   ``We won't try to characterize this particular operation one way
or the other,'' department spokesman Charles E. Redman said after
issuing a statement that lent no support to Israeli claims that the
raid was retaliatory.
   For more than a decade, the statement said, a long series of
cross-border violence has left death and destruction in southern
Lebanon and northern Israel.
   ``They're tragic, and inevitably set back prospects for
achieving security and stability in the area,'' Redman said.
   During the raid, at least 40 Arabs were killed along with three
Israeli soldiers, the Israeli army said.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said Israel would not hesitate to
conduct more raids in its ``security zone'' in southern Lebanon to
purge it. ``There is nothing worse than allowing terror elements
who are active against us to establish themselves freely and feel
free to act against Israeli and targets in the security zone,'' he
said.
   Rabin said the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, Shiite
Moslem movement was singled out by the Israeli forces because it
``has become one of the elements that most cooperates with
(Palestine Liberation Organization chairman Yasser) Arafat.''
   The State Department, however, said security should be pursued
through ``agreed-on arrangements'' between Israel and Lebanon that
could provide security ``for the peoples of southern Lebanon and
northern Israel, who deserve it.''
   Redman also called for the withdrawal of all foreign forces from
Lebanon as ``the only way'' to achieve security and stability in
the region.
   He apparently referred both to Syria, which plays a dominant
role in Lebanon and whose army controls large areas of the country,
and Israel, which periodically sends forces into a belt along the
border manned by pro-Israeli Lebanese soldiers.
</TEXT>
