<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ImpaledMan     05-05 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Impaled Man,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Impaled By Tree Limb Recovering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man impaled by a tree limb in a logging
accident got out of intensive care Thursday, and was recovering
from his injuries.
   ``I remember everything. I remember asking the Lord to help me,
to get the stick out of me,'' said Gary Crawford, 31, who was in
fair condition at a Savannah hospital.
   Crawford of Hazlehurst said he suffered only nerve damage when
22 inches of the limb pierced his groin.
   ``I consider myself pretty lucky,'' he said.
   Candler County Sheriff Homer Bell said Crawford was operating a
skidder, a type of heavy tractor used to haul logs, at a site near
Stilson last week when the limb penetrated the protective cage on
the tractor and pierced Crawford's body.
   He was flown to Memorial Medical Center in Savannah, where he
underwent surgery to remove the limb.
   Crawford's mother, Colleen Crawford of Hazlehurst, said the limb
entered her son's body in the groin area and bypassed his liver,
kidneys and bowels to press against the skin of his back. It was
more than 36 inches long, she said.
   ``It (the limb) didn't break the skin in his back,'' she said.
``But 22 inches of the stick were inside my son's body.''
   ``I am simply amazed. I am so happy,'' said Crawford's wife,
Dianne. ``I was scared, I was terrified. I thank God that my
husband is still with me and our kids.''
</TEXT>
