<HEAD>Iran Says It Intervened To Free French Hostages</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-France-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran claimed credit Thursday for the
release of three French hostages who had been held by Moslem
extremists in Lebanon for three years.
   Tehran Television quoted Ali Reza Moayyeri, a deputy prime
minister for political affairs, as saying in an interview that Iran
interceded on behalf of the hostages ``for humanitarian reasons.''
   Diplomats Marcel Carton and Marcel Fontaine and journalist
Jean-Paul Kauffmann were freed Wednesday near a seaside hotel in
Moslem west Beirut.
   The Tehran Television broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, quoted
Moayyeri as predicting the release of the hostages also would lead
to the restoration of French-Iranian diplmatic relations, severed
in July.
   Moayyeri said: ``The Islamic Republic of Iran asked the Moslem
people of Lebanon to help in connection with France's problem (the
hostages).
   ``As a result, the three remaining French hostages were
liberated and, according to the latest reports, they returned to
France,'' Moayyeri said.
   The three hostages were kidnapped separately in March 1985 and
May 1985.
   Moayyeri said Iran was encouraged to intervene in the case
because of ``positive reactions made by French Premier Jacques
Chirac regarding Iranian demands.''
   He did not spell out the demands. Media reports have said France
agreed to repay the outstanding balance of a $1 billion loan made
by the late Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi before the Islamic
revolution overthrew the Iranian monarchy in 1979.
   French government officials denied striking a deal.
   Fontaine, Carton and Kauffmann were held by a group calling
itself Islamic Jihad, or Islamic Holy War.
   The group comprises Shiite Moslem Lebanese followers of Iran's
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Eighteen other foreigners are still held in Lebanon by
extremists loyal to Iran. They include nine Americans. Terry
Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent for the Associated
Press, is the longest-held hostage. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
