<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CubanMuseum     05-05 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuban Museum,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Art Splits Anti-Castro Cubans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Art and artists still connected to Cuba have split
the Cuban exile community along generational lines as it struggles
to find a balance between anti-communism and artistic freedom.
   Seventeen older directors and five top officials resigned from
the Cuban Museum of Arts and Culture following a tumultuous
emergency meeting Wednesday night, 24 hours after a pipe bomb blew
out the empty building's front door.
   The resignation of the mostly older directors, in their 50s and
60s, left the museum in the hands of younger, less militant Cubans.
   Older anti-Castro activists make no pretense of objectivity.
They say the museum has lost touch with the community it serves and
the trauma suffered by Cubans oppressed and sometimes imprisoned in
the homeland, and now separated from their families.
   ``This is a museum of exiles,'' said founder Raul Alvarez, one
of the directors who resigned. ``This is not a museum in New York
or Little Rock.''
   The resignations were triggered by their failure to oust two
museum vice presidents who defended an auction that included
paintings by artists still living in Cuba.
   Many directors also wanted an upcoming exhibit by Cuban painter
Amalia Palaez canceled because they felt she is too close to Cuban
leader Fidel Castro.
   Exhibit curator Giulio Blanco said the chaos following the
resignations may accomplish that goal.
   ``Pseudo-patriotic hysterics are responsible for all this,'' he
said. ``They've made total fools of themselves and all of Miami.''
   The remaining directors, most in their 40s, drafted a statement
that energetically denounced the pipe bombing and vowed to
guarantee ``respect for diversity of views.''
   ``The museum reaffirms its unswerving commitment to freedom and
democracy, and repudiates totalitarianism, which has so made our
people suffer,'' they said.
   Wednesday's showdown followed increasingly bitter complaints
about the April 22 art auction. Phone threats to the museum and
slashed tires followed the event, and culminated in the pipe bomb
blast Tuesday night.
   No organization claimed responsibility for the attack, but
similar bombings have plagued other Miami-area facilities that have
had dealings with Cuba.
   Ramon Cernuda, one of the two vice presidents who refused the
board's request to resign, accused the directors of caving in to
fear.
   ``The issues are no longer censorship and intolerance,'' said
Cernuda. ``The issues are intimidation and terrorism.''
   A majority of the board's 54 members attended Wednesday's
meeting, at which museum president Nunzio Mainieri offered his
resignation, saying ``I'm not up to the pressure anymore.''
   The president invited all the musuem officers, including
auction-defenders Cernuda and Teresa Saldise, to join him. All went
along except Cernuda and Ms. Saldise.
   The directors then voted 19-16 to request their resignations as
well. Again Cernudca and Ms. Saldise refused, and 17 directors
stalked out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
