<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OriolesAd     05-05 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Orioles Ad,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orioles Losing Ways Now Part Of Ad Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chicago advertising agency has turned the
heartache over the Baltimore Orioles' losing ways this season into
a case of heartburn.
   A full-page newspaper ad with a picture of an Orioles jersey, a
bottle of Pepto-Bismol and the words, ``The one that coats is the
only one you need,'' started appearing Tuesday in some large
newspapers, including papers in New York, Chicago and Los Angeles.
   The team set a major league record for the most consecutive
losses at the start of the season, losing 21 in a row before
beating the Chicago White Sox 9-0 Friday.
   ``Everyone recognizes the situation, that the team has been
facing problems winning games,'' said Linda Ulrey, a spokeswoman
for Cincinnati-based Proctor & Gamble, the maker of Pepto-Bismol.
   The ad ``also helps to lighten a tense situation,'' she said
Thursday.
   The Orioles supported the concept created by the Chicago-based
Leo Burnett of USA advertising firm.
   Robert Aylward, the Orioles vice president of business affairs,
said the team agreed to allow P&G to run the ad with the Orioles
jersey ``if it doesn't make a mockery of the team. And it doesn't.''
   ``I think when people pick up the paper and see the ad they get
a little smile on their face. It's obviously tongue-in-cheek.
People laugh,'' Aylward said.
   He refused to say how much the Orioles received for the ad from
P&G.
