<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0724 05-05 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0724,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Expresses `Concern' Over Violence Against Polish
Strikers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 3 grafs with comment from East German official</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House said Thursday it deplored
Poland's use of violence to squelch the latest outbreak of labor
strikes and suggested the Polish government seek ``a dialogue''
with the Solidarity labor movement.
   Taking note of reports that Polish police on Wednesday used
percussion grenades against strikers to end a 10-day-old walkout at
a Krakow steel mill, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
the administration was ``watching with concern.''
   It was the second such statement in as many days. On Wednesday,
President Reagan said he hoped the government of Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski ``will hear the voice of the Polish people _ and that
economic reform and recovery will soon begin.''
   In Thursday's statement, Fitzwater said: ``We deplore the
reported actions of last night and we strongly urge the government
of Poland to begin a productive dialogue with all segments of
Polish society, including Solidarity,'' the outlawed Polish labor
union movement, he added.
   ``Such a dialogue would inspire confidence in economic reform in
Poland and in the country's future. Any resort to repressive
measures, and particularly the use of force against peaceful
demonstrators, can only have the reverse effect,'' Fitzwater said.
   The strikes that have swept across Poland since April 25 amount
to the most serious since the imposition of martial law and the
1981 military crackdown on Solidarity.
   ``The problems in Poland can only be resolved by the Poles
themselves. And they can only be resolved with wisdom and foresight
on the part of those in positions of authority,'' Fitzwater said.
``We hope and pray that the Polish government will hear the voice
of the Polish people.''
   Asked if the statement's reference to solutions being found by
the ``Poles themselves'' amounted to a warning against Soviet
interference in its Warsaw Pact ally's affairs, Fitzwater said:
   ``This is a matter best defined by dialogue between the Polish
government and the various elements that are involved in Poland.
Outside influences, from whatever source, are not always the best.''
   The spokesman said it was ``a helpful sign'' that the Catholic
Church was attempting to mediate.
   Asked if the administration was concerned the unrest might
affect the summit later this month between President Reagan and
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Fitzwater said he did not
expect it to present ``seriously detrimental effects,'' but that it
could come up for discussion.
   The spokesman was asked if any more strong-arm tactics by the
Polish government could trigger a new round of U.S. sanctions or
affect the country's relations with such organizations as the
Internatinal Monetary Fund.
   The United States imposed economic sanctions against Poland
after the imposition of martial law and attempts to repress
Solidarity.
   ``I don't want to make any threats,'' Fitzwater said. ``We
simply point out there could be detrimental effects in terms of the
reform process and we would urge them to be aware of those effects
and hope that they don't happen.''
   An East German leader on a trip to Washington, meanwhile, urged
both superpowers to avoid interference in Polish affairs.
   Politbureau member Herman Axen, the highest-ranking East German
to visit the United States, told a National Press Club audience
that the 35-nation East-West security and human rights agreement
signed in Helsinki in 1975 forbids interference, and he made clear
he was talking about both the United States and the Soviet Union.
   ``So nobody should interfere,'' Axen said. ``It's a Polish
problem. We are confident they will find an adequate solution.''
</TEXT>
