<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     05-05 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 20 Killed in New Outbreak of Guerrilla War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military officials said Thursday at
least 20 people were killed in a new outbreak of guerrilla warfare
during the previous 24 hours.
   Airports were put on alert across the nation to prevent ousted
President Ferdinand E. Marcos from returning for his mother's
funeral.
   Brig. Gen. Galileo Kintanar, deputy chief of staff for
intelligence, said 1,291 people had been slain in more than 1,200
``insurgency related'' incidents in the first four months of the
year: 584 rebels, 346 soldiers and 361 civilians.
   The communist New People's Army began fighting 20 years ago when
Marcos was in power.
   President Corazon Aquino said Thursday she was standing firm on
her refusal to let Marcos return for the funeral of his mother,
Josefa Edralin-Marcos, who died in a suburban hospital Wednesday at
age 95.
   Marcos lives in exile in Hawaii. Airports were alerted to stop
him or members of his family from slipping into the country.
   Military officials said nine soldiers were killed and eight
wounded on Negros Island in fighting between soldiers and 400 New
People's Army guerrillas that began Wednesday and continued
sporadically into Thursday.
   Officials said two soldiers were killed and eight wounded in the
initial fighting, when a military patrol stumbled onto an NPA
training camp in the mountain village of Umas, 350 miles southeast
of Manila.
   Seven more soldiers were killed in follow-up operations later
Wednesday and on Thursday, officials said. No rebel casualty
figures were available.
   Military reports said two other soldiers, eight rebels and a
military informant were killed in clashes Wednesday on the main
island of Luzon, on Samar in the central Philippines and on
Mindanao in the south.
   Mrs. Aquino cited national security in refusing permission for
Marcos to attend the funeral of his mother, who died a day after
asking that she be permitted to see her son.
   Marcos, his wife and children fled to Hawaii after the February
1986 civilian-military uprising that swept him from the office he
had held for 20 years and put Mrs. Aquino in power.
   He said in a statement released Wednesday in Honolulu that he
would ``exhaust all posibilities'' to return for the funeral.
   On Thursday, however, Mrs. Aquino told reporters her decision
was final.
   ``I suppose we'll have to wait for him to exhaust all those
measures, but I stand firm on my decision not to allow him to come
back,'' she said.
   The former president's younger brother Pacifico and sister
Fortuna Barba said they would bury their mother in Ilocos Norte
province, home of the Marcos family. They said they had not set a
date because they still hoped Mrs. Aquino would change her mind.
   Marcos was not allowed to attend the funeral of his youngest
sister, Elizabeth Marcos-Keon, who died in December 1986.
</TEXT>
