<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SteroidDefense     05-05 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steroid Defense,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murder Suspect Uses Steroid Insanity Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A body-builder accused of beating a
hitchhiker to death and tying his body between two poles was insane
at the time of the murder because he was taking anabolic steroids,
his lawyer says.
   Attorney Richard Lubin will rely upon a defense of
steroid-induced insanity during the trial of Horace ``Ace''
Williams, according to documents he filed with the court. The trial
is scheduled to begin Monday.
   Anabolic steroids _ synthetic versions of the male hormone
testosterone _ are used by some athletes and weightlifters to
stimulate the production of proteins that increase muscle size and
strength.
   But the drugs, which are available legally only by prescription,
are also blamed for making users more aggressive.
   Lubin said Wednesday that Williams, 23, had taken the drug
orally and by injection for months before the crime.
   The combination of the steroids and beer he drank that night
caused Williams to ``lose his ability to understand or reason
accurately,'' Lubin said.
   In an effort to prove the steroids made Williams insane, Lubin
said he would offer the testimony of two experts, doctors from Duke
and Harvard universities.
   Williams, 23, was charged with first-degree murder in the Sept.
6, 1986, death of Michael Shane Patterson. Police said Williams and
his weightlifting buddy, William Whitmore _ also charged with
murder _ picked up Patterson on a state highway.
   They drove Patterson to a remote field owned by Williams'
father, police said.
   Williams, a high school dropout, told officers he and Whitmore,
21, were ``bored _ nothing to do, so we figured we're going to have
fun with this guy,'' according to police reports.
   But Williams told police he and Whitmore never intended to kill.
   ``We weren't out to do this guy any major injustice, you know,''
Williams told police. ``We were all pretty buzzed and just laughing
... and we're not, nowhere near, murderers.''
   Police never asked Williams if he had been using steroids but
Whitmore told police Williams had been taking the drug.
   There, Williams and Whitmore allegedly beat Patterson with a
pipe and heavy pieces of wood, cut hair from his head and
underarms, rammed Patterson's body with a car and then hog-tied him
between two poles.
   Patterson's naked body was found the next morning.
   In an article in the April issue of the Amereican Journal of
Psychiatry, researchers said steroid abuse by athletes could lead
to severe depression, manic behavior and other serious mental
problems.
</TEXT>
