<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSHotline     05-05 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Hotline,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Hot Line Expecting More Calls After Home Mailings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DROSCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national AIDS hot line is trying to hire
more operators to deal with the calls expected after an educational
pamphlet on the fatal disease is mailed to every household in the
country, officials said.
   ``This is a pretty important subject and is hitting people in a
personal way,'' said Carol Humphries, 43, coordinator for the
National AIDS Hotline operated in the Research Triangle Park.
   The American Social Health Association, operator of the
toll-free hot line under a contract with the U.S. Centers for
Disease Control, will expand its staff by 50 percent over the next
few weeks to handle the expected increase in calls, she said.
   The pamphlet, ``Understanding AIDS,'' is being mailed to 110
million homes by the federal government and should appear in
mailboxes beginning May 26, Surgeon General C. Everett Koop
announced Wednesday.
   Humphries said the mailings have forced some ``high-powered''
recruiting of operators through advertisements and flyers. This
week, Humphries said, the hot line had 130 operators fielding calls
here, but she hopes to recruit an additional 120 by the end of the
month.
   The 24-hour hot line, 1-800-342-AIDS, has had its headquarters
in Durham County since October. The health association also
operates a bank of phones in New York City.
   Some 200,000 people called in April, bringing the total for the
past year to more than 1 million calls. The number of calls is
expected to double in 1988.
   The hot line operation also is working with telephone companies
to add 12 phone lines to the 32 already in use.
   ``We heard about the mailout in March and started to plan for
it. This is not something you do overnight. It's taken quite a
while to put things together,'' Humphries said. ``This is pretty
high tech when you get right down to it.''
</TEXT>
