<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Redenbacher throughout, including
keyword line</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Popcorn king Orville Redenbacher
will receive an honorary doctor of agriculture degree from Purdue
University on May 15 for his more than 40 years of corn research.
   ``This is truly an honor to receive such a degree from my alma
mater,'' said Redenbacher, a 1928 graduate of Purdue.
   ``After all, Purdue not only pioneered research in popping corn
hybridization, but they also helped begin my `pop to the top' in
the popcorn industry,'' said Redenbacher, 80, who now lives in
Coronado, Calif.
   Redenbacher worked as a county extention agent and then as a
farm manager in Indiana before establishing Chester Inc., a
diversified agricultural company, in Valparaiso in 1952. He
marketed his popping corn personally, traveling across the country
to persuade store owners to carry it and appearing in his own
commercials.
   In 1976 he sold his business to Beatrice-Hunt-Wesson, but he
continues to be a spokesman for the label that carries his name.
