<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Air Raid,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim Air Force Bombs Ancient Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels in Ethiopia's Tigre province
claimed Thursday that air force planes bombed Aksum, the ancient
northern capital, in a series of raids on towns no longer held by
the government.
   The Tigre People's Liberation Front also said 130 people were
killed in four earlier raids. It reported no loss of life in the
Aksum raid, which it said occurred Tuesday.
   It asked the international community and concerned organizations
to condemn the alleged attacks on Aksum, Wukro, Adigrat, Yehilla
and Hargereselam. The rebels made the claims in a telex from their
London office to The Associated Press in Nairobi.
   Rebels in Eritrea, north of Tigre, claimed Wednesday that planes
sent by the Marxist government in Addis Ababa dropped napalm on
houses and farms in Halhal, about 20 miles northwest of Keren.
   A broadcast by the clandestine radio of the Eritrean People's
Liberation Front did not mention casualties but said 10 houses and
some crops were destroyed by fire.
   Western sources in Addis Ababa recently confirmed a raid on
Wukro. They said MiG fighter planes supplied by the Soviet Union,
Ethiopia's main ally, bombed the town April 8, killing at least 50
people.
   Wukro was an important food-distribution center until the army
withdrew from much of Tigre and Eritrea after rebel offensives in
March. Western and government relief organizations also operated
drought-aid stations in Aksum and Adigrat.
   Aksum, 340 miles north of Addis Ababa, was the capital of a
northern kingdom from about 500 B.C. until the 7th century.
   Crop failures in Eritrea and Tigre have left an estimated 3.2
million people in the two provinces threatened with starvation. A
huge relief operation has been hamstrung by the government's
military priorities in the region.
   Western relief officials fear 2 million people are beyond the
reach of the aid network because of the government withdrawal and
its expulsion of foreign aid workers from the north.
   Secessionist rebels in Eritrea began fighting 27 years ago and
rebels in Tigre have been fighting 14 years.
</TEXT>
