<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SuperDelegates     05-05 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Delegates,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic ``Super Delegates'' Not Bound by Primary Results</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, who complained Thursday that
Democratic ``super delegates'' are supporting Michael Dukakis far
out of proportion to the popular vote, has won 28 percent of the
votes in primaries so far but has just 16 percent of the super
delegates who have expressed preferences.
   Jackson is supported by 46 of the super delegates _ the 643
party leaders and politicians, including governors and members of
Congress, who are delegates to the Democratic National Convention
by virture of the offices they hold.
   The Massachusetts governor, meanwhile, has won 37 percent of the
votes cast in the primaries and is supported by 166 super delegates
_ 58 percent of those whose views are known.
   Unlike the delegates picked through state primaries and
caucuses, the super delegates are not required to declare their
support for a presidential candidate and are free to change their
minds at any time.
   Overall, Dukakis has 1,500 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention, while Jackson has 927, according to The Associated
Press delegate count.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., even though he has suspended his campaign,
still has 45 super delegates in his 419 delegate total. Sen. Paul
Simon, who also has suspended campaigning, has 28.5 super delegates
among his 184.5. Gore has won 17 percent of the primary popular
vote, and Simon under 6 pervent.
   While campaigning in Nebraska on Thursday, Jackson complained
that Dukakis has an ``inflated, padded lead'' caused by the super
delegates. He said he would be contacting them with ``appeals to
fairness,'' asking that they make their votes correspond to the
popular vote in the presidential campaign.
   Earlier in the week, Jackson objected that the popular vote for
the nomination is not directly reflected in the number of delegates
each candidate wins.
   ``There must be some reasonable correlation between the popular
vote and the delegate count in a democracy,'' he said. ``We're not
talking about generosity. We're talking about reciprocity.''
   However, Tad Devine, who oversees delegate selection for the
Dukakis campaign, said the super delegates have been following
popular will.
   ``A lot of this campaign's success in recent weeks with super
delegates is directly related to its success with voters,'' Devine
said in a telephone interview from Boston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
