<HEAD>Dukakis Criticizes `Silent' Bush; Jackson Complains About
Democratic Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis said Thursday he wants a vice president
``who speaks up and speaks out,'' in a gibe at Republican George
Bush's explanation for staying silent at Cabinet meetings. Jesse
Jackson said Dukakis' delegate lead was disproportionately
``inflated, padded'' by party leaders and elected officials.
   Jackson said he will make ``appeals for fairness'' to the 643
Democratic ``super delegates'' to follow the lead of voters in
their districts.
   ``There must be some reasonable correlation between the popular
vote and the delegate count in a democracy,'' Jackson told
reporters in Kearney, Neb.
   In the 29 primaries held to date, Dukakis received 6.7 million
votes or 37 percent of the total, while Jackson got 5.1 million or
28 percent.
   In The Associated Press delegate count, Dukakis has 1,500 of the
2,081 delegates needed for a convention majority while Jackson has
927. Dukakis' total included 166 so-called super delegates, while
Jackson's total included 46.
   Jackson scheduled quick campaign stops in Nebraska and then New
Mexico before heading to California, where Bush spent the day.
California offers a delegate treasure trove _ 314 Democratic and
175 Republican _ bigger than all the other remaining state contests
combined. Next up are West Virginia and Nebraska primaries on
Tuesday, with a total of 62 delegates at stake.
   Bush told reporters in Sacramento on Wednesday that he sometimes
keeps silent at Cabinet meetings.
   ``I hold back speaking in meetings because I don't want the
president to have to be choosing between his vice president and the
other members of the Cabinet. And I hold back sometimes because I
worry about leaks,'' he said.
   Bush spokesman Stephen Hart told reporters the next morning that
Bush ``reserves his advice for the president.''
   Hart said Bush's reserve at Cabinet meetings ``has enabled him
to have a uniquely individual relationship with the president. ...
   ``He's been a very effective vice president, due in part to that
unique relationship he has had with the president for the past 7{
years.''
   Dukakis, campaigning in the coal country of West Virginia, said
he liked his lively, contentious Cabinet in Massachusetts.
   ``That's the way you get good give-and-take. ... I hope I'll
have a vice president who speaks up and speaks out,'' said the
governor.
   Dukakis also took a swipe at Bush's repeated statements that he
wants to be known as the ``education president.''
   ``The next president must be this nation's No. 1 advocate for
educational opportunity and good schools; not just during election
years, but every day and every week and every month,'' he said.
   Bush was asked at a high school in a Mexican-American
neighborhood in Los Angeles about the prospects for federal help to
pay college tuition. He replied there would be ``a changing of
priorities to some degree'' as part of his plan to stress education.
   But he went on to say, ``There has to be a limitation on what
the federal government can do.''
   Dukakis also released federal tax returns that showed the
governor and his wife, Kitty, had joint income of $108,957 last
year and paid $25,892 in federal taxes.
</TEXT>
