<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CalifAbortion 1stLd-Writethru a0763 05-05 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Calif Abortion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0763,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Allows Medi-Cal Abortions To Continue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 7 grafs at end with additional background.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conservative-dominated California
Supreme Court refused Thursday to let the Legislature cut Medi-Cal
payments for abortions for poor women, a stinging defeat for
anti-abortion groups.
   It is the 10th straight year that state courts have overturned
the Legislature's budget restrictions, which would have eliminated
state funding for all but a small fraction of Medi-Cal abortions.
   Anti-abortion groups hoped for a change this year, because it
was the first time the issue had been considered by a court with a
5-2 majority of Gov. George Deukmejian appointees. The Republican
governor backed the restrictions on abortion funding and was
prominent in the 1986 campaign that defeated the court's previous
liberal majority, led by Chief Justice Rose Bird.
   Only Chief Justice Malcolm Lucas and Justice Edward Panelli
voted to grant a hearing on the appeal by Deukmejian's
administration of a lower-court order requiring full funding of
abortions to continue. Four votes are needed for a hearing by the
seven-member court.
   ``It means that over 80,000 poor women in California are going
to continue to have the right to abortion, and that the Legislature
can't restrict their reproductive choices to only childbirth and
sterilization,'' said Martha Kegel, associate director of the
American Civil Liberties Union of Northern California.
   ``To the extent that the right-to-life movement was hoping that
a mere change in the composition of the California Supreme Court
was going to mean the overturning of established precedent, they're
dead wrong.''
   The 1988-89 state budget, similar to every budget since 1978,
would have allowed state-funded abortions in only a few types of
cases: if childbirth would endanger the woman's life, if the
pregnancy resulted from rape or incest reported to authorities, if
the woman was under 18 and had notified her parents of the
abortion, or if the fetus was severely deformed.
   The budget set aside $12.86 million for abortions and said no
other funds would be allowed. Abortion-rights groups said
unrestricted funding would cost $25 million, but that the
restrictions would eliminate about 90 percent of all Medi-Cal
abortions.
   The budget restrictions have never taken effect because of
orders by state courts.
   In 1981, the state Supreme Court ruled that as long as Medi-Cal
paid for childbirth, the restrictions on abortion funding violated
a poor woman's right of privacy, under the state constitution, to
decide whether to give birth.
   That ruling conflicted with a U.S. Supreme Court decision, under
less-protective privacy standards of the U.S. Constitution,
allowing states to limit abortion funding. California is one of
only 14 states that has continued to pay for poor women's abortions
since the federal government cut off most funding in 1977.
   The San Francisco-based 1st District Court of Appeal ruled Feb.
19 that the abortion restrictions were invalid on two grounds: a
violation of the right to privacy, as defined by the 1981 state
Supreme Court decision, and a violation of the state constitutional
rule that a new law cannot cover multiple subjects.
   Because the Medi-Cal law requires funding for all
childbirth-related medical services, including abortions, the
budget restrictions conflict with that law and should have been
contained in a separate bill rather than attached to the budget,
the appeals court said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1939EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ColdWar     05-05 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cold War,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold War Veterans Urge U.S., Soviet Non-Intervention in Third
World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and U.S. veterans of the Cold War on
Thursday proposed that their nations stop intervening in the Third
World as a step toward reducing tension, but they differed over the
use of Cuban forces abroad and agreed to overlook the 1981
crackdown in Poland.
   The proposal was presented in a working paper that one
co-author, Arthur Macy Cox, said could have been subtitled ``No
more Afghanistans, No more Vietnams.''
   Cox, a former CIA official, organized the 3{-year effort to
produce the paper, along with Georgi Arbatov, who is an adviser to
Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and head of Moscow's USA-Canada
Institute.
   ``We believe that military intervention by the superpowers in
regional conflicts has reached a dangerous dead end and should be
terminated by mutual agreements,'' said the paper, which was
produced by seven Soviets affiliated with official news
organizations and research institutes and seven American former
officials and scholars.
   The paper also touched on areas that already are under
negotiation, such as sharp cuts in strategic nuclear and
conventional arms, strict controls on chemical weapons and
adherence to the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, which would
doom President Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative.
   The new ground lay in the area of intervention in the Third
World, a topic believed to be under hot debate in the Kremlin
following the decision to withdraw the Red Army from Afghanistan by
early next year.
   The problem of defining limits to such intervention became
evident during a news conference Thursday as Cox and Arbatov,
professing harmony, could not agree whether the use of 45,000
pro-Soviet Cuban troops in Angola constituted ``proxy forces.'' The
paper calls for a ban on such forces.
   The U.S. government calls Cuban forces used in Third World
conflicts Soviet proxies.
   ``They are not our proxy forces,'' Arbatov said. ``This is
simply a friendly nation that has its forces on the invitation of
the Angolan government in Angola. I cannot regard them as our proxy
forces.''
   Cox interjected: ``Let me say that we do regard them as proxy
forces, and it is spelled out in here (in the position paper) ...
So I hope we cannot have any mistaken conclusions.''
   On another area of East-West tension, the working paper listed
the Soviet invasions of Hungary in 1956 and Czechoslovakia in 1968
as ``direct'' intervention, but did not mention the martial law
crackdown which crushed Poland's Solidarity trade union in 1981.
   The subject was not raised during the lengthy discussion that
preceded release of the paper, Cox said. ``There was no
intervention by the Red Army or by other proxies into the affairs
of Poland.''
   The Reagan administration had a radically different
interpretation at the time of the crackdown. Then-Secretary of
Defense Caspar W. Weinberger described Polish leader Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski as a ``Russian in a Polish uniform.''
   And Ryszard Kuklinski, a Polish colonel who helped draft plans
for the military crackdown and later defected to the West, has said
the Soviets were involved in preparations for martial law and
relentlessly pressured Jaruzelski, threatening to invade if the
Polish Army did not suppress Solidarity.
   Arbatov is a member of the policy-making Communist Party Central
Committee, and several other Soviets on the panel are regarded as
advisers to Gorbachev.
   Soviet participants in the paper included: Fyodor Burlatsky, a
prominent journalist; Valentin Falin, head of the semi-official
Novosti news agency; Vitaly Zhurkin, head of a newly created
institute on European affairs; and several of Arabatov's aides:
Sergei Plekhanov, Henry Trofimenko and Andrei Kortunov.
   The Americans who contributed to the position paper were all
members of the American Committee on U.S.-Soviet Relations and
included, besides Cox: Townsend Hoopes, undersecretary of the Air
Force under President Johnson; William Colby, a former CIA
director; George Ball, former undersecretary of state; John Culver,
a former U.S. senator; William Miller, formerly head of the Senate
Intelligence Committee staff; and Adele Simmons, president of
Hampshire College in Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0214 </DOCNO>
