<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Nebraska-Senate 1stLd-Writethru a0734 05-05 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nebraska-Senate, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0734,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nebraska's GOP Senate Primary Heats Up; Daub Calls Karnes Rubber
Stamp</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts graf of Orr reaction after 2nd pvs bgng ``Karnes
called''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Hal Daub turned up the temperature
Thursday in the increasingly bitter Republican primary for U.S.
Senate, criticizing incumbent David Karnes as a ``rubber stamp''
for President Reagan and Gov. Kay Orr.
   Karnes called the charge ``crazy'' but said he would not be
drawn into negative campaign tactics before Tuesday's election. His
top media aide, Brent Bahler, called Daub's comments the ``rhetoric
of a desperate candidate who knows he's lost the nomination.''
   Mrs. Orr said it was ``sad'' that Daub ``feels he has to take a
desperate approach.''
   The race for the GOP nomination is considered too close to call.
An Omaha World-Herald poll last week showed Karnes backed by 41
percent of those interviewed, while Daub was supported by 40
percent. Nineteen percent were undecided, and the margin of error
was 4 percentage points.
   The GOP candidate likely will face former Gov. Bob Kerrey, who
has only token opposition in the Democratic primary.
   Karnes was appointed by Mrs. Orr to replace Sen. Edward
Zorinsky, a Democrat who died in March 1987.
   Daub, a four-term congressman, has mounted an aggressive
campaign. Some party regulars have described him as a ``pit bull.''
   The latest assault by Daub came as the candidates _ first Daub
then Karnes _ appeared before 300 people at the Nebraska Life
Underwriters convention.
   ``I haven't been a rubber stamp for anybody,'' Daub said. ``I've
been independent of my governor and my president when I believe it
to be in the best interest of Nebraskans.''
   Daub said Karnes ``flip-flopped'' on many votes to please
Reagan, including last year's highway bill that raised the speed
limit to 65 mph.
   ``David Karnes first voted for the highway bill, but then
changed his vote when the president and the governor told him to,''
he said. ``When the trade bill came up, I knew all along it was
anti-agriculture, but David Karnes voted for it until the president
told him to change his vote.''
   Karnes made no reference to Daub's comments in his Thursday
speech to the underwriters.
   ``We're going to be positive for the rest of the campaign,''
Karnes said in an interview later. ``If he (Daub) wants to
rubber-stamp around the rest of the campaign, that's fine.''
   Daub was among the party regulars lobbying for the Senate seat
when Mrs. Orr appointed Karnes, a political unknown who helped the
governor in her 1986 election.
   Daub said Mrs. Orr and political ``outsiders'' were working to
re-elect Karnes against the wishes of Nebraskans.
   ``The governor and a small group of people in the Republican
Party with a narrow view are trying to control the process, the
process of electing our next United States senator,'' Daub said in
his speech.
   ``I believe Nebraska voters _ with our proud history of
independent thinking _ will reject this control of the process by a
few.''
   Mrs. Orr was in meetings in Omaha on Thursday and could not
immediately be reached for comment on Daub's statements.
   Daub, asked in a interview if he was trying to distance himself
from the Reagan administration, said:
   ``I'm trying to differentiate myself from my opponent and the
approach we will take to speak for Nebraskans in the U.S. Senate.
When the president is right, I've supported him.''
   Bahler said Daub's comments were ``absolutely nonsense.'' He
said Karnes had voted against Reagan on several issues and ``he
certainly has not been an arm of the governor.''
   Reagan has been a popular figure in Nebraska, piling up huge
margins of victory in both 1980 and 1984 in this traditionally
Republican farm state.
</TEXT>
