<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0683 05-05 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Keeps Quiet to Spare Reagan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush in calculus class, subbing 7 grafs for 4th
graf pvs, ``Generally speaking</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush says he sometimes keeps quiet in
Cabinet meetings for fear of leaks or of forcing President Reagan
to choose between him and other officials. But an aide said
Thursday that doesn't mean Bush avoids giving Reagan his opinions.
   ``He reserves his advice for the president,'' said Bush
spokesman Stephen Hart.
   The vice president, on a three-day campaign swing through the
West, told reporters in Sacramento on Wednesday, ``I hold back
speaking in meetings because I don't want the president to have to
be choosing between his vice president and the other members of the
Cabinet. And I hold back sometimes because I worry about leaks.''
   On Thursday, Bush focused on the issue of education, sitting in
on a calculus class at James A. Garfield High School taught by
Jaime Escalante, who has earned a national reputation for his work
in teaching advanced math concepts to disadvantaged students.
   One student asked Bush about possible problems class members
might have in paying for college expenses in light of reductions in
some federal educational loan programs.
   Bush said that, if elected, there would be ``a changing of
priorities to some degree'' to reflect more emphasis on education
in his administration.
   But he added, ``There has to be a limitation to what the federal
government can do.''
   Bush, who has stressed education in his campaign, drew scoffs
from the class and the teacher when he asked if they used
calculators or other machines.
   ``I'm sorry, Mr. Vice President, no calculators,'' said
Escalante, who was recently honored at a White House reception.
   The day before, talking of White House meetings and the
possibility that private discussions would become public, Bush
said, ``Generally speaking, I don't like kiss-and-tell books.''
That was an apparent reference to much-publicized books written by
former White House spokesman Larry Speakes and former chief of
staff Donald Regan.
   ``If you think somebody is there writing a book putting his or
her own spin on it, you hold back,'' Bush said, adding that concern
about such a possibility ``inhibits freedom of expression'' in the
White House.
   Hart denied that Bush's comments on his reluctance to speak out
reflected any meekness on the part of the man who has a lock on the
GOP presidential nomination.
   ``Some people may think he's ineffective, but it's only the way
he operates,'' Hart said.
   ``It's been long established that the vice president does not
give his advice in Cabinet meetings,'' Hart added. ``Rather he
reserves that for private meetings, his weekly lunches with the
president and morning staff meetings.''
   Asked if Bush had been afraid of speaking in front of former
chief of staff Regan, Hart said, ``I can't point to any specific
person who would cause him to worry about leaks.''
   In his own book, ``Looking Forward,'' published last September,
Bush said Reagan's Cabinet meetings were the only chance for many
Cabinet officials to communicate directly with the president.
   ``Knowing this, I saw the vice president's role at these
sessions as limited,'' Bush wrote. ``With open, direct access to
the Oval Office, there was ample opportunity to weigh in with my
opinion on administration policy, without cutting into Cabinet time
or putting the president in a position of having to decide `for' or
`against' his vice president.''
   In the past, Bush has not blamed concern about leaks or books as
a reason for his reluctance to speak out.
   Bush's reserve at Cabinet meetings ``has enabled him to have a
uniquely individual relationship with the president,'' Hart said.
</TEXT>
