<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Skyscraper-Operations     05-05 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Skyscraper-Operations,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumers Largely Unaffected by Blaze at First Interstate
Headquarters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Skyscraper Fire, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fire that gutted four floors of First
Interstate Bancorp's high-rise headquarters won't affect customers
at the bank's operations in 19 states, officials said Thursday.
   Most of the computers that control checking and savings
accounts, automatic teller machines, and other business of the
nation's eighth-largest banking company are in a building six
blocks away, said John Popovich, director of public affairs.
   Other computerized operations for First Interstate Bank of
California are controlled from similar centers in the San Francisco
Bay area and the company's banks in other states also have some of
their own computers, Popovich said. The bank continued trading in
securities, and international banking and loan activity were
unaffected.
   The main downtown Los Angeles branch, on the building's ground
floor, was the only one closed by the fire, Popovich said.
   The blaze that started Wednesday night and raged through the
early morning hours gutted four floors of the 62-story tower, the
tallest in the city, injuring 40 people and killing one maintenance
man who was trapped in an elevator.
   Engineers began checking the glass-and-metal tower for
structural damage, but by mid-morning, bank officials hadn't been
allowed in to see what records and files had been lost.
   Operations on the gutted floors _ the 12th through the 15th and
part of the 16th _ included the foreign exchange trading, corporate
loan administration, personal trusts, economics, advertising and
public affairs.
