<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Trial     05-05 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Trial,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key Defendant Claims Victim Of Power Struggle, Challenges Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIHAC, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main defendant in the trial of 25
officials indicted in a major financial scandal said Thursday he
was the victim of a power struggle and demanded that the case be
moved to another Yugoslav republic.
   Fikret Abdic, 49, director general of the Agrokomerc
food-processing plant, went on trial before the high court of this
Bosnian town on charges of circulating uncovered promissory notes
worth about $1 billion in the nation's biggest postwar financial
scandal.
   Both Abdic, who claimed that the Bihac court was biased, and
most of the 25 defense attorneys challenged the court's ability to
stage an impartial trial. Bihac is near Velika Kladusa, where the
Agrokomerc company is headquartered.
   Court president Rifat Konjic, head of a five-judge panel,
adjourned the trial until Monday to consider the defense's demands.
   Abdic also demanded that the national premier, Branko Mikulic,
and Raif Dizdarevic, who takes over the rotating federal presidency
this month, appear before the court.
   The main charge against the defendants is the criminal offense
of ``counterrevolutionary threat to the social system,'' which
carries a maximum of 20 years in prison.
   The 25 officials also were indicted for abuse of authority to
undermine the economy ``under especially grave circumstances,''
embezzlement, illegal dealings with foreign companies and attempts
to disrupt Yugoslavia's banking and financial system.
   Abdic spoke of an ``an unprecedented struggle for power on the
backs of 13,000 people and the back of Fikret Abdic.''
   His statement was a reference to Agrokomerc's 13,000 workers.
Four thousand have quit since the financial scandal surrounding the
firm was exposed by the state-supervised media last August. About
9,000 are still on the payroll with minimum wages.
   Abdic and the attorneys contended that by expelling Abdic from
the Communist Party and denouncing other Agrokomerc officials,
party leaders, the state-run media and officials in Bosnia have
prejudiced the republic's judiciary and made any trial in the
republic unfair.
   Abdic himself demanded the trial be held in Ljubljana, capital
of Slovenia; Zagreb, capital of Croatia; or Novi Sad, capital of
Vojvodina province.
   Asked about prospects for a transfer of the trial, Kresimir Abel
of Zagreb, Abdic's chief attorney, said with a smile, ``The
question is superfluous,'' suggesting this would not happen.
   Other defendants include Ibrahim Mujic, deputy chief of the
food-processing enterprise, Alija Alesevic, the director of the
Agrokomerc bank, and bankers Ismeta Junuzovic and Mujo Vukovic.
   ``The circumstances have forced Agrokomerc (to engage in) such
business practices,'' Abdic told the court about the large-scale
issuance of bad bills of exchange.
   He requested that ``the causes, the essence and the
consequences'' of the scandal be established rather than his
personal guilt.
   Demanding the appearance in court of top leaders, Abdic made a
fleeting reference to an alleged comment Mikulic made April 30,
1987, to the head of a Sarajevo company that ``it will all be
settled'' in connection with uncovered promissory notes.
   Mikulic and other senior leaders have denied any guilt in the
affair which was first reported by the Belgrade daily Borba last
August.
   Abdic also sought to implicate the Bosnian police and their
chief Dusan Zgojanin. ``We cannot influence a lot, but we can
influence some and assist you,'' Abdic claimed he was told by
police investigators when he was asked to testify against Hakija
Pozderac.
   Pozderac, now a 69-year-old pensioner, is the second most
important defendant and a former economics minister.
   His brother, Hamdija Pozderac, died in April after resigning as
federal vice president following allegations he was involved in the
Agrokomerc affair.
</TEXT>
