<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SpaceProgram     05-05 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Program,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Chief Says Civilian Space Program `Facing Extinction'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of NASA contended Thursday that the
country's civilian space program ``is facing extinction this year''
if Congress carries out threats to cut space funds.
   ``The outlook is grim,'' said Dr. James C. Fletcher.
   The proposed space station, he said, will be doomed if Congress
doesn't grant the money that the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration and President Reagan have requested.
   ``If there isn't enough money, we just can't go on,'' he said.
``It's curtains for the space station'' if Congress appropriates
much below the $900 million NASA needs.
   Fletcher carried his fight for funding to a symposium on science
education, saying the space program's future rides on the outcome
of current budget deliberations in Congress.
   Reagan has proposed $11.5 billion for NASA in the fiscal year
that begins Oct. 1, but members of the Senate and House
appropriations committees have said the amount will be $10.7
billion or less.
   ``It may come as a surprise to you, but the nation's civil space
program is facing extinction this year,'' Fletcher said. ``While I
remain optimistic about the launch of the space shuttle this
summer, I believe Americans must know that the long-term future of
the space program hangs in the balance this year.''
   Fletcher said that if the amount set in the House budget
resolution _ $10.2 billion _ prevails, the civil space program will
be stopped in its tracks.
   Originally, NASA wanted $1.8 billion in 1989 for the station, a
manned facility designed for 30 years of scientific research and as
a platform for exploration of outer space. The president cut that
request down to $967 million in the budget he submitted to Congress.
   Fletcher would not say how much below a funding level of $900
million would cause him to kill the station program. But he told
the educators that budget levels being discussed ``would spell
death.''
   The result would be, he said, that major commitments to the
station's international partners would have to be cancelled,
advanced astronomy observatories designed to be serviced from the
station would never get off the ground and scientific research
won't take place.
   ``The shuttle program, on which so much attention is focused
today, will be able to operate only at a reduced flight rate in the
years ahead,'' Fletcher said. That would mean, he added that
scientific and national security payloads would have to wait longer
and the country would fall further behind while the Soviet Union,
Japan and Europeans move ahead.
   ``I speak out today because the crisis is real,'' Fletcher said.
``If the United States, the richest nation on Earth, cannot afford
to invest a fraction of 1 percent of its budget in its future, then
clearly it cannot afford to be a world competitor in space or on
Earth.''
</TEXT>
