<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Amnesty Bjt   05-05 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>INS Says Amnesty Program Successful, Despite Not Hitting 2 Million
Mark</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The amnesty program that pulled in more than
1.6 million aliens seeking to live legally in the United States
won't be extended and ``has proceeded very successfully'' despite
not hitting the 2 million mark, the nation's top immigration
official said Thursday.
   ``We'll take our 85-percent batting average on that as quite
good,'' Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner Alan
Nelson told a news conference. He said INS officials had been
making a ``rough estimate'' a year ago when they predicted the
program would attract 2 million undocumented residents.
   He said the one-year amnesty application period which ended at
midnight Wednesday would not be prolonged even in the face of two
court rulings. He said the courts ``have both been extremely narrow
in their holdings.''
   A federal appeals court in Manhattan extended the midnight
deadline for aliens with children born in the United States who are
receiving welfare benefits. A federal judge in Washington extended
the midnight deadline for a broader group _ those aliens who
overstayed their visas.
   Hispanic groups say some 100,000 aliens could be eligible under
that ruling, but Nelson questioned the figure.
   ``The numbers we believe are very small ... and there's also a
lot of question as to what the rulings are,'' the INS commissioner
said.
   ``No one should read these court decisions as any indication
that they're going to be extensions here, other than there might be
some very narrow ones,'' Nelson added.
   But Charles Kamasaki, director of policy analysis for the
National Council of La Raza, a Hispanic advocacy group, said it was
possible there could be ``a crazy quilt pattern of judicial
extensions'' for the amnesty program, which Congress refused to
extend last week.
   Kamasaki pointed to class-action cases in federal courts in
California, one involving people who were out of the country for
extended periods after 1982 and the other for people who left the
United States briefly after the amnesty program began and returned.
   In addition, he said, there have been 15 changes in the INS
regulations since the amnesty program went in effect last May.
   ``I hope Nelson will reconsider his position on simply resisting
firm and then reluctantly complying with these court decisions,''
Kamasaki said.
   The INS ``did a good job, but they fell short,'' said Mario
Moreno, legal counsel for the Mexican-American Legal Defense and
Educational Fund.
   Immigration officials ``could have done a better job on public
information campaigns in the early months of the amnesty
application period,'' Moreno said. He estimated there were 600,000
to 800,000 illegal aliens who would have qualified for amnesty but
who did not apply.
   Nelson, however, said no one knows how many illegal aliens there
are who might qualify who didn't apply. He said the INS program
succeeded in the face of heavy criticism.
   ``The so-called fear factor, in which people were believed to be
afraid to submit applications directly to INS, never
materialized,'' Nelson said.
   He said more than 80 percent of amnesty applications came
directly to INS offices without the involvement of lawyers or other
agencies.
   ``Many illegal aliens may have a trust and an appreciation for
this country and this government beyond that of many citizens,''
Nelson said.
   The amnesty program is part of the 1986 Immigration Reform and
Control Act which was designed to stem the flow of illegal aliens
across the nation's borders. Under the amnesty portion of the law,
aliens who came to this country prior to Jan. 1, 1982, and have
lived here since then may apply for legalization.
   Following optimistic predictions by the INS of a heavy flow of
applications, turnout at many offices was light. But there was a
last-minute crush of requests under the program, and on Wednesday,
the final day of the program, the INS received some 125,000
applications.
   According to the INS, California had the most applicants, with
55 percent of the total, while Texas had more than 17 percent and
Illinois nearly 7 percent. New York was fourth with 5.9 percent and
Florida was fifth with 2.9 percent. Arizona was sixth with 1.7
percent, New Jersey was seventh with 1.3 percent and New Mexico was
eighth with 1.1 percent.
   More than 70 percent of the applicants were from Mexico, 8
percent were from El Salvador and less than 3 percent were from
Guatemala.
   The median age of applicants was 30 years old, and nearly 80
percent of those applying were between the ages of 15 and 44.
   There is a separate program for agricultural workers who may
continue to apply for legalization. The applications under the
agricultural program have totaled 479,500 to date.
</TEXT>
