<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1950EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BlastResidents     05-05 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blast Residents,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Community Assesses Damages Following Explosions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plant Blast Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Ron Bates of Nevada Glass Co., ``it's
busy, busy, busy.''
   But for many of the residents of Emerald Point, no such silver
lining exists in the aftermath of the toxic cloud and concussion
from the exploding space shuttle fuel plant nearby.
   As many in this desert community of 54,000 residents surveyed
the damage to their homes and businesses, they found foundations
and walls shifted, windows broken, nails popped loose and doors
blasted off. For some, cars were trapped because garage doors had
been warped by the explosion.
   The Emerald Point housing tract of about 100 homes, priced in
the $100,000 range and a mile from the blast site, sustained heavy
structural damage.
   One insurance company responded curtly to homeowner queries:
``You're on the list.''
   Resident George Horvath, flashlight in hand, was up at dawn
Thursday checking for damage. He saw wide cracks in his stucco and
cement, and smashed window panes.
   When the Pacific Engineering & Production Co. of Nevada fuel
plant blew up Wednesday, Horvath and his wife, Hilda, thought an
airliner had crashed at nearby McCarran International Airport.
   ``You just get that numb feeling,'' Horvath said.
   Across the street, the front door to Marvin and Pat Coolidge's
home was blown in by the force of the explosion. The couple spent
Thursday morning cleaning up the feathery fiberglass insulation
blown from the ceiling.
   Walls were cracked throughout the house, the door frame was
ripped out and splintered and a living room wall was pushed out
about an inch from its foundation.
   The couple's teen-age daughters refused to stay in the house,
fearing it would fall down. They spent the night with friends.
   ``They're under so much stress. They are sick. They are throwing
up,'' Mrs. Coolidge said.
   Schools were evacuated after the blast and ordered closed for a
week so inspectors could determine if the buildings were safe.
Teen-agers rode skateboards and congregated at a neighborhood
7-Eleven.
   Glass was shattered and drywall panels were ripped off by the
force of the blast at a new tract of $135,000 homes under
construction a mile from the blast site.
   ``I just hit the deck,'' said construction superintendant Larry
Reese, who was in a small trailer a half-mile from the plant when
the blast occurred.
   ``I ran out of the house,'' said Mrs. Coolidge, recalling the
moments after the explosion. ``I didn't have to open the door.''
</TEXT>
