<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Students-Jackson     05-05 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Students-Jackson,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Senate Members Apologize Over Defacing Jackson Picture</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 8th graf, `Of the...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WINONA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of the Student Senate at Winona
State University have apologized to a black group for defacing and
writing insults on a magazine cover picture of Jesse Jackson, a
school official said Thursday.
   Jon Kosidowski, administrative assistant to the vice president
of student affairs at the school, said an investigation by the
school's affirmative action office concluded the two students were
not motivated by racism, but that what was written on the picture
was ``derogatory and insensitive.''
   Kosidowski refused to identify the students, and others involved
in the matter also have refused to identify them. He said the
students will remain in the Student Senate.
   The two students wrote individual letters of apology to the
Black Cultural Awareness Association, which had filed a complaint
of harassment and discrimination with the school's affirmative
action office last month. The association is a multiracial group
with about 25 active members.
   The university, about 120 miles southeast of Minneapolis, has
6,400 students, about 96 percent of them white, Kosidowski said.
   Members of the Student Senate found the Jackson picture, from
the April 13 cover of Time magazine, on a desk used by several
people in the senate office. Senators and school officials who
investigated the incident said the magazine did not appear to have
been left for everyone to see. It was taken to the school
newspaper, shown to black leaders and published.
   The Democratic presidential candidate's face was disfigured,
horns were on his head and an arrow was drawn through it. Several
disparaging slogans were written on the picture.
   Of the slogans, some were racially neutral insults. Others
included, ``Let's go get whitey'' and ``Where's those hymies?'' The
second was an apparent reference to Jackson's off-the-record
comment, made public amid a storm or controversy during the 1984
campaign, referring to Jews as ``hymies.'' The BCA also had
demanded apologies from those responsible and it also sought their
resignations from the senate.
   But a BCA spokeswoman said Wednesday that the group has accepted
the apologies and would no longer seek resignations. ``We're
satisfied with everything so far,'' BCA President Dena Gosha said
of the written apologies.
   Gosha, a sophomore from Chicago, said the school's
administration ``has been very fair about it, especially President
(Thomas ) Stark. He took us seriously. That meant a lot to me and
gave me a little more faith in this school.
   ``At times, we feel we don't belong here. But the way this has
been handled makes me proud that I go here,'' Gosha said. She
referred to complaints by some black students about racist remarks
directed at them by some white students.
   ``We definitely agree it (magazine defacing) was not done with
racial motivation,'' Kosidowski said, but he conceded there are
complaints by black students that they are the targets of racial
slurs by some white students on campus.
</TEXT>
