<HEAD>Massachusetts Republicans Urge Dukakis To Take Leave Of Absence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three prominent Massachusetts Republicans called
Thursday for Michael S. Dukakis to step aside as governor while he
pursues the Democratic presidential nomination. Dukakis, through a
spokesman, refused.
   Citing a ``major mess'' in state government, the Republican
officials demanded that Dukakis take an unpaid leave of absence,
but stopped short of calling for his resignation.
   The call for Dukakis to step aside came from state Republican
Party Chairman Ray Shamie; state Sen. David Locke, who is a
Massachusetts election co-chairman for Republican Vice President
George Bush; and House Minority Leader Steven Pierce.
