<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GermanVisitor     05-05 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-German Visitor,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East German Calls For Broader Trade, Cultural Ties With U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's top foreign policymaker ended
talks in Washington on Thursday with a call for broader trade and
cultural relations with the United States, but U.S. officials said
little progress was made toward settling major differences.
   Hermann Axen, a politbureau member and the highest-ranking East
German to visit Washington since the country was established after
World War II, told a National Press Club audience ``we favor a
broadening and stabilization of the political dialogue btween our
governments, an expansion of contacts between our parliaments.
   ``The conclusion of a mutually advantageous trade agreement is
important.''
   Axen said that though the two countries have had diplomatic
relations for 14 years, real contacts ``are still at the
beginning.''
   ``This fact is especially striking when one looks at the dynamic
and continuous development of the German Democratic Republic's
interaction with the overwhelming majority of states in the
world,'' he said. ``We have to catch up in our mutual
relationship.''
   Of the Soviet Union's allies, East Germany traditionally has
been among those most willing to follow Moscow's lead on foreign,
economic and human rights policies.
   As a result, until the rise of Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, relations between the United States and East Germany
were icy, in large part due to U.S. unwillingness to expand
relations with a country considered to have one of the worst human
rights records in Europe.
   Relations remain cool _ as evidenced by a bilateral trade of
only $150 million last year _ but on the diplomatic level there
have been some signs of thaw. Deputy Secretary of State John C.
Whitehead visited East Berlin last year and Secretary of State
George P. Shultz met with Axen on Tuesday.
   A U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Shultz
raised the issue of individual freedoms, which according to the
State Department's latest human rights report are tightly
restricted in East Germany.
   The official said the East Germans continue to seek an increase
in trade but there is no inclination on the part of the United
States to grant special commercial privileges, including ``most
favored nation status,'' it has given to Hungary, Poland and
Romania.
   The two countries also remain aprt on the settlement of U.S.
claims against East Germany for seizure of American property during
and after World War II. The claims total more than $78 million.
   Axen acknowledged that differences remain but said ``it is our
belief that trustful dialogue and constructive bilateral ties can
positively contribute to the betterment of the international
situation.''
   His appeal included a personal note. Axen, a Jew who joined the
communist party in the early 1930s, was imprisoned in the Nazi
concentration camp, Buchenwald, which was liberated when U.S. Army
troops under General George S. Patton approached in April 1945.
   ``On my first visit to your country I feel I owe a debt of
gratitude to the great American people,'' he told the press club.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
