<DOCNO> AP880505-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 2051EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-StockMarket     05-05 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Stock Market,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brokers Say Stock Market Scares Small Investors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of stockbrokers told a House
subcommittee Thursday that last October's financial crash and the
prevalance of program trading is frightening the average American
away from the stock market.
   The brokers told members of the House telecommunications and
finance subcommittee that the dramatic price swings that have
characterized trading in recent months, and computer-driven
transactions by huge institutions, are making the public reluctant
to invest in stocks.
   ``The confidence level of the average investor in the stock
market is today appreciably below any level that I have seen in
almost 20 years in this business,'' said George Strum, senior vice
president of Legg Mason and Co., a Baltimore brokerage firm.
   Strum said most of his clients are middle-class investors with
portfolios that are in some cases worth less than $1,000, yet have
continued investing through tough economic times in the past.
   ``However, these same clients today are pulling back from making
any investments in any equities, fundamentally because they are
worried that the market seems to go up and down, very quickly and
very substantially, without any rhyme or reason,'' he said.
   ``They are absolutely disspirited over volatility in the market,
and look now at the market with almost disdain,'' said Richard J.
Heckmann, a senior vice president for Prudential Bache Securities
in Rancho Mirage, Calif.
   The subcommittee has been examining the nation's financial
markets since the record 508-point drop of the Dow Jones Industrial
Average last Oct. 19, and the wildly surging prices that have
become common ever since. The panel has yet to propose any
legislation.
   A number of federal agencies and financial market organizations
also have studied the crash's reverberations, and several have
concluded that a variety of program-trading strategies _ large
transactions driven by computers _ have diminished stability in the
markets.
   Some of the studies and several market participants have
produced figures showing that heavy program trading has, at times,
shoved the market downward, despite an absence of bad economic
news. Computer trading techniques such as index arbitrage are
instead driven by price differences between the stock markets and
the stock index futures and options markets.
   ``Our equity markets exist for the purpose of capital formation
and to provide investment vehicles for our people,'' said Rep.
Edward Markey, D-Mass., the subcommittee's chairman. ``When they
become playgrounds for computer traders, arenas where a very few
large institutions and investment banks can engineer nearly risk
free profits while scaring the individual investor out of the
market, something must be done.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
