<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Dealership,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Dealership Changes Hands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham has turned his
car dealership over to a former competitor, who says he plans to
spruce up the business and increase staff and advertising.
   Kemp Biddulph, who owns other auto franchises, took over the
business Wednesday as Mecham Pontiac license plates were scooped up
as souvenirs and workers replaced signs.
   The deal had been announced in March following several months of
quiet negotiations. Biddulph earlier in the year bought Mecham's
Jeep-Eagle franchise.
   The sale was announced during Mecham's impeachment trial, and at
the time Mecham Pontiac officials acknowledged a steady decrease in
sales as Mecham's troubles as governor increased.
   Mecham was removed from office April 4 when the Arizona Senate
convicted him of impeachment charges, one related to the
dealership. That accused him of misusing a state protocol fund by
loaning $80,000 from it to his dealership.
   Impeachment trial prosecutors contended Mecham Pontiac was in
financial trouble and needed the infusion of cash, but Mecham
denied that and said he ordered the loan to get a better interest
rate for the fund.
   Dennis Mecham, the former governor's son and general manager of
the dealership, said at the time the sale was announced that the
deal involved $4 million, but he said the transaction had other
components which he would not disclose.
   The dealership had 76 employees. Biddulph said he plans to bring
the staff up to about 100 employees.
   His first priority is to improve the business's physical
condition, Biddulph said.
   ``We need to clean up, patch up and get some sweepers in there.
We're going to put in new landscaping and put down some new
blacktop,'' he said.
   Biddulph, known for his aggressive marketing, also said he plans
to increase advertising of the dealership by including it in
campaigns already devised for his other dealerships.
   Mecham Pontiac had been the only area Pontiac dealership not to
participate in the local dealer advertising association.
</TEXT>
