<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BilligAppeal     05-05 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Billig Appeal,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Considering Challenge of Ruling that Freed Billig from Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Donal in 1st graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy is going to take another week to
decide whether to challenge the court ruling that freed Dr. Donal
M. Billig from prison, officials said Thursday.
   Billig, the former chief heart surgeon at the Bethesda, Md.,
Naval Hospital, was convicted two years ago at court martial of
killing patients through surgical negligence.
   On April 13, the U.S. Navy-Marine Corps Court of Military Review
struck down that conviction and ordered Billig freed from Fort
Leavenworth, Kan., concluding the evidence against him was simply
not sufficient to establish guilt ``beyond a reasonable doubt.''
   Lt. Brian Cullin, a Navy spokesman, said Thursday the Navy had
decided to forego its legal right to ask the same court to re-hear
arguments in the case. The Navy had until Wednesday to file such an
appeal.
   Cullin declined to offer a reason for the Navy's decision. But
another official who asked not to be named noted the Navy-Marine
Corps court had heard Billig's case ``en banc,'' or with all
members participating, and thus was unlikely to change its mind.
   By foregoing the right to appeal the matter with that court, the
Navy now has until May 13 to appeal the case to a higher court, the
U.S. Court of Military Appeals, Cullin said.
   ``Right now, no decision has been made on an appeal,'' the
spokesman added. ``But we are still within the time limit to
request such a review.''
   The decision on whether to challenge the Billig ruling will be
made by the Navy's judge advocate general and Navy Secretary
William Ball, Cullin said.
   According to the spokesman, Billig, who holds the rank of
commander, is still in the service. He has been assigned to the
Kansas City, Kan., Navy-Marine Corps Reserve Center pending the
next decision in his case.
   Billig, 57, was the former chief heart surgeon at the Navy's
flagship hospital. He was convicted in early 1986 on charges of
involuntary manslaughter and negligence in the deaths of three
patients, and subsequently sentenced on March 3, 1986, to four
years in prison. Last summer, he was rebuffed in his first bid for
parole.
   Billig's case attracted great public attention, in part because
of the sensational nature of some of the charges. It also prompted
congressional reviews of military health care in general and
several large monetary settlements between the government and
relatives of Billig's patients.
   Prosecutors described Billig as an egocentric man, nearly blind
in one eye, who hid his visual handicap and continued performing
complex heart operations despite numerous warnings that he was
killing patients.
   The appeals court concluded last month, however, the prosecution
never really produced any evidence or testimony to demonstrate that
Billig's surgical technique and conduct in the operating room were
so out of line as to constitute criminal conduct.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 2056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BeeMites     05-05 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bee Mites,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bee Mite Quarantine Canceled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A month-old, 13-state federal quarantine to
curb the spread of tiny bee mites is being canceled because it has
proved to be unworkable, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   The states are Florida, Illinois, Maine, Michigan, Mississippi,
Nebraska, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, South
Dakota, Washington and Wisconsin.
   James W. Glosser, administrator of the department's Animal and
Plant Health Inspection Service, said the restrictions are being
lifted, effective Friday, on the movement of bees and equipment
from those states.
   Although not known to be harmful to other creatures, the mites
are considered a major threat to the nation's honey and beekeeping
industry.
   The tiny killer mites, Varroa Jacobsoni, were first discovered
in the United States last September in a Wisconsin apiary. They
since have spread to the other states.
   The Varroa mite is an external parasite of adult bees and their
developing larvae, or brood. It causes decreased brood, deformed
bees and a weakening of the colony's ability to pollinate plants
and produce honey. Infestation can occur so gradually that the
mites may not be noticed until severe damage is done.
   ``Information received from state governments, beekeepers,
growers and researchers has caused us to conclude that the
regulatory program established under the quarantine is not the
appropriate mechanism to contain the interstate spread of Varroa
mites,'' Glosser said.
   The original purpose of the quarantines was to issue permits for
out-of-state movement of only bees and equipment found to be free
of the mites.
   ``However, we've found that the requirements under the
quarantine are not uniformly appropriate or workable because the
role of honeybees in the agricultural economy varies widely from
state to state,'' Glosser said. ``Many beekeepers have found it
impossible to comply with the regulations and still meet their own
deadlines.''
   For example, he said, a beehive might have to be moved out of
its home state several times a year. Treating a hive against mites
requires 21 days, which is longer than most beehives are scheduled
to stay in a state when they are moved for pollination purposes.
   Beekeeping is credited by USDA with the pollination of many
agricultural crops having an estimated annual value of around $20
billion. Those include many fruits, vegetables and hay crops.
   Glosser said other factors weighed on the decision to cancel the
quarantines, including a shortage of treatment materials, and
limited state and federal resources to conduct and coordinate
surveys and inspections.
   ``The movement of hundreds of thousands of hives and other
regulated articles tends to occur during short periods in the
spring and fall, intensifying the demand for inspection services
beyond the limits of current federal and state resources,'' he said.
</TEXT>
