<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Veterans-Suit     05-05 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Veterans-Suit,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veterans Group Challenging Bonuses For VA Appellate Boards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veterans group filed suit Thursday accusing
the Veterans Administration of violating law and procedure by
paying productivity bonuses to members of appellate boards that
rule on benefit claims.
   The lawsuit by the Vietnam Veterans of America Inc. challenged
the production quotas set by the Board of Veterans Appeal for
members who sit on three-member panels to review VA denials of
disability benefit claims for service-related medical injuries.
   The suit, also brought on behalf of a veteran who was denied
disability benefits for psychosis and depression, charged that the
board's chairman, Kenneth Eaton, kept a list of senators and
congressman whose constituents got favorable treatment of their
appeals.
   The practice of paying annual cash bonuses to members of the
appeal boards for high productivity ``compromises the quality of
BVA decisionmaking'' and denies claimants due process, said the
suit filed in U.S. District Court.
   In order to be eligible for annual bonuses, panel members must
decide at least 40 cases a week, according to the lawsuit. To speed
up decisionmaking to meet the quotas, one or two members of the
panel would review the case and get a ``courtesy'' signature from
the remaining members, according to the suit.
   As a result of these procedures, the lawsuit charged ``thousands
of vets have had and continue to have their appeals denied under
circumstances where the deciding BVA panel members do not review
the appeals thoroughly and carefully.''
   VA spokeswoman Donna St. John said, ``We don't normally comment
on pending litigation.''
   The lawsuit charged that complaints bearing supporting letters
from lawmakers on Eaton's list were referred to the chairman's
office for special consideration.
   This procedure ``has no rational basis and bears no relationship
to the purpose for which VBA was established,'' the suit said.
   In the 1987 fiscal year, the board decided 41,296 appeals from
initial reviews by VA regional offices.
   It allowed 12.8 percent of the disability claims, denied 65
percent and sent the rest back to VA regional offices for further
review, according to Eaton's testimony earlier this year to a House
Government Operations subcommittee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
