<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Sessions-Meese 1stLd-Writethru a0719 05-05 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sessions-Meese, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0719,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Chief Said He'd Quit if Public Doubted Him</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf with no comment from spokesman for Meese after
15th graf pvs, bgng: ``I think ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Responding to questions about Attorney General
Edwin Meese III's legal problems, FBI Director William Sessions
said Thursday he would resign his own post if the public felt he
had engaged in improprieties.
   ``If it is perceived that the director of the FBI ... is not
properly, legally and ethically carrying out his responsibility, I
always have open the route of resignation for myself,'' Sessions
said when asked, in the context of Meese's legal troubles, what he
would do if he sensed the public thought he was acting improperly.
   Sessions added that ``I think there's a great deal of difference
between'' a hypothetical situation involving himself and ``the
circumstances'' involving unproven allegations relating to Meese,
who has been under criminal investigation since last May 11.
   When a reporter asked whether Sessions would be unhappy if his
remarks were interpreted as suggesting that Meese, his boss,
perhaps ought to resign, the FBI director responded:
   ``No, I think you'll have to draw your own conclusions.'' But he
quickly added that ``I'm trying to talk about general principles
that I do believe apply to conduct of public officials. ... I can
speak as to myself, but I am not trying to speak as to those
circumstances that might involve Mr. Meese.''
   In an interview with reporters, Sessions refused to address
Meese's legal problems specifically. But he did respond in general
terms about the importance of the public perceiving that law
enforcement officials uphold the highest legal and ethical
standards.
   Independent counsel James McKay has been investigating Meese's
ties to scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp., a $1 billion Iraqi pipeline
and other matters Sources familiar with the probe say McKay is
expected to issue a report raising several ethical questions about
the attorney general's ties to longtime friend E. Robert Wallach,
who is under indictment in the Wedtech case.
   Sessions said it would be ``pure speculation'' for him to
address whether Meese's legal problems have contributed to a
general feeling among Americans that they can pick and choose the
laws they obey.
   But the FBI director added:
   ``I don't have any question in my mind that it's very important
to put leaders, particularly those who are related to the import of
the law, to be generally perceived by the American public as being
people who do abide by the law that they seek to enforce.''
   ``In the area of the (FBI) bureau itself, it's extremely
important ... that we are like Caesar's wife, above reproach,''
Sessions continued.
   ``I read the newspapers, I see the television and I know the
attack he (Meese) is generally under,'' the FBI director said.
   ``But until such time as there is a procedure that tells me that
he is in violation of the law, that is, a charge with criminal
offenses,'' it would be ``pure speculation'' to address whether the
attorney general has contributed to a loss of respect for law by
the public.
   Asked about the prospect of ethical questions being raised about
Meese's activities short of indictment, Sessions said that
``ethical conduct in connection with lawyers particularly is a very
sensitive matter.''
   ``I think it's even more important when you're dealing with a
person who is, in fact, the attorney general of the United States,
and I think that Mr. Meese would strongly agree with that,'' the
FBI director added.
   After checking with Meese about Sessions' remarks, Justice
Department spokesman Terry Eastland declined to comment.
   Sessions, a U.S. District Court judge in Texas before coming to
Washington, has been on the job about six months.
   He said the bureau has not launched an investigation of graffiti
written on Justice Department walls in recent weeks apparently
aimed at Meese. One inscription near the attorney general's office
said ``resign.'' Another said ``sleazy.'' It is a crime to deface
government property.
</TEXT>
