<HEAD>U.S. Criticizes Jordanian Press Restrictions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Thursday criticized
Jordan's expulsion of an American television reporter and the
removal of press credentials from two Jordanian reporters.
   ``We're strongly opposed to penalties imposed on journalists for
what they write and report,'' said State Department spokesman
Charles Redman.
   Redman said ``it's particularly disturbing to the U.S.
government when an American reporter is expelled from a friendly
country for what he's reported.''
   Jordan last week expelled NBC correspondent Rick Davis, citing
``dissatisfaction' with his coverage of the country and its ruler,
King Hussein.
   This week Jordan withdrew the press credentials of two
Jordanians who write for overseas publications.
   ``We have expressed our strong opposition to Mr. Davis'
expulsion and our deep concern over restrictions against
journalists in general. We're continuing to make these points to
the Jordanian authorities,'' Redman said.
