<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1751EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseSpending     05-05 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Votes to Use Military to End Narcotics Smuggling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reflecting what one lawmaker called
election-year concerns, the House voted overwhelmingly Thursday to
order President Reagan to use the nation's military might to end
drug smuggling.
   The 385-23 tally approved a proposal by conservative Republicans
directing Reagan to ``deploy equipment and personnel of the Armed
Forces sufficient to halt the unlawful penetration of United States
borders by aircraft and vessels carrying narcotics.''
   But even supporters of the measure admitted it is a long way
from becoming law. ``Yes, it is flawed,'' said Rep. Jack Davis,
R-Ill.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, said before the vote, ``Of course it will pass easily.
In an election year, it won't even be close. Drugs is an issue.''
   The proposal was attached as an amendment to the bill
authorizing defense spending of $299 billion for the fiscal year
starting Oct. 1.
   The House passed similar anti-drug amendments in 1985 and 1986
on the same bill, but the provisions were later dropped by the
House-Senate conference committees that reconciled the House bills
with Senate-passed versions.
   No such anti-drug proposals, which are opposed by the Pentagon,
are part of the Senate bill that will be on the floor of that
chamber starting next week.
   In other action, the House voted to spend $600 million for
research into the single-warhead Midgetman nuclear-tipped missile
and only $100 million for the rail-based version of the MX missile.
   The anti-drug proposal came when Aspin sought House approval to
increase spending by $350 million for the Coast Guard, which has
reduced anti-drug patrols by 55 percent because of budget problems.
   The money would be used to pay for more Coast Guard patrols,
along with buying six more patrol helicopters, six patrol boats and
a pair of radar aircraft to track smugglers.
   But Davis and other Republicans raised the total to $475
million. They also added an amendment ordering Reagan to have
military equipment and personnel seal the U.S. borders against drug
traffickers.
   ``Such equipment and personnel shall be used to locate, pursue
and seize such vessels and aircraft and to arrest their crews,''
the measure said.
   Davis said, ``The problem is that our southern borders are just
a sieve of cocaine and heroin coming over unchallenged every night.
We want to bring the front lines into this battle against this
poison coming across our borders.''
   Rep. Tommy Robinson, D-Ark., said, ``It's time to use the armed
forces to stop the drug cartel.''
   Aspin argued that the proposal should be considered in separate
anti-drug legislation now being prepared. ``We do not want to deal
with this problem on a piecemeal basis,'' he said.
   But Davis didn't want to talk technicalities. ``Americans aren't
going to understand what we're doing here. America only wants this
amendment to be adopted. They want the military involved in
stopping drug traffic,'' he said.
   The decision on the nuclear-tipped missiles was a blow to the
Pentagon, which is seeking to develop a railroad version of the
10-warhead MX and wants to eliminate the Midgetman.
   Rep. Ron Dellums, D-Calif., termed the MX rail plan a ``mobile
Chernobyl,'' referring to the 1985 accident at a Soviet nuclear
power plant.
   Reagan had sought $793 million for the MX plan and only $200
million for the Midgetman. The pending Senate legislation proposes
$700 million for the rail-based MX and $50 million for Midgetman.
   By a 233-171 margin, the House decided to spend only $100
million for the rail-based MX and $600 million for the Midgetman.
   Earlier, the chamber voted down, 309-100, a plan to halt all
Midgetman spending; rejected, 265-143, another amendment to
eliminate all money for the rail-based MX; and defeated, 247-156, a
third proposal to give $650 million to the MX and $350 million for
Midgetman.
   The dispute involves the future of America's land-based
missiles, which are part of the nation's nuclear ``triad'' that
also includes submarine-launched missiles and bombers.
   The Minuteman is now the heart of the land-based force, but
Reagan, after a long fight, has won approval of Congress to build
50 MX weapons for deployment in land-based silos. He wanted 50 more
and the Air Force is studying a plan to build 25 trains and put two
MX missiles on each.
   By contrast, tenative plans for the Midgetman call for building
up to 500 of the weapons, which supporters say would make it more
difficult for the Soviets to attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
