<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FireArrest     05-05 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fire Arrest,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Arraigned In 1984 Rooming House Fire That Killed 15</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: MaryJane is cq in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-year-old man accused of setting a 1984
rooming-house fire that killed 15 because he was jealous of a
tenant pleaded innocent Thursday.
   James Carver of Ipswich, whose arraignment was held up about 15
minutes after he broke down in tears, was ordered held on bail of
$1 million bond by Salem Superior Court Judge Peter Brady. He was
charged with 15 counts of second-degree murder and one count of
arson in the July 4, 1984, fire at the Elliott Chambers rooming
house in Beverly.
   Carver was arrested Wednesday night in Ipswich as he drove from
a drugstore with his wife, MaryJane, 21, and their 6-week-old baby,
Kaitlyn, who reportedly suffers from serious health problems.
   Essex County District Attorney Kevin Burke said Carver
apparently was jealous that his then-fiancee was dating a tenant of
the rooming house. Burke said the man was one of the victims of the
blaze but declined to identify him or the former fiancee.
   Burke said Carver had been a suspect during the entire four-year
investigation by Beverly and state police, becoming the principal
target last year after a person claimed that Carver had admitted
setting the fire. Burke would not identify that person.
   Carver was identified in an April 21 police line-up in Danvers
ordered by an Essex County grand jury, Burke said. Several
witnesses had reported seeing him outside the rooming house around
the time of the fire, the prosecutor said.
   But defense attorney Dennis Jackson said in court Thursday that
Carver's parents have told police their son was ill and asleep at
their Danvers home the morning of the fire.
   The fire, the worst in Beverly's history, raged out of control
for more than two hours in the rundown, frame building. It trapped
six people in their rooms and killed others while they tried to
break down a locked exit. One man leapt from a third-story window
to his death.
   One of the victims was an 8-year-old boy who was visiting his
grandfather. Six of the dead were so badly charred they could be
identified only through dental records and jewelry found on their
bodies.
   The blaze in the three-story rooming house, which had no
sprinklers, prompted calls by state lawmakers for tougher fire
prevention codes.
   Essex County Assistant District Attorney Robert Wiener, who is
prosecuting the case, said Carver allegedly lit a pile of
gasoline-soaked newspapers in a doorway on the first floor of the
rooming house.
   Carver, who suffers from mild epilepsy and ulcers, was led from
the courtroom in tears after he lost composure during reading of
the third murder count. He returned about 15 minutes later.
   If convicted, Carver faces a mandatory life sentence for each
second-degree murder count and up to 20 years for the arson charge.
   A pre-trial hearing wass scheduled for May 23.
</TEXT>
