<1ST_LINE>u p AM-KittyDukakis     05-05 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kitty Dukakis,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kitty Dukakis Earned $20,000 From Program To Spruce Up Public
Places</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Dukakis-Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis, wife of Democratic presidential
front-runner Michael Dukakis, earned $20,000 last year as a
part-time director of a Harvard program to spruce up public places,
according to tax documents made public Thursday.
   Mrs. Dukakis' earnings accounted for nearly one-fifth of the
total 1987 joint income of $108,957 she and her husband reported.
   Mrs. Dukakis was the founder in 1985 of the Program on Public
Space Partnerships, a department of Harvard's John F. Kennedy
School Of Government that tries to bring together business,
government and neighbors in cooperative projects to spruce up the
appearance of public places.
   As director, she draws a half-time salary of $20,000 annually.
   According to Renee Robin, the program's executive director, Mrs.
Dukakis approached Kennedy School Dean Graham Allison in 1985,
expressing her ``long-standing conern over the deteriorating
condition of public spaces in Massachusetts, ranging from downtown
plazas to larger conservation areas.''
   The department was established late in 1986, and Mrs. Dukakis
earned $2,500 from the job in that year.
   Robin said the program's goal is a combination of demonstration
projects and research, with a special interest in long-term
maintenance strategies that will prevent future cycles of vandalism
and neglect. The program is funded by grants from corporate and
philanthropic foundations.
   Examples of the program's work include Winthrop Park near the
heart of Harvard Square, a pocket park in Boston near the
Massachusetts College of Art and Government Center in suburban
Malden.
</TEXT>
