<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0736 05-05 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0736,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Accuses Managua Of Intimidating Political Opposition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 4 new grafs after 2nd graf, ``White House,'' with
Wright comment; edits to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration accused Nicaragua's
Marxist-led government Thursday of ``systematic moves ... to
undermine the peace process and intimidate its political
opposition.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater commented on reports from
Managua that police detained opposition leaders, suspended two
radio stations from broadcasting and closed one station for 24
hours.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, also said he was concerned
that the Contras have wound up on the losing side of an unbalanced
equation in the peace talks. He promised to send a message to
Nicaragua warning against moves to snuff out remaining Contra
opposition.
   In a meeting with Contra leader Adolfo Calero, rebel military
commander Enrique Bermudez and other members of the Contra
political directorate, Wright promised to signal ``that the
majority in the Congress would not look with favor at all on any
return or resort to military engagement,'' and hoped instead for
good-faith negotiations.
   Wright also said he had asked the State Department's Agency for
International Development, which is administering a $48 million aid
package for the rebels and for children injured in the war, to get
the aid flowing quickly.
   ``A near miracle happened at Esquipulas,'' the town in Guatemala
where the original regional peace accord was signed last Aug. 7,
the House leader said. ``A near miracle happened March 23 at
Sapoa,'' when the two sides agreed to a 60-day cease-fire. ``Let's
work for the third miracle.''
   In sharply critical remarks at the White House, Fitzwater said
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega had ``once again held his true
colors high, showing that he has little intention of supporting a
free press, of allowing democratic dissent or making the reforms
called for by the Guatemala City peace plan.''
   ``This intimidation of the media and political opposition can
only be a further hindrance to the peace process,'' Fitzwater said.
   In Managua, spokesmen for opposition parties said that police
detained more than 25 opposition leaders for about two hours after
they gathered to support workers on a hunger strike.
   On Tuesday, the Nicaraguan Interior Ministry barred the
privately owned Radio Mundial and the Roman Catholic station Radio
Catolica from broadcasting news for eight days. It also closed
Radio Corporacion for 24 hours for airing ``false news'' about the
strike.
   Meanwhile on Capitol Hill, members of the House Foreign Affairs
Committee met with Secretary of State George P. Shultz. Rep.
William Broomfield, R-Mich., said after the meeting, ``There is a
deep concern about the situation that is developing in Nicaragua.''
   ``The Sandinistas are stalling on the negotiations and holding
U.S. aid as hostage,'' Broomfield said. Shultz declined to answer
reporters' questions after the hour-long, closed-door meeting.
   Broomfield said the aid package approved a month ago to
encourage peace talks between the two warring sides ``has really
helped the Sandinistas jeopardize the Contras.''
   ``It seems to me the Democrat leadership has a responsibility to
put pressure on the Sandinistas to carry out the intent of Congress
and supply humanitarian aid,'' he said.
   The Sandinista-Contra cease-fire agreement allows the rebels to
receive humanitarian aid inside Nicaragua. But the only shipments
thus far have been to rebels based on the Honduran side of the
border.
   At a news conference, Contra leader Calero accused the
Sandinistas of trying to force the rebels into a choice between
``hunger and surrender.''
   He said the insurgents refuse to accept that choice and plan to
continue negotiations with the Sandinistas on the basis of the
temporary truce signed six weeks ago.
   But, he said, the rebel forces will not enter the seven
cease-fire zones which have been mutually agreed to ``if there is
no assurance of delivery of the aid which has been approved.''
   The aid of the U.S. government ``has been held as hostage by the
Sandinista government all this time,'' he said.
   Wright said none of the $10 million earmarked to pay expenses of
a Nicaraguan verification commission has been spent and added,
``That's where the thing may have broken down.''
   The commission was formed to monitor the March 23 cease-fire
agreement between the two sides, but negotiation have stalled. The
situation has been complicated by a split in Contra ranks over
negotiating strategy and who is to provide military leadership.
</TEXT>
