<DOCNO> AP880505-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 2354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Glasnost     05-05 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Glasnost,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Newspapers Call for a Broader Debate, Including Stalinists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet newspapers are challenging the limits of
the Kremlin's policy of greater openness by saying opponents of
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms should get also media attention.
   The latest press comments run counter to guidelines issued last
month by Pravda, the Communist Party daily, and show the
uncertainty and varying views on how far the state-run media can go
in the campaign for ``glasnost,'' or openness.
   The boldest of the commentators, Moscow News columnist Anatoly
Strelyany, holds that banning dissenting voices will not guarantee
the success of Gorbachev's campaign for ``perestroika,'' or social
and economic change, but could instead make reformers a lot like
their foes.
   ``I'm afraid that the conservatives will be forced to shut up
and go underground,'' Strelyany wrote in the May 1 edition of the
weekly. ``If we seal their lips, we may begin to resemble them, and
imperceptibly to ourselves, to become them.''
   Thursday's Sovietskaya Rossiya daily, in a lengthy article on
glasnost, said limits are necessary in public debate, but that
outright ``taboos'' were not permissible.
   Writer Lev Ovrutsky, interviewed in the latest edition of the
weekly Literaturnaya Gazeta, said: ``A dialogue between proponents
and foes of perestroika is normal in a democratic society.''
   In April, Sovietskaya Rossiya, which like Pravda is an organ of
the Communist Party Central Committee, was forced to knuckle under
after Pravda criticized its decision to print a letter from a
Leningrad teacher who defended dictator Josef V. Stalin.
   Nina Andreyeva lauded the role of Stalin in her country's
history and accused his detractors of subversion and ideological
collusion with Leon Trotsky, Stalin's archfoe.
   Pravda called the March 13 publication of her letter ``an
attempt, little by little, to revise party decisions,'' and said
papers should not print material that criticizes Gorbachev's reform
drive.
   Gorbachev, the Communist Party chief, has condemned the
political terror and repression of Stalin's 29-year reign. Pravda
said Gorbachev's opponents continue to bring praise Stalin because
because they feel more comfortable with his tyrannical ways, or
because it serves their personal interests.
   Pravda added: ``The Soviet press is not a private shop and
Communists writing in the press and editors should be aware of
their responsibility for articles and publications.''
   On April 6, two days after the Pravda attack, Sovietskaya
Rossiya had to eat crow by reprinting the full-page Pravda article.
   The Communist Party daily's criticism and Sovietskaya Rossiya's
backtracking seemed to indicate that glasnost would not extend to
conservative government critics, or to Stalinists at least.
   Moscow News protested, and Sovietskaya Rossiya strongly implied
that conservatives should be allowed freedom of expression.
   ``A Stalinist demands that my lips be sealed (that's what makes
him a Stalinist) and that people listen only to him,'' Strelyany
wrote in Moscow News. ``I don't want his lips to be sealed or mine:
people should be able to listen to both of us.''
   Sovietskaya Rossiya said that it was ``impermissible that taboos
be laid down that cover shifting opinions and judgments in
general.''
   If that happens, journalist Nikolai Yerofeyev wrote, glasnost
will resemble the heavy-handed censorship of the past.
   ``It will easily put us on the same level with those who only
recently exorcised the spirit of any dissent from literature,
cinema, the theater and newspaper pages,'' the paper said.
   Sovietskaya Rossiya did not mention the dispute caused by the
publication of the pro-Stalin letter, or Pravda's response, but the
majority of its readers would be aware of those incidents and would
regard the Wednesday article as the latest chapter in the debate on
glasnost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
