<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1846EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Brawley     05-05 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley,0824</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharpton: Brawley Story Bought by WCBS-TV</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY64</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A television reporter paid two teens to say that
Tawana Brawley was at a birthday party during the time she was
allegedly kidnapped and raped by a white gang, the girl's advisers
charged Thursday.
   And one teen's father said his son never knew Miss Brawley and
had treated the whole television interview as ``a big joke.'' The
boys received between $10 and $100, said the father, Gregory
Fleming Sr.
   The reporter, who was covering the news conference called by
Miss Brawley's advisers, denied the charge but said he reimbursed
one teen-ager $10 for gasoline.
   The dispute was the latest volley of charges and counter-charges
in the highly publicized case that has pitted the black teen-ager
and her family against state prosecutors and other officials.
   Miss Brawley, 16, of Wappingers Falls disappeared last Nov. 24
and was found four days later, huddled in a trash bag with racial
slurs scrawled on her torso and feces smeared on her body near an
apartment where she used to live.
   She has said she was a victim of a sexual and racial assault
involving up to six white men, one of whom flashed a police-like
badge.
   But the girl's advisers, the Rev. Al Sharpton and attorneys C.
Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox, have refused to allow her to appear
before a grand jury investigating the case and have charged
prosecutors with a cover-up.
   Wednesday night, WCBS-TV reported that Miss Brawley was seen at
a birthday party in Newburgh the day before she was found. And the
New York Daily News said Thursday that the girl had run away at
least twice before and had been beaten by her family when she was
found.
   At their news conference, Miss Brawley's advisers accused the
media of ``racist journalism'' and ``journalistic rape.''
   Sharpton labeled the WCBS report ``a media hoax built on the
whims of young kids and the paranoia of some crack addicts in
Newburgh.'' He promised legal action against the station.
   ``I would call it bribery,'' added Mason. ``I would call it
paying for a story. I would think there should be ethics even in
racist journalism.''
   Mike Taibbi, the WCBS reporter who broke the story, said the
only money he paid was for sodas at a fast-food restaurant for the
two teens, and $10 to one of the young men to reimburse him for
gasoline used up driving around during the interview.
   ``We offered no money, and we specifically told them we do not
pay for stories,'' said Taibbi.
   In the WCBS report, an unidentified witness who appeared on
camera with his face concealed said he spoke with Miss Brawley at a
Nov. 27 birthday party in Newburgh for Anthony ``Prune'' Burden.
   He also said that during part of the four-day period when Miss
Brawley claimed she was held captive she spent time with ``a former
boyfriend'' and ``drug dealer,'' identified by WCBS-TV as Jason
``Chico'' Colon.
   A second teen-ager also appeared briefly on the program. Taibbi
said he didn't know his name but assumed that he was the young man
that Fleming said was his son.
   Gregory Fleming Sr. said the mystery witness and his son came
home laughing after they appeared on camera.
   ``It was a big joke to them,'' Fleming told a roomful of
reporters. ``They didn't understand the position they were in. ...
They were taken advantage of by the reporter.''
   Attorney General Robert Abrams, who is the special prosecutor
for the Brawley case, issued a statement saying: ``All aspects of
this case, including reports that Tawana Brawley may have been seen
in Newburgh, are under continuing investigation.''
   The Daily News reported Miss Brawley twice ran away from home,
disappearing for more than 24 hours each time, before last November.
   According to the News, the first incident allegedly occurred
when Tawana was 13 and she spent the night with a teen-age boy
watching television. When the girl was 14, she took off from school
on a Friday afternoon and spent two days in Beacon, smoking
marijuana, drinking beer and partying with a girlfriend and two
men, the report said.
   In each case, her family searched frantically for the girl but
did not report the disappearance to police, the newspaper said,
quoting unidentified friends of the girl. And in each case, the
girl was beaten by her mother when she was found, the paper said.
   The paper quoted Sharpton as saying that he did now know if the
stories of the girl's running away and then being beaten were true,
``but if they did (hit her), it's not abnormal. If anything, it
ways Tawana came from a family who cared. ... It doesn't follow she
fabricated her story.''
</TEXT>
