<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp     05-05 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Gunboats Growing in Number and Increasingly Active</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's fleet of armed small boats has
grown and increased its activity since Iran's April 18 clash with
the U.S. Navy in the Persian Gulf, but observers said Thursday the
purpose of the buildup remains a mystery.
   Gulf-based shipping and salvage officials said commercial
vessels passing through the Strait of Hormuz, the southern gateway
to the gulf, noted more activity by Iranian craft in the last two
days.
   The officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``People reporting in say there haven't been any challenges, but
they see a lot of movement by the small boats,'' said one executive.
   In Washington, Pentagon officials also reported an unexplained
increase in numbers and activity of Iran's small boats along the
Hormuz coast this week.
   The fast boats carry weapons ranging from machine guns and
portable rocket-propelled grenades to mounted anti-aircraft cannon.
Iran's Revolutionary Guards use them to attack neutral ships, in
retaliation for Iraqi air raids on Iranian oil tankers.
   Iraq on Thursday claimed its warplanes hit a tanker off Iran as
the week's fourth convoy of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers headed
down the gulf toward Hormuz.
   There was no independent confirmation of the raid, reported by
Baghdad's official news agency. The report, quoting a military
spokesman, was monitored in Cyprus.
   On Tuesday, Iran's Parliament speaker, Hashemi Rafsanjani,
accused the United States of backing Iraq in the 7{-year-old gulf
war and said Iran would continue its blow-for-blow attacks on
shipping.
   The Pentagon officials, speaking on the condition of not being
identified, said U.S. intelligence monitors were alert for signs
that Iran might challenge Washington's new, get-tough policy which
went into effect on Tuesday.
   The policy permits American warships to intervene in Iranian
attacks on vessels not flying the American flag. Previously the
U.S. vessels were restricted to defending American-flagged ships.
   Iran condemned the change as proof of ``U.S. aggression'' and
promised to avenge last month's clash, in which U.S. forces wrecked
two Iranian oil platforms and sank or disabled six craft.
   Iran's losses included two of its best naval frigates, a
missile-armed patrol boat and three Swedish-built Boghammar Marin
speedboats.
   The U.S. action was in retaliation for Iran's laying of mines,
one of which damaged the U.S. frigate Samuel B. Roberts on April 14
and wounded 10 crew men.
   Tehran said 44 Iranians were killed. Two Marine Corps pilots
died when their AH-1 Cobra helicopter gunship was lost, evidently
to hostile fire.
   Pentagon officials said they were monitoring an increase in the
number of small gunboats at Bandar Abbas, Iran's main naval base,
overlooking the strait.
   One source said the fleet had grown in the last two days to
about 100 from a normal level of ``several dozen.''
   The officials said U.S. intelligence analysts were ``not overly
excited'' by the buildup, but the reason for it was not known.
   They said it was too early to conclude that Iran was planning a
large-scale move to test the new U.S. policy. Depite its losses,
Iran's naval force is still potent, according to military analysts.
   Adm. William J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, said during a visit to Manama that ``there are a number of
threats that the Iranian navy still represents.''
   Iran has about ten large ships _ not all of them seaworthy _ 10
fast patrol boats and a variety of other craft. The lost Boghammars
were only a small fraction of hundreds of high-speed armed boats.
   Iran said three days ago that its patrol boats in the Hormuz had
resumed challenging commercial vessels, in search of war-related
cargo for Iraq.
   Iran also claimed that an American warship stopped an Iranian
cargo ship, Iran Mehrab, on Tuesday and questioned its crew.
   U.S. officials in Manama were not available to comment on that
claim.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Cyprus,
said the incident ``proves Washington's intentions to expand its
aggression in the Gulf.''
   The United States now has 17 warships in the gulf, including a
missile cruiser, two destroyers and four missile frigates.
   The convoy sailing southward included the 79,999-ton oil
products tankers Chesapeake City and Ocean City. The voyage began a
day after another convoy arrived at Kuwait.
</TEXT>
