<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ForeignAid     05-05 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foreign Aid,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs $13.3 Billion Foreign Aid Bill With Few Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee, with relatively little
dispute, approved a $13.3 billion foreign aid bill Thursday for the
year beginning Oct. 1, largely continuing current programs.
   The Appropriations foreign operations subcommittee adopted the
measure on a voice vote at the end of a closed-door drafting
session. It represents about a 2 percent increase over last year's
aid spending level, and now goes to the full Appropriations
Committee, which is trying to expedite passage of its 13 individual
spending measures this year.
   ``It's a spare bill,'' said chairman David Obey, D-Wis. ``But it
addresses the most urgent needs we have.'' Obey said the
administration generally supported the measure, the passage of
which was eased by agreement on a spending ceiling in last year's
budget agreement between Congress and the White House.
   As usual, the lion's share of aid will go to Israel, which is
guaranteed $1.8 billion in military aid and $1.2 billion in
economic help. Egypt ranks a close second, with $1.3 billion in
military assistance and $815 million in economic aid.
   Pakistan, which has served as a conduit for U.S. aid to the
rebels fighting the Soviet army in neighboring Afghanistan, would
receive $220 million in economic aid and $240 million in forgiven
loans for purchase of military goods.
   Another $124 million in economic aid and $125 million in
military aid was earmarked for the Philippines, and $90 million in
economic support and another $655 million in economic development
money would be used for African countries.
   In Central America, Honduras would get $85 million in economic
aid, Costa Rica $90 million, El Salvador $185 million and Guatemala
$80 million. Military aid for those and other countries was not
earmarked, but would come out of separate military aid and credit
accounts.
   The bill also would give economic aid of $40 million to
Portugal; $20 million to Morocco; $10 million to Tunisia; $15
million to Cyprus; between $10 million and $35 million for Ireland;
and $2 million for Poland's Solidarity trade union.
   Some $34 million would be set aside for Middle East development
projects, of which $11 million is for projects in Jordan and $23
million for those in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza strip.
   The bill also would allocate $150 million to the Peace Corps,
$101 million for international narcotics control, $362 million for
migration and refugee assistance, $35 million for the prevention of
AIDS worldwide and $254 million to pay past-due debts of
international financial institutions.
   It would send $217 million to support a long list of United
Nations organizations, and stipulate that the money for UNICEF must
be obligated within 30 days of passage of the bill, or the
administration would suffer an automatic cut of $50 million in
money for military aid.
</TEXT>
