<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GdanskScene     05-05 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gdansk Scene,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Riot Police Besiege Shipyard</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weary strikers in the shipyard where the
short life of free unionism began roused themselves to chant
``There is no freedom without Solidarity!'' Hundreds of riot police
ringing the yard listened impassively.
   The workers began Thursday morning to prepare for an assault by
police, after riot squads stormed the Nowa Huta steel mill in
southern Poland, ending a 10-day-old strike. Their only question
was when.
   Lech Walesa said he would be the last to leave as the deadlock
continued into the night in this Baltic port. He is the shipyard
worker who built a fledgling strike in August 1980 into a movement
that brought down a government and won him the 1983 Nobel Peace
Prize.
   After withdrawing a blockade of the huge Lenin shipyard for a
few hours early Thursday, police returned in force before 9 a.m.
and put it under virtual siege.
   Officers diverted traffic several blocks from the main gate and
a cordon of riot police prevented entry to the plant. Strikers in
Poland occupy the place they work rather than leaving it.
   Security forces patrolled the streets of Gdansk, which are lined
with solid brown brick buildings and working-class apartment
houses, and they occasionally checked the papers of pedestrians.
Only people living near the yard were allowed through the blockade.
   Dozens of people watched the shipyard scene from their balconies
or windows.
   A huge Solidarity banner hung from the main gate. Dozens of
strikers sat on the gatehouse roof.
   Crowds of several hundred had gathered in front of the main gate
before the blockade, but riot police dispersed them.
   Shouts of ``There is no freedom without Solidarity!'' from
inside the yard could be heard several blocks away.
   Police built a metal fence during the day around the square
outside the gate.
   The square's dominating feature is a huge monument with three
crosses, honoring Baltic Coast workers killed during strikes in
1970 that brought down another Polish government.
   Building it was a promise Walesa made in 1980 and it was
dedicated later that year. Solidarity, the first independent union
in the Soviet bloc, was suppressed and crushed after martial law
was imposed Dec. 13, 1981.
   Dozens of police vehicles were parked about 300 yards from the
gate during the day, so the strikers could see them clearly.
   Management refused to meet with the strikers, who gradually
became convinced a raid was imminent unless they gave up. Walesa
told them: ``I'll be the last to leave.''
   The blockade appeared to relax somewhat by late afternoon.
Regular police withdrew, leaving only the riot officers, and most
of their vehicles moved out of view.
</TEXT>
