<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2dLd-Writethru a0829 05-05 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2d Ld - Writethru, a0829,0858</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Shuts Down West Bank Commerce</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 11 grafs arrest of Arab-American; picks up 8th
`Near Beita'; minor editing to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAPPUAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish settler trying to
drive Palestinian shepherds away shot one of them to death Thursday
and seriously wounded another, according to Israel radio and Arab
reports.
   In Jerusalem, plainclothes police arrested Mubarak Awad, an
Arab-American who advocates non-violent resistance to Israeli
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The radio said the shooting incident began when an Israeli woman
saw several Arab shepherds in a field between Turmus Aiya, a West
Bank village 17 miles northeast of Jerusalem, and the Jewish
settlement of Shillo.
   She called other settlers, the Arabs responded with stones and
``one of the settlers opened fire, apparently on the
stone-throwers, killing one and wounding another,'' the radio said.
   A reporter for the Al Quds newspaper in Arab east Jerusalem said
Jewish settlers tried to drive Arabs out of fields in which they
were working near Shillo. He said the dead man, Jude Abdallah Awad,
28, was shot in the head and Rizik Abu Naim, 29, was wounded in the
right eye when he tried to help Awad.
   About 18 plainclothes police arrived at Awad's house at
midnight, his wife Nancy Nye told The Associated Press. She said
the agents would not identify themselves and had no orders for the
arrest, but her husband was taken to Jerusalem police headquarters.
   Last year, Israeli authorities confiscated Awad's identity card
and said he would be expelled, but the order was not carried out.
   Awad, 44, has homes in Jerusalem and in Wapakoneta, Ohio. Many
elements of his strategy of non-violent resistance have been
adopted by Palestinian activists during the five months of
rebellion in the occupied territories.
   Earlier Thursday, Israeli troops shouting orders through
megaphones told all West Bank merchants to close for three days or
their shop doors would be welded shut.
   The army ordered the ban on commerce to punish Arabs in the West
Bank for a one-day strike Wednesday called by Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Many strikes have swept the occupied lands since Dec. 8, when a
rebellion against Israeli occupation began among their 1.5 million
Palestinian residents. Israel captured the territories from Jordan
and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Near Beita village, where a teen-age Jewish settler was slain
last month, hundreds of Jewish settlers trudged along a mountain
path Thursday waving Israeli flags. They chanted ``Expel the
Arabs!''
   In the Gaza Strip, troops fired tear gas at 150 children who set
tires ablaze and raised the Palestinian flag to protest the army's
closing of Arab schools. The youths chanted ``PLO yes, Israel no!''
Soldiers shot and lightly wounded a 15-year-old Arab in the Gaza
town of Khan Yunis, Israel radio said.
   Hundreds of Arabs have been wounded in the five months of
violence and at least 184 have been killed. Two Israelis were slain
_ the teen-ager, Tirza Porat, and a soldier.
   Police in Jerusalem detained Elias M. Zananiri, managing editor
of the Palestine Press Service and the weekly Al Awdah's
Arabic-language edition. Rafi Levy, the police spokesman, said
Zananiri would be held at least 48 hours for investigation on
charges of inciting to riot.
   Israeli authorities have closed the Arab-run press agency and Al
Awdah, which also has an English edition.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said the Palestinians have scored
a media victory with their rebellion, but said violence would not
help them.
   ``I don't deny that people have demonstrated courage, threw
stones and achieved a media victory,'' he said. ``But where it
leads to? What will happen tomorrow, in a month, in two months?
Nothing.''
   In Jericho, the army shut down the West Bank's largest vegetable
market, and stores were ordered shut in Nablus, Jenin, Tulkarem,
Hebron and Bethlehem.
   In Nablus, soldiers built roadblocks and prevented Arab taxis
and buses from leaving the city, to punish residents for adhering
to Wednesday's work stoppage.
   Businessman Saed Kenaan of Nablus said the army action was
intended to create dissension between Palestinians and the
underground leaders who order the strikes.
   During a four-hour march Thursday, about 1,000 settlers, many
with rifles slung over their shoulders, retraced the route planned
by teen-age hikers involved in a bloody clash in the Arab village
April 6. Miss Porat, 15, and two Palestinians were killed.
   ``We want to finish what we started 30 days ago,'' said Menachem
Ilan, one of two armed escorts with the hikers last month. ``We
intend to show people everywhere that the nation of Israel can walk
freely in every part of the land of Israel.''
   ``I'm proud to do it again, but it feels like a nightmare,''
said 15-year-old Ariel Avivi, one of 16 teen-agers on the April
hike.
   An army investigation concluded that Miss Porat was accidentally
shot to death by the other guard. Jewish settlers have said the
Arabs caused her death by stoning the teen-agers.
</TEXT>
