<HEAD>Hostage Says He Shared Cell With Terry Anderson</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-France-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A freed French hostage said Thursday he shared a
cell with Terry Anderson, the 40-year-old American journalist who
has been held longer than any other foreign captive in Lebanon.
   Asked by a French television reporter how he felt, Marcel
Fontaine replied: ``We survived. I passed the time playing dominoes
and chess with my cellmate.'' Asked who his companion was, Fontaine
replied, ``The American, Terry Anderson.''
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated
Press, was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   His sister, Peggy Say, said she was encouraged by the releases.
She said she planned to ask the French hostages ``what Terry is
thinking and dreaming about, what his hopes are, how he's
surviving.''
   Mrs. Say spoke with the AP by telephone from her home in
Batavia, N.Y.
   Fontaine, Marcel Carton and journalist Jean-Paul Kauffmann were
abducted in 1985. They were released Wednesday and arrived in Paris
on Thursday.
