<2ND_LINE>AM-Journalist Killed,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Photographer Killed in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Izvestia photographer was killed and another
seriously wounded by a grenade attack on the military convoy in
which they were riding in Afghanistan, Soviet media reported
Thursday.
   Izvestia, the government newspaper, published front-page
photographs of Alexander Sekretarev, 29, who was killed in the
attack Wednesday, and his wounded colleague Sergei Sevruk. The
headline on an accompanying article was: ``While Fulfilling
Professional Responsibility.''
   The newspaper and a Tass news agency report said others were
killed or wounded in the ambush three miles north of Kabul, the
capital of Afghanistan, but it did not say how many.
   ``Grief from Afghanistan has visited many a home in our
country,'' Izvestia said.
   Tass said Sekretarev was killed when three armored personnel
carriers came under fire from a grenade launcher in a vineyard
along the road to the Salang tunnel, which runs under the Hindu
Kush mountain range.
   Anti-communist rebels have fought the Soviet-backed government
since a communist coup in April 1978. Soviet military forces
entered the country in December 1979.
   About 115,000 Soviet soldiers now are in Afghanistan, but the
Kremlin has agreed to pull them out in nine months beginning May 15.
   Izvestia said Sekretarev was sent to Afghanistan two weeks ago
to report on the withdrawal.
   ``His memory will be preserved in the photos which he took and
transmitted to the editorial office,'' Tass said.
   The convoy probably was one of the military units preparing to
leave, since the route out of Afghanistan for the Soviets is
through the Salang tunnel.
   Western diplomats based in Kabul told reporters who have been
there in the past few weeks that rebels plan to attack Soviet
convoys leaving the country.
</TEXT>
