<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Namibia     05-05 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Namibia,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Namibian, in Washington, Calls for Policy Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Namibian rebel leader said Thursday the
United States should support independence for his homeland without
regard to the presence of Cuban troops in neighboring Angola.
   Sam Nujoma, president of the South West Africa People's
Organization, met with senior U.S. officials on Thursday and called
on the United States to pressure ``the racist South African
regime'' into granting independence and black majority rule to
Namibia, Africa's last colony.
   Nujoma visited the State Department after talks earlier this
week in London with officials from the United States, South Africa,
Angola and Cuba.
   Among the issues they discussed was the situation in Namibia,
where Nujoma's forces have fought South African colonial rule for
more than two decades.
   The United States and South Africa believe independence for
Namibia should be linked to the withdrawal of the more than 40,000
Cuban troops from Angola.
   ``We hope the U.S. will not continue to insist on linking
Namibia's independence with the withdrawal of Cuban troops,''
Nujoma said, reaffirming a long-standing position, after his
meeting with Michael Armacost, the State Department's third ranking
official.
   ``We don't want that linkage. SWAPO disagrees with that
linkage,'' he said, adding that SWAPO is ready to sign a cease-fire
with South Africa.
   Nujoma said he wants immediate implementation of a U.N. Security
Council resolution that sets down procedures for a transition to an
independent government in Namibia.
   South Africa would benefit from an independent Namibia, he said,
because the war is a drain on South African resources and the
occupation army has been suffering numerous casualties.
   While supporting independence for Namibia, the United States has
been wary of SWAPO because it has received Soviet backing for
years. Nujoma expressed hope that the ``atmosphere of
reconciliation'' between the United States and the Soviet Union
will speed the independence process in Namibia.
</TEXT>
