<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Dennis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0875,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Attorney In Philadelphia Under Consideration for Criminal
Division</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 2 to clarify source said Dennis was Meese's choice;
subs graf 5 to delete now-redundant first reference to Meese; picks
up graf 6: Dennis, 43...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAN GEHORSAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. attorney who formerly ran the Justice
Department's narcotics division announced through an aide Thursday
he is being considered as head of the department's criminal
division.
   On Wednesday, an administration source speaking on condition of
anonymity said that Edward S.G. Dennis Jr., U.S. attorney in
Philadelphia, was the choice of Attorney General Edwin Meese III to
fill the position.
   If approved, Dennis would be the highest-ranking black
appointment in the Justice Department during Meese's tenure. Meese
has been faulted for a dearth of appointments of blacks and women.
   First Assistant U.S. Attorney Thomas Lee confirmed that Dennis
is under consideration but declined further comment pending a
formal decision. Dennis was in meetings with the Justice Department
on Thursday, Lee said.
   The source on Wednesday said that Dennis is apparently the only
name Meese has submitted to the White House for the position. A
background check is under way.
   Dennis, 43, has built a reputation during his five years as
United States Attorney through a vigorous prosecution of political
corruption.
   Dennis would fill a vacancy created by the resignation of
Assistant Attorney General William Weld, chief of the criminal
division.
   Also forwarded to the White House was the name of Harold G.
Christensen of Salt Lake City for the job of deputy attorney
general. Christensen, 67, is a partner in the firm of Snow,
Christensen & Martineau.
   Weld and Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns resigned March 29
out of concern that Meese's continued tenure at Justice despite a
nearly yearlong criminal investigation hurt the department's
operation. Several top level Justice Department posts have been
left vacant.
   The two vacancies at the top have been an embarrassment for
Meese and the Reagan administration. Other candidates for the jobs
have rejected the offers or have withdrawn their names after
damaging disclosures about their personal lives.
   Republican Senate aides have said privately that anyone Meese
nominates for the vacant top posts in Justice may have a difficult
time being confirmed, but one such aide said Dennis might have a
better chance because he is a career Justice Department employee.
   Weld said Wednesday that Dennis ``is an outstanding'' U.S.
attorney and ``would be on my short list for any top job at the
Justice Department.''
   ``My understanding is that the attorney general has met and
talked'' to Dennis ``and the attorney general thinks very highly of
him,'' said Justice Department spokesman Terry Eastland.
   Any announcement on who will fill the criminal division post
``is a matter for the White House'' to decide, said Eastland.
   Weld said Dennis did an excellent job running the narcotics
section in the criminal division before taking the post in
Philadelphia in 1983. Dennis also has moved aggressively against
organized crime, he said.
   ``I cannot say enough good things about him,'' he said.
   Dennis attended the University of Pennsylvania Law School. He
worked as an assistant U.S. attorney in Pennsylvania's Eastern
District. In 1980, he became chief of the Justice Department's
Narcotics and Dangerous Drugs Division.
   When he took over the Philadelphia office, an investigation of
police corruption had just started. Dennis set out to crack the
``code of silence'' that prevented police officers from testifying
against each other.
   After a four-year investigation, his office won more than 25
convictions, ranging from patrolman to deputy commissioner.
   In his most notable case, Dennis personally won convictions
against reputed mob boss Nicodemo Scarfo; City Councilman Leland
Beloff, and Beloff's chief aide on charges of trying to extort $1
million from a developer.
   Scarfo was sentenced to 14 years in prison.
</TEXT>
