<HEAD>Overcrowded Motor Launch Rams Logs, Sinks; At Least 15 Drowned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CEBU CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overcrowded motor launch rammed
several floating logs and sank in the central Philippines on
Thursday and at least 15 people drowned, the Coast Guard said.
   Forty-eight others were rescued and a search was under way
between Leyte and Samar islands for more survivors, officials said.
   The 20-ton, wooden-hulled launch ``He-Man'' was approaching the
town of Lawa-an on Samar Island when it rammed floating logs and
broke up at 8 a.m. (8 p.m. Wednesday EDT), a Coast Guard report
said.
   It had left the port of Tacloban on neighboring Leyte Island
seven hours earlier with an undetermined number of passengers, the
report said.
   The sinking occurred 100 miles northeast of Cebu City and 365
miles southeast of Manila.
   Lt. Cmdr. Edgardo Duarte, chief of staff of the Coast Guard
regional office in Cebu City, said he has ordered an investigation
because the vessel was a cargo boat authorized to carry no more
than 11 passengers and a crew of nine.
   He said five of the confirmed fatalities were children and the
rest were women.
   A Coast Guard officer who spoke on condition he was not
identified speculated that up to 100 people may have been aboard
the vessel, trying to attend Lawa-an's town fiesta Thursday.
</TEXT>
