<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 2007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FuelHalt     05-05 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fuel Halt,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Production of Rocket Fuel Component Halted</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plant Blast, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production of a fuel component for the
space shuttle and military rockets was halted Thursday after a
blast destroyed one plant and a defense contractor closed the only
other plant making the compound.
   NASA and Pentagon officials said the accident should not
immediately affect the shuttle or military programs such as the MX
missile.
   However, Morton Thiokol Inc., a prime contractor on the shuttle,
said the blast Wednesday that leveled a Pacific Engineering and
Production Co. plant near Henderson could delay production of
shuttle booster rockets.
   The earthquake-force blast killed two people and injured more
than 250, four critically. The plant manufactured ammonium
perchlorate, which is used in solid rocket fuel for the shuttle and
the MX, Titan and Minuteman missiles.
   Kerr-McGee Corp. of Oklahoma City on Thursday shut down
production of ammonium perchlorate at its plant in Henderson, a
mile from the Pacific plant.
   The contractor said it wanted to determine what went wrong at
the Pacific plant and assess the minor damage that the Kerr-McGee
Henderson plant sustained from the blast's concussion, including a
damaged wall and broken windows.
   Kerr-McGee officials would not say when the plant would reopen.
   ``We're just being absolutely certain there's no problem,''
Kerr-McGee spokesman Paul Reed said in a telephone interview from
Oklahoma City. ``If we've got any doubt there's a joker in the
deck, we would take another look.''
   ``At this point we have no idea how it happened,'' said M.P.
Grotheer, director of process technology at Kerr-McGee.
   Grotheer said the Army Armament and Research Development Command
tested ammonium perchlorate in 1982 and found the compound ``is not
explosive per se.''
   The tests mixed the compound with blasting caps, black powders
and matches, and although the mixtures would burn, they would not
explode, he said.
   Pentagon officials said Thiokol has a two-year supply of
ammonium perchlorate. They said Pacific produced about 60 percent
of the ammonium perchlorate needed for the shuttle, with Kerr-McGee
producing the rest.
   Thiokol spokesman Rocky Raab said the Defense Department might
claim all of the ammonium perchlorate produced at the Kerr-McGee
plant for missiles.
   ``If the Pacific Engineering plant is down for an indefinite
period of time, there could be delays in our production,'' Raab
said.
   A Pentagon official on Thursday said it was too soon to say if
the military would monopolize Keer-McGee's production of ammonium
perchlorate.
   NASA officials have said that solid-fuel boosters have been made
already for the next five shuttle launches, including the planned
late August launch of Discovery, the first shuttle mission since
the Challenger accident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
