<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-05 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Hits East, Gusty Winds in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell from the Carolinas to New Jersey and Pennsylvania on
Thursday, and a strengthening storm over Nevada and California
generated strong winds over the Southwest.
   Sunshine prevailed over the Gulf Coast, the central Plains, the
Mississippi Valley and the Great Lakes.
   Rain was heavy in parts of the East, with Altoona, Pa., and
Quantico Military Corps Air Station, Va., receiving more than a
half-inch in the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT. Many other cities
received a quarter to a half inch.
   Thunderstorms produced marble-size hall over interior North
Carolina.
   The rain kept temperatures in the 50s to low 60s from North
Carolina to Pennsylvania and New Jersey, but temperatures climbed
into the upper 70s in northern New England, northeastern New York
and northern Midwest states.
   Caribou, Maine, reported 77 degrees at 3 p.m. EDT and Duluth,
Minn., set a record high for the day of 78 degrees.
   The Southwest storm whipped winds across southeast Idaho and
western Utah, and from southern portions of California and Nevada
to Arizona. Winds gusted to 43 mph at Pocatello, Idaho, and 45 mph
gusts were recorded at Milford, Utah.
   A high wind warning was posted for the southwest valleys of
Utah, southern Nevada, parts of southern California and all of
Arizona.
   Temperatures varied widely in the southwest, with Palm Springs,
Calif., reporting 68 degrees at 3 p.m. EDT and Tucson, Ariz.,
hitting 87.
   Scattered thunderstorms hit parts of New Mexico and were
expected to develop across much of the rest of the western third of
the nation.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 34 degrees at Mammoth
Lakes, Calif., to 91 degrees at Harlingen, Texas.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast for the
western Plains across to the Northwest and parts of California.
Windy conditions were expected for the northern and central Plains
and central and southern Rockies. Rain was predicted from New
England and the Middle Atlantic states to North Carolina.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 50s in coastal New England,
western Pennsylvania and the Pacific Northwest; and in the 80s in
Florida, the lower Mississippi Valley, the Great Plains, southern
New Mexico and southeast Arizona. Highs were predicted to be in the
60s and 70s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
