<1ST_LINE>r a AM-`ET'Video     05-05 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-`ET' Video,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`E.T.' Video Gets Big Fall Promotion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial,'' the most
popular movie of all time, will be released in video come fall with
a mammoth advertising campaign.
   Pepsico and MCA announced the promotional effort Thursday at a
Universal Studios sound stage decorated to look like a wooded scene
from the 1982 movie.
   The videocassette will be released Oct. 27 at a retail price of
$24.95, said Gene F. Giaquinto, president of MCA Home Entertainment
Group.
   Pepsi Cola will support the release with a series of TV
commercials featuring ``E.T.'' and by offering a $5 rebate on the
video's purchase, said Roger Enrico, president of Pepsi Cola World
Wide Beverages.
   Enrico said Pepsi will have ``E.T.'' displays in more than
60,000 stores and sponsor a sweepstakes giving away more than
100,000 copies of the video.
   Giaquinto said the two companies will spend $25 million
promoting the release.
   Steven Spielberg's movie tells the story of an endearing little
alien who is marooned on earth and befriended by children. They
protect him from government agents looking for him and help him
return to his world.
   The worldwide box office for the movie is estimated at nearly
$500 million.
   Giaquinto said MCA is taking unprecedented security steps to
ensure that customers receive a legitimate copy, not a counterfeit.
He did not say what those steps would be.
   MCA, Pepsi and Spielberg's company will contribute some of the
proceeds of the video sale to the Special Olympics for the mentally
retarded.
</TEXT>
