<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hostages-Syria     05-05 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages-Syria,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mediator Says French Hostage Release Involved Shah Loan Repayment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-France-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Syrian businessman involved in efforts to free
the last French hostages in Lebanon said Thursday that France
finished repaying a $1-billion-dollar Iranian loan in order to free
the men.
   ``It was paid back in three installments, the last one just very
recently,'' Omran Adham said in an interview with The Associated
Press. ``This is my information from the French, Syrians and
Iranians.''
   Adham, 41, a commodities trader with a Syrian diplomatic
passport, was expelled from France Tuesday night and is staying at
a Geneva hotel.
   He said he was certain the French government offered
``compensation for the kidnappers,'' although he had no proof.
   ``There were presents for everybody,'' he said, declining to
elaborate.
   Reports in Paris and Beirut said that in exchange for the
release of Marcel Carton, Marcel Fontaine and Jean-Paul Kauffmann,
France agreed to repay the outstanding balance on a loan originally
totaling $1 billion made by the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
The French government froze payments after the 1979 Islamic
revolution in Iran.
   Radio France Internationale, citing diplomatic sources, said two
payments had been made and the French government will sign a check
for $400 million in the next few days.
   Interior Minister Charles Pasqua vigorously denied Thursday that
France paid a ransom.
   Adham said French President Francois Mitterrand asked him to
mediate in March 1986, and gave him a letter for President Hafez
Assad of Syria.
   Adham said he contacted Assad about 10 times in two years and
asked the Syrian leader to pass messages to Iran, which was
believed to have influence over the kidnappers.
   Adham said he most recently traveled to Damascus, the Syrian
capital, on March 9 as part of an official French delegation
including negotiator Jean-Charles Marchiani, Pasqua's personal
representative.
   Prior to his expulsion, Adham lived in Paris for 11 years with
his French wife and four children.
   He charged Prime Minister Jacques Chirac ordered him to leave in
order to monopolize credit for the release of the three hostages,
held since 1985. Chirac is a candidate for the French presidency in
a runoff election on Sunday.
   In Paris, Arab diplomatic and French government sources have
said that Pasqua, who is close to Chirac, was annoyed by Adham's
statements to the media about an imminent release of the three
hostages just before the first round of the presidential elections
April 24.
   Adham said the French government wanted to ``divert all credit
from me.'' ``They are seeking maximum advantage from the hostage
affair. They knew on Tuesday that the liberation was nearly at
hand,'' he said.
   He said he drew no material benefit from his missions.
   ``I don't need the French government financially because I have
good business all over the world. I can live wherever I want,'' he
added.
   But he said lawyers are challenging the expulsion and he expects
to return to Paris.
</TEXT>
