<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DapperBandit     05-05 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dapper Bandit,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Identify Suspect As Much-Sought `Dapper Bandit'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By READ MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank-robber who shot and wounded himself when
police cornered him was identified Thursday as the courteous Dapper
Bandit who baffled authorities for a decade with dozens of smoothly
executed hold-ups.
   Mark Ervin Reeves, 34, was held on $500,000 bail on an
aggravated robbery charge in a hold-up Wednesday of a bank, police
Capt. John Holt said.
   Reeves, who shot himself in the neck as police surrounded his
car at a stoplight a half-hour after the robbery, was in critical
condition in Humana Hospital Medical City Dallas, spokeswoman Linda
Henry said.
   Holt said Reeves is the Dapper Bandit, the well-dressed,
well-groomed robber with a meticulous knowledge of banking
procedures. The Dapper Bandit has been blamed for 25 robberies,
most in the Dallas-Fort Worth area.
   Other state and federal charges are being considered against
Reeves because of evidence, including surveillance-camera
photographs, linking him to a number of other holdups, Holt said.
   ``We have photographs from virtually all of those'' 25
robberies, Holt said.
   ``First of all, he's very good. Second of all, he's very
lucky,'' Holt said of the Dapper Bandit's ability to elude capture.
``He planned well, he executed well and he was well-disguised''
with wigs and false moustaches.
   ``We and the FBI naturally are very relieved,'' he added.
   Officers who searched Reeves' expensive apartment found weapons
taken from bank security guards _ the Dapper Bandit's method was
always to disarm any guards before robbing the bank _ as well as
explosives, police said.
   The Dallas Morning News quoted an unidentified woman Thursday
who said she had dated Reeves for two years. She described him as a
gun-toting cocaine abuser who lived like a playboy and had no
apparent source of income.
   He raced cars professionally in the Southwest and maintained an
apartment in a Dallas complex that charged between $525 and $900
per month, she said.
   Police caught up with Reeves at an intersection Wednesday,
recognizing his car as matching the one used in other Dapper
crimes, Holt said. Reeves shot himself as police shouted at him to
drop the gun, witnesses said.
   An undisclosed amount of money was recovered from a briefcase in
the car, and a handheld police monitor, wig and false moustache
were also found, police said.
</TEXT>
