<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NewAngels     05-05 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Angels,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New `Angels' Selected for Fox Television Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four little known actresses have been
selected to star in an updated version of the late 1970s hit series
``Charlie's Angels.''
   The four, selected from more than 20,000 interviewed, were
introduced at a news conference Thursday by producer Aaron Spelling
and Fox Broadcasting. They will appear in ``Angels '88'' on the Fox
network.
   The show will not be a sequel of its predecessor, a private-eye
series that ran on ABC from 1976 to 1981 and catapulted Farrah
Fawcett to stardom. There won't be any Charlie, there will be four
Angels instead of three, and one is black.
   ``This is the 1980s and we really wanted a black angel and we
set out to find one. We found so many talented actresses it was a
tough choice,'' said Spelling, creator of the original ``Charlie's
Angels.''
   ``These angels will not report to any man,'' said Spelling.
``The premise is that they're actresses whose show went up against
`The Cosby Show' and was canceled. They stumble upon a case and
solve it.
   ``It's a contemporary show. We'll also see their private lives.
They'll date, we'll get into sex, safe sex, but it's not going to
be sexy. It's action-adventure with a lot of comedy.''
   The four actresses were introduced as Claire Yarlett, a blonde
raised in an English convent; Karen Kopins, a brunette and native
of New York who is appearing on ``Dallas''; Sandra Canning, the
first black Angel, born in the Virgin Islands, and Tea (pronounced
TAY-a) Leoni, who was discovered in Boston and says her previous
``occupation'' was wind-surfing.
   Spelling said he had a commitment from Fox for a two-hour movie
and 13 episodes.
   It is uncertain when the show will go on the air because of the
two-month-old strike by the Writers Guild of America. Spelling said
only the movie pilot has been written.
</TEXT>
