<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0834 05-05 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0834,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Criticizes Delegate Rules, Early Crowning of Dukakis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 18th graf pvs, After the, with more
Jackson comment; ADDS 1 graf with departure for Los Angeles</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KEARNEY, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson sharpened his criticism of
the Democratic delegate-selection process Thursday, complaining of
a push for ``coronation'' of rival Michael Duakis.
   ``We must not give the impression by the inflated, padded lead
made by the super delegates and their friends'' that the race is
over, resulting in a feeling among Jackson supporters that ``their
vote does not count,'' he said.
   Jackson complained vigorously about party rules during his 1984
presidential bid but has generally steered clear of such objections
this year.
   He said Thursday he has no intention of formally challenging the
rules as he did in 1984 but expects party leaders to intervene when
the delegate count _ especially among at-large delegates and the
643 ``super delegates'' _ varies widely from the popular vote in
the Democratic primaries.
   ``That's all we're asking for, a matter of good judgment,'' he
said.
   Jackson has won 28 percent of the votes in primaries so far but
is publicly supported by just 46 super delegates. The Massachusetts
governor, meanwhile, has won 37 percent of the votes cast in the
primaries and is supported by 166 super delegates.
   The super delegates were created for this year's campaign
specifically to give the party establishment a significant voice
outside the primary process in choosing the nominee. They are party
leaders and politicians, including governors and members of
Congress, who are delegates to the Democratic National Convention
by virture of the offices they hold.
   Overall, Dukakis has about 1,500 delegates while Jackson has
about 930, according to The Associated Press delegate count.
   Jackson brought up the delegate matter as he ate breakfast with
a Nebraska farm family outside Kearney, and again in talking to
reporters at the airport.
   He said his campaign will contact super delegates and at-large
delegates in congressinal districts where he won and try to
persuade them to follow the voters' choices when they vote at the
party convention this summer.
   ``We'll be making appeals for fairness and we certainly hope
people will respond,` he said.
   Jackson delegate counter Steve Cobble said he and other
officials recognize that the rules do not require delegates to
commit themselves proportionately with the popular vote.
   ``We're saying here's another way they could behave,'' Cobble
said.
   Some states do choose delegates in proportion to the popular
vote. But in Pennsylvania, for example, which does not have such a
system, Jackson got 28 percent of the vote and only 8 percent of
the delegates, Cobble said.
   ``The race is much closer than the pundits and the press
project,'' Jackson said. ``What the people are saying must not be
covered up by all the horse talk of the coronation and `the race is
over.' The race is on,'' he said.
   Jackson said he was not threatening to withhold support from the
party if his wishes are not met, but he also recounted past
elections in which he said Republicans won a embittered Democrats
stayed home.
   He cited the 1980 re-election bid of then-President Carter, who
had been challenged in the primaries by Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
   After the divisive primary race, many of Kennedy's followers
became ``embittered by the process (and) some had taken an
anybody-but Carter position,'' Jackson said. Carter lost to Ronald
Reagan.
   ``At this point, let's be positive about it. Let's be hopeful
about it. The most positive consequence of being fair is that
people are inspired ... When people are inspired and diligent, they
work diligently,'' Jackson said.
   However, he added that the perception he was being treated
unfairly could keep his supporters away from the polls in November.
``They get discouraged,'' he said.
   Jackson addressed a high school audience in Kearney, a small
rural town of mostly white residents.
   Dressed for the day in blue jeans, a vest and trucker's cap,
Jackson then flew to Albuquerque, N.M., for a rally.
   Talking there with a busload of Hispanic and civic leaders,
Jackson spoke against the idea of making English the national
language, saying that is ``not reaching out, it's pushing out.''
   The movement is strongly opposed by Hispanics.
   He also spoke about immigration affairs, saying U.S. policy
should begin with efforts to help Latin American nations improve
their standards of living.
   Jackson flew from Albuquerque to Los Angeles, where his schedule
included a visit to the city's historic downtown Olivera Street,
traditional hub of Hispanic culture, and a Hollywood fundraiser
later.
</TEXT>
