<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 2204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Trawler     05-05 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Trawler,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Arrest Canadian Trawler in St. Pierre-Miquelon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian trawler was arrested
Thursday by authorities from the French-held islands of St. Pierre
and Miquelon, which are the subject of a boundary and fishing quota
dispute between Canada and France.
   Tom Rideout, Newfoundland's fisheries minister, said preliminary
reports indicated the trawler was stopped in contested waters about
48 miles from St. Pierre.
   ``If that is the case, both countries have agreed not to arrest
boats in that area and this is a very, very serious matter,''
Rideout said. ``The only motivation I can think of is political _
the French presidential elections.''
   He was referring to the runoff elections this Sunday between
incumbent Socialist Francois Mitterrand and conservative Prime
Minister Jacques Chirac.
   A French military vessel arrested the trawler, said John Banys,
a federal Fisheries Department official in Ottawa.
   Residents in St. Pierre said the trawler, the Maritimer, fishes
out of Fortune, Newfoundland, and has a crew of five or six. After
the arrest at sea, the trawler was directed into port at St. Pierre
and Miquelon.
   ``I'm outraged by it and I'm sure all Newfoundlanders will be
outraged as well,'' said Richard Cashin, head of the fishermen's
union that represents the crew. ``It's an example of French
arrogance.''
   The incident appeared to be retaliation.
   Last month a trawler from St. Pierre was arrested in Canadian
waters and 21 French citizens on board, including four politicians,
were jailed for fishing illegally. The French government posted
bail of $510,300 (U.S.) to get them released and temporarily
withdrew its ambassador from Ottawa.
   At the heart of the dispute is France's claim of a 200-mile
economic zone around St. Pierre and Miquelon, where the population
of 6,000 relies on fishing and tourism to survive.
   Canada recognizes only a 12-mile French zone around the islands,
whose closest point is just 10 miles from Newfoundland.
   The two countries dispute the international boundary of St.
Pierre and Miquelon, and the share of cod and other fish they can
take from the waters south of Newfoundland. When attempts at a
negotiated settlement failed last year, Canada closed its ports to
all French fishing vessels and banned them from the nearby Gulf of
St. Lawrence.
   Talks resumed last month in Paris and both sides agreed to seek
a neutral mediator.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
