<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TreatyBeer     05-05 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Treaty Beer,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Treaty Beer' May Go Flat In Washington State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treaty Beer, the brew touted as a
fund-raiser for groups fighting Indian treaty rights, appears to
have flat in Washington state.
   Following negative publicity, cries of racism and a call by Gov.
Booth Gardner for a boycott, sponsors are having trouble finding a
distributor.
   Indian leaders said Thursday they're gratified by the public
reaction against ``this racist product.''
   The key distributor that marketers had planned to use, Lindberg
Distributing Co. of Tacoma, backed out Wednesday. General Manager
Gary Mustain said the controversy was more trouble than it was
worth.
   ``We're not here to champion causes,'' he said. ``We became
involved in a political decision we did not want an part of.''
   Dean Crist, the Minocqua, Wis., man who created the product to
help finance groups fighting Indian treaty rights to fish and game,
said plans to sell in Washington are on hold while sponsors
scramble to find a distributor.
   Crist, who sells the brew in his home state, charged that
distributors are responding to the political pressures whipped up
by the liberal media.
   He added that his news conference in Seattle last week was a
little like ``President Reagan addressing the Iranian press.''
   He denied that his intent was racist and said he wants to help
finance efforts to manage and allocate the fish runs on an equal
basis.
   The governor, church and civic leaders, environmentalists, the
timber industry and Indian rights groups banded together last week
to blast Treaty Beer and urge a boycott.
   Bill Frank Jr., chairman of the Northwest Indian Fisheries
Commission, on Thursday praised Lindberg's decision not to carry
the beer and the ``groundswell of public support we have received
in rejecting this product.'
   ``It should be obvious to anyone that Indian and non-Indian
relations have come a long way here,'' he said. ``We are building
something very positive together, and confrontation ... is being
left behind. We are setting an example for the entire nation to
learn from.''
</TEXT>
