<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Denmark-Defense     05-05 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denmark-Defense,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danish Military Opts for Sexual Equality in the Ranks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women in Denmark's armed forces can
now drive tanks and perform other duties once carried out
exclusively by men, the Defense Ministry announced Thursday.
   The decision was based on a study of women's performances in the
army, air force and navy.
   Women have been training and serving alongside men on naval
vessels on an experimental basis for several years. Psychologists
and physicians monitored the experiment and recommended that the
arrangement be made permanent.
   ``After evaluating the reports from the experiments I am
satisfied that the time has come for opening up generally for women
in the armed forces,'' said Defense Minister Bernt Collet.
   The action was in keeping with a government policy of moving
toward full equality in all fields, Collet said in a statement.
   ``In principle, equality applies throughout the military, but a
final decision on allowing women to train as F-16 jet fighter
pilots depends on the results of continuing medical
investigations,'' Collet said..
   So far no country allows servicewomen to fly supersonic F-16s.
   Defense authorities did not say whether women would enter combat
but it appeared they would do so under new policy.
   The minister stressed that admittance and education reqirements
in the military will be the same for men and women.
   ``We cannot compromise with respect to the units' combat
readiness and efficiency,'' the statement said. ``Therefore,
everybody regardless of sex must fulfil requirments set by the
different branches.''
</TEXT>
