<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 2213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua     05-05 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Workers End Fast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 42 striking construction
workers and car mechanics ended their 10-day fast Thursday after
the Sandinista government agreed to negotiations next week, union
leader Alejandro Solarsano said.
   Solarsano, a leader of the General Workers Federation, said the
fast for higher wages was a success because it ``restored dignity
to workers.''
   The group began a hunger strike at federation headquarters on
April 25 to back a strike that began Feb. 25 and is supported by
4,500 workers, according to the union.
   Rolando Velasquez, the federation's secretary of labor relations
and one of the hunger strikers, said the construction workers and
auto mechanics would continue their walkout.
   ``The hunger strike is suspended, but the work stoppage will
continue until the demands of the working class are obtained,'' he
said.
   The federation groups socialist unions. The fast has been a
particular irritation to a leftist government that considers itself
in the vanguard of workers rights.
   Sandinista police diverted traffic from a four-lane highway at
the site of the federation headquarters. The strikers filed out and
were loaded into civilian cars. Some held their arms above their
heads.
   Police barred journalists from approaching and roughly pushed a
TV crew.
   Solarsano said four of the hunger strikers were taken to a
hospital for treatment.
   Labor activist Nilo Salazar said 42 workers took part in the
fast.
   Federation director Carlos Salgado told reporters Thursday the
deteriorating physical condition of the hunger strikers was a
factor in calling off the fast. He said the government cut off
water supplies to federation headquarters and kept relatives from
bringing medical supplies inside.
   Police have detained more than 70 people since the hunger strike
began.
   The Interior Ministry shut down news shows for eight days on two
private radio stations for broadcasting what it said was false
information. A third station was shut down completely for 24 hours
but allowed to reopen Thursday.
   Also on Thursday, the Foreign Ministry said a CIA center based
in neighboring Costa Rica provided false documents to sully the
Nicaraguan government's image.
   ``It has been increasing in direct relation to the negotiation
process'' with Nicaraguan rebels, Alejandro Bendanda, the
ministry's secretary-general, told a news conference.
   He blamed the Reagan administration, saying ``the line is to
prove negotiations have not produced results.''
   The Sandinistas have been trying to work out a definitive
cease-fire agreement with the U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras.
An agreement between the two sides was signed March 23, shortly
after the U.S. Congress voted down additional military aid for the
rebels.
   The Contras have fought the Sandinista government since late
1981, two years after it came to power in a revolution that ended
42 years of rule by the rightist, pro-American Somoza dynasty.
   Bendana said the CIA documentation center was in San Jose, the
Costa Rican capital, and was uncovered by an Interior Ministry
investigation. He declined to elaborate.
   He said at least eight false documents surfaced recently and
said they were an attempt to rob the government of credibility.
   In San Jose, a person answering the phone at the Costa Rican
government's Organization of Judicial Investigation said the agency
knew nothing of any such activity. The person refused to give a
name.
</TEXT>
