<1ST_LINE>u w AM-CapitolHill-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0887 05-05 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Capitol Hill-Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0887,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Breaks Out in House Speaker's Office; No Injuries</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOPS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with two officers treated for
smoke inhalation, cause of fire, estimate of damages; PICKS UP 5th
graf pvs bgng, `We'd have'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out late Thursday in the Capitol
Hill office of House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and the blaze
raged unimpeded for 10 minutes due to a lack of fire hoses and
alarms, says a congressman who was one of the first at the scene.
   Two U.S. Capitol Police officers were treated for smoke
inhalation at the scene, but they did not require further medical
attention, said officer Dan Nichols.
   The fire in Wright's second-floor corner office of the Longworth
Building, across the street from the Capitol, was caused by an
electrical problem, said District of Columbia Deputy Fire Chief
Jamelia Jackson. He estimated the damages at $120,000 and said the
offices will need extensive restoration.
   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., whose offices are next door to
Wright's, said the fire was able to spread for at least 10 minutes
after it broke out shortly after 6 p.m. because fire hoses which
are supposed to be in emergency cabinets throughout the building
were missing.
   ``I'm totally frustrated by a congressional building that has no
fire alarms and absolutely no fire hoses in the standpipe
cabinets,'' said Weldon, who is a former fire chief.
   ``We'd have had the fire out. We knew where it was, we were in
there, and we just couldn't get to it,'' he told reporters on the
sidewalk outside, his shirt smudged with soot. ``I guarantee you
I'll raise Cain about it the next time we're in session, which I
guess is Monday.''
   The House had adjourned for the weekend a short time before the
fire erupted.
   Weldon said he and some Capitol police officers smelled smoke
and ran to Wright's office, where they found the fire just starting
in a kitchen area and climbing one wall. They tried to use small
dry-chemical fire extinguishers ``which were just no good,'' he
said.
   There is no alarm system in the seven-story building, so guards
had to be sent running down hallways to evacuate congressional
offices, Weldon said. When District of Columbia firefighters
arrived, they had to drag hoses up to the second floor to get water
on the blaze, he added.
   ``And this is supposedly the nation's Capitol. We're going to
have some heads spinning next week,'' Weldon said.
   Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., was forced onto the sidewalk in the
rain dressed in a tuxedo. A party he had been holding in the
building to pay off a bet on the NCAA basketball tournament had
been interrupted by the fire.
   ``I don't think anybody was upset. A fire is a fire. You gotta
get out,'' Kolbe said. ``Nobody had even gotten any food. We had to
leave all the food there.''
   ``The speaker's office is pretty much burned out. There's a lot
of heat damage,'' said Weldon. ``That whole corner is going to have
to be redone.''
   Wright's primary office as house speaker is in the Capitol
building. The office where the fire occurred primarily handles his
congressional district business.
   Weldon said he had just formed a congressional fire caucus _ a
group of members concerned about fire prevention issues _ three
months ago, ``because America doesn't have a fire policy.''
   He pointed to a rocket-fuel plant explosion in Nevada, a fire in
a Los Angeles high-rise and the Capitol Hill incident _ all in the
past two days _ as ``the best examples you could have'' of the need
for such a policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
