<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 2215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Anti-BiasRuling     05-05 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Bias Ruling,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Commission's Anti-Bias Requirement Upheld</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court on Thursday allowed
the California Coastal Commission to require an exclusive Los
Angeles club to take an anti-discrimination pledge in exchange for
permission to develop beach property.
   The Jonathan Club admitted its first black and female members
last summer, and said in court papers it does not discriminate in
its membership practices.
   However, the club has refused to comply with a Coastal
Commission requirement of declaring a non-discrimination policy in
order to receive a permit to expand its Santa Monica facilities.
Part of the land the club occupies is leased from the state.
   The Supreme Court refused a hearing on an appeal by the club of
a lower-court ruling in the Coastal Commission's favor.
   However, the high court unanimously withdrew the ruling as a
precedent for other decisions, leaving the scope of the
commission's power unclear.
   Attorney John Shiner said the club had not decided whether to
appeal.
   Deputy Attorney General Anthony Summers, the commission's
lawyer, said club officials publicly stated their policy for the
first time in their court papers.
   ``It seems to me that if they were willing to tell the
commission (the same thing) they would be complying,'' he said.
   ``That misses the point,'' countered Shiner. ``The Coastal
Commission lacks the authority and the jurisdiction to impose a
condition of this sort on any applicant.''
   In his court papers, Shiner said the commission was seeking
``the power to intrude into the private affairs of every citizen of
this state.''
   The case illustrates how ``perfectly well-intentioned persons
who are seeking to remedy a social evil may develop a witchhunt,
vigilante approach,'' Shiner wrote.
   The club wants to build new paddle tennis courts and a parking
lot, all restricted to members only, on 122,000 square feet of
Santa Monica beach property, 58,000 square feet of which are on
lots leased from the state.
   The leases do not contain anti-discrimination clauses. But when
the club applied for a development permit in 1985, the commission
said it would require a written promise not to discriminate against
minorities or women.
   The club refused, saying its membership policies were irrelevant
to the issue. But a Superior Court Judge ruled in the commission's
favor and was upheld in January by a state appeals court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
