<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 2256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Guerrillas     05-05 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Guerrillas,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Guerrillas Attack Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of guerrillas belonging to a
group holding 13 foreigners and Colombians attacked an eastern
border town before dawn Thursday and battled with police for four
hours, officials said.
   One officer was killed and four were wounded in the attack on
Salazar de las Palmas, a town of 15,000, by about 60 members of the
National Liberation Army, police said.
   The guerrillas said in a news release that the hostages,
captured Monday and Tuesday in various Colombian cities, were in no
danger and will be released by week's end with an important
message. The captives include two West Germans, two Swiss men and a
Frenchman.
   In the statement delivered Wednesday at the Medellin home of
West German Honorary Consul Helmut Luecker, one of the captives,
the group said the hostages were held in the ``New Colombia'' camp
in northeastern Colombia.
   The news release, a glossy pamphlet in Spanish, German and
French, was delivered in an envelope with Luecker's car keys. Other
copies were delivered to news media organizations in Bogota and
Bucaramanga.
   The release said European countries ``should make their
positions known about the dirty war that sweeps our country today
and demand that the Colombian government stop the genocidal
practices.'' This was an apparent reference to recent killings of
peasants in several areas of the country, in which 122 people have
been killed in less than two months.
   Police said Thursday they had no clues. They identified the
abducted foreigners as Sigfried Markert and Luecker, the West
German honorary consuls in Bucaramanga and Medellin; Jean
Christophe Rampal, a press attache at the French Embassy in Bogota;
and Richard Aufereggen and Wilfred Lehner, two Swiss nationals
working for the Colombian-Swiss Chamber of Commerce in Bogota.
   The guerrillas were also holding eight Colombians, including
journalists and the president of the Santander State Assembly and
two politicians of that city.
   The news release, signed by Roman Catholic priest Manuel Perez,
head of the guerrilla group, said the purpose of the abductions was
to ``denounce'' that ``the Colombian oligarchy has surrendered the
best of the country, its natural resources and the national
sovereignty to American imperialism.''
   The group says the Colombian government has placed its oil
resources in the hands of U.S.-based Occidental Petroleum, which
has a 15 percent stake in a 2-billion-barrel oil deposit in eastern
Colombia.
   Ecopetrol, the state oil company, owns 60 percent, Anglo-Dutch
Shell Oil, 20 percent and a Spanish company 5 percent.
   In its campaign against foreign oil companies, the guerrillas
have staged 22 attacks against an oil pipeline with a capacity of
215,000 barrels per day. It runs from the Cano Limon fields near
the Venezuelan border to the Caribbean port town of Covenas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
