<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 2257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MethodistConference     05-05 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Methodist Conference,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Methodists Condemn Interventions In Other Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Methodists on Thursday narrowly
voted in favor of a boycott of Royal Dutch Shell Petroleum, parent
company of Shell Oil U.S.A., to protest its business dealings in
racially segregated South Africa.
   On vote of 475 to 418, the denomination's governing body
endorsed a resolution urging Methodists to refrain from buying
Shell products.
   The vote at the 9.6-million member denomination's conference
came after a sharp debate in which several blacks pushed for the
move and two Texas delegates argued against it, saying Shell is
using its influence to end apartheid.
   Numerous Protestant and Catholic groups, below denominational
level, and labor organizations previously have called for such a
boycott, as has the Unitarian Association, a relatively small
denomination.
   In October, the 1.7-million member United Church of Christ
became the first major Protestant denomination to join in urging a
boycott.
   The American subsidiary has emphasized it has no operations in
South Africa and that it and Royal Dutch Shell firmly oppose
apartheid.
   In a statement Thursday, Shell expressed disappointment with the
vote by the nearly 1,000 Methodist delegates, saying those who will
be hardest hit ``are the innocent American service station owners
and jobbers who sell Shell products.''
   Delegates also urged the use of full ``moral and corporate
resources'' to end South Africa's system of racial apartheid, but
stopped short of an outright call for ``complete disengagements of
companies and banks'' doing business there.
   The delegates at the 11-day conference running through Friday
noted that there is disagreement over such methods.
   The boycott is part of a campaign endorsed by such groups as the
United Mine Workers, the AFL-CIO, the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.
</TEXT>
