<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Polyester 1stLd-Writethru a0889 05-05 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polyester, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0889,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Polyester Capital' Gets Its Revenge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `The polyester ...' to CORRECT Lincoln's
population to 172,000 sted 35,000.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The headline in USA Today could read:
``Proud Prairie People Pounce on Polyester Pundit.''
   In other words, don't mess around with Lincoln residents when it
comes to polyester.
   The polyester wars began Tuesday when USA Today wrote a story
about Cliff's Notes, those yellow-and-black booklets explaining
literary classics that have been a boon to untold legions of high
school and college students. The company that puts out Cliff's
Notes is based in this town of 172,000.
   ``Some might call this birthplace of Cliff's Notes the edge of
nowhere, a city still comfortable with fulsome waistlines and
polyester,'' wrote the reporter, Karen S. Peterson.
   In mock retaliation, Scott Young, co-host of KFOR radio's
morning show, urged Lincolnites to participate in the ``Plethora of
Polyester Pile-Up.'' The plan was to send Peterson pounds and
pounds of polyester.
   The turnout was better than expected, with a little help from
the folks at Goodwill Industries.
   On Thursday, two Goodwill trucks loaded with 5,000 pounds of
baled polyester clothing pulled up to the station. That was added
to the 50 pounds already collected at the station.
   There were polyester shirts, polyester slacks and polyester
leisure suits.
   Lots and lots of leisure suits.
   After checking the cost of shipping more than 2 tons of
polyester to Peterson at USA Today headquarters near Washington,
D.C., Young and company opted to send her a representative sampling
of Lincoln's sartorial ``best.''
   Peterson will soon be the proud owner of a ``beautiful polyester
collage'' of the state, emblazoned with the tourism slogan
``Nebraska, the Good Life,'' Young said.
   ``We're also going to send her some polyester lingerie and some
snappy polyester slacks,'' he said.
   And, of course, a few leisure suits.
   At USA Today on Thursday, the 50 to 60 members of the Life
section, where the story appeared, were decked out in University of
Nebraska red-and-white to greet a film crew from an Omaha
television station.
   Peterson was not in the office Thursday night, but was preparing
to do some radio interview on Friday _ including one with KFOR.
   ``Obviously, we've been following this very closely,'' Tom
McNamara, managing editor of the section, said in a telephone
interview. ``We're more than willing to good-naturedly eat some
crow on this.''
   ``We love Nebraska. We love Lincoln. We're trying to make
amends,'' McNamara said. Then, knowing the way to a Nebraskan's
heart, he added:
   ``The Life department roots every year for Nebraska to beat
Oklahoma.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
