<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChowchillaParole     05-05 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chowchilla Parole,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schoenfeld Denied Parole in Chowchilla Kidnapping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN LUIS OBISPO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of three men who kidnapped
and buried a busload of Chowchilla schoolchildren in 1976 was
denied parole a ninth time Thursday.
   The three-member State Board of Prison Terms panel voted
unanimously to keep Richard Schoenfeld, 33, in Central Men's Prison
here for his role in the abduction of the 26 children and their bus
driver in 1976.
   Alameda County Assistant District Attorney Don Whyte had argued
that continued imprisonment would be a deterrent to others.
   ``I have no doubt in my mind that Mr. Schoenfeld would not
commit an offense like this (if released),'' said Whyte. ``But I'm
not sure there aren't others lurking around who might.''
   The panel agreed Schoenfeld poses an ``unreasonable risk of
danger to society.''
   Schoenfeld, along with his brother James and Frederick N. Woods,
are serving life sentences for abducting the bus at gunpoint from
rural Madera County about 150 miles southeast of San Francisco. The
men shut the victims in a poorly ventilated moving van buried in a
quarry about 100 miles away in Livermore.
   It took the captives 16 hours to dig their way through the
wood-and earth-covered hole to safety.
   Karen Snell, Schoenfeld's attorney, said he will seek parole
again next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
