<DOCNO> AP880505-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 2326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r n PM-WI-Payton-Racing     05-05 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WI-Payton-Racing,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NY CX</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELKHART LAKE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Chicago Bears running back
Walter Payton, the all-time career rushing leader of the NFL, says
car racing takes total concentration, skill and finesse _ just like
football does.
   ``Racing is so mental,'' Payton said. ``It's exactly like
football. You have to be concentrating on every down. In racing,
you have to be concentrating on every lap....
   ``When you're out on the track, you're not only competing for a
fast lap, but you're competing against the other guy,'' he said.
``Besides, I love to go fast.''
   Payton, who retired from the NFL after last season, took part in
a driving school at the four-mile Road America sports car racing
course here, and it was his third driving school in six weeks.
   As for the interest in car racing, he told The Milwaukee
Sentinel that was nothing new.
   ``I've always been interested in racing,'' Payton said. ``Ever
since I was a kid and looked under the hood of my dad's car. It's
just the natural thing.
   ``I thought about racing motorcycles about four or five years
ago, but then that was impossible,'' he said. ``About three years
ago, I thought about racing sports cars when I retired from
football.''
   In the training sessions here, he took the classroom studies, as
required, in a Formula Ford.
   During break times, he got some practice in his own Sport 2000
racer.
   Payton said he hopes to return to the Road America course to
compete in the June Sprints, and he can feel his improvement as a
driver.
   ``I'm getting more confidence with the car,'' he said. ``The
trick is to be smooth with the car coming into and leaving the
turns. Anybody can run fast on the straightaways.''
</TEXT>
