<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionProtests     05-05 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Protests,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DA Says He Does Not Want To Prosecute Abortion Protesters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HICKSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 401 anti-abortion
demonstrators outside a gynecological service Thursday, but the
district attorney said he does not want to prosecute because he
feels they did no wrong.
   ``I do feel very strongly that when one trespasses at an
abortion clinic in a peaceful and non-violent way, they are doing
so to save lives,'' said Nassau County District Attorney Denis
Dillon.
   Dillon said he was asking a Nassau County administrative judge
to appoint a special district attorney to handle the arrests.
   The demonstrators from Operation Rescue were accused of blocking
the entrance to the clinic. They were charged with disorderly
conduct and released, said Officer Peter Lambert, a Nassau County
police spokesman.
   ``You can use the analogy of someone trespassing on private
property to save the life of someone being strangled. The
trespassing becomes relatively unimportant in that case, in my
view,'' Dillon said.
   A federal judge on Wednesday had continued an order prohibiting
Operation Rescue and its director, Randall Terry, from blocking
entrances to abortion clinics.
   U.S. District Judge Robert J. Ward had threatened $25,000-a-day
fines that would be turned over to the National Organization for
Women.
   However, city attorney Lorna Bade Goodman said it was unclear
whether the fines could be levied because Terry apparently had not
been served with the order prior to the protest in this New York
suburb.
   Demonstrations by Operation Rescue on Monday and Tuesday in New
York City resulted in hundreds of arrests.
</TEXT>
