<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugTesting     05-05 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Testing,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Excepts Nuclear Utility Workers From State Privacy Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court ruled Wednesday
that private unionized employees can't use state privacy laws to
challenge drug testing, allowing random screening to resume at the
San Onofre nuclear power plant.
   The San Onofre workers can fight a company testing program only
by claiming a violation of their contract through National Labor
Relations Board grievance procedures, said the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in a 3-0 decision.
   The court rejected arguments by the 850 workers that the privacy
rights involved in drug testing are so fundamental that they cannot
be negotiated away. Union contracts often authorize employers to
search workers' possessions, the panel noted.
   In the San Onofre case, the union contract did not mention drug
testing, but the company has interpreted it as allowing such a
program.
   The union has asked the NLRB to review the dispute. But in a
case where a contract expressly authorized drug testing,
Wednesday's ruling would appear to leave workers without recourse.
   ``I'm quite dismayed,'' said attorney John True of the
Employment Law Center, a legal aid office whose clients include
workers challenging drug testing.
   The ruling's scope is limited to unionized workers in
California, since non-union workers still could invoke the right to
privacy against a private employer under the state constitution.
   Southern California Edison Co., the operator of San Onofre,
praised the ruling, saying in a statement that ``unannounced
testing is legal and appropriate under the circumstances to protect
the public health and safety.''
   Although the suit had been filed only on behalf of 850 union
members, Edison spokesman Lou Phelps said the company had halted
testing of a total of 2,000 to 3,000 workers, including non-union
employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
