<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis and his tenacious rival
Jesse Jackson both plotted strategy for the final push of the
primary season, and readied for a pair of smaller-scale contests
after weeks of big-state battles. Vice President George Bush,
meanwhile, says fear of ``kiss and tell'' books has sometimes kept
him from speaking up in Cabinet meetings.
   Bush said Wednesday that other times he keeps quiet at the
meetings ``because I don't want the president to have to be
choosing between his vice president and the other members of the
Cabinet.''
   Jackson was vowing to press on despite bruising losses to
Dukakis in Ohio and Indiana on Tuesday. Those defeats capped a
six-week losing streak in the primary contests, broken only by
Jackson's victory the same day in the District of Columbia.
