<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:VanPeebles Adv11   05-05 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Van Peebles, Adv 11,0831</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, May 11 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sonny Spoon On His Own</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Note the show title in the 4th graf may be objectionable to
some readers.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY17 of May 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANNIA CLEATON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mario Van Peebles was an economics student. He
dealt in limited partnerships in films, and worked as a New York
City budget official. But he wanted to be a star, and he went to
his father for help.
   He got advice, nothing more.
   ``I think it was hip that my dad let me do it myself because if
I couldn't, then I shouldn't be here,'' said Van Peebles, star of
NBC-TV's detective-comedy series, ``Sonny Spoon.''
   His father is Melvin Van Peebles, the author-producer-director
who created the controversial movie, ``Sweet Sweetback's Baadasssss
Song,'' Broadway's ``Ain't Supposed to Die a Natural Death'' and
``Waltz of the Stork.''
   The elder Van Peebles never interceded on the behalf of his son,
except to caution, ``Show biz is a business, learn that business
side.''
   So he took the tortuous route to stardom, from Columbia
University to Wall Street to City Hall and finally to Broadway and
Hollywood.
   Following small parts on stage and in the movies, Van Peebles
appeared in the play ``Waltz of the Stork.'' His film appearances
include ``Heartbreak Ridge,'' ``Jaws: The Revenge,'' ``Exterminator
II'' and ``The Cotton Club.'' He also has appeared on ``The Cosby
Show,'' ``L.A. Law'' and the daytime soap opera ``One Life to
Live.''
   Having a famous father helps, Van Peebles said.
   ``But if you don't have the talent to stay there, they'll slam
the door on your foot,'' he said. ``They're not going to give you a
lead in a show based on who your dad is and people are not going to
watch you.''
   Mario Van Peebles was born in Mexico City. He, his father and
mother, Maria, traveled and lived throughout Europe for eight years
before settling in San Francisco. The time in Europe served him
well.
   ``I learned a lot of accents like that,'' he said. ``I speak a
little French, I speak a little Spanish, a little uptown, a little
downtown. It helps me a lot now in my work.''
   His character on ``Sonny Spoon'' is a streetwise detective who
regularly slips into other characters _ a Japanese chef, an old fat
man, a Frenchman, a church woman, an attorney _ to get the job done.
   Van Peebles finds that having the ability to change characters
helped prevent him from being typecast.
   ``When I first came to LA (Los Angeles) people sort of said,
`you're a young (Harry) Belafonte, you're going to play black
leading men' _ which sort of meant unemployment if you missed `A
Soldier's Story,''' he said, referring to the critically acclaimed
film and play.
   The actor decries the lack of film and TV roles for blacks and
other minorities. ``You have to understand _ whatever you look
like, whether you're fat with red hair, you have to deal with that.
... It's hard.
   ``This is the deal. The bottom line is the golden rule: He who
has the gold, rules,'' he said. ``So just get in there, do your own
show and shut up; have a handle on how you're presented if you
can.''
   Van Peebles said blacks have been supportive of ``Sonny Spoons.''
   ``A lot of people have come up to me and said, `Are you worried
because you're doing a show and there's no hour show where a tan
guy like yourself is in the lead?'
   ``Maybe I would feel more pressured if I didn't feel I was
showing a positive image _ or they (black community) didn't seem to
feel it _ or we didn't seem to feel that we were showing a positive
image.
   ``I insisted the cops and villains be mixed (races) so we break
away from this silly color stuff. I want a human show. If I have a
black show, I've lost,'' he said.
   Van Peebles said his ultimate goal is to become a filmmaker. He
is working on a feature film he wrote and co-produced with his
father called ``Identity Crisis.'' He stars and his father directs.
   ``My dad once said you got two loves in your life: who you're
with and what you're doing. I'm working with my dad and people I
love and care about. I'm doing what I like doing,'' Van Peebles
said.
   ``It's funny,'' he said. ``I remember people used to say `the
only reason you got the job is because of your daddy.' And now,
(they say) `the only reason your dad got the job is because of
you.' So it all comes around, you just have to laugh on it on both
sides and do your thing.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, May 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Montand Adv12   05-05 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Montand, Adv 12,0863</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, May 12 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Tenderness Cannot Become Old</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY16 of May 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The actors Yves Montand likes are the kind of
actor he is himself.
   ``I admire Sean Connery very much,'' he said. ``I like Columbo _
Peter Falk. I like this kind of actors who become older but they
don't lose their youth, really. They go on with some charm and are
human beings. They don't destroy themselves with face lifts, which
are terrible.''
   Montand was recently in New York to receive this year's tribute
from the Film Society of Lincoln Center, the 17th person to be
honored and the first Frenchman. His two most recent films are
``Jean de Florette,'' which won the British Film Academy's prize
for best picture, and ``Manon of the Spring.'' In both, he portrays
a farming village patriarch, Cesar Soubeyran.
   ``The reason I didn't want to make the movies was not because I
look 20 years older,'' said the 66-year-old Montand. ``I said, `Let
the years do their job.' It was because I wanted to go on tour.''
   Montand started as a singer, was discovered by the legendary
Edith Piaf, made his first movie with her in 1945 and sang on stage
and made movies until 1968 when he decided to concentrate on film
acting. In 1982, he made a world singing tour which was a smash
success, and planned to repeat in 1984 but made the two movies
instead.
   ``I think it is a very good story, based on a wonderful book
(Marcel Pagnol's `L'Eau des Colines'). But it was courageous to
make this kind of part, contrary to what people wait for from you.
He is a nasty man. He could be very cruel in some ways,'' he said.
   Montand and actress Simone Signoret, who were married from 1950
until her death in 1985, used to read each other's movie scripts.
   ``Sometimes she would say, `You're going to shoot this thing? It
is awful.' I would say, `You're right but I promised this young
director.' Of course the movie is a flop,'' he recalled.
   ``Sometimes you fall in love with a story you're reading. If a
director has good taste, he puts you in his pocket.''
   Montand has advice about getting older: ``Humor, tenderness and
lucidity cannot change and are important in life as you become
older. You need to laugh, have a sense of humor, first of all
against yourself. Everybody needs tenderness. Tenderness cannot
become old. Never. And if you are clear _ this is right, this is
not right _ you stay a young man or woman.
   ``I'm going to look a little pompous now but I say, never, never
stop working with your memory. You remember a girl. What is her
name? You say it isn't important, forget it. No, no. Make the
effort to discover again the name of this girl, even if it is not
important. This is exercise, like for the muscles.''
   For physical exercise, Montand walks four or five miles every
day when he can. ``Sometimes I make a seven or 10-minute dance in
the morning. Then I take a shower and that's it.''
   At the tribute, French filmmaker Louis Malle called Montand
``one of the most romantic figures the French cinema has ever
known.''
   Montand, however, still hasn't figured out romance. ``I
remembered this morning, lying in bed, the first time a girl kissed
me or I kissed her. I didn't like it. Two months later, someone
else comes, you collapse. Both are very nice looking. It's very
peculiar.
   ``When you are an adult, it is a mystery. You love me. I love
you. It's the only thing you can say. You are mad. It's
unbelievable. It's a volcano inside. What does it mean? We can
understand nothing. Death, love, we don't know anything about.
Maybe it's better, I don't know. It's a wonderful mystery anyway,
thank God.''
   During the interview in Montand's suite in Hotel Maxim's, the
telephone rang several times and a Film Society representative
spoke to women who wished to stop by. ``I'm sure it is only for
autographs,'' the actor said with a charming smile.
   Since ``Jean de Florette'' and ``Manon of the Spring,'' Montand
has done a few TV appearances. He plans a TV version about Alfred
Dreyfus, the French army officer who was convicted for treason but
later found to be the victim of anti-Semitism. He also plans to do
a movie about terrorists.
   Montand's next movie, though, will be a musical, ``Three Seats
for the 26th,'' directed by Jacques Demy with music by Michel
Legrand, who collaborated on ``The Umbrellas of Cherbourg.''
   ``I don't want to tell you the story; I want it to be a
surprise,'' he said. ``It will not be a beautiful masterpiece as
made by Gene Kelly or Fred Astaire.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, May 12</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Tunisia'sNewEra Adv11   05-05 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tunisia's New Era, Adv 11,0811</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, May 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`New Era' in Tunisia as Pro-Western Bourguiba Slips into Oblivion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Habib Bourguiba's statue still dominates a
square in central Tunis, but the man who towered over Tunisia for
32 years has slipped into oblivion six months after his ouster.
   His successor as president, Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, has
proclaimed a ``new era'' for the North African nation, appealing to
the nation's Islamic and Arabic heritage, a stand that has won him
immediate widespread support.
   Bourguiba, who had set the nation on a Western course after he
won independence from France in 1956, now is 84 years old and
confined to a chateau outside Tunis. He was declared no longer
capable of governing when he was removed from office Nov. 7.
   Ben Ali took power during a tense crackdown on Islamic
fundamentalists and is universally credited, even by political
opponents, with sparing the nation from a more serious upheaval.
   He has sought to make peace with the Islamic fundamentalists and
others in the Bourguiba opposition.
   Newspapers once banned by Bourguiba are back on newsstands. Many
people say they no longer fear the police. Tunis University,
disrupted three days a week last year by demonstrations, is quiet.
   About 5,000 prisoners, many of them members of an outlawed
Islamic fundamentalist group, have been pardoned.
   The national legislature, dominated by Bourguiba's ruling party
since Tunisia's independence in 1956, has moved toward pluralism
with a new law on political parties.
   In his most risky move, however, Ben Ali has extended a hand to
the growing Islamic fundamentalist movement, Bourguiba's chief
target in his waning years.
   Television and radio now broadcast the five daily calls to
Islamic prayer.
   Islam has alway been the official state religion, but Bourguiba
maintained a secular character in government and daily life.
   Ben Ali, a military man once in charge of the crackdown on
fundamentalists, invokes Allah (God) at the start of his speeches.
   ``It's life that's changed, not just politics,'' said Chakib
Douss, a brassware merchant in the Tunis bazaar. ``Now everyone is
free. We feel it every day, every minute. It's not something you
read about in the newspaper. It's something you touch.''
   Many in the opposition approved of the new climate, if only for
now.
   ``Incontestably, Nov. 7 was a comfort to everyone,'' said a
leading member of the Socialist Democrat Movement, the largest
opposition party, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``It's still the honeymoon, so everyone feels obliged to
publicly approve him,'' commented M'hamed Jaibi, editor-in-chief of
the weekly Maghreb, reopened in September after being shut down
four years ago.
   ``I hope this is a temporary situation,'' he said of Ben Ali's
popularity. ``Otherwise, we'll be back in the old system with a
president who thinks he is infallible.''
   That was an allusion as well to Bourguiba, who had become so
dominant that he was declared president-for-life, a benign dictator
in charge of a nominal democracy. His Destourian Socialist Party
controlled all seats in the National Assembly. None of the three
legal opposition parties had a meaningful voice.
   But Ben Ali has promised that his new era would ``open the
horizons to a truly democratic and evolved political life.''
   Since taking office, he has moved to abolish the lifelong
presidency, change the electoral code and press laws, dismantle the
feared state security court and given Amnesty International, the
London-based human rights group, a permit to operate here _ its
first in the Arab world.
   Ben Ali has also restored diplomatic relations with neighboring
Libya and stresses closer ties with the Arab world.
   While citizens appear won over by the changes, some opposition
politicians remain cautious and fundamentalists are reserving full
judgment.
   The final year of Bourguiba's leadership was marked by a battle
against the fundamentalist Islamic Tendency Movement, culminating
in a trial in September of 90 fundamentalists on charges of
plotting against the state.
   ``The Islamic dossier remains the hottest one on Ben Ali's
desk,'' said Hassen Ghodhbani, an Islamic lawyer who defended some
of the 90 in the trial.
   He contended the measures taken by Ben Ali remain insufficient.
   ``Islam isn't just prayer and pilgrimage. It's an entire life
system,'' he said.
   In late April, the legislature quashed any hopes that the
Islamic Tendency Movement might become a legal opposition party _
one of its demands. A new law allowed new political parties but
forbade those based on religion, language, race or region.
   ``The government has adopted a double attitude toward Islam,''
said the opposition politician who spoke anonymously.
   ``It is a position both clever and dangerous.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, May 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1404EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a w AM-Drought Adv09   05-05 1204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought, Adv 09,1251</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release AMs Mon May 9 and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Northwest-Southeast Parched</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The specter of drought hovers over both sides
of America, and climate experts fear that recent rains won't be
enough to alleviate the dryness.
   While some rain has fallen along the Pacific Coast and parts of
the Southeast in recent days, both areas remain dry.
   ``It's one of these very elusive things right now. We are
getting rains, so we're keeping our fingers crossed,'' commented
Paul Sabol of the federal Climate Analysis Center.
   If this summer brings drought, it will fit into a decade that
has been more often dry than wet.
   Indeed, a look back at weather records since 1980 shows only
1982 with no serious drought areas.
   Much of the Southeast is 12 percent below normal in rainfall in
this decade _ the equivalent of a year without rain. Some parts of
Georgia are 70 inches below normal, according to water resources
officials in that state.
   Across the country, dryness has prompted water rationing in San
Francisco and may threaten crops in Washington, Oregon and Idaho.
   The Agriculture Department has established a task force to
monitor conditions in both regions.
   Northern California is experiencing its worst water shortage in
11 years, and farmers, businesses and residents have been asked to
cut back on water use. Some water districts have adopted rationing.
   San Franciscans have been told to cut consumption by 25 percent.
In Oakland, some residents are protesting a plan to limit water use
and significantly raise fees for households exceeding the
allocation.
   This winter's precipitation was normal or even above normal
until the end of January, said Gary Barbato, a hydrologist with the
U.S. Weather Service at San Francisco International Airport. ``But
February and March of this year were dismal, drought-producing
months.''
   Officials say the dryness in California isn't as bad as 1976-77,
when rainfall was only 25 percent of normal.
   In Nevada, ``the drought is still on with a passion,'' said the
state's climatologist, John James, who chairs a committee
considering both long-range and short-range measures to alleviate
the problem.
   Farmers are not the only ones affected by drought. Forest fires,
reduced hydroelectric output and increased river and stream
pollution also can be blamed on the dryness.
   ``Back in November people were beginning to become concerned
again about the Pacific Northwest,'' said Tom Ross of the U.S.
Geological Survey.
   That region suffered a drought last year, which extended into
the normally wet winter season.
   Rivers and streams in the Northwest were 35 percent below normal
in March, according to a study by the U.S. Geological Survey. In
the Southeast, streamflows were 54 percent of normal for the month.
Record low flows were recorded at 11 streams in the Southeast and
two in the Northwest.
   Thomas Heddingshaus of the federal Agricultural Weather Center
said that despite recent coastal rains, the interior of eastern
Washington and southwestern Idaho remain very dry, in addition to
California. The Center is operated jointly by the National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration and the Department of Agriculture.
   In the Southeast, many regional reservoirs are even lower than
they were at this date in 1986, preceeding the drought of that
summer, Ross said.
   Rainfall in parts of North Carolina and Tennessee measured as
little as 25 percent of normal in the first three months of this
year, according to Ross. And problem areas extended into Virginia,
South Carolina, Georgia and Alabama.
   The 1986 drought stemmed from a shift in the Jet Stream, the
strong upper atmosphere wind that tends to move weather from place
to place, said Heddingshaus.
   In normal weather, the Jet dips south over the Mississippi
Valley and then turns back to the north again, pulling along
moisture from the Gulf of Mexico to water the Southeast.
   In 1986, the Jet Stream dip occurred farther East, with the
result that the return movement north missed the Southeast, he said.
   Elsewhere in America, portions of central and northern Minnesota
also could be vulnerable to drought even with normal rainfall
through the summer, according to state climatologist Jim Zandlo.
   Researchers set odds at from 2-1 to 3-1 in favor of a drought in
those areas this summer, Zandlo said.
   ``It's almost like you saw in the typical 1930s scenes where
clouds of dust are moving across the fields,'' said Fred Kollman,
district conservationist for the Soil Conservation Service in
Norman County. ``You see drifts of dirt almost like snowdrifts in
the road ditches. There is lots of dirt in the air and lots of dirt
in the houses.''
   Here is a year-by-year outlook at dryness in this decade:
   1980:
   Hot and dry summer from the Missouri Valley throughout the
Southeastern states. Rainfall was 25 percent to 50 percent of
normal across much of the nation. The heat wave has been blamed for
as many as 1,200 deaths and crop and livestock damage estimated at
$20 billion.
   Dryness records were reported in parts of Texas, Kansas,
Wyoming, Arkansas and Virginia.
   1981:
   Much of the nation remained in the grip of the drought, which
began in 1980. Light winter snowfall meant that groundwater was not
recharged and municipal water supplies in the Northeast slipped to
dangerously low levels.
   Rains starting in May brought relief to some farm areas,
although abnormally dry weather continued in the northern Great
Plains, Southeast and Middle Atlantic states.
   1982:
   There were no extensive areas of drought, as cool Canadian air
helped produce active rain fronts during most of the summer.
   1983:
   Searing heat struck in July and August, producing severe drought
east of the Rockies.
   The drought was similar to that of 1980 but centered slightly
farther north, in the western corn belt states. Corn and soybean
crops were severely damaged and the dryness extended to the
Mid-Atlantic region. Rain was less than one-quarter of normal in
parts of Texas, Kansas, Oklahoma, Nebraska, Missouri, Iowa and
Illinois.
   1984:
   Damage to wheat crops totaled more than $1 billion in Montana
and North Dakota, where rainfall was only one-third of normal in
the first half of the year. Many brush fires were reported.
Persistent dryness also damaged crops and grasslands in central
Texas.
   1985:
   Dry conditions led to serious brush and forest fires in
California and in the Northern Rockies and Northern Plains states.
   1986:
   Virginia, the Carolinas, Georgia, Alabama and Tennessee were hit
by a drought that has been described as the worst in more than a
century. Less than one-quarter the normal rain fell in some areas.
   Some relief came in August when rains helped soybean crops, but
it was too late for hay and corn. Regional damage estimates topped
$1 billion.
   1987:
   Forest fires scorched more than 2 million acres when a dry
winter was followed by a sweltering summer in parts of Idaho,
Washington, Oregon and California. Water shortages occurred in
Spokane and some other communities.
   Hot, dry conditions in July and August also contributed to
drought conditions in the Southeast, reducing crop yields sharply.
Heavy rains came along in September, but excessively dry conditions
returned to the Southeast in October and November, particularly
affecting West Virginia, Kentucky and Tennessee.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 9</NOTE>
