<1ST_LINE>a a BC-BehindtheWheel Adv14-15   05-05 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 14-15,0658</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14-15</NOTE>
<HEAD>Advance for Weekend Editions, May 14-15, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dodge Dynasty First Impressions Don't Hold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first impression of Dodge's new luxury
full-size sedan, the 1988 Dynasty LE, was of a refined Dodge, one
better than the rest.
   The exterior had some of the same styling of Chrysler's K-cars
but was updated with a nicely squared-off trunk lid in the rear.
The interior, on first glance, seemed a comfortable mix of modern
touches and familiar, old gauges _ all with good quality.
   Unfortunately, first impressions don't always hold up.
   More than 300 miles after picking up the test car, a few things
had gone wrong. The power antenna stuck midway through the test and
wouldn't go up until I pulled off the highway and pried the antenna
free with my fingernails.
   The cigarette lighter didn't fit right and never popped back up
once it was pushed down. The temperature control lever fell out, so
heat could not be regulated. In desperation one day, I finally
figured out a way to jam the lever back in and maneuver it along a
horizontal axis to get some warmth.
   The dashboard was admirably designed as one piece to prevent
squeaks and rattles, but in the test car it didn't seem to fit
quite right. Though there were no squeaks, a passenger noticed he
could see right down to the underlying metal through a gap between
the dash and window pillar.
   And, like Chrysler's K-cars on which it is based, the Dynasty
had a pentastar logo capped over the trunk keyhole that kept
snapping back and pinching fingers as the trunk was opened.
   The Dynasty also had the characteristic K-car hole in the center
of the trunk for a full-sized spare tire that, without a tire
there, meant garment bags would fall inside in a rumpled heap.
   The Dynasty does have decent leg room in the rear, a back seat
that is comfortable and doesn't feel like a bench, and a fine,
optional Infinity II sound system ($767).
   The exterior fit and finish was excellent, and a standard
feature that automatically locks all doors when the car is in gear
and speed reaches more than 15 mph was startling at first but later
comforting.
   The optional electronic fuel-injected V-6 ($660) performed
smoothly.
   Additionally, Chrysler Motors Corp. priced the car below many
competitors. The lowest-priced Dynasty starts at $11,666 compared
with more than $14,400 for an Oldsmobile Delta 88 and more than
$14,000 for a Pontiac Bonneville.
   That fits with Chrysler's plan to lure less affluent buyers _
median income of targeted Dynasty buyers is $36,000 compared with
$40,000 annually for the average buyer in this market segment.
   Target Dynasty buyers also are a bit younger, age 55, compared
with the average age of 61 in this market segment, Chrysler said.
   Seventy percent of the Dynasty buyers are expected to be male.
Chrysler said it introduced the Dynasty in the 1988 model year to
lure new buyers.
   In a press release, the automaker's Dodge Division says the
top-of-the-line Dynasty will compete with Oldsmobile Delta 88 and
Pontiac Bonneville for the younger, more upscale and better
educated buyer looking for up-to-the-minute technology in a
traditionally styled family car.
   But buyers of any age and income expect better quality than what
was on the test car, especially considering that with options, the
price came to $16,700-plus.
   For that price, the Dynasty had best hold up under close
inspection.
   Because the vehicle is new, there are no reliability reports.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 14-15</NOTE>
