<1ST_LINE>s a BC-TowninTrouble Adv08-2Takes   05-05 0820</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Town in Trouble, Adv 08-2 Takes,0840</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>East St. Louis: Ragged Riverfront City Struggles to Survive</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deep in debt and scarred by scandal,
this ragged riverfront town has witnessed political brawls and
street shootouts. Now it's fighting again _ to survive.
   Too little money and too many problems have created what some
say is the worst crisis ever in this long troubled city, where
crime and corruption are so common the mayor has 24-hour bodyguards
and ex-cons have lined up for his job.
   East St. Louis has garbage on its streets, debts in the millions
and bill collectors at its doors. It also owes $4.1 million to a
man who suffered brain damage after being beaten by a cellmate in
the city jail.
   What's more, two mayoral appointees are under indictment. And on
May 11, the city faces trial on charges of reckless conduct,
accused of endangering several police officers by not supplying
properly working radios or cars.
   The situation? ``Critical,'' said Alderman Melvin Frierson.
``It's in worse shape than I've ever seen it before.''
   ``We've got a lot of poor people, a lot of problems and no money
to deal with them,'' said lawyer Rex Carr, a member of a panel
convened to study those problems. ``I see no hope of getting
adequate funds. There is no hope for East St. Louis under present
circumstances.
   ``Someone I heard say they expect (cities) like East St. Louis
to lift themselves up by the bootstraps,'' he added. ``People have
no boots to lift on. You've got to give them the boots.''
   Mayor Carl Officer, criticized by some for running a
``reckless'' administration, is defiant in the face of bankruptcy
rumors.
   The city's predicament is ``not without pain,'' Officer said.
``But it's not something that you roll up the red flag and say, `I
give.' I don't think that you should panic over it.''
   Officer blames council members for excessive spending. ``That's
not bad financial condition,'' he said. ``That's poor financial
planning.''
   Political squabbles are frequent. The city's twice-monthly
paychecks were finally issued three days late last Monday after
money was borrowed from other accounts. The treasurer argued the
city didn't have the money; the mayor said it did.
   East St. Louis was once a vibrant town with chemical, metal and
glass works until crime, corruption and labor troubles, beginning
about 1960, led to white flight and job losses. This virtually
all-black city has shrunk to 55,000 people from 82,000 in 1960.
   Today, most of the major industries operate outside city limits
and provide no tax base. Residents are poor; recent estimates
indicate 60 percent receive goverment aid.
   East St. Louis has some assets: land, a large labor force and a
prime location. Officer, a third-generation funeral director, hopes
to breathe new life into his city with a $500 million riverfront
development plan that includes housing, a recycling facility and an
inland port.
   But the riverfront now is a dismal jumble of weeds and garbage,
a sharp contrast to St. Louis' gleaming high-rises and soaring
Gateway Arch just across the Mississippi. And away from the water,
signs of decay are everywhere: gutted buildings, boarded-up
businesses and trash on the streets.
   Crime has become so routine it's a sight gag in the movie
``National Lampoon's Vacation,'' when the family's hubcaps are
stolen as they drive through East St. Louis.
   The city's finances, however, are its greatest burden; it is
already $2 million in debt, and projected annual revenues fall
$200,000 short of this year's $6.8 million budget.
   Comptroller LaMar Gentry says up to 90-100 city employees _ a
third of the workforce _ may have to be laid off. Officials say 25
workers were laid off recently and 25 more are expected to be cut
soon.
   Gentry cited other drains on city coffers, including:
   _ $1.3 million in lost federal revenue sharing funds.
   _ about $400,000 that could be due this year in an arbitration
judgment awarded to firefighters involving back pay and raises.
   _ $262,000 owed to a refuse service that halted collection last
fall and sued; it's only one among scores of unpaid vendors. A
$350,000 contract has been signed with a new service, but Officer
contends the city can't afford regular garbage pickup. Gentry
already has strict priorities: payroll, then gas for fire and
police vehicles. Then, he said, ``You pay off who raises the most
hell.''
   _ $4.1 million owed to Walter DeBow, an electrician who suffered
brain damage and needs perpetual nursing care after a jail beating,
said his attorney, Clyde Kuehn.
   Police checking DeBow's car after a 1984 accident said they
found an open bottle of malt liquor. Although he should have been
able to post his driver's license and leave, he was jailed in lieu
of $100 cash bond.
</TEXT>
