<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-Principal-Arthritis Adv08   05-05 0987</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Principal-Arthritis, Adv 08,1016</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Victoria Principal Has Mother's Day Message on Arthritis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Victoria Principal has a Mother's Day
message for millions of American women: pay attention to aches and
pains that could be early signs of arthritis.
   ``You don't have to live the last years of your life with the
degree of discomfort that elderly people have lived with for
years,'' she said in a recent interview.
   One in seven Americans _ some 37 million people _ have been
diagnosed with arthritis. The disease affects twice as many women
than men.
   The key, Miss Principal said, is to take a few minutes to learn
the basic symptoms of the 100 various forms arthritis and then seek
medical attention, if it seems warranted.
   ``If you're more aware of your body, if you seriously listen to
the indications of your body that something is wrong and go to a
doctor you aren't being an alarmist,'' she said. ``You are simply
listening to your body and taking good care of yourself.''
   Miss Principal, head of the Arthritis Foundation's national
campaign since 1983, emphasizes early detection _ not because there
is a cure for the disease _ but because research advances of the
past few years have developed more and better ways to alleviate
suffering.
   ``Crippling pain is no longer something that is inevitable,''
she said. ``We don't have all the answers yet, but we have more
answers than we've had before. By an early diagnosis you can
perhaps prevent the kind of crippling that we have seen in
generations of Americans in older age.''
   Miss Principal's mother and father have lived with arthritis for
years.
   Arthritis sufferers can find help at Arthritis Foundation
chapters in all 50 states, which provide referral to free, local
self-help programs.
   For those not yet aware of problems, the warning signs of
arthritis are soreness or redness or swelling of the joints and
morning fatigue that persist for two weeks or more.
   ``The inflamation is a tip-off,'' she said. ``If you have that,
then something is definitely wrong. Even if you don't think you
have arthritis, that indicates you should go see a doctor.''
   A major problem, she said, is that most people eventually
diagnosed with arthritis didn't see a doctor until three years
after their first symptoms appeared.
   ``If you suspected you might have cancer or heart disease, you
would probably go out and see your doctor right away,'' she said.
``We're asking people to take it seriously in a medical sense
because things can be done, particularly the sooner you get it
diagnosed.''
   Generally, those things are a combination of medication and
exercise.
   ``The range of medication ranges from the very mild such as
aspirin to some very, very, very powerful drugs if you have a real
severe form or arthritis that is not responding to other types of
medication,'' said Peter G. Mathon, a vice president of the
Atlanta-based Arthritis Foundation.
   In the most extreme cases, surgical joint replacement can be an
option _ as it has been for Mathon, who has had seven hip joint
replacements.
   While medication would to be taken under the guidance of a
physician, exercise, too, should be carefully monitored.
   ``There is a fine line,'' said Mathon. ``You want to keep the
joint moving enough so it doesn't freeze up, yet you don't want to
overwork to the point where you do more damage to the joint. Each
person is going to be a little different.''
   In addition to medication and exercise, researchers are working
hard to link certain diets with the onset of arthritis.
   ``I think we're starting to see some preliminary results in that
area and I think that eventually we will have better answers and
there will probably some links between some types of arthritis and
some foods,'' said Mathon.
   Miss Principal, who has written books on diet and exercise, said
she is convinced the links will be found.
   ``It's that old thing your mother used to say, `You are what you
eat,''' she said. ``I really believe that. I think we're going to
discover that certain foods can perhaps trigger more profound
reactions.''
   Scientists have discovered there are genetic patterns, but Miss
Principal said ``the reason something fires that genetic marker, no
one really understands yet.''
   The actress said she became involved with the Arthritis
Foundation, at first as a high-profile fund-raiser, to try to do
something for her parents ``on a larger scale,'' something more
than just helping with their own treatment.
   ``After I got involved, it escalated to an even larger scale and
I discovered how many people I know who have arthritis and had
never told me,'' she said.
   Miss Principal and Mathon were in Washington for a
government-backed general health care forum.
   One of the ``new and different'' programs sponsored by the
Arthritis Foundation is self-help classes around the nation, Mathon
said.
   In addition to learning more about the disease, the programs
sometimes involve exercise programs run in conjunction with local
YMCA's and similar organizations.
   ``We also offer support groups.'' he said. ``They get together
to talk about their experiences and share little tips and tricks
with each other. One of the main things is they realize they're not
the only ones going through these feelings of up and down because
arthritis does tend to be a roller coaster disease. You can feel
better some days and worse some days. You can got into remission,
in effect. You can be lulled into a false sense of security.''
   Locations of state Arthritis Foundation offices can be obtained
through local telephone directories or by writing the national
headquarters at 1314 Spring St., N.W., Atlanta, Ga., 30309.
   The foundation also works through the American Association of
Retired Persons, or AARP, to get out information about its programs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
