<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers union and
Chrysler Corp. have reached a tentative agreement on a two-year
national labor contract, following about 40 hours of non-stop
bargaining.
   ``We achieved the full pattern settlement we set out to achieve,
and we accepted no deviations from what we have in effect today at
GM and Ford,'' the union said Wednesday in a statement attributed
to UAW President Owen Bieber and Vice President Marc Stepp.
   The proposed contract, which would replace a three-year pact
covering 66,000 UAW workers in 15 states that expires in September,
still must be approved by Chrysler's national labor council and the
rank and file.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestically made cars fell 6.7 percent
in late April, with Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. posting sales
gains and General Motors Corp. reporting a decline, the companies
have reported.
   GM said Wednesday that its car sales for the April 21-30 period
trailed 19.7 percent behind unusually strong sales in the same
period last year.
   Chrysler posted a 10.3 percent gain for the period and Ford's
car sales were up 8.7 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Desert Partners has presented USG Corp. with new
takeover proposals valued at about $2.6 billion, seeking to head
off a reorganization plan being pursued by the building materials
company.
   In a letter to USG's board, Texan Cyril Wagner Jr. of Desert
Partners said Wednesday that ``the time has come for you to stop
spending time and money in an effort to avoid discussing an
acquisition of USG with us.''
   Wagner, who heads Desert Partners with fellow oilman Jack E.
Brown, said the partnership's latest proposal was superior to the
$2.2 billion recapitalization plan USG unveiled on Monday.
   But USG Chairman Robert J. Day said the ``proposals are not
credible.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly two years after seeking federal bankruptcy
protection, LTV Corp. has unveiled a reorganization plan that keeps
the steel-aerospace giant largely intact but scales back its steel
operations.
   The reorganization plan unveiled Wednesday envisions no further
layoffs or plant closings but would restructure the company around
existing businesses.
   Chairman Raymond Hay said LTV's principal components will be a
steel company concentrating on flat-rolled products, two aerospace
and defense operating groups and a streamlined energy products
division.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest cigarette manufacturer says
it will begin test-marketing a nearly-smokeless cigarette in the
final three months of the year.
   F. Ross Johnson, chairman of RJR Nabisco Inc., told a
shareholders meeting on Wednesday the company was ``very positive
about the prospects for this new cigarette.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will have to spend $6.5 billion
more a year on housing over the next 15 years if every American is
to have a decent, affordable place to live, an industry-backed
study says.
   The study, financed by the National Association of Realtors,
estimated Wednesday that the nation will need to spend $41 billion
to help build or renovate housing and $56 billion to subsidize
families that would otherwise have to pay more than the recommended
30 percent of their income for housing.
</TEXT>
