<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     05-05 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Sales Dip in Latest Selling Period</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Lower car sales at General Motors Corp. during late April helped
depress total national sales of domestically-made cars, which fell
6.7 percent during the period.
   Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. posted sales gains in the
April 21-30 period, but GM reported a decline, the automakers
reported Wednesday.
   In other economic news, the stock market, the dollar and the
credit markets declined.
   GM said its car sales for the April 21-30 period trailed 19.7
percent behind unusually strong sales in the same period last year.
Chrysler posted a 10.3 percent gain for the period and Ford's car
sales were up 8.7 percent.
   Domestic truck sales rose by 6.5 percent, but combined car and
truck sales were 2.6 percent less than in the year-ago late April
period.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average _ up about 26
points in the two previous sessions _ fell 22.05 to finish at
2,036.31.
   Analysts said Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan's
comments that an anticipated improvement in the nation's trade
deficit could lead to increased inflation unless domestic spending
was restrained summed up investors' mixed feelings about the
economy.
   Many investors are looking toward the Labor Department's report
on unemployment, scheduled to be released Friday, for the next clue
to the nation's overall economic health.
   Bond yields edged higher, as prices eased. The Treasury's
bellwether 30-year issue fell $2.50 per $1,000 in face value to
yield about 9.1 percent. Investors avoid fixed-income instruments
during periods of inflation, which erodes fixed yields.
   In the currency markets, the dollar was narrowly mixed in dull
trading.
   Oil futures prices slipped, pressured by a report that showed
larger-than-expected domestic inventories in gasoline and crude.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
