<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     05-05 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have tumbled in the wake of a
report showing domestic inventories of gasoline and crude were at
higher-than-expected levels.
   In Wednesday trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, June
contracts for West Texas Intermediate, the U.S. benchmark crude,
fell 17 cents to close at $17.20 per barrel.
   Among refined products for June delivery, wholesale unleaded
gasoline lost 0.56 cent per gallon, settling at 49.72 cents, and
wholesale heating oil dropped 0.57 cent to 46.20 cents per gallon.
   The American Petroleum Institute, a Washington-based trade
organization, reported late Tuesday that domestic gasoline supplies
grew by 5.9 million barrels in the week ended April 29, while crude
stocks shrunk by 700,000 barrels.
   Those figures in particular sent prices lower in London and New
York, because they left more inventory than was expected, said Mary
L. Haskins, an analyst at the Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   When inventories rise faster than demand, prices tend to fall.
   Wednesday's declines also reflected continuing market
perceptions that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
would be unable to agree on a way tighten up its production, even
when it meets next month in Vienna, Ms. Haskins said.
   Technical factors also contributed to the day's declines, she
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryBorrowing     05-05 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Borrowing,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US to Borrow $26 Billion to Boost Public Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department has set plans to
borrow $26 billion to replenish government coffers next week, down
3.7 percent from the borrowing needs in the first three months of
the year.
   The lower borrowing resulted in part from efforts by foreign
governments to prop up the value of the dollar by making heavy
purchases of U.S. securities in recent months.
   Treasury has been able to reduce its public borrowing demands
because of the large volume of securities sold to foreign central
banks, which have been selling their Japanese yen, German marks and
other foreign currencies to buy dollars as a way of stabilizing the
dollar's value.
   The foreign governments then used their newly-purchased dollars
to buy U.S. treasury securities.
   At a briefing Wednesday, William Bremner, deputy assistant
secretary for federal finance, told reporters that the purchases by
foreign central banks totaled $12 billion from October through
December last year and $16.5 billion from January through March
this year.
   The heavy purchases of U.S. debt by foreign governments have
raised concerns about the growing influence U.S. allies have over
the U.S. economy. If they suddenly curb their purchases of U.S.
debt, it could send interest rates up sharply in this country.
   The announcement that $26 billion in new debt would be sold next
week was in line with market expectations. The auctions, known as
quarterly refundings, provide the main source by which the
government finances the $2.5 trillion national debt.
   The auctions next week call for:
   _$8.75 billion in three-year notes in minimum denominations of
$5,000 to be auctioned on Tuesday.
   _$8.75 billion in 10-year notes in minimum denominations of
$1,000 to be auctioned on Wednesday.
   _$8.50 billion in 30-year bonds in minimum denominations of
$1,000 to be auctioned on Thursday.
   The $26 billion to be raised includes $9.5 billion in new cash
and $16.5 billion to pay off maturing securities.
   A total of $1.5 billion of the new cash will be used to retire
existing debt, something the government has not done since the
first year of President Reagan's first term in office.
   But Bremner said that did not mean the total national debt would
be reduced by $1.5 billion during the quarter because the
government also borrows money from such non-public sources as the
Social Security trust fund.
   A reduction of the public debt during the spring quarter was
commonplace before Reagan took office because the government always
benefited from the April tax deadline.
   However, this debt reduction has not occurred since 1981 because
the level of the government's borrowing needs has grown
dramatically with the string of huge federal deficits.
   The $26 billion to be borrowed next week is down from $27
billion raised at the last quarterly refunding in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0305 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ColecoChairman     05-05 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coleco Chairman,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coleco Chairman Resigns; Latest Chapter For Troubled Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coleco Industries Inc. will have to
intensify its cost-cutting and streamlining efforts to bounce back
from a string of financial losses, according to the outgoing chief
of the toymaker.
   Arnold C. Greenberg, the company's chairman and chief executive
officer, resigned his posts Wednesday, but will remain a consultant
and director of the company.
   Coleco's board of directors named Morton E. Handel to succeed
Greenberg as chairman and chief executive, and promoted Handel to
the board, Coleco said in a statement. J. Brian Clarke will
continue as president and chief operating officer.
   In the statement announcing his resignation, Greenberg said:
``It is necessary to intensify and accelerate cost cutting actions
already begun and to further contract the size of the company'' to
help it recover from a string of financial losses.
   Greenberg said ``financially directed leadership is desirable
during this period, and I believe Morton Handel, working together
with...Clarke can accomplish these critical objectives.''
   Coleco, which once rode high on the success of its Cabbage Patch
Kids dolls, has suffered declining sales in recent years along with
other major toy manufacturers. The toymaker posted losses of $105.4
million in 1987 and $111.2 million in 1986, following record
profits of $64.2 million in 1985.
   Coleco has slashed its work force by more than 50 percent since
last November, including layoffs of about 475 workers announced
Tuesday.
   The company also is attempting to stave off having to file for
bankruptcy protection from creditors by seeking to restructure $335
million in debt.
   Coleco paid $59.6 million in interest during 1987 _ or nearly 12
percent of the year's sales _ compared with $42.7 million in 1986.
It failed to make a $19 million interest payment due on debentures
on April 1.
   However, Coleco debt holders have been cool to its proposal to
exchange their debt securities for a combination of new debt and
common stock, and Coleco has been forced to extend the deadline for
the offer twice. The new deadline is Friday, May 13.
   Coleco also announced Wednesday that it had hired Hallwood Group
Inc. to help it restructure its balance sheet and provide working
capital. Hallwood is an international merchant banking group
specializing in financial restructurings.
   Greenberg has said the company planned to pare its 1988
operating costs by about $70 million, or 25 percent.
   After a series of spotty financial performances in the late
1970s and early 1980s, Coleco began moving toward prosperity in
1982 with the introduction of its ColecoVision home video game
system. But the $600 Adam home computer it unveiled in 1983 proved
a flopm, sales of ColecoVision cooled, and in 1984 Coleco lost
$79.8 million.
   Coleco's fortunes soared on the phenomenal strength of its
Cabbage Patch Kids.
   The dolls accounted for sales of $67 million when introduced
quietly in 1983 but skyrocketed during a national craze that
boosted sales to $540 million in 1984 and a peak of $600 million in
1985.
   Coleco boasted total sales of $776 million in 1985, but by 1986
was on a downward trend, led by Cabbage Patch sales that plummeted
to $230 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
