<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   05-05 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Automakers Report April Monthly Sales Decline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Late April domestic car sales sagged below
year-earlier levels, while for the full month import car makers
showed signs of rebounding despite pricing disadvantages stemming
from the weaker U.S. dollar.
   Combined domestic car and truck sales fell 2.6 percent to
420,626 in the sales period of April 21-30, the automakers reported
Wednesday.
   General Motors Corp. car sales for the late April period fell
19.7 percent from a stronger-than-usual sales period a year
earlier, leading a 6.7 percent decline in domestic car sales.
   Chrysler Corp. car sales rose 10.3 percent from the year earlier
and Ford Motor Co. sales were up 8.7 percent.
   Domestic truck sales for all makers rose by 6.5 percent.
   Industry analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in
New York, said the figures were skewed because GM sales surged last
April due to sales incentives.
   ``They were 55 percent of the market, so the comparison will be
kind of distorted. GM will look poor,'' Healy said.
   For the month, GM car sales were down 14.2 percent to a total of
314,671, Ford's were down 1.4 percent to 186,175 and Chrysler's
sales rose 8.8 percent to 95,170.
   GM held a 47.2 percent makret share during the late April
period, compared with 27.9 percent for Ford and 13.9 percent for
Chrysler. GM's share in the year-earlier period was 54.9 percent,
due largely to the special sales incentives.
   Imported car sales totaled 236,451, up 0.7 percent, for April,
though imported light truck sales plunged 37.4 percent to a 50,318
monthly total. Importers report their sales monthly.
   The decline of the dollar over the past three years has forced
Japanese and European automakers to raise their prices, to reflect
the strengthening of their own currencies.
   As a result, the Japanese imports have begun using the tactic of
sales incentives that domestic manufacturers have focused on for
the past couple of years, said Chris Cedergren, analyst at J.D.
Power & Associates in Agoura Hills, Calif.
   Nissan, with aggressive incentive programs, sold 31,197 imported
cars for the month, up 7.3 percent, and 6,545 U.S.-produced cars,
up 2.8 percent.
   Toyota sold 43,605 imports, up slightly from 43,339, and 2,200
U.S.-made cars, up from 2,187.
   Honda import sales dropped 3.6 percent to 19,702, but sales of
domestically made Hondas rose 7.5 percent to 17,512.
   Volkswagen import sales dropped 25 percent to 11,922 and
domestic sales sank 7.5 percent to 2,712.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-United-Smoking     05-05 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-United-Smoking,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United Clarifies Its No-Smoking Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines said Wednesday it would ban
smoking on all its flights of 1,000 miles or less within the United
States or Canada as of June 1, in an attempt to remedy confusion
over a new federal rule banning smoking on short-duration flights.
   Federal regulations that took effect April 22 prohibit smoking
on flights scheduled to take two hours or less.
   But because of headwinds or air traffic, flights between the
same cities can take different amounts of time when travel is in
different directions, United spokesman Rob Doughty said Wednesday.
   That has caused some confusion among United passengers and crew,
he said.
   The new rule will add 53 pairs of cities to the list of
non-smoking United flights, said John R. Zeeman, a United vice
president.
   Doughty said the two-hour rule affects 57 percent of all United
flights, and the new 1,000-mile rule would affect 77 percent of the
airline's flights.
   ``We certainly think it works better for the customers and for
United Airlines to make the criterion mileage instead of time,''
Doughty said.
</TEXT>
