<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 0911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-InsuranceCollapse     05-05 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Insurance Collapse,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Said to Have Doctored Financial Records</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officers of Integrity Insurance Co.
illegally drained the company of cash and committed corporate
racketeering that caused its $300 million collapse last year, the
state says in a lawsuit.
   The lawsuit, filed here Wednesday by the state Department of
Insurance, accuses former company President Christian Yegen of
Tenafly and others of doctoring financial records to convince
regulators and customers alike that the company was sound and able
to pay its claims.
   The lawsuit describes the Paramus company's deficit at more than
$300 million, one of the largest insurance failures ever, according
to state officials. The deficit may eventually exceed $1 billion
once all claims are settled several years from now, the state
alleged.
   ``We are trying to get the money back,'' said state Insurance
Commissioner Kenneth D. Merin. ``The collapse has had a major
impact, not only on people who bought insurance, but on the
industry, because it has raised questions about its ability to
carry out its mission.''
   In its lawsuit, the state charged that Integrity was insolvent
as early as 1981, six years before the state ousted its owners and
took control of the company.
   Yegen denied that the company filed false financial reports.
   ``We stated the numbers as they appeared at the time,'' Yegen
told The Record of Hackensack.
   To hide its deepening financial woes, the state charged, the
company periodically transferred cash among related corporations
and fraudulently inflated its worth by claiming uncollectable debts
as assets.
   Company officials, including Yegen, also authorized up to $13
million in illegal dividends to shareholders and furnished
falsified reports to the state Department of Insurance, the federal
Securities and Exchange Commission, and other regulatory agencies,
the state alleged in the Superior Court suit.
   The company is also under investigation by the state attorney
general's office, which could file criminal charges.
</TEXT>
