<1ST_LINE>u f PM-UnitedPilots Bjt   05-05 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-United Pilots, Bjt,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilots Make Renewed Offer for United Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group led by United Airlines' pilots is making
a new $4 billion bid to take over the airline, saying the takeover
would benefit shareholders and energize workers.
   The pilots' offer _ their third in a year to propose an employee
takeover or restructuring of the carrier _ includes payment of $110
cash per outstanding share of Allegis Corp., the airline's parent
company, the refinancing of certain Allegis debts, and wage cuts
and other concessions to trim labor costs, said William R. Howard,
chairman of Airline Acquisition Corp.
   The corporation was formed by the United Air Lines Pilots Master
Executive Council to oversee a proposed takeover of the airline.
   ``We are excited about our proposal,'' Howard wrote in a letter
to Stephen M. Wolf, chairman of Allegis, which is based in suburban
Elk Grove Village.
   ``It offers Allegis' stockholders a significant premium over
current market for their shares,'' Howard said. ``It also offers
United ... an opportunity to be the premier airline in the United
States and employees an incentive to achieve that result by
allowing them to reap directly the fruits of their own labors.''
   Wolf said Wednesday he would have no immediate comment on the
offer.
   Allegis stock closed at $90 a share Wednesday, up $5.25 in
trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The takeover would be financed through $3.1 billion in bank
loans provided by a syndicate of banks led by Chemical Bank, a $600
million bank credit facility, and the sale of $800 million in
subordinated notes, Howard said.
   Chemical and the investment firm Salomon Brothers have indicated
they were highly confident they could raise the needed financing,
the pilots group said.
   In a statement read by Allegis spokesman Dan Sheehy, Wolf said,
``The board of directors has indicated it will do what is in the
best interest of our shareholders and our employees, and we will
respond as soon as we have had a chance to understand whether this
is a valid offer.''
   The pilots' group made two offers last year to buy or
restructure the airline, and company officials rejected both.
   In his letter, Howard proposed a 25 percent pay cut for some
pilots, a reduction in company contributions to a pilots' benefit
plan, and changes in compensation and work-rules of non-contract
employees. Those moves, he said, would save as much as $350 million
a year.
   But the proposed takeover hinges on the union's success in a
lawsuit challenging the company's takeover provisions.
   Last week, the United pilots group sued the airline, along with
Allegis and the Machinists union, to strike down Machinists'
contract provisions that the lawsuit claimed could block an
employee takeover of United.
   Hank Krakowski, a pilots union spokesman, said at the time the
contract prohibited the pilots union from participating in an
employee ownership plan unless the Machinists agree to the terms.
   Unless parts of the Machinists' contract are declared
unenforceable by the U.S. District Court in Chicago, the
``protective covenants'' in them would be a ``significant
obstacle'' to Wednesday's proposed takeover, Howard said.
   Howard, former chairman of Piedmont Aviation, proposed in his
letter that he be chairman and chief executive officer of the new
company formed by the employee takeover.
   The proposal also states that all employees would participate
``on a fair and equitable basis, in the ownership of the company.''
   Howard also indicated that the group might seek to have its
proposal put to a vote of United shareholders once it resolved the
Machinists issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
