<1ST_LINE>u f PM-USG-DesertPartners     05-05 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USG-Desert Partners,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USG Announces Financing For Recapitalization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. said it has received commitments to
finance a $2.2 billion recapitalization plan designed to thwart a
hostile takeover bid from Desert Partners L.P.
   In making the announcement Wednesday, USG Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer Robert J. Day said, ``Let's make it clear. USG is
not for sale.''
   Earlier in the day Desert Partners, a partnership headed by two
Texas oilmen, offered to acquire the Chicago-based building
materials company in a negotiated deal that Wall Street analysts
estimated would be worth about $50 a share, or about $2.6 billion.
   Under one of two proposals, Desert Partners would pay $39 in
cash and $9 in bonds for each outstanding share of USG stock.
Shareholders also would receive stock representing 15 percent of a
new company.
   Under a variation, Desert Partners offered to pay $50 a share in
cash for 37.1 million, or 72 percent of USG's outstanding shares.
The remaining shares would be exchanged for bonds and stock in the
new company valued at ``the same aggregate amount,'' Desert
Partners said in a statement.
   Day said the ``proposals are not credible. Desert Partners'
financing commitments prohibit it from offering more than $45 per
share ''
   After jumping $1.62{ a share on Wednesday, USG declined 75 cents
a share to $45.87{ in early trading today on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   Texas oilmen Cyril Wagner Jr. and Jack E. Brown, who head the
partnership, have been trying to negotiate a deal for some time. In
a letter to USG's board of directors on Wednesday, Wagner stressed
that ``the time has come for you to stop spending time and money in
an effort to avoid discussing an acquisition of USG with us.''
   Desert Partners also has a $42-a-share tender offer outstanding.
That bid, including cash for up to 39 million shares and debt
securities and warrants valued at $42 each for the remainder, has a
value of about $2.2 billion.
   USG has been fighting off Desert Partners for months.
   Under its recapitalization plan, USG would borrow $2.2 billion
to pay its shareholders $37 in cash, debentures with a face value
of $5 and a share of stock in the recapitalized company for each
common share. It said it would have to sell off its Masonite and
Kinkead businesses to finance the restructuring.
   Desert Partners owns about 9.9 percent of USG's shares and said
that as of Friday about 19.3 million shares, or 37.5 percent, had
been tendered under its $42-a-share offer.
   In addition to Masonite and Kinkead, USG owns United States
Gypsum, USG Interiors and several other operating subsidiaries.
</TEXT>
