<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Sugar     05-05 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Sugar,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazil Joins Sugar Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazil, the world's third largest sugar exporter,
has decided to join the new International Sugar Agreement, the
pact's spokesman said Thursday.
   Constantin Politoff said he hoped the necessary legal procedures
could be completed by May 18 when leading sugar-trading nations who
signed the agreement meet in London.
   Brazil had refused to join the new accord when it came into
force March 24 because it provides for the cost of running the
London-based International Sugar Organization to be borne most
heavily by producer nations.
   The agreement, reached at a London meeting called by the United
Nations, is set to run until the end of 1990.
   It has no provisions for controlling world sugar supplies and
prices but Politoff said he expects the May 18 meeting to discuss a
clause allowing members to negotiate a new pact with regulatory
powers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880505-0319 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet11am     05-05 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0279</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell today as traders warily
awaited the latest monthly report on employment.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 15.09 to
2,021.22 by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 2 to 1 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 366 up, 839
down and 492 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 74.20 million shares at
midmorning.
   The Labor Department is scheduled to report Friday on the
employment situation for April. Economists generally expect the
data to show continuing job gains.
   But analysts say they expect investors to respond negatively to
any evidence of increasing strength in the economy, interpreting it
as a portent of mounting inflationary pressures and an upward
influence on interest rates.
   Wall Streeters reason that the Federal Reserve is likely to give
the employment figures considerable weight in deciding whether and
when to tighten its credit policy.
