<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade, with soybeans and oats moving higher
and corn and wheat posting early losses.
   The National Weather Service issued an extended forecast
Wednesday calling for normal rainfall in the Midwest, which
prompted some selling of corn futures, analysts said.
   Selling interest in the soybean pit evaporated quickly in the
wake of Wednesday's big losses. Soybean traders, worried that a
small crop this year could result in tight supplies, lately have
seemed as fickle as the weather forecasts they so closely monitor.
   ``One moment, they're optimistic about no rain, the next minute
they're optimisitic about more rain,'' said Jerry Gidel, a grain
analyst with G.H. Miller & Co. in Chicago.
   Wheat futures continued to feel pressure from the approaching
winter wheat harvest, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3 a bushel; corn was { cent to 1\
cents lower with May at $2.04\ a bushel; oats were \ cent to 1 cent
higher with May at $1.60{ a bushel; soybeans were { cent to 1}
cents higher with May at $6.85{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .58 cent higher with June at 72.05
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .25 cent higher with
May at 79.77 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .58 cent higher
with June at 51.02 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .28 cent
to .78 cent higher with May at 51.95 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Wednesday; pork futures were
mostly higher.
</TEXT>
