<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WPPSSSettlements     05-05 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WPPSS Settlements,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Utilities Settle In Washington Public Power Supply System Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more public utility districts that are
defendants in the securities fraud case brought against the
Washington Public Power Supply System have announced out-of-court
settlements.
   The two, Kittitas County and Ferry County, will not have to
raise rates to cover the $1.75 million they agreed to pay to be let
out of the case, said Malcolm Harris, a Seattle attorney
representing the utilities.
   The case was filed in 1983 after WPPSS defaulted on bond
payments for two scrapped nuclear plants.
   The settlements and defense costs, if approved by a federal
court judge, will be paid by the utilities' insurance companies,
Harris said.
   Neither utility was among the 88 participants in the two nuclear
plants, Nos. 4 and 5, but both are members of WPPSS and were named
as defendants in a federal suit brought by holders of the bonds
that financed the two plants. The plants were terminated in early
1982.
   The settlement, reached on April 27, was not made public until
Wednesday.
   The lawsuit is scheduled for trial Sept. 7 in Tucson, Ariz.
   The Ferry-Kittitas settlement was the ninth to be announced
since the suit was filed and brings total settlement amounts to
about $242 million. Among others that were settled were the bond
underwriters (for $92 million) and Seattle ($50 million). Three
other public utility districts that were participants in the
projects settled for $20 million.
   WPPSS terminated the two plants, No. 4 at Hanford and No. 5 at
Satsop, in 1982, after $2.25 billion had been invested. No. 4 was
24 percent complete and No. 5 was 16 percent finished.
   Termination of the plants eventually resulted in default on the
$2.25 billion in bonds sold to finance the construction of Nos. 4
and 5. It was the biggest default in the history of the municipal
bond market. Most of the litigation has been consolidated into the
case set for trial in Tucson.
</TEXT>
