<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0329</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market showed a broad loss today as
traders warily awaited the latest monthly report on employment.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 18.74 to
2,017.57 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 5 to 2 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 350 up, 939
down and 495 unchanged.
   The Labor Department is scheduled to report Friday on the
employment situation for April. Economists generally expect the
data to show continuing job gains.
   But analysts say they expect investors to respond negatively to
any evidence of increasing strength in the economy, interpreting it
as a portent of mounting inflationary pressures and an upward
influence on interest rates.
   Wall Streeters reason that the Federal Reserve is likely to give
the employment figures considerable weight in deciding whether and
when to tighten its credit policy.
   Yields on long-term Treasury bonds have lately been hovering
around 9 percent. If they were to go much higher, brokers say, they
would pose a formidable competitive threat to stocks.
   General Motors led the active list, down ] at 75| on volume of
more than 26 million shares. Analysts said much of the activity in
the stock involved short-term trading strategies keyed to the
company's impending quarterly dividend.
   Bethlehem Steel dropped ] to 19\. The company announced an
offering of 10 million new shares at $19 apiece.
   Among other blue chips, International Business Machines lost 1[
to 111; Sears Roebuck { to 35\, and American Telephone & Telegraph
] to 26.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
1.09 to 146.20. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off .99 at 301.55.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 97.83 million shares at
noontime, against 64.02 million at the same point Wednesday.
