<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Kraft-Duracell     05-05 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kraft-Duracell,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kraft Agrees to Sells Duracell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. has agreed to sell its Duracell
battery unit for $1.8 billion in cash to a new company formed by a
New York investment firm and Duracell's management, the companies
said today.
   The New York investment firm, Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.,
specializes in finding, financing and investing in management
buyouts.
   Kraft had said it planned to sell its profitable Duracell
division, the world's leading maker of alkaline consumer batteries,
to concentrate on its food business.
   ``The sale price is fair and adequately compensates Kraft for
this fine business,'' Kraft Chairman John M. Richman said in a
statement.
   Henry R. Kravis, a partner in Kohlberg Kravis, called the
definitive agreement ``the first step in the creation of a great
new independent consumer products company.''
   ``We are very excited about the future growth prospects of the
company and our future association with the management and
employees of Duracell,'' he said.
   Duracell, headquartered in Bethel, Conn., earned $53.9 million
on sales of $1.1 billion last year.
   Kraft had 1987 sales, excluding Duracell, of $9.9 billion.
   Kraft said it would use the proceeds from the sale to purchase
up to 12 milion shares of its own stock, to reduce its debt and to
``be prepared'' for food-related acquisition opportunities.
</TEXT>
