<1ST_LINE>u f PM-SpaceFactory 2ndLd-Writethru   05-05 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Factory, 2nd Ld-Writethru,f0058,0737</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Demands Final Say on Private Space Factory</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Fletcher remarks. Picks up 2nd graf pvs,
``The probabilities ... Also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA administrator James C. Fletcher said
today that space budget levels being discussed in Congress will
cripple America's space program and bring 30 years of progress to a
halt.
   ``It is not a pretty prospect to imagine the United States as a
second-rate or even a third-rate power in space,'' Fletcher said in
remarks for a symposium on science education. ``That is what this
country will quickly become if Congress doesn't act responsibly and
give NASA the resources it needs to do its job.''
   The Reagan administdration asked Congress to give NASA $11.5
billion in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. But key lawmakers have
said that the agency can expect no more than $10.7 billion and a
House budget resolution would slash the amount to $10.2 billion.
   ``The civil space program will be stopped in its tracks'' at
those levels, Fletcher said, and it ``would spell death to the
space station, the key to our future in space.'' He said the space
shuttle would be able to operate only at a reduced flight rate in
the years ahead.
   At an authorization hearing Wednesday, the House space science
subcommittee turned its back on a Reagan administration plan to
sign a contract this year to lease a robot space factory from a
private company.
   ``The probabilities are that there is going to be only one lousy
bidder on it and that's a group of guys who couldn't sell to the
private market,'' said Rep. David Nagle, D-Iowa.
   That fear and a suspicion that building the factory might drain
funds and future support for the planned large U.S. space station
prompted the House space science subcommittee to vote Wednesday to
prohibit contracts for the Commercially Developed Space Facility.
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration will be required
to obtain express permission from Congress first.
   Nagle said the proposed lease was ``a project to benefit a group
of people in Houston.''
   Space Industries Inc. of Houston has proposed leasing 70 percent
of a robot space factory to the government for five years at $140
million a year and leasing the rest to private industry. The
facility would be carried into orbit aboard the space shuttle and
be serviced periodically by astronauts.
   ``A vote for this is a vote to cripple the space station,''
Nagle said. ``A vote for this is a vote to intimidate the efforts
to build a space station. A vote for this is to reward an
incompetent presentation by the space agency that this committee
should not tolerate.''
   His reference was to complaints by members of both the House and
Senate that NASA, which once said it had no use for such a
facility, reversed itself but failed to make a case for why the
space factory was needed.
   ``NASA was obviously told to change its position,'' said Rep.
Bill Nelson, D-Fla., chairman of the House space science
subcommittee.
   The panel voted against a Nagle amendment that NASA should not
even be allowed to issue a request for industry proposals for the
facility. But it expressly forbade the agency to sign any contracts
for it.
   The instructions are included in a bill approved by the
subcommittee Wednesday to authorize $11.5 billion for NASA in the
fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. That amount, an increase of $2.5
billion over the current spending, was asked for by President
Reagan and includes $967 million for the proposed U.S. space
station.
   The space factory prohibition decision is a rebuff to Reagan
whose space policy, announced in February, included the intention
to sign a contract in midsummer for such a facility to be available
by late 1993.
   Reagan's overall funding request for NASA also could be in
trouble. The House and Senate appropriations committees, which
actually allocate funds, have said they will not approve more than
$10.7 billion for the agency.
   The committee's bill also authorizes funds for the Advanced
Communications Technology Satellite, which the administration
opposes; it would grant arrest powers to private security guards on
NASA facilities; and it would require NASA contractors to maintain
a drug-free workplace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
