<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-PersonalFile-Icahn Adv06   05-05 1162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Personal File-Icahn, Adv 06,1199</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday May 6 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Icahn: The `Deal Man' Vs. Texaco</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was noontime in front of a bank of elevators,
and takeover artist Carl C. Icahn, Texaco Inc.'s largest
stockholder, was cornered.
   Yes or no? the reporters asked. Would he vote his shares in
favor of the company's bankruptcy reorganization plan or not?
   Icahn, who had all but said yes at a press conference, continued
to hedge, lunging for the elevator as the ``down'' bell rang.
   But each time the doors opened, the car was full. Packed. No
room for the tall, gangly Icahn. The doors closed, and the
questions resumed.
   Two edgy advisers pulled their boss aside. After a brief,
animated discussion, Icahn flicked the back of his hand, walked
back to the reporters and fired off his answer: ``Yes. I'm voting
for the plan.''
   Always his own boss, the brassy corporate bearhunter is at once
a book that's open and shut, a master strategist who knows the
value of a well-kept secret, but who's not afraid to make a quick
decision.
   Icahn _ who recently described himself in Fortune Magazine as
``obsessive in everything I do'' _ draws attention easily, in
manner and presence.
   He stands over 6 feet tall, and his face bears a startling
resemblance to comedian Mel Brooks. Often reluctant to speak to the
press, he is actually quite loquacious in person, people who know
him say.
   ``I talk to him all the time. I mean, I listen to him all the
time. There's a difference,'' joked Texaco President James W.
Kinnear recently.
   Icahn's involvement with Texaco has been no laughing matter to
Texaco's managers _ especially Kinnear.
   They believe he wants to gain control of Texaco in order to milk
its assets dry _ a process that would leave the company in
shambles. Holding 14.8 percent of Texaco's stock, Icahn has
demanded that Texaco put itself up for sale, and has nominated his
own slate of candidates _ including himself _ for the company's
board of directors.
   Not long ago, more than a few industry analysts were betting
privately that Icahn would win, saying disgruntled shareholders
were itching to get back at Texaco's management for its
multibillion-dollar Pennzoil debacle.
   Now, they say, the tide may have shifted in Texaco's favor,
especially since the company reinstated its annual dividend to
shareholders.
   Texaco on Tuesday asked a federal court to block all of Icahn's
maneuverings against the company, charging him with a long list of
securities laws violations.
   Icahn denies the allegations and says he's not through with
Texaco yet.
   ``I've learned one thing: What counts is which way the tide is
going _ on the last day,'' he said.
   Whatever happens, it is generally agreed that if anyone could
dislodge the status quo at Texaco, it's Icahn, the man whose very
name can send shivers through boardrooms across the land.
   The 52-year-old financier has made his reputation by buying up
shares in companies with assets worth more than their stock price,
then selling the companies off later, in whole or in pieces, at a
higher price.
   Sometimes companies agree to buy the stock back at a premium to
get him to leave them alone, a practice known as greenmail. Other
times, as with Trans World Airlines Inc. and ACF Industries Inc.,
Icahn has retained a management role, but always with the intent of
using the company as a vehicle for later takeover attempts.
   Recently, for example, he offered to buy the 23 percent of TWA
stock he does not already own. TWA holds nearly 60 percent of his
Texaco stake. By taking the company private, Icahn would be freer
to sell TWA or use it as an investment vehicle.
   One way or another, Icahn almost always walks away millions of
dollars richer. Some of his more than 20 takeover targets have
included: Chesebrough-Ponds Inc.; Marshall Field & Co.; Hammermill
Paper Co.; Phillips Petroleum Co.; Unocal Corp. and USX Corp., in
which he still holds a sizable stake.
   To his critics, Icahn is little more than a pirate in a coat and
tie.
   Icahn says the real villains are corporate chieftans who are
wasteful, inefficient and more interested in protecting their
high-salaried jobs than looking out for the interests of their real
bosses _ the stockholders.
   That, more than the money _ which he does not need _ is what
keeps him in the takeover game, Icahn told The Associated Press.
   ``I think there's no question there's a competitive force in me.
But it's also a sense of outrage about the way companies are run,''
he said.
   In the case of Texaco, Icahn has said he would withdraw his
slate of board candidates if the company were put up for sale at a
minimum $55 a share. Selling his stake at that level would net
Icahn about $757 million before costs, compared with roughly $540
million, if he sold out now.
   But Icahn's holding is too big to unload on the open market
quickly without diluting its value. Unless he wants to stay in the
oil business, Icahn's only other choice may be to sell to another
big entity, such as an oil company.
   Some were watching hungrily as Texaco emerged from a year of
bankruptcy court protection, paying $3 billion to Pennzoil Co. _ to
settle the lawsuit Texaco lost over its 1984 acquisition of Getty
Oil Co. _ and promising to unload billions of dollars in assets.
   Analysts say those potential buyers could provide a way for
Icahn to make his profit _ without having to worry about running
the company.
   Actually, Icahn's management has been paying off at both TWA,
which he took over in January 1986, and ACF, a conglomerate he
bought in 1984 and stripped down to its core railroad-car business.
   Airline industry analysts acknowledge that TWA has recovered
remarkably under Icahn, reporting its best earnings ever in 1987
after a string of big losses. But they also say he was lucky,
particularly in winning labor concessions from unions eager to
escape Texas Air's Frank Lorenzo, whom they perceived as anti-union.
   In the end, Icahn is ``in it for himself primarily,'' said Louis
A. Marckesano of Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. ``I don't think he
really cares what happens to TWA in the future ... He's a financier
who happens to own an airline.''
   Icahn argues, in response, that TWA would have been bankrupt, if
he hadn't come along: ``Sure, we used a lot of leverage to do this
thing, but what's wrong with that? Basically, we saved the
airline.''
   Indeed, regardless of his intentions, Icahn's financial wizardry
often evokes praise.
   ``The guy is a deal man ... one of the toughest negotiators
you'll ever see,'' said John Pincavage of PaineWebber Inc. ``We
ought to use him against the Russians. I mean, this guy is good.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday May 6</NOTE>
