<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with closing stock prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange dropped
Thursday as the market fell victim to declining prices on Wall
Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed down
5.2 points, or 0.28 percent, to 1,789.5.
   Share prices had opened slightly lower but picked up some steam
at midmorning following reports of favorable company earnings.
   But by midafternoon, London stocks began to feel some of the
pressure from Wall Street's soggy opening and drifted lower.
   Some London dealers said computer-generated program-selling on
Wall Street, which accounted for a sharp loss Wednesday, lingered
in the market Thursday. By the close of London trading, Wall
Street's most widely watched index, the Dow Jones industrial
average, was down 17.91 points at 2,018.40.
   Pervasive nervousness also contributed to the London selloff,
dealers said, after Wednesday's news that the British Department of
Trade and Industry would refer the Kuwait Investment Office
purchase of British Petroleum Co. shares to the Mergers and
Monopolies Commission.
</TEXT>
