<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Close Lower While Soybeans Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures closed lower Thursday on the
Chicago Board of Trade while soybean prices advanced due to
worsening crop weather forecasts, analysts said.
   Private forecasts suggested the amounts of rain this weekend in
the western Corn Belt could be lighter than anticipated. With
soybean planting just getting under way, the market is especially
sensitive to any indications of dry weather.
   Soybeans for May delivery traded as high as $6.92{ a bushel at
mid-session but profit-taking later in the day brought prices down
three to four cents, analysts said.
   Wheat continued to slump in anticipation of a plentiful
winter-wheat harvest.
   Memphis-based Sparks Commodities predicted a winter-wheat
harvest of nearly 1.64 billion bushels, up about 70 million bushels
from last year despite lower plantings. Other estimates ranged as
low as 1.55 billion bushels.
   ``There may be some people evening up ahead of Tuesday's
Agriculture Report on wheat production estimates,'' said Jerry
Gidel, an analyst in Chicago with G.H. Miller & Co.
   Corn prices drifted lower amid sluggish export demand, he said.
   At the close, wheat was 3{ cents to 4} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $2.96} a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 2\ cents lower with May at $2.02} a bushel; oats were \ cent to
1 cent lower with May at $1.60 a bushel; soybeans were 3} cents to
7 cents higher with May at $6.89 a bushel.
</TEXT>
