<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BeloStock     05-05 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Belo Stock,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belo Changes Stock Structure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A.H. Belo Corp. shareholders have approved a
board-backed anti-takeover plan that allows the media company to
issue a new class of stock that enhances voting rights of existing
stockowners.
   Under the plan, approved at Belo's annual meeting Wednesday, the
company will distribute as a dividend one share of a Series B
common stock for each common share outstanding to shareholders of
record May 13. Each share of that special series carries 10 votes.
   Distribution of the Series B stock is expected May 19, the
company said.
   The plan, though, has been the subject of a lawsuit by New York
shareholder William Steiner. He filed suit Tuesday to block the
issue in Delaware, where Belo is incorporated.
   By providing more votes per share Belo will make itself a more
difficult target for future hostile takeover attempts.
   Belo is the parent of the Dallas Morning News. In addition, it
owns television stations in Dallas, Houston, Sacramento, Calif.;
Norfolk, Va., and Tulsa, Okla. It also operates Dallas-Fort Worth
Suburban Newspapers Inc.
</TEXT>
