<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices fell the second straight session in the
stock market Thursday as traders warily awaited the latest monthly
report on employment.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 22.05 on
Wednesday, fell another 16.08 to 2,020.23.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 3 in New
York Stock Exchange-listed trading, with 559 up, 925 down and 509
unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 171.84 million shares, against 141.32
million in the previous session. The NYSE's composite index dropped
.78 to 146.51.
   The Labor Department is scheduled to report Friday on the
employment situation for April. Economists generally expect the
data to show continuing job gains.
   But analysts say investors may well respond negatively to any
evidence of increasing strength in the economy, interpreting it as
a portent of mounting inflationary pressures and an upward
influence on interest rates.
   Wall Streeters reason that the Federal Reserve is likely to give
the employment figures considerable weight in deciding whether or
when to tighten its credit policy.
   Yields on long-term Treasury bonds have lately been hovering
around 9 percent. If they were to go much higher, brokers say, they
would stand to pose a formidable competitive threat to stocks.
   General Motors led the active list, down \ at 75} on volume of
more than 26 million shares. Analysts said much of the activity in
the stock involved short-term trading strategies keyed to the
company's impending quarterly dividend.
   Bethlehem Steel dropped { to 19[. The company announced an
offering of 10 million new shares at $19 apiece.
   Among other blue chips, International Business Machines lost ~
to 111\; Sears Roebuck { to 35\; Merck 1~ to 155\; DuPont 1\ to 84,
and American Telephone & Telegraph \ to 26[.
   Kraft rose 1{ to 53{. The company said it would sell its
