<HEAD>Posts Big Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loews Corp., a diversified holding company, said
Thursday its first-quarter profit nearly tripled on strong results
from insurance operations and gains on investments.
   Loews, which also has interests in hotels, tobacco, broadcasting
and watches, said its earnings rose to $231.4 million, or $3.03 a
share, in the three months ended March 31 compared with $87.1
million, or $1.08 per share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the first quarter rose 19 percent to $2.5 billion
from $2.1 billion a year earlier.
   The company said its income from continuing operations rose to
$213.4 million compared with $79.1 million a year earlier.
   It said it realized $90.4 million in investment gains on
securities in the latest quarter in contrast with investment losses
of $9.8 million a year earlier. Income from continuing operations
in insurance rose to $147.3 million from $74.8 million a year
earlier.
   The latest results also included an $18.1 million gain in the
latest quarter from its 24.9 percent stake in the broadcast giant
CBS Inc. that resulted from CBS' sale of its records group.
   Loews has an 82 percent stake in the insurance concern CNA
Financial Corp., a 94 percent stake in the Bulova Watch Co., owns
the tobacco concern that markets Newport, True and Kent cigarettes
and operates Loews hotels.
   Loews' chairman, Laurence A. Tisch, is chief executive of CBS.
</TEXT>
