<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Stevens     05-05 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stevens,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorneys General Agree Not to Block Stevens Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorneys general of North Carolina,
South Carolina and New York said Thursday they would not block the
takeover of J.P. Stevens & Co. in exchange for commitments to keep
the textile giant's plants open for two years.
   Stevens is being acquired for $1.22 billion by rival fabric
maker West Point-Pepperell Inc., which plans to split Stevens's
assets with two other companies.
   ``While these commitments do not guarantee absolute protection
of all plants and jobs, these commitments do provide significant
protections to Stevens workers,'' North Carolina Attorney General
Lacy Thornburg said at a news conference.
   The states reserved the right to go to court later ``if it is
necessary to protect competition in the textile industry,''
Thornburg said.
   The attorneys general had threatened to file a suit on Friday
over the takeover, which will see Pepperell acquire Stevens' sheet
and towel operations. Pepperell plans sell some operations to
another textile producer, Bibb Co. of Macon, Ga., to satisfy
federal antitrust concerns.
   Odyssey Partners, a Wall Street investment firm that had been
vying with Pepperell for Stevens, will get the company's other
operations, including its carpet and industrial fabrics plants.
   In return for the states agreeing not to file suit Friday, West
Point-Pepperell and Bibb agreed not to close plants for two years
and make good-faith efforts not to reduce current employment
levels; to provide preferential consideration to former Stevens
managers, and to continue to use and maintain present contracts
with local vendors.
   Odyssey Partners said in writing it does not anticipate plant
closings and will not engage in significant plant closings for two
years.
   Stevens employs about 34,000 in its 54 plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
