<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RockwellPlant     05-05 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rockwell Plant,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rockwell To Halt Operations At Columbus Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp., citing
declines in government defense contracts, announced Thursday that
it will halt production at its airplane plant here, idling about
1,000 employees.
   Dent Williams, a spokesman for the Pittsburgh-based Rockwell,
said production would be phased out over the next 15 months.
   ``There's just not enough defense business out there to support
all the aircraft facilities,'' Williams said.
   Rockwell produced major structural components for the B-1B
bomber for six years at the government-owned plant here. The last
of the B-1Bs was delivered to the Air Force last week, Rockwell
said.
   The company said the plant's current employment of 1,000 is down
from a peak of 7,200 at the height of B-1B production.
   Rockwell said it will continue aircraft activities at plants in
California and Tulsa, Okla.
   There was no immediate response from the Rockwell union to the
company announcement.
   The Columbus plant was built in 1942 for the Navy and was
operated for eight years by the Curtiss-Wright Corp. A predecessor
of Rockwell, North American Aviation Inc., began operating the
plant in 1950 and continued to do so after the plant's ownership
switched to the Air Force.
</TEXT>
