<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-05 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pork Futures Surge On Strong Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pork futures prices climbed sharply Thursday on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange as cash markets reflected strong demand for
pork products and chart signals indicated the market was ripe for a
rally.
   Most cattle futures also advanced.
   On other markets, energy futures were higher; grains and
soybeans were mixed; gold gained slightly; and stock-index futures
retreated.
   The movement of hogs to market this week has been running about
equal to a year ago but slaughters are up and so are prices, said
Tom O'Hare, an analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham
& Co.
   ``Today, more than anythying, I think the cash markets did a
little better than most people had thought,'' he said. ``And with
beef as high as it is, I think retailers are probably going to be
featuring more pork, so the demand is there, too.''
   Technical factors also played a role in Thursday's rally,
especially in the pork belly pit, where prices have been trending
lower due to a glut of frozen bellies.
   Cattle futures advaned on follow-through buying from Wednesday's
strong close. Steady cash markets and gave the cattle market
additional support, O'Hare said.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent to .55 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in June at 72.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle
were .08 cent lower to .30 cent higher with May at 79.75 cents a
pound; hogs were .15 cent to 1.20 cents higher with June at 51.65
cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .28 cent lower to 1.20
cents higher with May at 52.37 cents a pound.
   News reports of a fiery explosion at a Shell Oil Co. refinery in
Norco, La., boosted energy futures prices on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   ``That set the tone right off the bat with people buying
gasoline outright as a supply hedge and, as a speculative trade,
buying gasoline and selling crude against it,'' said John Azarow,
an analyst in New York with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The positive technical implications of Thursday's higher opening
and the June crude oil contract's close above $17.37 a barrel
``should bode for higher prices,'' Azarow said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent lower to 19
cents higher with June at $17.39 a barrel; heating oil was .37 cent
to 1.68 cents higher with June at 46.57 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .40 cent to .89 cent higher with June at 50.61 cents a
gallon.
   Grain futures settled lower on the Chicago Board of Trade while
soybean prices advanced in response to new crop weather forecasts,
analysts said.
   Private forecasts suggested the amounts of rain this weekend in
the western Corn Belt could be lighter than anticipated. With
soybean planting just getting under way, the market is especially
sensitive to any indications of dry weather.
   Wheat continued to slump in anticipation of a plentiful
winter-wheat harvest, analysts said, while corn drifted lower amid
sluggish export demand, he said.
   Wheat settled 3{ cents to 4} cents lower with May at $2.96} a
bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2 cents lower with May at $2.03 a
bushel; oats were \ cent to 1 cent lower with May at $1.60 a
bushel; soybeans were 4\ cents to 6 cents higher with May at $6.89{
a bushel.
   Gold and silver futures prices rose slightly on New York's
Commodity Exchange in sluggish trading marked by a lack of
influential news, analysts said.
   Gold settled 40 cents to $1.40 higher with June at $447 a troy
ounce; silver was 3.5 cents to 3.7 cents higher with May at $6.364
a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures retreated slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for June delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled .50 point lower at 259.35.
</TEXT>
