<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Teamsters-Salerno 1stLd-Writethru   05-05 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters-Salerno, 1st Ld-Writethru,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presser Takes Leave As Teamsters Takeover Case Falters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Presser hospitalized, INSERTS New 3rd graf,
Climaco said ... A version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Embattled Teamsters President Jackie Presser
is taking a leave of absence from the job just as a jury's verdict
in the trial of a New York mob boss has set back federal efforts to
oust him and other leaders of the nation's largest union.
   John R. Climaco, the union's chief attorney, said Thursday that
Presser had advised the other 20 members of the Teamsters'
executive board over the previous 24 hours that he ``will be
temporarily unavailable for the next 120 days'' because of his
health.
   Climaco said Presser is hospitalized at the Cleveland Clinic in
Ohio, where he is undergoing a new round of radiation treatments.
   Presser, 61, underwent surgery in January 1987 for lung cancer
and has not returned to work full-time since then while undergoing
a series of radiation and chemotherapy treatments.
   However, he has made several appearances at various union
functions, including the AFL-CIO's convention last October at which
he gave an often rambling speech on the occasion of the Teamsters
reaffiliation with the labor federation after a 30-year period.
   In Presser's absence, the 1.6 million-member union will be
directed by Secretary-Treasurer Weldon L. Mathis, Teamsters
officials said. Presser was expected to keep receiving his salary,
now about $600,000 annually, they said.
   Meanwhile, federal law enforcement officials acknowledged their
efforts to wrest control of the Teamsters from Presser through a
civil takeover suit was faltering under a jury's verdict Wednesday
in the trial of New York mob boss Anthony Salerno.
   Salerno was convicted of racketeering in the construction
industry but was acquitted with two other reputed mob figures on
charges of rigging the elections of Roy Williams and Presser to the
Teamsters' presidency in 1981 and 1983.
   A federal law enforcement source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Salerno's acquittal on the Teamster-related counts
was ``a serious setback.''
   Because of the verdict, the source said the government will have
to conduct a ``major re-evaluation'' of the prospects for bringing
a civil suit to put a court-appointed trustee in charge of the
union.
   Climaco said Presser made the decision to step asie temporarily
after he was told by his physicians ``to avoid stress, conserve his
health and undergo additional therapy.''
   However, Climaco answered ``not necessarily'' when asked if
Presser would seek another delay of his trial on federal charges of
racketeering in connection with an alleged payroll-padding scheme
at a Teamsters local in Cleveland that he also heads.
   The trial, already postponed several times because of Presser's
health, is now scheduled to open in U.S. District Court in
Cleveland on July 12.
   ``Mr. Presser is looking forward to his July trial and hopes he
will be physically able to stand trial so that he can once and for
all vindicate himself,'' Climaco said.
   Presser is accused of participating in a scheme in which two men
with alleged organized crime ties were placed on the Cleveland
local's payroll at a cost of $700,000 over several years while
performing no work for the union.
   He has pleaded innocent to the charges and his attorneys have
contended the FBI acquiesced in and even encouraged the employment
of the two men in their use of Presser as a government informant.
   The Justice and Labor departments a year ago began preparing the
Teamsters takeover suit under the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations (RICO) Act.
   But federal prosecutors had delayed filing it out of concern the
suit might prejudice Salerno's trial and the belief that his
conviction would enhance their case for seizing control of the
union.
   John Russell, a Justice Department spokesman, declined to
comment on the outcome of the Salerno case.
   Climaco, however, said the Salerno verdict ``shatters once and
forever the myth'' that the elections of Presser and Williams ``had
been engineered and manipulated by organized crime elements.''
   ``The FBI and the Department of Justice know that at this time
no such influence exists,'' he said. ``It's a fiction, pure
fiction.''
   Some Teamsters officials, nonetheless, said they still feared
Rudolph Giuliani, the U.S. attorney for Manhattan, would pursue a
civil takeover attempt of their union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
