<1ST_LINE>r f AM-KaiserTech     05-05 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-KaiserTech,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Studying Acquisition Possibility; Stock Climbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   KaiserTech Ltd., hampered by uncertainty
over its control and a legal dispute with chairman Alan Clore, said
Thursday its board of directors is considering selling the company.
   The world's fifth-largest aluminum producer said the board
appointed a special committee of independent directors to consider
proposals to acquire all of KaiserTech after being informed that
``one or more'' such offers are expected.
   KaiserTech's stock jumped more than $2 in the first hour of
trading on the New York Stock Exchange and closed up $2.87{ at $18.
   At least one of the acquisition proposals is expected to involve
a leveraged buyout of the company in which its current management
would be offered participation, KaiserTech said.
   The Oakland-based Kaiser Aluminum & Chemical Corp., also said
its board has adopted what it called a ``very limited''
stockholders' rights plan designed to permit the directors and
shareholders to consider a possible sale.
   ``The board of directors believed that given the possibility as
to the future direction of the company ... and given the
possibility of protracted litigation, it makes sense to explore the
possibility of a transaction which would offer all of the company's
stockholders a fair price for their stock,'' said James Pasman,
president and chief executive officer.
   KaiserTech filed suit last month against Clore and the Maxxam
Group investment group to resolve a dispute over rights to nominate
directors. The suit is part of an effort to block the financially
troubled Clore from passing on control of KaiserTech's board to
Houston investor Charles Hurwitz, who has agreed to buy Clore's 27
percent voting stake for about $200 million.
   KaiserTech's management also has sued Clore for alleged
securities-law violations, and a group of directors have sued him
for alleged breach of contract. Both deal with his handling of
company stock.
   Robert Irelan, a KaiserTech spokesman, cautioned that the board
``has not yet decided to sell the company'' despite forming the
special committee.
</TEXT>
