<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Playboy     05-05 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Playboy,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Playboy Profit Up Sharply In Latest Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Playboy Enterprises Inc. said Thursday its profit
more than doubled in the latest quarter, due primarily to the
favorable outcome of a casino bankruptcy case and an income-tax
audit.
   The publisher of Playboy magazine reported net income of $2.7
million, or 29 cents a share, for the three months ended March 31,
compared with $1.1 million, or 12 cents a share, for the same
period a year ago.
   Revenue for the quarter rose to $38 million from $36.2 million.
   The results were for the third quarter of Playboy's fiscal year,
which ends June 30.
   Revenues from Playboy's publishing and
licensing-and-merchandising groups were up, but its video group
reported a loss for the quarter, due to a decrease in subscribers
to its Playboy Channel cable television service, the company said
in a statement.
   Quarterly results included a gain of $1 million from the
approval last month of a reorganization plan for the Atlantis
Hotel-Casino in Atlantic City, N.J. Playboy sold its interest in
the hotel in 1984 and had sued to recover its assets.
   Playboy also posted one-time gains totaling $1.8 million from
various tax-related items.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Playboy netted
$7.8 million, or 83 cents per share, compared with $4.1 million, or
43 cents per share, in the year-earlier period. Revenue rose to
$122 million from $118.1 million.
</TEXT>
