<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-CandyBarWars     05-05 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Candy Bar Wars,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Employers' Group Head Says Swiss Takeover Bid Should Be Blocked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the employers' organization the
Confederation of British Industry said Thursday that the government
should block an attempted Swiss takeover of British confectioner
Rowntree PLC.
   Swiss food manufacturers Nestle SA and Jacobs Suchard SA said
separately Thursday that each had increased its respective stake in
York-based Rowntree, maker of the Kit Kat candy bar.
   CBI director general John Banham stated that Swiss regulations
stopped British companies from easily bidding for Swiss companies
and that a Swiss takeover of Rowntree therefore should be blocked.
   ``We can't safely continue to play football against teams which
have built brick walls across their own goals and expect to win,''
said Banham.
   Nestle last week launched a hostile $3.9 billion bid to acquire
Rowntree. Suchard at the same time said it also had acquired a
stake in Rowntree.
   Nestle stated Thursday it had hiked its stake in Rowntree to 7.1
percent from 6.7 percent to 7.1 percent.
   Suchard said it had hiked its stake to 25.4 percent from 23.5
percent, but it has not indicated whether it plans to launch a full
takeover bid for Rowntree.
   Another British company, Cadbury Schweppes PLC, is the target of
a possible bid from the U.S. leisure group General Cinema Corp. in
what has been dubbed by London newspapers as the candy ``bar wars.''
   General Cinema said last week it would raise its 17.7 percent
stake in Cadbury, whose products include Peter Paul candy bars such
as Mounds and Almond Joy.
   Cadbury Chairman Sir Adrian Cadbury has called on the government
to intervene against a hostile takeover.
   The raids on Cadbury and Rowntree, which are Britain's two top
confectioners and are major players in the world market, have
sparked controversy in Britain.
   Press reports said the government's decision to investigate the
Kuwaiti government's acquisition of a 22 percent stake in oil giant
British Petroleum Co. PLC had led to speculation that it might take
similar action over Rowntree.
   The government's Department of Trade and Industry said Wednesday
it would refer the acquisition by the Kuwait Investment Office to
the Monopolies and Merger Commission. The commission will rule
within four months whether or not the Kuwaiti stake in BP,
Britain's biggest company, is in the public interest.
</TEXT>
